<HEAD>
<TITLE>Aid and Conditionality</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/de.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Aid and Conditionality<p>
<I>Peter Waller</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 1, January-February 1994: pages 4 - 5</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Germany after World War Two was subject to a very strict aid conditionality
under the Marshall Plan. When it became a donor of aid itself,
it gradually introduced conditions connected with its aid. Today,
aid conditionality is accepted as a concept by government, NGOs
and the public.</B>
<P>
Before the role of conditionality attached to German development
aid can be analysed it has to be realized that the Federal Republic
of Germany itself was exposed to severe conditionality during
the Marshall Plan period after World War II. Contrary to general
belief it was not so much the amount of money transferred to the
Western European countries which made this exercise &quot;history's
most successful structural adjustment programme&quot;, but rather
the strict conditionality attached to it. Each recipient had to
sign a bilateral pact with the United States in which they agreed
to balance government budgets, restore financial stability and
stabilise exchange rates at realistic levels. In addition for
every dollar of Marshall Plan aid received, the recipient country
was required to place a matching amount of domestic currency in
a counterpart fund to be used only for purposes approved by the
U.S. government.
<P>
<B>The emerging political conditionality</B>
<P>
When Germany switched from an aid recipient to an aid donor in
the early 1960s, there was a first attempt at political conditionality
by connecting diplomatic relations and development aid with the
nonrecognition of the German Democratic Republic. This was not
successful at all, since in the end the Federal Republic had to
accept that the GDR became a member of the United Nations.
<P>
A second attempt, which was much more in line with international
trends began in the early 1980s when development aid was linked
to human rights and democracy. In 1982 the federal parliament
(Bundestag) stated in a unanimous resolution: &quot;ln its development
cooperation the Federal Republic of Germany regards the implementation
of human rights as an essential goal of the federal government...
those countries
should be especially supported, which try to establish democratic
structures... In states where despotism, intimidation and physical
threat characterize~the relationship between the governing and
the governed only those projects can be supported which benefit
directly the oppressed population.&quot;
<P>
Although two years later the Bundestag adopted again unanimously
guidelines for the federal government stating that the goal for
development cooperation should be to guarantee a life in dignity
(securing basic needs) and to contribute to a higher level of
civil and political rights in developing countries the ministry
for economic cooperation did not really react to these resolutions
and left the human rights policy to a large extent to the foreign
office.
<P>
It was only five years later, when political reforms in countries
with structural adjustment processes seemed to be unavoidable
and especially after the collapse of the socialist states in Eastern
Europe that political conditionality and &quot;help through intervention&quot;
were discussed in Germany. Finally in October 1991, the minister
of economic cooperation, Carl-Dieter Spranger, publicly announced
five criteria for German development cooperation: respect for
human rights, popular participation in the political process,
observation of the rule of law, market friendly approach to economic
development and the recipient government's commitment to development.
Thus the first three criteria constitute a clear political conditionality
based on the respect for human rights and an orientation towards
democracy.
<P>
<B>The administration of the political conditionality</B>
<P>
In order to ensure that the criteria were applied in the country
aid allocations the development policy section developed a
<P>
check list of indicators. As far as the first three human rights
related criteria were concerned it was made sure that all indica
tors were based on internationally codified UN human rights like
freedom from torture equality before the law or freedom of as
sembly so that no recipient country could object on the ground
of being subjugated to German standards. Also in this checklis
there is a clear distinction between the as sessment of the current
status of respect for human rights in a given country and the
tendency in the human rights performance which is considered even
more important.
<P>
The introduction of the human rights criteria for country allocations
also led to an increased support for human rights and democracy
projects, the so called &quot;positive measures&quot;. Especially
the foundations ol the major political parties but also church
organizations and other NGOs have a long tradition of projects
to strengthen the civil society of developing countries like support
for trade unions, chambers of commerce, human rights groups, etc.
Now the ministry also engages directly in such positive measures
like strengthening the legal system, demobilisation and reintegration
of soldiers (Mozambique, Uganda, Ethiopia, Nicaragua) or decentralisation
and communal development. The Foreign Office is converting a fund
which was formerly used for military aid and training of policemen
into a source for positive measures like supporting free elections,
consulting services for parliaments or seminars on democratic
constitutions.
<P>
The major administrative instrument for the implementation of
a human rights orientation is the country concept. There has been
a major effort to draw up such concepts for about 40 countries.
Besides the usual economic analysis they also have to deal with
social and political conditions and should explicitly refer to
the situation and trends in relation to the five criteria. The
country concepts are the basis for decisions in relation to country
allocations and serve as a basis for government to government
consultations.
<P>
A recent assessment of these concepts by the policy section of
the ministry revealed that the implementation of the new criteria
within the administration is quite a complicated process and will
take some time. It is however hoped that a series of internal
training workshops will improve the quality of the country concepts.
<P>
<B>Conditionality and the German public</B>
<P>
The reception of the new criteria for development aid in the German
public was very positive, the opposition in parliament could only
state that they would watch their implementation and even the
most critical NGOs did not reject the criteria but criticised
the double standards applied in their implementation. Even with
the &quot;ordinary voter&quot; not very much interested inThird
World affairs, this new policy was quite popular under the slogan
that no taxpayer's money should be given to dictators who oppress
their own people or to corrupt regimes, which use development
money for their private purposes. There was no criticism from
the private sector, as far as the general policy guidelines were
concerned, different interests of the business community were
however very relevant at the implementation stage in certain economically
important countries (see below the case of China).
<P>
<B>Some case studies</B>
<P>
As a human rights conditionality in German development cooperation
can only be observed since the announcement of the five new criteria
in October 1991 just a first tentative assessment of the implementation
of this new policy can he given. Already in the country allocations
for the 1992 budget there were a number of changes which exceeded
by far the usually very minor variations. Thus countries like
China, India, Indonesia and Pakistan saw their allocations substantially
reduced either because of human rights violations or because of
excessive arms spending. With Zaire, Malawi, Togo and Haiti development
cooperation was stopped because of very strong human rights violations
and obstruction of the process towards democracy.
<P>
On the other hand countries where civil wars had ended saw their
development aid resumed or newly started (Ethiopia, El Salvador,
Namibia) and countries that had implemented democratic reforms
like Benin, Zambia, Bangladesh, Nepal and Chile had their aid
allocations substantially increased. However for countries like
Turkey, where human rights violations continue and spending on
arms is high, allocations were not changed at all.
<P>
A very instructive case, which shows that aid conditionality can
work, is Kenya. When in 1990 and 1991 the opposition to the repressive KANU one-party
system was mounting and people were more and more demanding a
multi-party system and the respect for human rights, it was the
German ambassador together with his American colleague, who was
openly supporting the drive towards democracy and the application
of aid conditionality. Finally in November 1991 the Western donors
with the exception of France decided during a meeting of the Consultative
Group for Kenya to suspend any quick disbursing aid until the
multi-party system was reestablished, corruption was reduced and
economic reforms implemented.
<P>
Within a few days president Moi announced that article 2a of the
constitution declaring Kenya a one-party state would be abolished
and free elections be held. Although these elections were far
from being fair and although the KANU regime was able to stay
in power, there is no doubt that in comparison to the pre-1991
situation the human rights situation has improved considerably.
<P>
A very interesting case that shows the limits of applying conditionality
in development cooperation is China. After the massacre on the
Tianmen square in June 1989 the German Parliament decided unanimously
that development cooperation should be stopped with the exception
of projects &quot;that directly benefit the population&quot;.
On October 30, 1990 the Bundestag with the majority of the coalition
parties voted for a limited resumption of development cooperation
adding projects &quot;for the protection of the environment and
projects which contribute to the reform of the Chinese economy&quot;.
This change was justified with the necessity for protection of
the environment and with the constructive position of China in
the Iraq conflict.
<P>
Based on the amended resolution of the Bundestag minister Spranger
in November 1991 refused his signature for a special financial
arrangement for a contract for container ships which were to be
built in an EastGerman shipyard, because none of the exceptions
of the Bundestag resolution would apply. After continued criticism
from members of the coalition reflecting mainly massive economic
interests, the majority in the Bundestag in June 1992 cancelled
its resolution of October 1990 enabling the government to finance
the shipbuilding contract on preferential terms. The arguments
were that although the respect for civil and political rights
was very poor the improvement of economic and social rights was
very impressive, that economic reforms would eventually lead to
improvements in the human rights situation, that China was of
high security interest and that other countries were ready to
capture the big export contract. Although the ministry did reduce
its aid allocation for China by DM 40 million, major improvements
of the human rights situation could not be observed.
<P>
<B>Conclusions</B>
<P>
The major experience with the human rights conditionality in German
development cooperation was that this policy can be implemented
with good success in countries which depend heavily on foreign
aid and where economic and foreign policy interests are minimal.
There is little chance for success in economically important or
strategically interesting countries. This has led to severe criticism
in the German public accusing the government of &quot;double standards&quot;.
As a consequence greater &quot;coherence&quot; of all policies
towards developing countries is demanded, which means that development
policy should have a higher priority than economic or security
interests.
<P>
This demand, however, would have to be based on strong political
support in the German public and in important interestgroups.
Although development aspects have in general increased in importance
after the disappearance of the EastWest conflict, other interests
like preservation of jobs or economic development of Eastern Germany
have a much higher priority and will have higher priority for
quite some time.
<P>
The basic question is then: should one accept &quot;double standards&quot;
in relation to political conditionality and try to slowly increase
the number of countries where development orientation has highest
priority orshould one postpone in amore puristway the application
of a human rights oriented conditionality even in those small
countries where it is implementable and wait until such time when
human rights conditionality can be successfully introduced in
all countries? Since such a policy would be at the cost of potential
improvement of human rights and democracy in many countriesthe
answer that human rights and development oriented NGOs in Germany
give is to support the political conditionality where it is sincerely
applied and to to use the &quot;double standards&quot; argument
as political pressure to increase the application of political
conditionality in as many countries as possible.
<p>
<HR>
