<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 9 Friday 26 April 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1 PARLIAMENTARY AGENDA</B>

<P>

When the European Parliament meets in full plenary session on

20 to 24 May in Strassbourg they will find the agenda packed with

aid-related issues.  Included for discussion are

<UL>

<LI>The agreement for cooperation between the EU and MERCOSUR

<LI>A report on rehabilitation and reconstruction in developing

countries (already approved by the development committee this

week)

<LI>A report on the management of food aid and the development

of food security (already approved by the development committee

this week)

<LI>A report on humanitarian aid outside of the EU (already approved

by the development committee this week)

<LI>A communication from the commission to the parliament concerning

the future of economic aid to Jordan and the Ghaza strip

<LI>A report on the fisheries agreement between the EU and Mauritania

<LI>A report on aid for population programmes and policies in

developing countries

</UL>



<P>



<P>

<B>2 BANANAS ESCALATION OF THE CONFLICT</B>

<P>

Controversy still surrounds the commissions proposals for reform

of the banana importation quotas to take account of the accession

of Austria, Finland and Sweden to membership of the union.  The

commission has proposed that the quota be increased by 353,000

tonnes, and that this additional quota be given exclusively to

dollar banana importers.  This denies any of the new quota to

ACP producers and reduces the ACP share of the overall quota (2.553

million tonnes) from 30% to 26%.  The proposal has managed to

please no one.  For the Germans, who are supported by Belgium,

Denmark, Holland and Luxembourg, the increase in quota is not

enough.  They also want to see even more of the overall quota

going to cheap Latin American producers.  On the other side of

the argument, the UK, France, Spain and Portugal are fighting

to maintain the ACPs share of the banana quota.  

<P>

The stalemate is now overshadowed by the fact that the United

States, which has for a long time been complaining about the system

of preferences offered by the EU to ACP banana producers, has

started proceedings to refer the issue to a panel of the World

Trade Organisation.  The American complaint is similar to that

of the Germans.  They want to see a larger quota - up to 2.9 million

tonnes - and greater access for American producers.  Between the

German desire for cheap bananas and the American insistence of

access to the EU market, the ACP quota is looking increasingly

vulnerable.  Mickey Cantor, the United States Trade Representative,

is reported to be very confident of winning at least part of its

complaint.  This would leave the EU liable to pay compensation

to the USA if it did not comply with the ruling of the WTO panel.

<P>

<B>3 FUTURE OF LOME CONVENTION</B>

<P>

The discussions on the future of the Lom&eacute; Convention are

taking place in many different forums.  Some more open than others.

 On the weekend of May 4 to 5 a small group from DGVIII, the development

Commission of the European Union, will travel to Abidjan for a

48 hour informal discussion on what happens after 1999.  They

will spend their weekend in intense conversation with leading

members of the African business and political community in a spirit

of exploring all possible avenues.  Hopefully those of us who

are not members of such elite circles will have a chance to input

to the discussions before everything is signed and sealed.

<P>

<B>4 EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT DEVELOPMENT COMMITTEE</B>

<P>

The development committee of the European Parliament met in Brussels

this week for two days.  The committee adopted three major reports

on humanitarian aid, food security, and rehabilitation and reconstruction

<UL>

<LI>Humanitarian aid<BR>

The committee adopted the position of the council, which defines

the scope of humanitarian activities and the legal basis

<LI>Food Security<BR>

All food aid should seek to encourage the future self-sufficiency

of the populations in current need

<LI>Rehabilitation and Reconstruction<BR>

covering all areas of rehabiltation and reconstruction, which

should be seen as preparing the way for future development work

in the medium to long term

</UL>



<P>



<P>

Emma Bonino, Commissioner with responsibility for ECHO, spoke

to the committee.  In response to a question about ECHOs approach

to the question of women in emergencies, Ms Bonino said that ECHO

would be producing a report on the subject but that it would only

cover women in refugee situations.  

<P>

<B>5 RWANDA NEGATIVE NGO EVALUATION</B>

<P>

The Rwandan government's project to assess the work of all international

NGOs in Rwanda is nearing completion.  We have seen an early draft

of their report which takes a decidedly negative tone.  NGOs are

criticised for being wasteful, for not achieving their stated

objectives, and for working outside of the government structures,

particularly communal and provincial authorities.  Individual

NGOs are dealt with in detail in the report.  However, the quality

of the criticism is not always very high.  One NGO running a centre

for unaccompanied children is criticised for not sending a child

to a specialist hospital in USA where he could have undergone

intensive heart surgery.

<P>

The committee which produced the report contains a representative

from UNDP and from one international NGO.  However, the process

of research and reporting was largely dominated by the official

Rwandese members of the committee.  Given the recent history of

expulsion of NGOs from their operations in Rwanda, there is some

concern over the use which the RPF government will make of such

a negative report.  Meanwhile <I>Eurostep</I>'s own position paper

on the Great Lakes crisis will shortly be released, following

official endorsement.

<P>

<HR>



