<title>British ODA - Aid to Kurdish Villages</title>
<!!keys: ODA>
</head>
<body>

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="oda_info.html">  Overseas Development Administration</a></i><hr>


							

<h2>BRITAIN CONTINUES AID TO KURDISH VILLAGES IN NORTHERN IRAQ</h2>

<b>Britain is to provide an aid grant of £1.8 million to rehabilitate villages in Kurdish areas of northern Iraq.  The grant will enable Save the Children to continue their work with Kurdish families returning to their native villages. An estimated 4,000 villages have been destroyed in northern Iraq since 1975.</b><p>


The grant is designed to help villages become self-sustaining: services such as feeder roads, irrigation, drinking water, latrine blocks, schools and clinics will be provided.  Where appropriate flour mills, smithies and mechanical services will also be rehabilitated.  The project will target over 1,770 families, offering each family a voucher worth £150 to be exchanged against goods.  <p>


<h3>NOTE FOR EDITORS</h3>

The ODA's total expenditure on humanitarian aid to Iraqi civilians is over £70 million since April 1991.  This includes over £6.2 million to Save the Children for a variety of projects.<p>
