<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/ngdoc.gif" height=120> 
<H3>Liaison News: <BR>
NGO news on North-South action in the EU<BR>
No. 23, December 1996-January 1997</H3>
<H3>Role of NGOs in EU-decentralised co-operation: from a seminar to a newsletter<br>The seminar on decentralised co-operation, 6-7 December 1996</H3>
by <I>Debjani Das</I>
<p></CENTER><HR>
<I>More than sixty participants from 54 NGOs in 17 countries came together for two days (6-7th December 1996), to 
discuss among themselves and with members of the decentralised co-operation unit of the European Commission, the role of 
EU-NGOs in strengthening Southern partners in EU-decentralised co-operation. The following is an initial summary of 
its main conclusions, drawing from reports made during the seminar. A fuller report of the Seminar and related 
documentation can be made available upon request.</I>
<P>
<H4>Why the European Commission co-operates with NGOs</H4>
<P>
Does decentralised co-operation mean the same thing to its various 
proponents?
<P>
What should it achieve?
<P>
What are the central issues and dilemmas arising from present practice 
and recent tendencies?
<P>
In the introductory plenary session, dedicated to achieving theoretical 
clarity on the concept of EU- decentralised co-operation, Mr. 
Bernard Ryeland (head of the decentralised co-operation unit, DG VIII of the 
European Commission), recalled the reasons for the EC to sign a contract 
with the Liaison Committee on decentralised co-operation : to mobilise 
NGOs to identify possibilities of support for partners in developing countries, 
to identify political conditions and practical possibilities of intervention 
for NGOs and disseminate concrete procedures on the basis of on-going 
experiences.
<P>
Mr. Ryelandt described some typical cases of decentralised 
co-operation, and mentioned sources of financing, but emphasised that decentralised 
co-operation was not to be seen as a financial tool, but as a &quot;new 
developmental approach&quot; whose key element was grassroots democracy through 
a political and operational dialogue by decentralised agents with 
governments.
<p>
<H4>Issues raised by Southern NGOs</H4>
<P>
Panellists from southern NGOs (George Huggins, Nancy 
Kachingwe, F. Stephen), welcomed this new orientation in EU-co-operation 
towards democracy, and civil society participation in policy dialogue, but 
highlighted critical issues and dilemmas in implementation.
<P>
The changing State-NGO relations (from early &quot;hostility&quot; through a 
&quot;honeymoon&quot; to a more mature basis of critical co-operation) are a measure 
of the changing character of Southern NGOs towards more 
professionalism in service provision, with better 
organised community organisations - oft a product of earlier NGO efforts- 
taking over their earlier activist role.
<P>
Huggins resumed on the Caribbean context: &quot;genuine success&quot; in 
decentralised co-operation will depend on &quot;three inter-related actions&quot;: the 
service-delivery capacity of NGOs, State willingness to provide genuine 
space for NGO participation and EU ability to disseminate information on 
opportunities and resources and co-operate at a local level with NGOs and 
Governments.
<P>
How should bureaucrats be retrained into alternative management 
systems congruent with participatory value premises?
<P>
How should new interfaces(1 - The Commission uses the term &quot;interface&quot; for the co-ordinated structures or platforms within which the range of 
decentralised actors are represented. The existence of such an 
interface is a key condition for setting up a decentralised 
co-operation system -- see the LC Handbook on decentralised co-operation, 
page 28) be involved between civil society 
actors, State and international aid to ensure &quot;participatory&quot; and &quot;sustainable&quot; development? 
<P>
At which level should these interfaces be located and DC actors 
representative of civil society, across different levels, in contexts of conflicting 
agendas and unequal balances of power be identified and involved?
<P> &quot;How should identities be respected and power be shared without 
attempting to convert by allurement or intimidation or co-opt or steal?&quot; 
(P. Stephen)
<P>
Such questions raised at the beginning of the seminar underlined the 
complexities of translating a laudable theory into practice. Participants 
made a strong case for locating these issues in the international political context 
of &quot;globalised exclusion in the North and the South&quot; (P. Tilus), and structural adjustment-related weakening of Southern Governments, as well as 
within their local and regional specificities.
<P>
The seminar was a first step towards evolving coherent responses to 
these challenges.
<P>
<H4>Workshops: &quot;Models&quot; of EU-decentralised 
co-operation under the Lom&eacute; Convention</H4>
<P>
Through workshops on case studies centred on Zimbabwe, 
Senegal, Haiti and other country experiences, facilitated by inputs from 
resource persons from Southern as well as 
EU-NGOs, participants informed themselves on the state of the 
debate on decentralised co-operation in specific contexts and gained 
an understanding on the main issues facing NGOs, practical 
mechanisms in the preparation and setting up of a decentralised 
co-operation system, choices made, and the role of the &quot;interface&quot;.
<P>
The workshops provided a practical information basis on the functioning 
of decentralised co-operation in specific contexts, thus enabling an 
informed discussion on the potentials and constraints of decentralised 
co-operation as the EU-approach to participatory local development. They laid the 
basis for the plenary discussions on the following day on issues facing 
Southern NGOs, and consequences for EU-NGOs in general, and the 
Liaison Committee project on decentralised co-operation in particular.
<P>
<H4>Role of EU NGOs</H4>
<p>
The areas outlined below were identified in which the role of EU-NGOs 
in general and the Liaison Committee project in particular was discussed:
<P>
Sharing of knowledge, understanding and practices of 
decentralised co-operation from an &quot;NGO perspective&quot;, lobbying and 
advocacy, to facilitate dialogue. The specific value-added by EU-NGOs in 
general and the Liaison Committee project on decentralised 
co-operation in particular, lay in providing alternative information to 
official sources, and in communicating outcomes of discussion between the 
Liaison Committee and the European Commission to Southern decentralised 
co-operation actors; Capacity Building of Commission Staff, EU-NGOs, Southern 
Governments and Southern NGOs: While gender and 
centralisation-awareness training of official actors 
was considered crucial to the success of decentralised co-operation, 
this should arguably be undertaken by the Commission rather than the 
Liaison Committee. Capacity building in the South on the other hand 
should, where possible, be entrusted to local support organisations. 
EU-NGOs could play a liaison role in bringing Southern NGOs together to 
approach the EC for ensuring representativeness of the DC-interface and its 
accountability to civil society;
<P>
Evolving monitoring and evaluation systems and developing 
indicators for decentralised co-operation: here an emphasis was laid on 
linking NGO experiences in &quot;participatory development&quot;, &quot;institution 
building&quot;, &quot;NGO-State co-operation&quot; and 
&quot;partnership&quot; to EU-decentralised 
co-operation;
<P>
Notwithstanding the Liaison Committee's primary responsibility to 
the NGO-constituency, the need was stressed for a broad-based 
approach building bridges to other organised civil society actors.
<P>
In the midst of a plethora of suggestions concerning the role of 
EU-NGOs in strengthening their southern partners in decentralised 
co-operation, there was also awareness of the threat posed by the 
decentralised co-operation concept to EU-NGOs accustomed to 
working on a bilateral basis with Southern partners. Put on the defensive, 
EU-NGOs could take refuge in abstractions which did not touch their 
day-to-day work. This reinforced the need for clarity and credibility in 
the conceptualisation and implementation of decentralised co-operation. 
<P>
<H4>A mechanism for sharing information, and encouraging dialogue : The Newsletter on decentralised co-operation</H4>
<P>
Some of the needs articulated, such as the organisation of a 
seminar in the South on decentralised 
co-operation, the setting up of resource centres 
on decentralised co-operation, and capacity building of institutional actors 
cannot realistically be undertaken by the present Liaison Committee project 
on decentralised co-operation. During the next year, the project can however 
organise resource inputs from EU-NGOs when required, in seminars initiated 
in the South by Southern NGOs or other civil society organisations. The 
seminar was a major step in pooling such resources.
<P>
One of the principal mechanisms at the disposal of the Liaison 
Committee project on decentralised co-operation is a NEWSLETTER aimed 
primarily for circulation in the South. This should 
 facilitate dialogue and the sharing of experiences on decentralised 
co-operation among institutional actors, perceived by Southern and EU-NGOs 
as playing a crucial role for the success of decentralised co-operation. 
The newsletter will be launched in March. Six issues are planned on a 
quarterly basis.
<P>
<H4>How far can a newsletter function as a resource centre on decentralised co-operation?</H4>
<P>
The success of the Liaison Committee Newsletter project in 
evolving into a source of alternative information, policy discussion 
and exchange of experiences made in decentralised co-operation 
by NGOs in the South and the EU, with a broad base in civil society, 
will largely depend on the involvement of the 800 NGOs of the fifteen 
EU-platforms of the Liaison Committee, in identifying Southern NGOs 
and other partners to whom the newsletter should be initially sent, 
for feedback, evaluation or information.n
<P>
The organisers take this occasion to thank resource 
persons from GRET and CCFD (France), Movimondo (Italy), FES, EZE 
and DED (Germany), SNV, ICCO and ECDPM (NL), COTA (Belgium), 
as well as Mwengo (Zimbabwe), Search (India), Fonhsud (Haiti), 
SIC (Senegal), Proshikha (Bangladesh), the former 
co-ordinator from CPDC (Barbados), and the decentralised co-operation 
unit of the European Commission, for their contributions.
<p>
<H3><a href="../index.html">Liaison Committee Home Page</a></H3>
