<HEAD>
<title>Towards More Donor Coordination?</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<h3>Towards More Donor  Coordination?<br>OECD Prepares for 21st Century<P>
<i>Klemens van de Sand</i></h3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 5, September-October 1996: pages 22 - 25</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>In May 1994 the Working Group on Participatory Development
and Good Governance  established by the Development Assistance
Committee (DAC) of the OECD met for the  first time. Klemens van
de Sand, head of planning at the German Federal Ministry for 
Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ), was elected chairman.
The group  elaborated recommendations for a segment of its tasks
which were adopted at the DAC's  34th High Level Meeting held
in May this year. Van de Sand summarises the group's work  to
date.</B>
<P>
The industrial nation members of the  DAC have never lacked for
statements  on donor coordination. But practice at  developing
country level has often been  different. The sea change in  international
politics in 1989/90 at first  also made little difference to that
 situation. As the DAC's 1994 report  noted <a href="#1">(1)</a>, due to the dramatically
 worsening economic and budgetary  problems in all industrial
nations, &quot;the  commercial pressure on development  assistance
has in fact grown in recent  years&quot;, and thereby the competitive
 pressure on the donors.
<P>
Recently, however, the forces in the  OECD that oppose the overemphasis
of  national egotism in international  relations appear to be
gaining ground. In  contrast to the champions of an  undifferentiated
multilateral approach in  the  1970s and 1980s, they put their
faith  in a &quot;new global partnership&quot; <a href="#2">(2)</a> between  bilateral
and multilateral development  cooperation organizations and their
 government and NGO partners in the  developing countries.
<P>
The most recent expression of this  partnership approach was two
DAC  decisions at cabinet minister level (High  Level Meeting
of May 1996). These were  the report Shaping the 21st Century:
The  Contribution of Development  Cooperation <a href="#3">(3)</a>, and the Policy
Note on  Strengthening Country Level  Coordination for Participatory
 Development and Good Governance <a href="#4">(4)</a>.  The 22 DAC members documented
with  both declarations their will to define  more concretely
the goals and strategies  of development cooperation, and above
 all to coordinate its implementation  where it has practical
relevance:  in country.
<P>
<B>Development strategy for the 21st  century?</B>
<P>
Paradoxically, the new trend of  cooperation can be attributed
to the  same internal economic and budgetary  problems that have
also intensified the  competition among the industrial  nations.
<P>
Even more than the public scepticism  over development aid which
is  increasing everywhere, the funding crisis  that has led to
heavy cuts in development  budgets, above all in the USA, Canada
 and some Scandinavian countries, with  unforeseeable impacts
on the  multilateral system, has moved  development administrations
to reflect  on the future of their cooperation.
<P>
The report on the DAC's one year  <I>exercice de</I> <I>reflexion,
</I>as it was officially  called, contains some points that are
 definitely open to criticism. One may  doubt if it will live
up to its rather  high flown title, Shaping the 21st  Century.
It was, however, a remarkable  achievement that in a situation
which  shows crisis like tendencies, and not  only in the development
policy sector, the  industrial nations were able to agree on 
a comprehensive strategy paper  containing such trend setting statements
 as:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>
Despite disappointments, development policy is also a success
story. (As  proof, the report cites among other  things the &quot;green
revolution&quot;, the  decline in poverty, sickness and birth
 rates in many countries, and an  improved physical and social
 infrastructure.)<P>
<li>Despite foreign trade pressures, the donor community acknowledges
anew and with emphasis that reducing poverty is the paramount
goal of development  policy.<P>
<li>The DAC defines clear indicators  (standard of living,
literacy, access for  girls to the educational system, infant
 and maternal mortality) as the  yardstick of the success of 
development policy. (It thereby  distances itself from the prevailing
 focusing of the debate, including in  Germany, on quantitative
transfer  inputs, which ignores the qualitative  prerequisites
and criteria of success  for development processes.)<P>
<li>At the same time, the DAC  acknowledges the need for an
 &quot;appropriate and calculable&quot; financing,  particularly
in multilateral work, and an  increase in ODA volumes.<P>
<li>Partnership means mainly the  responsibility of the developing
 countries, but no shabby blaming them  for a lack of development
success. The  document emphasises the need for  political action
by the industrial nations  beyond development policy (debt  forgiveness,
trade, etc.).<P>
<li>Partnership and cooperation  presuppose reciprocal obligations
 based on fundamental values (human  rights, participation, social
justice,  protection of natural resources).</ul>
<P>
The entire paper is based on a simple finding: nothing helps development so
much as its success. True, conjured up appeals that it is a question of securing the
future for all people  that, of course, is also in the document  are essentially correct.
But they are obviously not enough to transform the public's lethargy
and scepticism into support for development policy. The
taxpayer must also be convinced that  development assistance works.
<P>
<B>Greater effectiveness by in-country  coordination</B>
<P>
The DAC's awareness that a quite  considerable potential for the
 much quoted &quot;increase of effectiveness&quot;  lies in improved
coordination was a  start point for its second decision, the  Policy
Note on Strengthening Country  Level Coordination for Participatory
 Development and Good Governance.  The document concretises the
strategy  paper in an essential area. Political  agreements between
the donors give  extra weight to their dialogues with the  partner
governments. Concentration and  division of labour tie up fewer
capacities  of all involved, and boost the impact of all  development
projects.
<P>
The background: the changed political  constellation at the beginning
of the   1990s allowed the conclusion to be drawn  that, first
and foremost, bad governance  was responsible for the wretched
 development in parts of Asia, in Latin  America, and above all
in Africa. Putting it  positively, the systems of government 
must be more efficient, more calculable,  more socially responsible
and thereby  more stable. State powers must be  divided and decentralised.
Because  these virtues are also prerequisites for  economic growth
and internal peace, the  German Minister for Economic  Cooperation
and Development (BMZ),  Carl-Dieter Spranger, in 1991 put into
 place the five most important general  development promoting conditions
as  criteria for applying development  cooperation instruments
and funds.
<P>
Right from the start, the BMZ pursued  the strategy of tackling
the reorientation  of development policy together with other 
donor countries instead of a national  go-it-alone. In that approach
it could count  on the commitment of the &quot;like-minded&quot;
 countries, especially in the Netherlands,  Scandinavia, Canada
and the USA. The  finding in the World Bank's Development  Report
of 1990 that reducing poverty was  above all a problem of the
political  balances of power in the developing  countries was
also trailblazing.  (Although in implementing this finding,  the
Bank was hampered not only by its  mandate as a finance institute,
but also   at any rate until James Wolfensohn  became its president
 by its staff's  &quot;economic&quot; orientation.)
<P>
In November 1991 the Council of  Europe drew up a Resolution on
human  rights, democracy and development that  largely corresponded
with the BMZ  criteria and the
conceptual reasoning behind them.  Among other things, at BMZ
pressure the  DAC paid more attention to this theme,  and in December
1993 adopted its  Orientations on Participatory  Development and
Good Governance  (PD/GG). This 30 page document  contains recommendations
for  development policy in the sectors: 1.  Participatory development;
2.  Democratisation; 3. Good governance  (including the rule of
law, public  accountability, control of corruption,  reduction
of excessive arms spending);  4. Human rights.
<P>
At the same time, the DAC High Level  Meeting commissioned a Working
Group  on Participatory Development and Good  Governance, which
was set up for an  initial three years, to process the DAC  members'
various experiences in these  sectors and deduce from them specific
 recommendations for development  cooperation. The working group
focused  on the following five subjects: the role of  civil society
in the democratisation  process; promotion of human rights;  judicial
reform; decentralisation and  &quot;local democracy&quot;; and
coordination  in country, as well as in the Consultative  Groups
(CGs) and Round Tables (RTs)  organised by the World Bank or UNDP.
 In the latter sector, the group completed  its work with the
Policy Note referred to  above.
<P>
<B>Joint country assessments as  basis for cooperation</B>
<P>
The Policy Note defined strengthening  the partner governments'
 self responsibility and promoting their  cooperation with civil
society  organisations (CSOs) as a general  objective for country
level coordination.  Thereby the DAC members assume that  improvements
of the political,  administrative and legal general  conditions,
in particular &quot;through  constructive dialogue rather than
the  adoption of absolute standards or  models&quot;, can be achieved.
<P>
The Policy Note adds that the  foundation for PD/GG discussions
 should be a process of in-country  assessment of the status of
PD/GG  issues as defined in the DAC  Orientations, and which focuses
on the  general conditions not covered by the  World Bank's country
reports. These  assessments should not be produced  solely by
donor organisations in the  developing countries, but together
with  independent research institutes,  especially from developing
countries.  The country assessments are then to be  discussed
with the government and  CSOs, &quot;including those representing
the  poor and less politically engaged, in  order to work out
strategies and support activities which could then be  incorporated in donor
programmes&quot;.
<P>
In countries where institutions and the  capacity to undertake
such reviews are  still lacking, the DAC members' priority  would
be to help build such capacity  both in government and civil society.
 Wherever possible, the members aim to  draw on the expertise
of other  developing countries that already have  the required
capacity.
<P>
<B>NGO networks in developing  countries</B>
<P>
On the need to build the capacity of the  CSOs, the Policy Note
takes up in  condensed form the demands of a  workshop on their
role in the  democratisation process which the  Scandinavian members
of the working  group held in Uppsala <a href="#5">(5)</a>:
<P>
<ul>
<li>In order to establish themselves as  dialogue partners
of not only their  governments but also the donor  organisations,
and influence general  conditions at the macro level, the  CSOs
in the developing countries  must do exactly what the German 
NGOs have just done with the founding  of VENRO (Association of
 Non Governmental Organisations):  build networks.
<P>
<li>The CSOs must determine their own  professional and ethical
standards  and legitimise themselves as  respectable cooperation
partners.
<P>
<li>The DAC members should help CSOs  to develop their professional
efficiency  and thus also their capacity for  dialogue, and share
expertise with  them. &quot; For example, interested donors  and
CSOs could establish  independent funds, managed  cooperatively,
for financing activities  such as information dissemination, 
networking, promotion of public  awareness, and training.&quot;
(This idea  had its origins in a fund set up by  Denmark in Eastern
Europe, but also  in elements of the &quot;self administered 
capital assets&quot; formula of German  Technical Cooperation.)</ul>
<P>
<B>Criteria for NGOs</B>
<P>
The building of networks and  elaboration of criteria for cooperation
 with and among NGOs has  this is  inserted here  played a major
role not  only in Uppsala, but, for example, also at  the BMZ-initiated
&quot;quadrilogue&quot; of  German and Ghanaian NGOs in Ghana
 in July 1995, as well as in Sri Lanka in  May 1996 at a conference
organised by  the Konrad Adenauer Foundation of  representatives
of NGOs, research  institutes and Southeast Asian  governments
on the status of  participation and poverty reduction in the 
policies of the SAARC governments. I regard this discussion as
 exceptionally significant and topical for  several reasons. Almost
all bilateral  donors, and not least also the World  Bank group,
provide more and more  funds for the promotion of the &quot;civil
 society&quot;. The &quot;Micro credit Summit&quot; next  year
is to muster further hundreds of  millions of dollars for this
sector.  Accordingly, NGOs are everywhere  shooting up like mushrooms.
Many are  founded by the established elite only in  order to secure
their accustomed  sinecures and &quot;mop up&quot; the flow of
 money diverted from the government  sector to the NGOs. On the
other hand,  there can be no doubt that in view of the  failure
of governments, new and dynamic  CSOs in many countries, above
all in  Africa and Latin America, offer new hope.  Their role
lies not only in assuming  substitute functions, but especially
in  organising the participation of the poor  and thus challenging
governments to  fulfil their core tasks. Ever more  governments
are responding to this  process of empowerment by attempting 
to regulate the CSOs' scope by laws and  decrees which go far
beyond the  legitimate interests of the state, and  binding NGOs
to activities which are in  accordance with the constitution and
 oriented to public well being. In this  ambivalent situation,
it is in the urgent  interest of not only the donor  organisations,
but also the NGOs, to go  on the offensive in countering the 
threatening degradation of promoting  development through CSOs.
<P>
The current status of the debate  suggests the following general
criteria  for the cooperation of NGOs, not only  among each other,
but also with donor  organisations:
<P>
<ul>
<li>independence from the government;
<P>
<li>democratic and transparent organisational structure;
<P>
<li>broad-based representation among the people;
<P>
<li>open membership;
<P>
<li>responsible, efficient management;
<P>
<li>clear and specific objectives; and
<P>
<li>readiness for cooperation and for  collaboration on structural
reforms.</ul>
<P>
These criteria are not to be treated as  absolute minimum standards,
but as  benchmarks subject to review which are  to be realised
in a dynamic process.  They are to be modified according to the
 type of organisation and purpose  involved or  for finance organisations,
 for example  widened. Thus features  such as &quot;broad-based
representation&quot;  and &quot;open membership&quot; have greater
 relevance for self-help organisations  than for intermediary service
or human  rights organisations.
<P>
With regard to participatory  development, the criterion &quot;readiness
for  cooperation&quot; is especially important. It  demands of
the NGOs that they review  their role in the development process
 and, if necessary, redefine it.  Consequently, the strategic
objective of  getting to grips with the structural  causes of
poverty applies also to the  work of the NGOs. It can then no
longer  be &quot;only&quot; a matter of implementing more  or
less isolated projects at the  micro-level and seeking to alleviate
the  symptoms and impacts of wrong  development. &quot;Social
mobilisation&quot; and  &quot;capacity building&quot; are not limited
to the   still important  task of strengthening  self-help forces
in a bid to satisfy  material needs. What is more important  is
seeing that the poor have influence on  political and economic
power structures.  Building networks and alliances of  NGOs facilitates
such influence, and by  bundling different interests creates more
 clout for the civil sector as a whole.
<P>
This &quot;pattern change&quot; in the NGOs  perception of development
presents an  enormous challenge, especially for  those of the
South. The work of classic  NGOs in many countries is still  characterised
by fragmentation, jealousies and rivalry, paternalism  and the
striving for dominance of more or  less charismatic leading personalities.
 But solidarity among NGOs is a must if  as the counsel for the
poor they want to  have a constructive influence on national 
development policies and oppose the  repression attempts of governments.
<P>
Equally, this principle  which is also  the basis of the Policy
Note  demands  changes in the attitude and behaviour of  the government
and NGO &quot;donors&quot; of the  North. Their current promotion
policies  are part of the problem. So long as the  NGOs of the
South are financially  supported on a narrow project basis,  they
must align their concepts and  organizational structures largely
ad hoc  on the implementation of individual  projects. This means
it is difficult for  them to develop into a driving force of 
structural changes. In this respect, the  innovative forms of
cooperation  addressed in the Policy Note are viewed  as very
important.
<P>
<B>Flexible process</B>
<P>
The Policy Note emphasises in  several places that the coordinating
 mechanisms in the PD/GG sector  should be flexible and adjusted
to the  conditions of each country. The  discussion on PD/GG matters
should be  integrated into existing in country  coordination forums,
such as those  already in place in a number of  countries on certain
sectors or general  conditions. These include strengthening  the
justice system in Haiti, important  political events such as elections,
or  implementing the peace agreements in  El Salvador and Mozambique.
According  to the respective political conditions,  coordinating
bodies could be set up  alternatively or cumulatively between
the  various actors. Between donor-country  embassies and development
 cooperation offices, between donors and  partner governments,
between donors  and CSOs, and  wherever possible   between donors,
governments and  CSOs of the partner country. The Policy  Note
says the primary role of in country  donor groups would be to facilitate
 PD/GG through promotion of dialogue,  exchange of information
and  coordination of external support with  partner country institutions
and groups. It  adds that in polarized situations the  group would
be a donor reference point  for the factual basis of significant
 incidents, thus contributing to  appropriate donor reactions
to political  trends and events.
<P>
However, flexibility does not mean  do-as-you-please. If governments
 adamantly refuse to talk about general  conditions and
participation of CSOs, that will impact on the extent and type
of cooperation on offer to  them. In this respect, the objectives
of country  level coordination (strengthening the self responsibility
and cooperation of CSOs) also imply the conditionality of promotion.
<P>
 <B>Coordination with the World Bank and UNDP</B>
<P>
One of the Policy Note's main concerns is the meshing of the in country
coordination  process with the World Bank's Consultative  Groups
(CG) and the UNDP's Round Tables  (RT). On behalf of the working
group, the DAC  Secretariat evaluated all meetings of the CGs
 and a number of those of the RTs from 1990  on the basis of how
they had handled  problems in the sectors of human rights,  democratisation
and the rule of law. The  finding was ambivalent. On the one hand,
 obstacles to development in the sectors of  human rights and
general conditions were  discussed at almost all meetings, including
 those with Asian countries. On the other hand,  this took place
as a rule without systematic  preparation and follow up. So the
successes  of the donors' united actions, such as the  removal
of the dictatorships in Zambia and  Malawi, and in the peace process
in El  Salvador, remained exceptions rather| than the rule. Especially
recently, complaints have mounted from participants, including
German delegates, that the formal sessions of some CGs are increasingly
 rigidifying into rituals. They also  complain that the informal
meetings on  political and legal general conditions are  surprised
by individual participants with  uncoordinated
 ventures, so that a well founded dialogue  targeted on results
is hardly possible.  The DAC members aim to remedy this  situation.
The Policy Note says: &quot;In view  of the vital connection between
PD/GG  and sustainable development, the  importance of PD/GG in
donors' aid  allocation decisions, and experiences in  recent
CG and RT discussions, DAC  members support, as a medium term 
objective, the systematic treatment of  these issues in CGs and
RTs in a  manner suited to their nature and  importance in each
specific country  context.... Broad-based, in country  consultations
... could lead to the  identification of actions and  commitments
on the part of the partner  country and its donors and of points
 under active debate to be addressed as  a matter of priority.
Presentations (of the  findings) could be made to the plenary
of  the CG or RT meeting by lead speakers  participating in the
in country process.  The output of the CG or RT meeting should
 be monitored through in country  coordination mechanisms and reviewed
 in the next CG or RT meeting.&quot;
<P>
At the High Level Meeting,  UNDP Administrator Gus Speth and the
 World Bank representative emphatically  backed these recommendations.
 However, the World Bank pointed out that  because of its statutes
it had problems  in chairing CG meetings when human  rights issues
were raised as separate  agenda points. In the view of the working
 group, this problem should be resolved  by the participants from
case to case. As  a rule, this can be done by framing the  agenda
adequately (&quot;Good governance&quot;  comes indisputably within
the World  Bank's mandate!). If necessary, a  bilateral donor
could take over the chair  for a time.
<P>
<B>Step-by-step implementation</B>
<P>
The Policy Note's findings,  recommendations and decisions are,
of  course, at the moment only on paper.  True, the DAC members
in Paris  reached consensus at High Level. But  that does not
mean the many sceptics in  the donor capitals and embassies, who
 can cite the practice that has prevailed to  date, no longer
have to be convinced.  One may certainly have doubts about the
 extent to which the in country donor  offices can provide sufficient
qualified  staff to meet the additional requirements.  (The DAC's
&quot;exams&quot; have for years rightly  criticized Germany in
particular for not  staffing its embassies with the right  numbers
of development officers!)
<P>
The goal of achieving binding  agreements in the sector of political,
 legal and administrative general  conditions through institutionalized
 dialogue is certainly ambitious. However,  it appears realizable
if donors proceed  pragmatically, flexibly and at the same  time
systematically, in line with the  recommendations. The DAC intends
to  begin the coordination process at first in  some pilot countries.
Individual donors,  including Germany, have said they are  prepared
to assume ultimate  responsibility for them.
<P>
It also sounds optimistic that the new  trend to coordination
will not be limited to  the OECD. At Germany's suggestion, the
 EU and its members are also testing  systematic and binding forms
of  operational coordination in six pilot  countries. These, however,
relate to  sectors and regions, not general  conditions. The World
Bank is organizing  sectoral investment programmes to be  implemented
by partner governments  and several donors. The particular  appeal
of these programmes is that without coordination they would in
no way  come about. (Thereby, however, the  political and administrative
 preconditions must not be overlooked   as has happened with many
structural  adjustment programmes!)
<P>
Not least, the DAC's decision on joint  assessments of general
conditions and  agreement on reform steps can  contribute to preventing
armed conflicts.  Political and social events will inevitably
 be much more transparent if there is  regular communication between
the  relevant government and social forces.  There will then be
no need to rack one's  brains over new early warning systems.
<P>
Regular communication delivers a  harmonized donor information
base.  That creates the basis for joint strategies  to handle
threatening crises. (Not least,  that was lacking in, for example,
Rwanda  and Burundi!) The Policy Note implies  this point without
going into further  details. The international forum on  Development
Cooperation as Preventive  Peace Policy, organized by the German
 Foundation for International  Development (DSE) and BMZ in Berlin,
 April 912 this year, gave it more tangible  form. The forum recommended
that not only partner governments, but also  opposition leaders
and relevant social  organizations, should be tied in to the 
consultations on crisis prevention.  Together with them, attempts
must be  made from case to case to reach  agreements on specific
measures, and  the monitoring of them. International  conferences
on preventing or mediating  in conflicts would take on a new quality
if  they could fall back on such a  consultation process. This
would apply  both to the preparation and the  implementation of
the findings.
<P>
To return to the opening question, the  conceptional prerequisites
for greater  efficiency in development cooperation  and more joint
action by the donors are in  place. The core of this concept of
 &quot;operational participation&quot; is that  cooperation between
governments and  civil society organizations based on  equality
is an essential element for  structural changes, in both the social
 and government sector. A new quality of  cooperation and partnership
must now  manifest itself in concrete and continual  steps in
in country practice.
<P>
<b>Notes</b>
<P>
<a name=1></a>1.OECD/DAC: Development Cooperation, Paris 1994, p.28
<P>
<a name=2></a>2. See OECD/DAC: Development Partnership in the New Global  Context,
Paris, draft 24.4.1995, 4pp., DCD/DAC (95)3/rev.3 
<P>
<a name=3></a>3. OECD/DAC: Shaping..., Paris 2.5.1996, 23pp., DCD/DAC (96)1 5/rev.1
<P>
<a name=4></a>4. OECD/DAC: Policy Note..., Paris, 13.5.1996, 7pp., DCD/DAC (96)1
 4/rev.2
<P>
<a name=5></a>5. Report on the Uppsala Workshop on Civil Society and  Democracy,
Paris, 24.11.1995, 41pp., DCD/DAC/PDGG (95)2
<p>
<HR>
