<HEAD>

<TITLE>Some Lessons from the Luxembourg experience</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>Some Lessons from the Luxembourg experience</H3>

<P>
by <I>Gaston Stronck</I> 
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:
pages 10-11</I> </CENTER><HR>

<H4>Historical Setting</H4>

<P>
Luxembourg is a founding member of a number of international organisations
-- e.g. Benelux and the European Union (EU) in the economic field
and WEU and NATO in the political field. The impact of these regional
institutions on the content of national policies has increased
enormously over the half century since the end of the Second World
War. As a consequence Luxembourg has had to establish both formal
and informal administrative processes to ensure that it participates
effectively in the determination of regional policies and their
implementation.
<P>
The Luxembourg experience is presented neither as a model nor
as a set of solutions for implementation in other countries. It
is nothing more than one experience among many. However other
countries may find some elements of the experience to be interesting
and relevant as they confront similar problems.
<H4>Impact on Determination of Regional Policies</H4>

<P>
The potential for any one country to control, or even influence,
regional policy will be limited. It is clear that small countries
such as Luxembourg are likely to carry less weight than larger
countries. Nevertheless this constraint can be reduced if governments
of small countries show genuine commitment to regional objectives
or if they play an active role in the discussion and determination
of regional policies in general or of those policies in which
they have a particular interest. 
<P>
What undermines the ability of any country to have an impact on
regional policies, is when its government is unable to concentrate
on these policies because its concerns are overwhelmingly on domestic
political problems or because it faces strong opposition from
key domestic interest groups.
<P>
The impact of a country on regional policy is also significantly
influenced by the extent to which its government has organised
itself for this purpose. This applies to the establishment of
a capacity to undertake policy analysis, to the development of
effective decision-making processes within government, and to
the creation of a capacity to participate actively in regional
decision-making.
<P>
Having said this, it will be apparent that one general conclusion
of this paper which can be anticipated right now, is that the
national management of regional relations does not differ basically
from normal national management of domestic affairs. If the administrative
system to manage domestic policy is lacking in quality and performance
it cannot be expected that it will be any better in managing regional
policy. Presented more positively, what the paper also concludes
is that a well organised, efficient and motivated national administration
should have no difficulties in coping with the management of regional
cooperation.
<H4>Policy Analysis and Policy Decision-Making</H4>

<P>
The ability to participate effectively in regional decision-making
will depend on adequate preparatory work having been under- taken
within the national administration and on the subsequent effectiveness
of procedures within the administration for reaching agreed policy-decisions
on regional issues. Several factors are important in this regard:
<UL>
<LI>Civil servants can only operate efficiently if they have general
guidelines on policy which are defined at the highest political
level.
</UL>

<P>
 
<UL>
<LI>The clear division of responsibilities between ministries
has to be respected by civil servants. This is particularly important
when these divisions have arisen out of the political negotiations
lying behind the formation of coalition governments.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>A high degree of delegation of power from the political level
to the administration.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Coherence in the administrative apparatus which, in its turn,
requires a high degree of administrative tradition and culture.
This cannot, of course, be established in the short run. 
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Although it is developed as a continuous process, it is not self-generating.
It emerges from continuous attention by governments and senior
civil servants acting in a professional manner. It then requires
determined action in the light of experiences.
<UL>
<LI>Coordination, both formal and informal, is necessary, and
this must be based on a good flow of information. Formal mechanisms
of coordination are necessary but are sometimes too slow and cumbersome.
Thus the crucial importance of informal coordination has to be
stressed and civil servants educated and encouraged to use these
informal procedures.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Where coordination fails to lead to agreement, a process is
required to resolve internal conflicts with credible mechanisms
of arbitration.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>As far as possible, there should be similarity between administrative
procedures at the national and at the regional levels.
</UL>

<P>

<H4>Participation in Regional Decision-Making</H4>

<P>
However efficiently national analytical work and decision-making
might be undertaken, to be effective there must be a capacity
to negotiate effectively at the regional level. The following
factors are important in this regard:
<UL>
<LI>There needs to be excellent knowledge of the institutional
and procedural setting of the regional organisations. For instance,
of particular importance for a member of the European Union is
whether on any issue decision is by majority vote or whether a
veto power exists. If it is the former then concessions and compromises
might be preferable to being out-voted. While a veto power in
principle confers more power on each country and especially on
small countries such as Luxembourg, in practice too frequent a
use of this power will weaken goodwill towards a country and thereby
damage its own long-term interests.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The quality of national administrators in negotiation skills
and techniques is important. Regional negotiations involve extensive
tactical manoeuvring and are typically focussed on technical matters
rather than on issues of broad policy. The competence of individual
negotiators varies not so much between states as between individual
representatives.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Efficient networking between those at the interface between
national and regional bodies. Every civil servant should know
his counterparts in the regional system. In the European Union
regular attendance at meetings of the Council and of the Commission
facilitates this process.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The development of efficient procedures to link the national
administration to the regional organisation. Significant variations
exist in the ways in which governments attempt and are able to
control their inputs into the regional cooperation system. Some
countries, such as Luxembourg, allow their representatives to
work in a fairly loose framework. Other states tend to be reluctant
to negotiation on policy issues below ministerial level. In the
European Union, the permanent representation in Brussels has to
play a key role and with the growth of the workload these mechanisms
have to be constantly improved.
</UL>

<P>

<H4>Implementation of Regional Policies</H4>

<P>
Decision made at the regional level which are not then implemented,
make no sense. Several factors are important in this regard:
<UL>
<LI>The political commitment to regional decisions perhaps disregarding
the more 'technical' details.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Flexibility and loyalty to decisions at the administrative
level by those managing regional cooperation.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Adequate instruments and means to implement regional decisions.
Implementing European Union regulations and directives requires
appropriate administrative skills and in certain circumstances
financial means.<P>
<LI>Coordination through a well organised flow of information.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Systematic and institutionalised monitoring and control of
implementation including recognition of the timetable agreed at
regional level.
</UL>

<P>

<H4>Concluding Comment</H4>

<P>
In the case of Luxembourg, regional cooperation has created no
major change in the style of administrative behaviour because
working with different levels of autonomous decision-centres was
already a central part of the daily life of civil servants. Also
a general openness toward partners, governmental or social, as
well a predisposition to seek a consensus and avoid deep conflicts,
is part of the Luxembourg administrative style which has easily
been applied to the requirements of regional cooperation. A high
degree of administrative skill and experience, including a sufficient
degree of flexibility enables the Luxembourg administrators to
digest the acts of regional cooperation.
<P>
In addition, these administrators are being pushed to modify their
institutional processes by the environment in which they work.
The political leadership and economic and social interests in
regional cooperation also influence them. These interests have
access to information on regional issues and dispose of 'sanctions'
such as the courts or public opinion.
<P>
Thus both the internal motivation of administrators and the environment
in which they work create a dynamic situation which ensures that
they are always digesting new regional issues in an effective
manner. 
<P>
To conclude where we began. The requirements for effective national
institutions to manage regional cooperation do not differ basically
from those required to manage domestic policies. A well-organised,
well-trained and well-motivated national administration should
have no difficulties in managing regional cooperation.<HR>

<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <I>Updated on
April 15, 1996</I></H6>

