<html>
<title>A Governance Approach to Civil Service Reform</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg">
<p>
A Governance Approach to Civil Service Reform:<br>Notes from a Consultative Meeting,
Maastricht, 27-28 June 1994</h3>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: page 7</i>
</center>
<p>
<hr><p>
Immediately before its 1994 Round Table, ECDPM and the World Bank's Africa Technical
Department organised a meeting
of senior public servants from Ghana, Guinea, Tanzania, and Zambia. They examined the utility
of the 'Governance
Approach to Civil Service Reform' proposed by the World Bank; and reviewed the effectiveness
of Institutional
Environmental Assessment (IEA), as used in the Gambia, in relation to their own reform
programmes.
<p>
Among other things, discussions focused on two essential processes. First, the process by which
external agencies
and host governments consult on the adoption of the governance approach; and second, the
process by which host
governments consult with other actors and stakeholders in promoting the use of the approach.
<p>
<h3>Donor - Government Consultation</h3>

It was stressed that careful sensitisation is needed before adopting the approach. In ongoing
reform initiatives, the
approach may help energise and give new direction to the reform process, but its methodology
cannot be imposed,
especially from the outside. In the process, consultation is used to build ownership, and a sense
of shared conviction
between donor and recipient, rather than a sense of imposed conditions from outside. Ghana's
present reform
programmes were cited as an example of partnership where the donor community - in this case
the World Bank -
provided expertise on techniques and approaches but were kept at 'arms-length.' Ultimately, it
is planned that the
Bank, acting as a facilitator, will gradually work itself out of a job.
Consultation between Governmental Institutions and Stakeholders
<p>
Participants emphasised that consultation between donor and government is not in itself
sufficient to secure
acceptance of a reform process. To build consensus and support, it is essential to ensure
understanding and
acceptance of the approach within the country -- at both political and administrative levels.
<p>
Politicians should be fully sensitised on the nature of the governance approach. This avoids
possible rejection, allays
fears they may have, and allows facilitators to anticipate necessary modifications. It is also
important to ensure that
different parts and levels of the public service are involved in elaborating the approaches to be
used -- since they are
most affected by changes, and most involved in their implementation.
<p>
It was stressed also that the general public needs to be aware of the implications of reform,
especially where
significant retrenchment is likely. Consultation and debate is particularly important where
extended families depend
on family members employed in the public sector.
<p>
Finally, it was considered necessary that reforms are designed within a broader social and
economic context in which
negative outcomes of reform, such as unemployment, can be dealt with.
<p>
Further information on the meeting is available from Ms. <a href="mailto:jc@ecdpm.org">Joan
Corkery</a>, ECDPM, O. L. Vrouweplein 21, 6211 HE 
Maastricht, the Netherlands.

<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a> <i>Updated on February 19, 1996</i><br>
Copyright is held by the European Centre for Development Policy
Management.  Users are encouraged to make single copies of any document for non-commercial
purposes.<p>
