</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Technical Cooperation between  Sustainability and Significance</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Technical Cooperation between  Sustainability and Significance<p>
<I>Wolfgang Hillebrand, Dirk Messner and J&ouml;rg Meyer-Stamer</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 2, March-April 1995: pages 8-12</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>The general objective of development cooperation, to provide help
for self help, means for Technical Cooperation (TC) above all improving
the capacity of the partner countries to solve problems. Ways
of further developing the concepts and instruments to be applied
to this end have long been discussed at international and national
levels. The need for a reorientation of TC has in particular become
clear in the deliberations of the OECD's Development Assistance
Committee (DAC) since the end of the 1980s.</B>
<P>
The thrust of the principles developed by the DAC for such a realignment
is clear <a href="#1">(1)</a>. The most important headings are: orientation on the
concept of sustainable development; stronger orientation on the
partners; subsidiarity; forming points of main effort in the areas
of institutional development/strengthening of management capacities
in the public and private sectors/human resources development;
stronger orientation on strategy and programmes instead of individual
projects; emphasis on an effective and efficient use of funds;
and improving coordination among the multiplicity of donors and
aid organisations.
<P>
These guidelines also largely define the framework for a further
conceptional development of German TC. This and the following
article on this crucial problem area will illustrate how important
 but also how difficult  it is to take the route recommended by
the DAC. Upfront is one question: to what extent is the call for
a stronger orientation on strategy and programmes  thus a TC aligned
on broad impacts or significance  compatible with the demand for
a TC that is also sustainably effective.
<P>
<B>Sustainability in development cooperation</B>
<P>
The professional development policy debate of recent years has
above all paid great attention to the criterion of sustain&quot;ability. This has been related not only to the development process
as a whole, but also to project oriented cooperation. With regard
to the project level, one can see that the results of the discussions
have been used above all, and rightly so, to further define the
requirements for effective project planning and implementation.
<P>
Monitoring of impacts over many years has in particular shown
that TC projects up to their handover have a chance to achieve
their targets and have sustainable impacts precisely if:
<P>
<ul>
<li>the general political, legal, economic, sociocultural and
institutional framework conditions which impact on the project
are favourable, or that the project  within the bounds of necessity
 can influence them;
<li>the project is placed with an executing agency which is
either already motivated and efficient, or can be sufficiently
strengthened by the project; here it is of crucial importance
to achieve a partnership cooperation, involving a step-by-step transfer
of responsibility to the project executing agency;
<li>the target group is tied in closely to the project in both
the planning and implementation phases;
<li>the resources available to the project are realistic in
terms of its target;
<li>a realistic, i.e. not too short, time horizon is foreseen
for implementing the project;
<li>the qualifications of the German and local project staff
are up to the task.</ul>
<P>
The intensive discussion on sustainability has above all made
clear that in the final analysis sustainable project impacts
are achievable if an effective project planing and implementation
is ensured.
<P>
<B>Different concepts of sustainability</B>
<P>
There is, however, in no way unanimity on the definition of sustainability.
Thus, a cross section analysis by the Federal Ministry for Economic
Cooperation and Development on the sustainability of TC projects
discusses three different concepts of it:
<P>
<ul>
<li>sustainability exists when the targeted project impacts
remain robust for the target group after the project has been handed
over to them;
<li>sustainability is not determined by what is preserved from the
project but by what the project gets under way;
<li>sustainability can also be achieved when, first, horizontal
spill overs from the project occur in neighbouring regions/sectors,
or, secondly, the project idea or approach takes root at a higher
decision level as the basis or part of national standards or national
policies and thus assumes the role of a model.</ul>
<P>
Under the conditions of a rapidly changing project environment,
the first definition is in many cases too narrow. Just as during
a project's life cycle its goal and targeted output must often
be adjusted to a changed environment, this is also mostly required
after the end of the project. Therefore it is precisely those
projects that have enabled the executing agency independently
to adapt the project conception to changing framework conditions
which should be rated as sustainable.
<P>
The gist of the third definition addresses the broad impact of
projects, and is therefore too wide. Even projects with modest
objectives and small impacts, but which the executing agency can
continue or develop further on its own bat, are to be identified
as sustainable. The two dimensions of sustainability and broad
impact should therefore be analytically carefully held apart,
and sustainability understood in the sense of the first two definitions.
<P>
<B>Neglected criterion of significance</B>
<P>
In view of the developmental stimulus, however, it is not sufficient
to ensure that a project will be implemented effectively and sustainable
impacts are achieved. Indeed, the decisive question is not whether
a project makes some contribution to solving one of many problems.
Rather, it is about to what extent a project, or a bundle of projects,
makes a significant contribution to solving a problem that in
the context of a specific development strategy is recognised as
particularly urgent. The question of significance thus asks to
what extent project successes are converted into palpable development
stimuli and successes. This is the case when a project:
<P>
<ul>
<li>has broad impact, e.g. it triggers tangible stimuli in
a sectoral or regional context;
<li>or contributes to structure building, e.g. it supports important structural reforms or deepens interlinkage
between institutions or government and nongovernment actors;
<li>or has a model character, i.e. it can be replicated in
other sectors or regions.</ul>
<P>
Of the total of 26 projects we included in a series evaluation,
only a few met one of these requirements. In other words, the
criterion of  &quot;significance&quot; was hardly explicitly made
an agenda, although we tried to consider only such projects whose
conception suggested they had potential for significance.
<P>
<B>Demands on significant projects</B>
<P>
Projects planned to develop significant impacts, however, make
particularly high demands on the process of project identification,
planning and implementation.
<P>
First, particularly in countries with a low development level,
one cannot as a rule presume that they have sufficiently favourable
framework conditions. Rather, these must be co designed by the
projects.
<P>
Secondly, in projects with sectoral and/or regional broad impacts
or model character, an efficient executing agency or a strong
executing organisation structure must often be built up first.
<P>
Thirdly, it is not sufficient to optimise the internal structure
of a project; rather, this must be purposefully and actively embedded
in the sectoral and/or regional context.
<P>
Next, orientation on significant projects requires every time
more intensive cooperation between the recipient and donor countries,
as well as better harmonisation among the donors. The latter is
above all necessary so that development cooperation makes a sustainable
and significant contribution to strengthening the capability of
the national actors in the partner countries to draw up strategies.
<P>
Finally, the demands on project planning and the project management
generally grow in line with the increasing complexity of a project.
<P>
<B>Sustainability versus significance?</B>
<P>
In the most extreme case it is possible to achieve sustainable
project impacts (e.g. an installation in a permanently functionable
university laboratory), without contributing significantly to
solving the real problem (e.g. covering the most urgent research
needs of the most important target group, putting in place close
interaction between R&amp;D and application).
<P>
Thus, &quot;project islands&quot; not interlinked with their environment
can definitely be sustainable. Evaluations of sustainability in
agricultural projects found, in fact, that &quot;projects with
high sustainability were almost exclusively monocausal ones: the
more modest they were, the greater impact they had&quot;.
<P>
The same goes for the trend that, particularly in a turbulent
and inefficient environment, sustainability is easier to achieve
in projects with marginal impacts than in those aimed at significance,
or influencing and changing the environment.
<P>
The following conclusions arise from these considerations:
<P>

<ul>
<li>Sustainability and significance will often have a tense
relationship. On the one hand, sustainability is the prerequisite
for significant project impacts. A project that founders cannot
be significant. On the other hand, sustainability is apparently
easier to achieve in less complex, more modest projects than in
those targeted on significance. If the sustainability of TC projects
is to be seen as the most important criterion of success, demanding
and thereby risky  projects will be more likely to be passed up.
The effect of that would be that sustainable projects would contribute
only marginally to solving social and economic development problems.
Thus, in developmental terms, it does not make sense to resolve
the tension between significance and sustainability by rejecting
demanding projects;
<li>The criteria significance and sustainability relate to
very different dimensions of the developmental effectiveness of
projects. Accordingly, both criteria must every time be explicitly
considered in the project cycle.</ul>
<P>
<B>Resolving the tension zone</B>
<P>
In view of the relevance of both significance and sustainability
for development cooperation planning practice, it is important
to come to a balanced relationship between them. That presupposes
in particular that the greater risks linked with more complex
projects can be effectively limited and controlled.
<P>
Limiting the sustainability risk requires on the one hand attention
criteria which today are seen as essential for effective and efficient
project planning and implementation (see above). Further important
 starting points, in order to reduce the  risks of failure of
significant projects, are  above all the purposeful use of  orientation
phases and an  unambiguous establishment of key  areas of bilateral
TC.
<P>
Given the prerequisites identified  above, the tension inherent
in a TC  focused on both significance and  sustainability appears
to be largely  manageable. In this respect, it is time for  the
criterion of significance to be seen as  equally crucial in project
selection as  effectiveness and sustainability.  Specifically,
this means:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Orientation on significance at  individual project level: Seen
from the  developing country, the main problem is  not to acquire
as many effective  development projects as possible.  Rather,
it is about how individual project  successes can be transformed
into  tangible &quot;systemic&quot; development  successes. This
question particularly  applies to the few developing countries
 in which there is no lack of effective  projects of the international
donor  community. Nevertheless, the  developmental contribution
of the  manifold project activities is limited, and  in fact above
all because the projects  often integrate into their environment
only  very insufficiently. Therefore the more  relevant developmental
question of a  project's possible contribution to  structure building
in an important area  must be moved front and centre. The still
 frequent practice of overemphasising  the internal perspectives
of  often small   projects must be overcome.
<P>
<li>System promotion: The ultimate  answer to ensuring significance
in an  inefficient but important sector would be  to abandon point for point
approaches in  favour of promoting a  programme related structural
reform of  broad TC impact. A system promotion  which built on
harmonised promotional  instruments would be conceivable. As far
 as possible at the same time, the  following should be targeted:
<P>
<ul>
<li>
horizontal interlinkage of individual projects;
<li>vertical interlinkage of projects at different levels,
e.g. of projects to promote  institution building with consultancy
 measures at the system level.</ul>
<P>
The objective of implementing  structure building projects that
are as  significant as possible and purposefully  integrated in
their environment leads to  the question of how, beyond the  classical
promotion of an executing  agency, other local institutions or,
in fact,  executing organisation structures can be  strengthened.
Such attempts to enhance  the capability for social self organisation
 are demanding. In the light of the initial situation, which as
a rule is  characterised by a low efficiency of the  relevant
intermediary government and  private institutions and weak interaction
 between them, such projects are above  all successful if:
<P>
<ul>
<li>a realistic specification of costs and  quantities is taken
as a basis, and, if  necessary, TC and Financial  Cooperation
(FC) are combined;
<li>a sufficient time horizon is planned;
<li>and, as far as possible, a continuous  and spreading transfer
of knowhow  from Germany is organised, s&ugrave;ch as  by the
promotion of partnerships,  cooperation agreements between  important
institutions or scholarship  programmes.</ul>
<P>
When such projects are successful  they can make an important
contribution  to increasing problem solving capacities  in a sector
or region. Projects which are  to carry out moderating and interlinkage
 functions, without enough efficient actors  already on hand,
are less successful.  Projects aligned on interlinkage  presuppose
more or less stable  framework conditions in the respective  sector
and require actors capable of  drawing up strategies.
<P>
Bad experiences in cooperation with  less efficient government
institutions led  recently to a reorientation in selecting  project
executing agencies. Preference  is now given to working with NGOs.
 However, hopes of being able to  substitute weak government institutions
 by mobilising social actors overlook the  fact that durable development
remains  dependent upon both, as well as the  building up of stable
framework  conditions. Projects aiming at  significance should
take account of this  correlation.
<P>
<li>Setting of key areas: These  considerations suggest a clear
setting of  key areas for German TC. Only a  long term commitment
in, say, two or  three policy fields or sectors instead of  scattering
project activities over many  sectors:
<P>
<ul>
<li>enables the accumulation of sectoral  knowhow on the German
side which  facilitates the embedding of individual  measures
in the project environment;
<li>permits the supplementing and  combining of different instruments
and  thereby the creation of synergy effects;
<li>contributes through continuous  cooperation with the recipient
side to  strengthening national actors'  capacities to draw up
strategies;
<li>strengthens the know-how and donor  profile of the German
side, and allows  the elaboration of project modules  which can
be replicated in other  countries;
<li>facilitates coordination of donors;
<li>reduces administrative effort on the  German side;
<li>enhances transparency on the recipient side.</ul>
<P>
<li>Development of a pronounced  German offer profile: The required
 establishment of key areas should  consciously be carried out
mainly in  fields in which, compared with other  donors, the German
side has special  strengths in offers, i.e. &quot;comparative
ad  advantages&quot;. These include in particular  those areas in
which exemplary  structure have been created in  Germany, so that
by international  comparison German policies,  institutions, instruments
and human re  sources exhibit special efficiency. That  applies
to such important fields as dual  vocational training, MSTQ (metrology,
 standardisation, testing and quality  assurance environmental
technology  and policies, industry related R&amp;D and  use of
productive forms of cooperation  between the government, the private
 sector and social group (public-private  partnership) within the
framework of  economic policies which are oriented  on dialogue.
<P>
Of course, the policies and institutions developed for our specific
conditions  over many years cannot simply be  transferred to developing
countries.  Rather, a more significant contribution to  structure building in the partner-countries is only to be expected when  the
problem-solving capacity that we  have developed is adapted to
prevailing  initial situations and developed further  by continuous
and growing own efforts.</ol>
<P>
<B>Summing up and outlook</B>
<P>
The intensive discussion on  sustainability in recent years has
brought  important clarifications of the question of  the conditions
for success and risk  factors for effective development  cooperation
at project level. In particular,  it has sharpened the focus on
the  demands on effective project  implementation. A similarly
intensive  debate must also be held in future on the  criterion
of significance. In particular,  thought should be given to the
 possibilities of contributing to the  development of sound strategies
and  policies at sectoral, regional or national  level through
a strategy-related and  programme-oriented employment of TC  (and
possibly FC) in the partner-countries.
<P>
<B>Footnote:</B>
<P>
<a name=1></a>1. OECD (1992): DAC Principles for Effective Aid: Development
 Assistance Manual, Paris, especially paras 163-241.
<p>
<HR>
