<head>
<title>Seven thousand at motorway street party demand end to car culture</title> 
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">

<center>
OneWorld News Service<p>

<table width=440 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 width=440>
<b><font size=-1>This report has been written and produced by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>

<center><h2>Seven thousand at motorway street party demand end to car culture</h2>

<h3>A photographic report from Reclaim the Streets</h3></center>

<p>

<b><font size=2>To see the full-size photograph (between 60 and 100K) click on the pictures below.  All photos and text by Mark Lynas</font></b><p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=220>
<a href="station_full.jpg"></a><br clear=all>
<font size=2>The word has gone round that the destination is on the Central Line of the Underground. People crowd the escalators.</font><p>  

</td>
<td width=220>
 <a href="tube_full.jpg"></a><br clear=all>
<font size=2>Several thousand people gather at London's Liverpool Street station, waiting for directions to the secret location.</font><p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top colspan=2>
<b>'Reclaim the Streets', said a colourful banner stretched across the 6-lane M41.  Below it, instead of the usual traffic jam and choking fumes, a full-scale street party was underway.</b><p>


Loud rave music boomed out from two parked lorries.  Children played in sand on the road.  People danced, drank, painted designs on the road, even stripped naked - all in the name of opposing 'car culture'.<p>

They are part of a growing movement - in Britain and abroad - which is forcing governments to confront the problems of an unsustainable economy.  Work and living patterns which depend on the car have resulted in dangerous smogs blanketing cities, a likely hastening of global warming and a spiralling of demand for oil.<p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top>
   <a href="motorway_full.jpg"></a> <br clear=all>   
<font size=2>The last cars on the M41 are driven out by protesters.</font><p>
</td>
<td valign=top>
 <a href="police_full.jpg"></a><br clear=all>

<font size=2>Vanloads of police try to keep the road open, but are eventually forced to retreat by the sheer weight of numbers against them.</font><p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top colspan=2>
Socially too, people are beginning to see that the pitfalls of the car culture.  Communities have become divided and isolated by traffic, and children who once played football outside their houses are kept inside for fear of them being run over by speeding drivers.<p>

On Saturday the children in Shepherd's Bush, London, could again kick a ball around in the road.  A crowd of over 5000 people had massed together and driven the cars out.<p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top>
 <a href="sound_full.jpg"></a><br clear=all>

<font size=2>A mysterious lorry is parked on the motorway hard shoulder.  Its side is removed to reveal a huge sound system - to the jubilation of the crowd.</font><p>
</td>
<td valign=top>
   <a href="sign_full.jpg"></a><br clear=all>
 
<font size=2>'Temporary closure for street festival'. The sign says it all.</font><p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top colspan=2>

This is one of the central themes of Reclaim the Streets: that urban areas belong to - and should be developed for - the communities that live in them.  <p>  

It was a protest with a difference.  Gone are the days when a well-behaved column of demonstrators would carry banners to Westminster to petition the politicians.  Today's protesters say they don't care what the politicians think.  Change can only come from below.<p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top>
