<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Cross-Border Initiative</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>The Cross-Border Initiative</H3>

<P>
by <I>Ali Mansoor</I>
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:
pages 8-9</I> </CENTER><HR>

<H4>Objectives and History</H4>

<P>
The Cross-Border Initiative (CBI) aims to facilitate private investment,
trade and payments between the countries of East and Southern
Africa and the Indian Ocean which are members of the PTA, SADCC,
and IOC. By so doing it is hoped to move these regional groups
towards increased economic integration.
<P>
The CBI was jointly launched in early 1992 by the African Development
Bank (ADB), the European Commission (EC), the IMF and the World
Bank with financing from the US, Swiss and Canadian governments.
The Initiative reflects extensive discussions between the co-sponsors,
the relevant regional institutions and public and private sector
representatives of most of the Eastern and Southern African States
(Burundi, Comoros, Ethiopia, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius,
Namibia, Reunion, Rwanda, Swaziland, South Africa (in observer
status), Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe).
<P>
The first phase consisted of a desk study that proposed terms
of reference for work by national Technical Working Groups (TWGs).
The TWGs were appointed by interested governments and had equal
representation from the private and public sectors. The second
phase began in June 1992 in Mauritius where representatives of
the TWGs from 15 countries finalised these TORs. In November 1992,
the representatives of the TWGs synthesised their various proposals
into a Common Program of Action (CPA) that would be used as the
basis for a Concept Paper. This paper would propose how governments
could implement the CPA with donor support and under the auspices
of the PTA, SADC and IOC. The Concept Paper was modified  by a
meeting of senior officials in Brussels in June 1993 and then
endorsed without further changes by a Ministerial meeting in 
Uganda in August 1993. As of January 1994, Kenya, Malawi, Mauritius,
Namibia, Rwanda, Uganda and Zimbabwe have invited the co-sponsors
to initiate discussions on implementation.
<H4>Institutional and Managerial Aspects that Contributed to the
Success of the CBI</H4>

<UL>
<LI><B>Involvement of the private sector</B>. Right from the outset,
the focus was on finding out from the private sector what was
hindering cross-border economic activity. This active participation
of the private sector kept the proposed package practical, avoided
ideological pitfalls, and helped to overcome some initial resistance
by some of the regional organisations. In Mauritius for example,
private sector representatives demanded that the regional organisations
should recognise their failure to eliminate barriers to private
intra-regional economic transactions and  that they rally around
the CBI. The one weakness has been the insufficient involvement
of the international private sector, but that is now being remedied
by instituting a dialogue with organisations such as the Group
of Seven and the European Roundtable (organisations regrouping
European firms interested in assisting the development of Africa).
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Local support to the TWGs</B>. The initial enthusiasm of
individual TWG members could have declined with competing demands
on their time. To avoid this, a local resident was hired to provide
the services of a secretariat to the TWG. This consultant also
undertook research required by the TWG and put together various
documents including the final report. As a local resident, the
consultant could be integrated into the TWG structures and was
aware of cultural and political sensitivities. Moreover, since
the consultant was responsible to the TWG and not to the co-sponsors,
any work was requested, digested and approved by the TWG. Thus,
the output reflected the consensus of the group and, to the extent
that the TWG was chosen in a representative manner, a wider social
consensus. A foreign 'expert' making the same recommendations
would not have had the same impact. 
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Gradual consensus building</B>. Asking local businessmen
and public officials to discuss problems and possible solutions
in the TWGs allowed the development of consensus at the national
level among key economic agents and decision-makers. Furthermore,
the TWGs are an embryonic pressure group for implementing the
required reform package recommended by the group. Local participants
bring an awareness of areas where reforms need to take account
of social sensitivities and administrative bottlenecks.
</UL>

<P>
 
<UL>
<LI><B>Involvement of all  players -- domestic, regional and international</B>.
The initial co-sponsors have been reinforced by an intense dialogue
with regional and pan-African organisations. At the regional level,
an intensive dialogue was undertaken with regional and pan-African
organisations to ensure that the package was acceptable to all.
It is noteworthy that the OAU and  have endorsed the CBI despite
their condemnation of variable geometry in general and the UEMOA
initiative in particular. This outcome reflects their close involvement
in the process as well as the pressures for realism and pragmatism
exerted on the process by the private sector. In dealing with
the problems of economic fragmentation in Africa, there is sufficient
common ground and a large enough agenda that a role for all relevant
organisations can be found.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>An agenda set by the most interested parties: the private
sector in consultation with government</B>. Dialogue, consensus
building and sharing out responsibilities are the foundations
upon which the CBI is built. This internalisation of the process
has allowed a compromise between the measures that the private
sector perceives as desirable and those the government sees as
politically feasible.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Loose mechanisms and arrangements for coordination within
a clearly specified framework</B>. With a large variety of domestic,
regional and international institutions, coordination of efforts
could have been a nightmare. A flexible structure was chosen where
broad principles were developed by a small  Steering Committee
(SC) drawn from the co-sponsors. The SC guided the process and
incorporated reactions and inputs from all parties. From the desk
study through to the Concept Paper, this approach worked because
the inner core was able to gauge the common ground and maintain
group consensus in identifying and moving. While a general time
frame and broad directions for reform were identified at the outset,
the SC was flexible in moving down the path from initial TORs
to recommended reforms. As the process moved closer to implementation,
the SC became more formalised with a more structured agenda and
timetable for its own actions.
</UL>

<P>

<H4>Weaknesses of the Process </H4>

<P>
The main weaknesses of the process are common to all efforts at
institutional development and not necessarily linked to the institutional
arrangements set up under the CBI. They essentially rest on the
need for any organisation to rely on the interaction of people
each of whom has his/her own institutional roles. Addressing such
problems requires close monitoring, much of which could be undertaken
through the secretariats of the PTA, SADC and IOC. Unfortunately
these organisations are not structured to play this role. Under
the CBI, resources are available to help them play a stronger
monitoring role to help address some of the shortcomings. These
include:<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Insufficient internalisation</B>. The CBI has only succeeded
superficially in developing the required social and institutional
consensus for the required reforms. This reflects the difficulty
in ensuring that information flows properly within and across
organisations and gets properly internalised. Thus many of the
actors end up representing personal as much as institutional positions.
For example, even though Zambia would benefit significantly from
only marginal reforms, it has had difficulty in developing an
implementation strategy due to a change of TWG Chairman. Similarly,
due to inadequate internal information flows, key units of the
concerned ministries are not sufficiently aware of the implications
of the CBI. Even though the Cabinet discussed and endorsed the
Concept Paper, many officials seem willing to go along only until
an issue of direct concern to their area of competence arises.
Moreover, internalisation by the sponsoring agencies has suffered
from similar difficulties. This is particular true in the IMF
and World Bank where the institutional culture has a traditional
antipathy for regional as opposed to multilateral measures and
given internal organisation set up to deal on a case by case basis
with national governments.</UL>
<UL>
<LI><B>Competing issues</B>. Another difficulty is the short attention
span of key policy-makers also need to deal with other, often
more pressing issues. For example, at the last Consultative Group
meeting for Kenya, mobilisation of donor financing for the adjustment
programme crowded out the CBI with its programme of medium term
reforms.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Maintaining focus and consistency</B>. In implementing
the agreed reform package, it has been difficult to maintain the
focus of the decision-makers. The TWG is only an advisory body
and weak internalisation has complicated the task of putting the
reforms on the agenda of senior policy-makers. Given weak internalisation,
the required decentralised approach (on a country by country basis)
that is a strength of the CBI can also be an Achilles heel. Policy-makers
(and the donors working with them) find it hard, in such a context,
to see the linkage between national and regional goals.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Changing balance of power</B>. The TWGs were often appointed
without any real belief that their recommendations would filter
through to national policy-making. As the CBI enters the centre
stage to be considered by policy-makers, the relevance and role
of the TWGs changes. Internal rivalries arise over who should
represent various institutions on the TWG or indeed there are
attempts to circumvent the TWG with other institutions. This disrupts
the process and delays the development and implementation of the
reform package.
</UL>

<P>
<HR>

<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <I>Updated on
April 15, 1996</I></H6>

