</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Farewell to Long term Experts</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Farewell to Long term Experts<p>
<I>H. Vogel</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 3, May-June 1994: pages 25-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Foreign donor agencies should gradually hand over project responsibility
to domestic management. Presence of expatriate staff is to be
reduced to short-term assignments to strengthen local self-reliance.
These are some conclusions by the author from working in a development
project on Conservation Tillage (Contill) in Zimbabwe.</B>
<P>
Development cooperation is frequently being criticized for lack
of sustainability and effectiveness in improving living conditions
in the so called underdeveloped world. Some critics have even gone
further, charging that the Western concept of development cooperation
has, and still is, contributing to underdevelopment. Local bureaucracies
and the expatriate staff working for the multitude of international
organizations and donors have also been under similar crossfire for gross inefficacy
and alleged development-tourism and country-hopping and project-hopping
respectively. Recently, some of this fundamental criticism has
been echoed in a much publicized conference keynote address by
the World Bank's Vice President for Africa E. W. K. Jaycox. He argues
that the implementation-style characteristic of Western development
cooperation is undermining the institutional and human capacity building
needs of most African countries.
<P>
This painful self-reflection from within the 'development fraternity'
comes at a time when the Western countries are increasingly plagued
by economic woes and, at the same time, faced with the colossal
task of helping restructure the economies of their former Cold
War rivals. The resultant budgetary constraints not only pose
a tremendous challenge for their development organizations such
as the German Agency for Technical Cooperation (GTZ), but they
also provide a unique chance for reconsidering cooperation concepts
and project implementation.
<P>
It is quite clear that projects have to become truly effective
in empowering the locals to find their own solutions to overcome
poverty and to achieve environmental sustainability. Although
seemingly self evident, it also needs to be stressed that this
process of developing self reliant project approaches has to begin
with genuinely listening to and really involving the local people.
Equally important, in order not to respond to the new challenges
with outmoded reactions, this process also needs to commence with
vision creation in collaborating agencies. In fact, the present
challenges faced by both North and South call for a different
way of looking at what progress and development is all about.
<P>
Although a lot of development projects stand like ruins because
they were 'doing development' rather than assisting in development,
some projects have succeeded in contributing to the empowerment
of people, even if only to a relatively small degree. In fact,
since people only learn from experience, some projects obviously
even have to fail. The response to failure should not be to throw the
entire approach on the scrap yard, but rather to reform it. This
needs to begin with freeing development cooperation of its Western
notion of exclusive correctness. What is required are flexibility,
perspectives, and iterative self reflection. Static approaches
stand no lasting chance in development cooperation, nor in any
other field of human interaction. Development cooperation, needs
to be embedded into a process of genuine giving and taking thereby
providing advantages for both sides and making nobody a loser.
With regards to the Contill project, the following process was
agreed upon during a joint planning exercise:
<P>
<ul>
<li>Expatriate project staff retires contrary to present project
agreement in favour of short term assignments (back stopping);
<li>Domestic project staff become fully responsible for project
implementation according to a mutually agreed plan of operation
(adjustable through project cycle management);
<li>Direct support to domestic project staff for further postgraduate
studies at the University of Zimbabwe in line with project goals
(thus harmonising work requirements and personal aspirations);
<li>Institutional support of the University of Zimbabwe through
the involvement of overseas scholars;
<li>Local GTZ project administration office provides services with
regards to project finance, staff training, and future project
agreements (decentralisation provides more flexibility in the
implementation of projects).</ul>
<P>
Through the implementation of this process, GTZ will show that
she is serious about building in expatriate redundancy; as should
happen in development cooperation. AGRITEX, on the other hand,
will have a sufficiently strong technical and managerial structure
to provide an enabling environment for her professionals and thus
ensure the sustainability of the project.
<P>
<B>General outlook</B>
<P>
It is clear that the process outlined for the Contill project
is time and location specific with respect to the above proposals.
Therefore, there should be no rigid blueprint for technical cooperation.
However, the process itself can be replicated in any project provided
the domestic conditions are favourable. Apart from a trusted relationship
all that is then required is a mutual readiness to pursue flexible
modes of project implementation. These should allow the management
to incorporate new ideas and adopt new concepts and strategies
for their cooperation when and if required. Surely, the challenge
of a successfully implementated technical cooperation process
is to achieve active, joint, learning-by-doing.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on October 29, 1996<BR>
