<html>
<header>
<title>Partnership in Development Cooperation</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Partnership in Development Cooperation: Editorial</h3>
by <i>Stanley Please</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: pages 2-3</i>
</center>
<hr>
There is widespread agreement that donor financial and technical assistance can only promote
economic and social development if the projects, programmes and policies which it supports are
'owned' by recipient countries. Yet the association in sub-Saharan countries of massive flows of
donor assistance with poor and, in some instances, disastrous economic performance, has led to
the equally widespread call for greater 'accountability' of assistance to legislatures and to
electorates in donor countries. This call is made notwithstanding a recognition that it would
almost inevitably imply greater donor intrusion in recipient countries and therefore a weakened
sense of 'ownership'.
<p>
It is this dilemma and the danger that it will set in motion a vicious downward spiral of aid
effectiveness, that led ECDPM to devote its 1994 Round Table Conference to the subject of
'Partnership in Development Cooperation: Combining Recipient Responsibility with Donor
Accountability.' A full report contains the introductory speech by Louk Box, Director of ECDPM
and the keynote speeches by Simba Makoni, former Secretary General of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) and by Jan Cedergren, Deputy Director of the Swedish
International Development Agency (SIDA).
<p>
This issue of the Bulletin reproduces papers which were presented by some of the other
participants at the Round Table. They have been selected to provide varying perspectives on the
issue of partnership in development cooperation. They have also been selected on the grounds
that they effectively address the challenge which Louk Box presented to participants in his
introductory speech, namely: "to focus on practical ways to improve partnership taking into
account real life constraints;" and "to provide operational guidance on how to do it better." He
further laid down three preconditions for meeting the challenge: first, there should be "no
taboos" on raising any relevant issue; second, participants should "refrain from defensive
attitudes;" and third, participants should concentrate on "practical and feasible management
approaches."
<p>
Jos&#233; Filipe Fonseca from the Embassy of Guinea Bissau in Brussels captured this spirit
of the Round Table in his contribution. He attributes the failure of partnership to the combination
of the weakness of recipient African countries and the arrogance of donors. However, he
emphasises that the weaknesses he has in mind are not simply the economic and technological
weaknesses of African countries nor even their institutional weaknesses although all of these are
very important. He is more troubled by the moral weaknesses of country leaders. He is equally
troubled by the arrogance of donors who "are always so convinced that only they have the right
ideas." More modesty and a greater willingness by donors to share responsibility for mistake is
essential, he believes, for improving the partnership relationship.

This frank and hard-hitting analysis of the problem by Fonseca set the tone for the whole of the
Round Table discussion. To capture the flavour of these discussions, Fonseca's contribution is
followed by a selection of quotations from the discussions.
<p>
The methodological note by Rogerio Pinto provides a useful guide for moving beyond the mere
repetition of the buzz words commitment and ownership to something more practical. He
emphasises that 'commitment' is simply associated with the "intent of the leadership" whereas
'ownership' is concerned with "the players who will determine implementation." He concludes
that: "you can have commitment without responsible ownership, but you cannot have responsible
ownership without commitment." He presents a brief description of Institutional Environment
Assessment (IEA), a procedure by which ownership can be both assessed and improved. Its
success, however, is dependent on governments being willing to bear the additional costs
involved, and donors being willing to amend their own internal operational procedures.
<p>
The distinction between the roles of political leaders and of technocrats in the policy process is
also emphasised by Derick Brinkerhoff. He is concerned that technocrats treat policy-making
as a "linear process" with an emphasis on "first-best prescriptions" rather than recognising that
it is a "political and interactive process" in which "consensus building around second and third-best solutions is required." From this analysis he outlines a procedure called Implementing
Policy Change (IPC) which USAID has developed in its operations in several countries. As with
Pinto's IEA procedure, IPC is designed to ensure both national commitment and ownership of
policies and programmes and to develop a partnership relationship with donors. He illustrates
the use of IPC by reference to his own practical involvement in its application in Zambia.
<p>
In his introductory speech, Louk Box had asserted that the issues facing the Round Table were
as relevant to NGO's as they were to official multilateral and bilateral donors. Hugh Goyder of
Actionaid acknowledges this in his contribution. In it, he emphasises that while partnership
continues to be the guiding philosophy of NGO's, "most NGO's have faced real difficulties about
making the concept fully operational." The national pressures to be more accountable and to
introduce new concerns over the environment, gender, etc., make it "difficult to be accountable
to the communities with whom we are working." He then presents Actionaid's experience in
facing up to this problem: do not rush into financing but let projects emerge from community
action; appoint local staff living and working in the project area; work through local government
and local communities rather than national governments; do not over-burden field workers with
excessive reporting requirements. From this experience he draws possible lessons for official aid
agencies.
<p>
There were those at the Round Table who were markedly less optimistic about the chances of
reforming the aid relationship towards an improved sense of partnership. They argued that it is
necessary to be less idealistic and more pragmatic; to recognise that the "forces in favour of
inertia within long-standing bureaucratic systems" are strong and pervasive. This quote is from
the contribution by Steven Tabor who drew lessons from experience with donor involvement in
agricultural research. Despite the "largely unchanging needs for new technologies to address
rural poverty and country food requirements," donor involvement has been short-sighted, biassed
towards unsustainable physical facilities, and subject to unnecessary donor-promoted policy
changes. Tabor argues for a much less ambitious approach for the 1990's. This would be an
approach in which particular partnership arrangements are negotiated where "a good fit can be
found between a country's needs and a donor's assistance instruments." Any longer term
partnership relationship would "be more a product of serendipity (i.e. a happy accident) than of
deliberate policy."
<p>
It is clear from all these papers that participants both recognised the importance of the
ownerhsip-accountability dilemma posed by the Round Table and that they had taken seriously
Louk Box's request that they focus on practical conclusions emerging from their experiences. Of
course, there was persistent reference in discussions to the difficulty - some would say
impossibility - of generating anything approaching a partnership of equals when the economic,
technological, professional, institutional and political power of donors and/or recipients is so
unequal.
<p>
SIDA is clearly one of the few donors willing and politically able to explicitly recognise and
address this inequality. Through its 'Changing Roles' policy, SIDA is deliberately attempting to
fashion its strategic and operational relationships with the recipients of its assistance in a manner
which will prevent, or at least mitigate, the adverse impact of this inequality on the ownership
of projects and programmes by the recipients. It recognises that this is risky, but SIDA asserts
that unless ownership is genuinely with the recipient, the risks of failure are even greater.
<p>
But while the SIDA strategy makes eminent sense for partnership relationships between
countries where both the donor and the recipient country place economic and social development
policy high on their list of political priorities, is it relevant to the many other donor and recipient
countries in which - sadly - this is not the case? The Round Table, perhaps understandably, did
not focus on these country differences.
<p>
But what is more worrying is that donors do not differentiate their operational procedures to any
marked extent as they apply to 'good' performers and to 'bad' performing recipient countries. If
the partnership concept is be nurtured, there must be a greater willingness by donors to move
towards the SIDA strategy in their relationships with those countries which are struggling
seriously with their horrendous economic and social problems. These countries should generate
sufficient confidence to permit the ownership of policies to be clearly in the hands of the
government.
<p>
Certainly the high profile conditionalities associated, for instance, with World Bank structural
adjustment lending and with their overtones of domestic economic policy being run from
Washington, are highly undesirable and counter-productive.
<p>
However for other recipient countries, such high profile conditionality might, at least for a
limited period, be very desirable. This would be particularly the case where, after a period of
economic and/or political disaster, there is a need to build up confidence between donors and
recipient countries. Once confidence is established, increasing movement towards partnership
becomes possible and desirable.
<p>
A final reflection on the Round Table returns to the first of the two keynote addresses which
launched the proceedings -- that of Simba Makoni: "Genuine partnership," concluded Makoni,
"will result not just, not even mainly, from good institutions and procedures, but rather from a
clear community of interest, strong political will and commitment, and honesty and sincerity."
Donors on their part must not simply "blame incompetent or corrupt host governments" and, for
their part, these governments "must take their destiny in their hand to determine what help they
need and to say 'no' to that which they do not need." 
<p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <i>Updated on February 20, 1996</i><p>
