<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Small but Excellent: The Development Policy of Switzerland</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/ch.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Small but Excellent:<br>The Development Policy of Switzerland<p>
<I>Michael Hofmann</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 1, January-February 1994: pages 24-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>

<B>Small but excellent - this is how Switzerland likes to present
itself and its development assistance. With barely 1.5 billion
Swiss francs of official development assistance (ODA), it is just
not possible to move mountains. The Swiss do not even try. Rather,
they emphasize quality. Other policy concerns, however, interfere
with this concept, such as their position on flight capital.</B>
<P>
In regard to the terms of its aid, there is no doubt that Switzerland
is one of the most generous donors: Almost 100 percent of all
aid is given in the form of grants (since 1988, bilateral assistance
has consisted exclusively of non repayable grants; no loans are
provided). Assistance is more or less unconditional, and the instruments
are very flexible. Although Switzerland pursues its own foreign
trade interests through mixed financing (8% of ODA, or 1 % of
Third World exports), even the usually faultfinding NGOs acknowledge
that the bulk of assistance is decidedly oriented toward development.
Proof is in the selection of partners, predominantly low income
countries, and the concentration on rural development and food
security.
<P>
<B>Volume of Swiss aid</B>
<P>
In the past, however, the Swiss were not exactly the most generous
donors. Until the end of the eighties, their relative total contributions
were at the lower end of the donor list (in 1970, ODA was only
0.12% of GNP, 1980 only 0.24%). Thanks to high growth rates, the
DAC (Development Assistance Committee) average was met for the
first time in 1991, and again increased to 0.46% in 1992. However,
downward movements are anticipated and it is not very likely that
the goal for 1995 of at least 0.4% will be reached. Despite good
intentions on the part of the government  the federal council
 to increase the volume of development assistance in future years
by 8 per cent annually, parliament  the council of states and
the national council  again applied the budget brake. In view
of its deep economic recession even rich Switzerland must economize.
<P>
At any rate, the Swiss have a bad conscience. This was obvious
during the 700th anniversary celebration of the confederacy in
1991, when 700 million francs in excess of ODA appropriations
were approved for debt relief. (Even commercial banks contributed).
The extremely active NGOs had gone all out with their publicity
campaign and submitted a petition signed by 250 000 Swiss citizens,
which asked the federal assembly to be generous. Furthermore,
creative approaches ensure that the population's willingness to
donate to development projects continues (0.06% of GNP). However,
the social consensus that more needs to be done for the South
quickly comes to a stop when the Swiss economy airs its concerns
as to fair foreign trade, opposition to the bank secrecy act,
or asylum policy. When in doubt, the confederates are in favour
of cautious restraint.

<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 1: Quantitative trends</b> (in million Swiss francs)</caption>
<tr><td><td><B>1977</B><td><B>1980</B><td><B>1984</B><td><B>1988</B><td><B>1989</B><td><B>1990</B><td><B>1991</B><td><B>1992</B>
<tr><td>bilateral aid<td><td><td>484<td>651<td>691<td>765<td>912<td>955
<tr><td>multilateral aid<td><td><td>132<td>206<td>203<td>241<td>244<td>430
<tr><td>Total<td>286<td>412<td>616<td>857<td>894<td>1006<td>1156<td>1385
<tr><td>in % of GNP<td>0.19<td>0.23<td>0.27<td>0.30<td>0.29<td>0.31<td>0.34<td>0.39
<tr><td>Source: DEH
</tr></table>
<p>

<B>Guidelines of Swiss aid</B>
<P>
Political guidance is provided by the 1976 federal law on international
development cooperation and humanitarian aid. The department for
development assistance (DEH) in the Ministry for Foreign Affairs
operates on this generally accepted basis. It channels approximately
80 per cent of Swiss ODA. In implementing its measures mostly
small projects  the DEH cooperates closely with consulting firms
and NGOs.
<P>
While the image of the DEH is that of a basic needs oriented helper,
the civil servants at the BAWI, the federal agency for foreign
trade, are generally looked upon as representatives of domestic
export interests, which are realized through mixed financing and
balance of payments assistance. For a long time, responsibilities
were clearly separated due to division of labor and dissimilar
lobbies. Recently, these lines have been blurred because of coordination
pressures and personnel changes. The new head of the DEH, Walter
Fust, is a known expert in Swiss trade promotion. Nevertheless,
there can be no question of a general change of direction, since
personnel was also transferred from the DEH to the BAWI. Besides,
the political direction is determined by the cabinet and parliament,
after all.
<P>
Given the relatively low ODA volume and the modest staffing of
development agencies, it is only logical to concentrate assistance
in a few priority countries. About 70 per cent of bilateral assistance
goes to 19 countries where the Swiss work predominantly in regions
and sectors which are not already pervaded by other donors. It
is hardly surprising that the effort to find a niche literally
led to the mountains to develop dairy farming and small industries.
Traditionally, Nepal, Pakistan, Bolivia, Peru, Rwanda, and Madagascar
have been priority countries, where rural projects have been quite
successful.
<P>
Regionally, Swiss aid is increasingly concentrated in Africa (40%),
followed by Asia (30%), and Latin America (12%). Since the nineties,
a small amount of ODA funds has been given to Eastern European
countries for humanitarian purposes (Albania and the former Yugoslavia).
<P>
Sectorally, the Rio Conference on Environment and Development
in 1992 was responsible for a shift in favor of environmental
protection. Environmental impact studies are now required for
all projects. Furthermore, food security, education, handicrafts,
and small industry are preferred project sectors. Following the
trend of other international donors, more attention is devoted
to migration, the war on drugs, and AIDS. Conditionality is openly
supported, which was manifested in the highly selective allocation
of the &quot;anniversary contribution&quot;. Switzerland rewards
efforts on the part of the recipient countries toward &quot;good
governance&quot; (in a rather vague sense) and observance of human
rights, although it is quite aware of its limited leverage.



<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 2: Geographical distribution</b> (in million Swiss francs)</caption>
<tr><td><td><B>1990</B><td><B>1991</B><td><B>1992</B>
<tr><td>Africa<td>343.7<td>344.3<td>354.8
<tr><td>Asia/Oceania<td>179.9<td>234.2<td>253.8
<tr><td>Latin America<td>90.1<td>123.0<td>116.6
<tr><td>Europe<td>2.7<td>5.0<td>37.2
<tr><td>not allotted to regions<td>148.5<td>205.2<td>192.2
<tr><td>Total bilateral aid<td>764.9<td>911.7<td>955.2
<tr><td>Multilateral aid<td>241.1<td>244.3<td>429.8
<tr><td>Total of aid<td>1006.0<td>1156.0<td>1385.0
<tr><td><b>Priority countries</b>
<tr><td>India<td>17.9<td>40.7<td>51.9
<tr><td>Indonesia<td>27.0<td>19.8<td>41.8
<tr><td>Tanzania<td>26.3<td>19.9<td>41.1
<tr><td>Jordan<td>0.9<td>8.6<td>28.8
<tr><td>Bangladesh<td>13.2<td>20.8<td>27.9
<tr><td>Mozambique<td>36.6<td>42.0<td>26.7
<tr><td>Madagascar<td>44.7<td>21.9<td>26.3
<tr><td>Pakistan<td>13.4<td>20.4<td>25.4
<tr><td>Source: Annual Report 1992 DEH
</tr></table>
<p>



<B>Organization of Swiss aid</B>
<P>
Both aid agencies are responsible not only for ministerial decisions,
but also for their implementation (the DEH for one third of its
projects). Institutions comparable to the German KfW (Reconstruction
Loan Corporation) or GTZ (German Agency for Technical Cooperation)
have not been established. The higher education sector cooperates
with federal institutions, as for instance the Confederate Technical
University in Z&#252;rich with the Development Institute in Geneva.
Usually, the implementation of projects is subcontracted to consulting
firms and NGOs. This cooperation is facilitated not on only by the
transparent personnel structure but also by the multi year budgets
of the federal council, which are flexible as to spending priorities
and include conditional credits approved by parliament. (Although annual appropriations;
i. e. cash payments, cannot be carried over to the next fiscal
year, a loss of funds is usually avoided by shifting expenditures
between programs).
<P>
Conceptionally, the DEH is fully committed, particularly in regard
to its country programs. The first one was introduced in 1988
for Bangladesh. These programs utilize the findings of regular
evaluations. The goal is to link technical cooperation (of the
DEH) with balance of payments assistance (of the BAWI).
<P>
<B>No country quotas for Swiss aid</B>
<P>
Swiss missions and local coordinating agencies play an active
role in project planing, which makes it unnecessary to adhere
to specific quotas. Countries do not receive general promises
of assistance. Planning is done by sector. Project proposals take
into account local potential sustainability, and help for self help.
In Switzerland, these are more than just slogans that sound good.
<P>
Fast and efficient humanitarian aid is definitely one of Switzerland's
strongest attributes. It builds on the vast experience and professionalism
of the Swiss Disaster Relief Corps. Food aid, on the other hand,
has been very controversial, since the domestic agro lobby has
not been very concerned about its negative impact on the recipient countries. Still, relief
organizations are trying to follow a sensible distribution policy
within the framework of food-for-work projects.
<P>
Relief agencies and other NGOs are quite involved in Swiss development
cooperation. Since 1980, ODA funds for NGOs have quadrupled. It
is no coincidence that the NGOs are better known among the general
public than the public aid agencies. To name only the largest
organizations: The Swiss Red Cross and Caritas provide mainly
humanitarian aid; Helvetas, Swissaid as well as the religious
organizations &quot;Bread For Brothers&quot; and &quot;Fasting
Sacrifice&quot; provide primarily development assistance. The
importance of these NGOs becomes clear when one considers that
they implement about one third of bilateral technical cooperation.
Swissaid, whose international reputation equals Oxfam's, does
not manage any projects, but receives DEH subsidies in the form
&quot;block grants&quot;. Several NGOs have pooled their resources
to solicit donations and publicize their activities, which has
a positive impact on the coordination of aid measures as well.
<P>
<B>Multilateral aid</B>
<P>
Notwithstanding the negative referendum on joining the United
Nations, aid agencies are not averse to working with multilateral
organizations. For many years, Switzerland has contributed cash
and special services to UN institutions, particularly to UNDP
and UNICEF. With its positive vote in 1992 to join the World Bank
group and the IMF, the electorate finally sanctioned this already
well established cooperation (although many NGOs pleaded for a
no vote). Even before joining, Switzerland was allowed to participate
in World Bank tenders, since Washington was very aware of the
great importance of the Swiss credit market. The fact that Switzerland
profited from this relationship as well as from the orders it
obtained was instrumental for the yes vote.
<P>
Aside from such profit calculations, aid agencies feel obligated
to provide multilateral assistance. For example, they co financed
structural adjustment programs and readily participated in IDA
replenishments. Switzerland is also involved with the regional
banks of the IFAD.
<P>
A big question mark remains concerning Switzerland's ties to Europe
after the negative referendum on joining the European Union (EU),
which made it less likely that the desired membership in the EU
would be approved in the near future. Will Switzerland join after
all in the nineties and accept all the rights and obligations
that go with membership? These will probably be more stringent
after the likely entry of all the Nordic nations. Or will Switzerland
continue to go it alone, under the motto &quot;small but excellent?&quot;
<P>
Relative to its affluence and capacity, the development policy
of Switzerland is actually too small and certainly not excellent
in general. Much remains to be desired relevant to trade policy,
since Switzerland is even more protectionist in the agricultural
sector than the EU states. And the Swiss financial world, despite
all its lip service in the wake of the Marcos accounts affair,
does not give any indication that flight capital is returned to
where it is so urgently needed. With all due respect to Swiss
neutrality non partisanship is a questionable attitude in view
of the global conflict situation. 
<p>
<HR>
