<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>At the Top of the League: The Development Policy of Sweden</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/se.jpg"></H3>
<H3>At the Top of the League:<br>The Development Policy of Sweden<p>
<I>Hans H. Lembke</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 2, March-April 1996: pages 24-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<b>Hardly any other industrial nation has given its development policy
a higher status in its overall foreign policy than Sweden. In
many questions of concept, Sweden has been the opinion leader,
advocating for example a &quot;third way&quot; between capitalism
and socialism. The bourgeois government which came to power in
1991 started to change this line and reduced development aid.
Even after the Social Democrats' return to government in 1994,
the old line was not fully restored.</b>
<P>
Sweden has concentrated considerable human and financial resources
on development cooperation since the 1970s and set high benchmarks
of quality for its inputs. In doing so, the country did not aim
at being a model of self sufficient modesty: Sweden's claim to
leadership in quality was above all asserted offensively during
Olof Palme's time as head of government. And in the North south
dialogue the country frequently took stances which deviated decisively
from the mainstream dominated primarily by the USA.
<P>
These efforts to shape a high developmental profile won Sweden
worldwide respect, but not always agreement. Other countries appreciated
the fact that discussions of conceptual issues in Sweden at all
levels political, administrative technical and scientific methodical
were tackled quickly and competently. But the ideological background
of Sweden's development policy, expressed above all in its preference
for socialist models in the Third World, in its partisanship keeping
its distance from the Superpowers for the nonaligned countries
and the Group of 77, and not least in its claim to be &quot;pure&quot;
and free from economic interests, was either viewed critically
or rejected.
<P>
This negative response of other donor nations and the developing
countries excluded from Swedish cooperation could not be explained
solely by the fact that Sweden's orientations also always implied
criticism of other donor and recipient nations. The latter also
suspected that in practice Swedish policy on the South was not
as pure as it was made out to be. Indications and tangible proof
of this cropped up time and again. The Bofors scandal revelations
of deep Swedish involvement in the arms trade with the Third World
was a decisive milestone in this regard. It was also crucial because
it stirred up a great deal of suspicion among the Swedish public
about the model character of Sweden's relations with the South.
<P>
<B>Gradual changes in the Swedish profile </B>
<P>
In the autumn of 1991 a bourgeois government took office in Sweden
which propagated a marked departure from the country's &quot;third
way&quot;. By that it meant not only a fundamental revision of
the capital-labour relationship and social, fiscal and financial
policies, but precisely also a reorientation of foreign policy.
Political slogans such as the &quot;End of International Utopianism&quot;
and the necessary &quot;Europeanization of Foreign Policy&quot;
led people to expect that this reorientation would mean a shifting
of focus at the cost of Stockholm's relations with the South.
True, with the Social Democrats' return to government in 1994
these tendencies were in fact weakened. But they were by no means
reversed.
<P>
What does this mean for Sweden's development policy? Can one expect
Sweden to abandon its established positions? Will it let its high
profile deteriorate? Will Sweden cease to give orientation to
others, and will its function as a model even be reversed? Does
this mean that the current trends in international cooperation,
ranging from stagnation to recession, may even be strongly accelerated
by a change in Swedish development policy?

<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 1: Quantitative trends</b></caption>
<tr><td><td><B>1972-73</B><td><B>1982-83</B><td><B>1992-93</B><td><B>1995-96
<tr><td>ODA in $US mil.<td>897<td>1899<td>2386<td>--
<tr><td>ODA as % of GNP<td>0.5<td>0.93<td>1.01<td>0.87
<tr><td>Share of ODA of all DAC countries (%)<td>2.7<td>3.2<td>3.6<td>--
<tr><td>Source: DAC (Prices and exchange rate: 1992)
</tr></table>
<p>

Upfront, one should note that Sweden's claim to be an international
model was not only rhetoric. It really did lead to a high level
of performance in development cooperation. The performance indicators
applied by the OECD's Development Assistance Committee (DAC) leave
no doubt about that. Since the mid1970s, Sweden has put at least
0.8 per cent of its Gross National Product into development cooperation
as ODA (see Table 1) and thus been a member of the top group of
donors. Its grant element has long been 100 per cent, and this
was not reduced by the introduction of mixed credits at the beginning
of the 1980s (only the interest subsidy is counted as ODA). Traditionally,
Stockholm has taken a relaxed approach to tied aid, and only slightly
less than 20 per cent of bilateral assistance is linked to deliveries.
Because of that the return flow rate is relatively low, which
has drawn continual criticism from the Swedish association of
industries since the 1970s. Sweden reacted early and to a relevantly
great degree to calls for a relaxation of tying funds to specific
projects (by introducing sector programmes, financing imports
and assisting balances of payments). It also did the same in response
to pressure to finance costs in local currencies and fund recurring
costs. Sweden was in the vanguard in introducing country programming,
and on planning security (commitments over several years) and
project design (&quot;recipient orientation&quot;), went a long
way to meeting developing countries' wishes. New directions in
development cooperation the inclusion of NGOs, policy on women,
environmental policy, democracy and human rights were adopted
early in Sweden's developmental programme and implemented consistently.
<P>

<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 2: Bilateral cooperation programme structure<br> (Share of total bilateral aid in %)</b></caption>
<tr><td><td><B>1981-82</B><td><B>1991-92
<tr><td>Country frameworks (Project countries)<td>66.9<td>45.7
<tr><td>Other SIDA programmes<td>24.7<td>33.0
<tr><td>Other bilateral programmes (BITS, SAREC,...)<td>8.4<td>21.3
<tr><td><td>100.0<td>100.0
<tr><td>Source: SIDA
</tr></table>
<p>

The Swedish development cooperation administration has long had good prerequisites for a close and continual dialogue with the recipient governments. These are its focus on about 25 main recipient countries, its decentralization
in the form of local representation in those countries, its commitments over several years, and its
programming arrangements. Not least, Swedish development cooperation is
greatly respected due to its multilateral components, which stand out for their
scale and constructive involvement, above all in the UN area. These are the salient
features of the Swedish development cooperation profile. But a closer look at it
shows that it has long manifested signs of latent erosion. The environment for a
development policy which lays claim to international leadership had already
changed in the 1980s. The liberal and con servative parties, and
above all the association of industries, had always opposed
a radical development policy. The ruling Social Democrats took account of this
criticism not only in the sense of political bargaining, but also because of their con viction that development
policy should be based on a broad public consensus. The
most important adjustments made in the past decade (see Table 2) were:
<ul>
<li>limiting the competence and increasing control of the implementing agency SlDA (Swedish International
Development Authority) which was seen even by some Social Democrats as too radical, too highhanded, and inefficient;
<li>limiting the country frameworks (firm multi-year commitments to about 25 main recipients) in favour of sectoral or cross-sectoral programmes which are also open to other recipients;
<li>setting up other organizations and instru ments, above all the BITS organization
for mixed credits and technical aid, especially for cooperation with advanced
developing countries which are also of interest to Swedish industry, including Central and Eastern Europe;
<li>cutting back the share of multilateral ODA, linked with a more critical attitude towards the UN organizations and drawing closer to the World Bank and region al banks.</ul>
<P>
With these systematic and gradual adjustments, the Swedish government and development administration have avoided the abrupt changes which, if they had clung to the radical patterns of the 1970s, would
have been forced on them at the latest by the political changes which emerged
towards the end of the 1980s. With the collapse of the socialist
systems in Eastern Europe and the Third World two crucial reference points of a third,
radical way in Sweden's policy on the South disappeared for good.
And the coincidence of the acceleration of the European integration
process with signs of erosion of the Swedish economic and social
model made resisting a &quot;Europeanization&quot; of Sweden's
foreigns policy untenable.
<P>
<B>No model change but increased pressure to adjust</B> 
<P>
As Social Democratic governments had anticipated the necessary
adjustments to the international environment, there was no reason
for a real development policy change after the switch of government
in 1991. But there were drastic changes in aid volumes and in
disbursements to some of the traditional main recipients. Cuts
were made by the conservative government with the approval of
the Social Democrats which meant that even after the government
changed again in 1994, they could not be reversed. However, the
cutback in volume, part of a severe government restructuring package,
was at 14 per cent relatively mild and left the ODA-GNP rate at
0.9 per cent. But disbursements to individual countries were slashed
drastically. Compared with the inputs of 1990/91, those to Tanzania
plunged by 23 per cent, to Mozambique by 38 per cent, to Vietnam
by 47 per cent, and to Zambia by a swingeing 58 per cent. By contrast,
during the same period other major recipients such as India and
Zimbabwe enjoyed distinct increases. These were clear signals
to the governments of these long-time partner countries.
<P>
But the &quot;losers&quot; will also remain top recipients, even
though the rules of the game had changed. The narrower group of
partners has now been defined by three year country strategy papers
replacing the country programmes elaborated for selected recipients.
Countries covered by these so far are Botswana, Namibia, Sri Lanka,
Tanzania, Vietnam, Zambia, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Guinea-Bissau, Kenya,
Lesotho, Nicaragua and South Africa.
<P>
Besides these budgetary changes, there are highly detailed approaches
to overhauling the developmental programme and organization. They
feature new priorities for economic growth, new relationships
between the market and government, continuation of the structural
adjustment policy led by the World Bank and IMF, strengthening
of institution building, support for democracy and human rights,
more stringent monitoring of the use of funds by and effectiveness
of Swedish implementing agencies and developing country administrations.
These are all programme points which, although rendered in terms
unusual for the Swedish style of doing things, in fact only signify
accentuations and not real innovations.
<P>
Traditionally, the most important implementing organization by
far was the SIDA, responsible for disbursing a good 50 per cent
of the total funds and about three quarters of the bilateral transfers.
These ratios have remained stable since the mid-1980s. But there
has been a shift within the SIDA budget in the relation between
framework commitments to main recipient countries on the one hand
and other SIDA programmes on the other. This ratio was still 75:25
at the beginning of the 1980s; now it is 60:40 (see Table 2).
The SIDA has also made some changes to its organization and instruments
following pressure from parliament and the government. It assigned
a coordinator for population questions, and appointed senior advisors
for environmental, health and family planning issues. In addition,
the SIDA was told to intensify its monitoring of effectiveness
and spending. This has resulted in the introduction of a target oriented
planning system, a more systematic evaluation, an annual performance
report to the government, and a manual on controlling corruption
in the employment of funds in recipient countries. In terms of
instruments, a further expansion of non-project-tied aid is foreseen.
However, after integrating import financing and assistance with
balances of payments, most of this aid will be allocated outside
the country frameworks.
<P>
Besides the traditionally strongly promoted social sectors (one third
of the SIDA disbursements in 1993/94), the focal points of bilateral
cooperation are to be environmental protection, technical infrastructure,
and promotion of administrative efficiency and democracy. In addition,
disaster aid, with almost one quarter of the disbursements, is
being given an ever more important status in the SlDA's range
of inputs. In 1993/94 third of these funds flowed into European
crisis regions, mainly former Yugoslavia. The SIDA disburses about
10 per cent of its funds via NGOs.
<P>
BITS has competence for technical aid and mixed financing in the
cooperation with the more economically advanced recipient countries.
In addition, since 1995 Sweden has run an experiment in also allocating
ODA credits via BITS with a grant element of 80 per cent. Since
1990, this institution has also had an additional field of activity
in Central and Eastern Europe. About one quarter of Sweden's very
diverse aid for this region, which has meanwhile grown to an annual
volume of 1 billion SEK, is disbursed by BITS to support the change
in the political systems and for environmental protection. (By
definition, these programmes are outside ODA).
<P>
The promotion of Swedish direct investment and transfer of knowhow
by Swedish industrial companies was reorganized before the change
in government. Competence for these programmes now rests with Swedfund
International AB and Swedecorp. The Swedish Agency for Research
Cooperation with Developing Countries (SAREC) which, besides BITS
and Swedfund/Swedecorp, is responsible above all for the cooperation
with non programme countries, remained entrusted with scientific
cooperation. After the change in government in 1994 profound changes
in the organization of Swedish development administration were
once again in the offing. The various implementing organizations
the SIDA, SAREC, BITS and Swedecorp were integrated into one body.
The integration of SlDA's local representations in recipient countries
into the respective Swedish embassies was completed earlier.
<P>
<B>The EU question</B> 
<P>
The developmental dimension of Sweden's entry into the European
Union is also being discussed intensively in Sweden. Linked with
its application for membership, a foreign ministry working group
had analysed these implications together with representatives
of social groups. The ministry's official conclusion was that
EU membership would not demand a significant change of course
in Sweden's development policy. The Swedes regard the EU's development
policy as altogether compatible with their basic line, and hardly
expect any impacts on their bilateral aid. But on the other hand
they have also made it clear that Sweden will want to have a weighty
voice in questions of EU development policy concepts. Hence one
can assume that in the developmental field as well, Sweden's &quot;Europeanization
of foreign policy&quot; will not mean that it will renounce its
salient positions. Especially if its Nordic EU partners, Denmark
and Finland share these positions.
<P>
<b>References:</b>
<P>
Bo Karre, Bengt Svensson: The Determinants of Swedish
Aid Policy. In: O. Stokke (Pub.): Western Middle Powers and Global
Poverty. Uppsala: 1989.
<P>
Hans H. Lembke: Schwedens Entwicklungspolitik,
Berlin (DlE):1986. 
<p>
