<a HREF = "../coh.htm">Coordination</a>
<hr width=6 size=6>
<a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><img src="../images/acro.jpg">


<hr>
<BR>
<FONT size=2></FONT>
</UL></TD>
<TD width=100></TD>
<TD WIDTH=460><P>
<pre>

</pre>
<H2>Managing Cooperation</H2>
<UL>
<li><a href="../mgt.htm">Management of European aid</a>
<li><a HREF = "../dc.htm">Decentralised cooperation</a><ul><font size=2><I>Introduced as part of the fourth Lom&#233; Convention, this makes a wide variety of development actors eligible for Lom&#233; resources which, in the past, were the monopoly of central government agencies. It reflects changing (donor) perceptions on the state-society relationship and development cooperation modalities. However, putting the concept into practice is proving to be difficult.</I></font></ul>
<LI><a HREF = "../ngo.htm">NGO's and civil society</a>
<LI><a HREF = "../pri.htm">Private sector</a><ul><font size=2><I>The emphasis in the revised Lom&#233; on private sector development and investment promotion in ACP countries illustrates the growing ACP and EU consensus on the essential contribution of the private sector to development. This implies, amongst others, a supportive environment, the right incentives, new public-private partnerships, a wide range of new institutional arrangements and major investments in building entrepreneurial and management skills. The primary responsibility is with the ACP governments. However, the EU can also play a catalytic role, provided it fundamentally reviews its strategies, approaches and instruments in this sector.</I></font></ul>
<LI><a HREF = "../pol.htm">Aid policies</a>
<LI><a HREF = "../tc.htm">Technical cooperation and partnership</a>
<LI><a HREF = "../cap.htm">Capacity building and institutional development</a>
<LI><a HREF = "../eva.htm">Aid evaluation and effectiveness</a>
<LI><a HREF = "../reg.htm">Regional cooperation</a>
<LI><a HREF = "../coh.htm">Coordination, coherence and complementarity</a>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
