<h2>To order ITDG books, <a href="../../itdg/orders.html">click here.</a></h2>


<a name="environment"><hr><br>


<img alt="[International Institute for Environment and Development]"
align=left src="../../iied/oldiied/iied_pix/iied_logo.gif"><br
clear=left><br><br>

<b><li>The Cutting Edge: Small Business and Progress</b><br>
<i>Ernst A. Brugger, Jane Nelson and Lloyd Timberlake</i><br>
The text is divided into three main parts: the first introduces small
businesses and discusses their role in achieving sustainable development, the
second focuses on assistance for small businesses and the final section
discusses their role in future development.  The points made in the text are
complemented by many short accounts of individual companies
and entrepreneurs drawn from countries throughout Latin America.  This book
includes texts in Spanish and English and is illustrated with many
photographs.<p>
  
The first section argues that small is not beautiful and that small businesses
are often environmental polluters.  However they are significant players
within the development process and, therefore, need to be encouraged and
supported.  Small businesses within both the formal and informal sectors are
responsible for a large proportion of GDP and an
estimated  30-40 per cent of employment in Latin America.  The authors argue
that successful small businesses are an essential component of local economic
growth and that their increased prosperity will assist and offer opportunities
for those on low incomes in the surrounding area.<p>

 However, small businesses face a number of problems, in particular a lack
of access to credit and to technology and expertise, and the fact that
government rules and procedures favour larger companies.  These problems are
discussed and illustrated in the second section.  The final section discusses
the importance of securing investment in small
businesses in order to effectively reduce poverty within Latin America.<br>  
<b>1994<br>
170 pages<br>
Published by and available from FUNDES<br>
Haus Inseli<br>
Niederurnen<br>
CH-8867<br>
Switzerland.</b><br><br>
<a name="overseas">
<hr><br>



<img alt="[Overseas Development Institute]" align=left
src="../../odi/odi_pix/odi_logo.gif"><br clear=left><br><br>







<b><li>The Flexible Economy<br>
The Causes and Consequences of the Adaptability of National Economies
</b></b><br>
<i>Edited by Tony Killick</i><br>
The accelerating pace of global change demands that economies must be 
adaptable.
Economies which are flexible flourish, as in Eastern Asia. Inflexible 
economies stagnate, as in communist Eastern Europe and Africa. However, even
though adaptability governs the long-term development of economies, economists
have had little to say  about the nature and
determinants of economic flexibility. This book redresses that 
situation. The contributors address the key theoretical and empirical issues,
using a wide range of country studies. <br>
<i>(In association with Routledge)</i><br>
<b>£16.99 paper, £50.00 cased<br> 
1995 <br>
384pp <br>
ISBN 0 415 11776 3<br>
ISBN 0 415 11775 5<br>  
</b><br><br><br>

  
<b><li>Votes and  Budgets Comparative Studies in Accountable Governance in the
South</b><br>
<i>Edited by John Healey and William Tordoff. </i><br>
This book presents case-studies in accountable government and the 
management of public funds, with particular reference to the multi-party
political systems of Botswana, Jamaica, Sri-Lanka and Zambia under the Third
Republic. Criteria for judging accountability are set out, and the role and
influence of the political leadership, elections, parties, parliaments,
interest groups, the media and external donors are explored. Conclusions take
account of the comparisons which are drawn with the experience of single-party
regimes in Africa and Asia. <br>
<i>(In association with Macmillan).</i><br>
<b>£35.00  <br>
1995 <br>
240pp <br>
ISBN 0 333 63887 5 cased</b><br><br><br>  


<b><li>Economic Crisis in Developing Countries <br>
New Perspectives on Commodities, Trade and Finance </b><br>
<i>Edited by Machiko Nissanke and Adrian Hewitt.</i><br>
Part I relates economic development to the movement in world 
commodity prices and earnings and the terms of trade, and associated changes
in external debt and foreign aid. Part II evaluates major premises in the
mainstream economic paradigm of development in the
interrelated areas of trade, finance and technology. Contributors to 
this scholarly collection
of thirteen essays in honour of Alfred Maizels include Gerry Helleiner, 
Dragoslav Avramovic, Walter Labys, John Spraos, Hans Singer and Frances
Stewart. <br> 
<i>(Published by Pinter Publishers).</i><br>
<b>£39.50  <br>
1993 <br>
288pp <br>
ISBN 1 85567 152 2 cased  </b><br><br><br>


<img align=right border=1 hspace=10 vspace=3 height=118 width=85
src="../partners_pix/odi_crisis_thumb.gif"></a>

<b>ODI Special Report </b><br>
<b><li>Crisis or Transition in Foreign Aid? </b><br>
<i>Edited by Adrian P Hewitt </i><br>
Has the end of the Cold War caused a crisis in official aid, already 
beset by budgetary cuts, challenges on effectiveness and so called 'donor
fatigue'? Or is the problem specific to a few
donors, while others move ahead with more constructive policies, 
stronger and broader-based public support, and larger programmes? This Special
Report assesses the current position in ten of the leading donor countries
(UK, USA, Canada, Japan, France, 
Germany, Netherlands, Norway, Sweden and Denmark) and looks to the future role
of foreign aid.  <br>
<i>(In association with the Overseas Development Council and the 
North-South Institute) </i><br> 
<b>£17.50  <br>
1994 <br>
97pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 208 3 paper </b><br><br><br>
 

<b><li>Foreign Aid Reconsidered</b><br>   
<i>Roger C Riddell </i><br>
Examines in depth the moral and theoretical questions raised in the 
aid debate and weighs up the different arguments in the light of the range and
quality of current evidence.  '...the most thorough and authoritative analysis
of foreign aid that I have seen.  It is balanced and well
argued and based on a broad range of relevant sources. In the 
literature on development, it is a landmark that no doubt will attract
interest among both academics and professional aid administrators.' Goran
Hyden author of No Shortcuts to Progress. <br> 
<i>(In association with James Currey) </i><br> 
<b>£14.95 <br>
1987 <br>
320pp <br>
ISBN 0 85225 104 5 paper <br> 
1995 third reprint</b><br><br><br>


<b>Development Policy Studies Series <br>
<li>IMF Programmes in Developing Countries Design and Impact</b><br>
<i>Tony Killick </i><br>
Do IMF policies help Developing Countries? As linchpin of the global 
financial system, the International Monetary Fund provides balance of payments
support, chiefly to developing
countries, conditional on strict remedial policy measures. Its approach to
policy remains highly controversial, however. While the Fund claims it has
adapted, critics allege its policies are harshly doctrinaire, imposing
hardships on already poor people.  For the critics, the half-century of its
existence is 'fifty years too long' and radical change is essential. This book
examines the arguments, tracing the extent of Fund adaptation, presenting
major new evidence on the consequences of Fund programmes, and considering its
future role. <br>
<i>(In association with Routledge) </i><br>
<b>£11.99 <br>
1995 <br>
224pp <br>
ISBN 0 415 13060 9 paper <br>
Provisional publication date September 1995    </b><br><br><br>


<b> Development Policy Studies Series<br> 
<li>IMF Lending to Developing Countries Issues and Evidence </b><br>
<i>Graham Bird, University of Surrey</i><br> 
The International Monetary Fund was created to centralise the 
management of the global monetary system. As international financial markets
evolved, the richer countries turned to other, more flexible sources of
finance and IMF lending became almost exclusively focused
on the developing world. And yet the IMF has been widely criticised 
for its lending role in developing countries, with some arguing that it should
not be lending to all and others claiming that net reverse flows since the mid
1980s suggest that the Fund has abrogated its
responsibilities. This book provides the first detailed theoretical 
and empirical analysis of Fund lending and concludes that key changes are
needed if the Fund is to realise its full potential for assisting developing
countries. <br>
<i>(In association with Routledge) </i><br>
<b>£11.99 <br>
1995 <br>
216pp <br>
0 415 11700 3 paper</b><br><br><br>


<b>ODI Development Policy Study <br>
<li>Democracy, Governance and Economic Policy: Sub-Saharan Africa in 
Comparative Perspective</b><br>
<i>John Healey and Mark Robinson </i><br>
Examines the nature of the relationship between democracy and 
development in developing countries, drawing on historical experience and the
impact of economic adjustment in the 1980s. Focusing on sub-Saharan Africa, it
reviews political developments and the growth and
decay of the state since independence, and explores the political dimensions
of economic policy making. The authors also analyse the current trend towards
democratisation in Africa and its implications for improved economic
management.   'Succinctly characterizes the
political culture of African states through the 1960s and 70s..' 
Richard Dowden African Affairs, October 1993 <br>
<b>£10.95 <br>
1994 <br>
200pp <br>
Revised Preface  <br>
ISBN 0 85003 211 3 paper </b><br><br><br>
 

<b><li>Monetary Policy in Developing Countries </b><br>
<i>Sheila Page </i><br>
In this, the first book to analyse the interaction between monetary 
policy, the financial sector and the rest of the economy in developing
countries, case studies of three African and three Asian countries are
complemented by special studies of the role of the informal sector and
the relationship between monetary policy and exchange rate management. 
Country studies include statistical background on the economies and their
financial sectors, and use econometric tests to establish what stable
relationships can be assumed in the financial sector. <br> 
<i>(In association with Routledge)</i><br>  
<b>£45.00 <br>
1993 <br>
384pp <br>
ISBN 0 415 08822 4 cased</b><br><br><br>
  

<b><li>The Adaptive Economy</b><br>
<i>Tony Killick</i><br> 
All economies need to adapt if they are to achieve reasonable rates 
of development. This book analyses the principles of adjustment policy, with
special reference to small low-income countries. Subjects covered include:
relationships between economic development and
structural flexibility; determinants of economic flexibility; 
strategies and principles of adjustment policy; the socio-economic context of
adjustment policies; the use of the exchange rate; adjustment in agriculture
and industry; and policies for financial sector adjustment. <br>
<i>(In association with the EDI, World Bank)</i><br>   
<b>£22.45 <br>
1993 <br>
399pp <br>
ISBN 0 8213 2125 0 paper 
</b><br><br><br>


<b>ODI Development Policy Study<br>
<li>A Reaction Too Far: economic theory and the role of the state in 
developing countries </b>  <br>
<i>Tony Killick</i><br> 
Studies the lessons that can be learned from modern economics for the 
role of the state in developing countries. Surveys the uses, limitations and
dangers of applying prescriptions developed in the North to conditions in the
South, and considers the implications for aid donors. Argues the case for
caution, modesty and experimentation. <br> 
<b>£4.95 <br>
1990 <br>
77pp <br>
ISBN 0 85003 147 8 paper 
</b><br><br><br>
  


<img align=right border=1 hspace=10 vspace=3 height=118 width=85
src="../partners_pix/odi_debt_thumb.gif"></a>

<b>ODI Special Report <br>
<li>Africa's Multilateral Debt, A Modest Proposal</b><br>
<i>All Party Group on Overseas Development </i><br>
Many African countries now see the lending policies of the World Bank 
and the IMF as an impediment to development rather than a help. What is the
truth behind this perception?
Should the international financial institutions now reverse their 
policy of refusing to reschedule or write off bad debts? Are our own
governments bailing out the IMF and the World Bank with scarce bilateral aid
to keep debts current and if so should the donors be prepared to continue? The
Working Party has drawn up a framework of 
recommendations after meeting representatives of all points of view   banks,
creditor and debtor governments, as well as the international financial
institutions and independent experts. <br>
<b>£10.00 <br>
1994 <br>
79pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 213 X paper</b><br><br><br>


<img align=right border=1 hspace=10 vspace=3 height=126 width=85
src="../partners_pix/odi_trade_thumb.gif"></a>

<b><li>How Developing  Countries Trade: The Institutional Constraints </b><br>
<i>Sheila Page </i><br>
Over the last fifteen years there have been dramatic increases in 
both private and public intervention in international trade. Traditional
barriers to market-based trade such as commodity cartels and tariffs have been
augmented by new developments such as the rise of regional trade blocs and the
growth of intra-firm trade. This book argues that these changes are large and
persistent enough to have an impact on total 
development performance, and on the performance of both individual countries
and sectors. It illustrates this with a wealth of theoretical arguments,
empirical evidence and country studies.<br>
<i>(In association with Routledge) </i><br>
<b>£14.99 paper, £45.00 cased<br>
1994   <br>
234pp <br>
ISBN 0 415 11778 X  <br>
ISBN 0 415 11777 1  </b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Prospects for Trade and Capital Flows in the Developing Countries: 
New Sources and Directions for Investment</b><br>
<i>Sheila Page</i><br> 
Produced for ODI s annual conference on the economic prospects for 
developing countries, this report summarises the leading published forecasts,
analysing their differences, and drawing out their policy implications. It
also presents data on the current pattern of investment flows. <br>
<b>£35.00 <br>
1995 <br>
45pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 219 9 paper
</b><br><br><br>
 

<b>ODI Special Report <br>
<li>Trading with South Africa: The policy options for the EC </b><br> 
<i>Sheila Page and Christopher Stevens </i><br> 
Provides wide ranging analysis of South African trade post-sanctions, 
detailing its current exports, and examining what types of external support
South Africa needs, and how South Africa and its trading partners can
encourage new products and markets. It also identifies which existing
suppliers to the EC could be affected. The report compiles and analyses data
on South African trade, commodity data for all major trading partners, tariff
and non-tariff data, and competitiveness indicators.  <br> 
<b>£20.00 <br>
1992 <br>
78pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 187 7 paper
</b><br><br><br>


<img align=right border=1 hspace=10 vspace=3 height=120 width=85
src="../partners_pix/odi_reform_thumb.gif"></a>


<b>ODI Special Report<br>
<li>World Trade Reform: Do Developing Countries Gain or Lose?</b><br>
<i>Sheila Page and Michael Davenport </i><br>
The Uruguay Round of trade negotiations reduced barriers to trade in 
all economic sectors, with the largest changes in  food and clothing. An
unprecedented number of activities and government policies related to trade
will come under international regulation for the first time, as the move from
GATT to the World Trade Organization creates a new 
institution with stronger powers as well as wider responsibilities. For the
developing countries the effects of this new international framework are
increased because their special privileges are defined more precisely, but
also more narrowly. Estimates of the consequences have varied from
massive gains to crippling losses. <p>

This Special Report analyses the 
changes and where possible quantifies them. It sets out their impact on a
range of countries at different stages of development. Finally it considers
how the new trading system may need to evolve to meet its increasing
responsibilities. <br>
<b>£17.50   <br>
1994 <br>
128pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 221 0 paper 
</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Diversifying Exports: The Supply Response of Non-Traditional Exports 
to Ghana's Economic Recovery Programme </b><br>
<i>C D Jebuni, Abena Oduro, Yaw Asante and G K Tsikata </i><br>
The authors review Ghana s overall export performance and its 
policies towards non-traditional exports, drawing upon survey evidence on the
response of output. Remaining constraints on exporters are examined and the
report concludes with policy recommendations. <br>
<i>(In association with the University of Ghana)</i><br> 
<b>£7.95 <br>
1992 <br>
64pp <br>
ISBN 0 85003 189 3 paper 
</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Small Enterprises and Adjustment: The Impact of Ghana's Economic 
Recovery Programme </b><br>
<i>Nii K Sowa, A Baah-Nuakoh, K A Tutu and B Osei </i><br>
Examines the place of the small-scale sector in Ghana' s economy and 
the effects of the country's Economic Recovery Programme upon them. With
policy recommendations.  <br>  
<i>(In association with the University of Ghana) </i><br>
<b>£7.95 <br>
1992 <br>
64pp <br>
ISBN 0 85003 188 5 paper   
</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Manufacturing Africa: Performance & Prospects of Seven Countries in 
Sub-Saharan Africa</b><br>
<i>Roger C Riddell </i><br>
This analysis of the role of industry in the development of Africa 
features chapters by experienced specialists on Botswana, Cameroon, C"te d
Ivoire, Zimbabwe, Nigeria, Zambia, Kenya. Roger Riddell places these case
studies in the context of a wide overview of the trend
among all the countries of the continent, and draws on this wealth of 
material to argue that the future prosperity of sub-Saharan Africa is likely
to be enhanced by a three-pronged approach to industrialisation. 'This study
is undoubtedly the most significant work on the manufacturing industry in
sub-Saharan Africa to be published in the last decade or indeed
in any decade.' Colin Stoneman, Development Policy Review <br>
<i>(In association with James Currey)</i><br> 
<b>£16.95<br>
1991 <br>
419pp <br>
 ISBN 0 85255 119 3 paper </b><br><br><br>

<b>ODI Special Report <br>
<li>Europe's Preferred Partners? The Lome Countries in World Trade </b><br>
<i>Michael Davenport, Adrian Hewitt and Antonique Koning</i><br> 
Countries in Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific (ACP) have enjoyed 
preferential access to the European Market under the Lom, Convention for over
twenty years. This report assesses the impact of their special treatment,
examines in detail their trade performance and
investigates the difficulties that ACP exporters experience. The 
Report also explores potential effects on ACP trade performance of changes in
EU policy regarding the Lom, Convention and of trade liberalisation that
resulted from the Uruguay Round. <br>
<b>£17.50  <br>
1995 <br>
70pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 218 0 paper <br> 
(Provisional publication date July 1995)
</b><br><br><br>


<b>ODI Special Report<br> 
<li>The GATT Uruguay Round Effects on Developing Countries </b><br>
<i>Sheila Page, Michael Davenport  and Adrian Hewitt</i><br> 
For the first time, developing countries participated fully in multilateral
trade negotiations with the Uruguay Round. This report assesses in detail the
probable results of a GATT settlement on the countries of Asia, Africa, Latin
America and the Caribbean.  <br>
<b>£12.50 <br>
1991<br>
64pp A4 <br>
ISBN 0 85003 165 6 paper  
</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Trade, Finance and Developing Countries: Strategies and Constraints in
the 1990s</b><br>
<i>Sheila Page </i><br>
This study considers the impact of external opportunities and 
constraints on developing country trade policies and development financing.
With detailed analysis of 26 countries and extensive case studies of Malaysia,
Thailand, Zimbabwe, Colombia and Peru. <br>
<i>(In association with Harvester Wheatsheaf) </i><br>
<b>£47.50 <br>
1990 <br>
443pp <br>
ISBN 0 7450 0606 X cased </b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Managing Water as an Economic Resource </b><br> 
<i>James Winpenny </i><br>
In this book the author argues that suppliers and consumers should 
treat water as a scarce commodity with an economic value. He evaluates
policies for the improved management of existing demand, and draws on case
studies from different countries as he discusses how polices could be
implemented to treat water as an economic good, conferring major economic,
financial and environmental benefits. <br>
<i>(In association with Routledge) </i><br>
<b>£10.99 <br>
1994 <br>
133pp <br>
ISBN 0 41510378 9 paper 
</b><br><br><br>

 <img align=right border=1 hspace=10 vspace=10 height=121 width=85
src="../partners_pix/odi_erosion_thumb.gif"></a>

<b><li>More People, Less Erosion<br>
 Environmental Recovery in Kenya </b><br>
<i>Mary Tiffen, Michael Mortimore and Francis Gichuki </i><br>
Pessimism about population growth and environmental deterioration is 
not borne out by transformation of the semi-arid Machakos District, Kenya.
This area was characterised by soil erosion and frequent food shortages
between 1930 and 1960, but had greatly improved by 1990. Combining the
findings of physical and social scientists from ODI and the University of
Nairobi, Kenya, this study uses conventional data, oral history and the
photographic record from 1937. It concludes with an explanation of the
contribution of population growth to economic and social development,
technology change and environmental sustainability under the right policy
conditions, highlighting the role of investment by 
small farmers. <br>
<i>(In association with John Wiley & Sons) </i><br>
<b>£22.95 <br>
1993 <br>
328pp <br>
ISBN 0 471 94143 3 paper</b><br><br><br>


<b>ODI Development Policy Study<br>
<li>The Energy Industry and  Global Warming: New Roles for International Aid
</b><br>
<i>Dennis Anderson </i><br>
Concern about global warming has escalated at a time when the share 
of developing countries in world energy demand is rising rapidly. The author
analyses worldwide energy output and demand, the limitations of nuclear power,
and the future potential for cost- effective expansion of production from
renewable energy sources solar energy and biomass. He also examines possible
measures for increasing energy efficiency, and the 
uses and limitations of carbon taxes and afforestation programmes.  <br>
<b>£6.95 <br>
1991 <br>
72pp <br>
ISBN 0 85003 156 7 paper
</b><br><br><br>
    
<img align=right border=1 hspace=10 vspace=3 height=121 width=85
src="../partners_pix/odi_research_thumb.gif"></a>

<b><li>Development Research: the Environmental Challenge </b><br>
<i>Edited by James Winpenny </i><br>
Development economists now have to come to terms with a wide range of 
environmental issues, including: global environmental threats, natural
resource degradation, the feasibility of natural resource accounting, the
impact of macroeconomic policies, the scope for economic valuation, social,
gender and population questions, energy and biodiversity. This book outlines
the current state of knowledge, identifying gaps to be filled by economic
research. <br>
<b>£9.95 <br>
1991 <br>
228pp <br>
ISBN 0 85003 141 9 paper 
</b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Values for the Environment: A Guide to Economic Appraisal  </b><br>
<i>James Winpenny  </i><br>
A practical guide to the economic treatment of the environment in 
project appraisal, using cost-benefit- analysis as the decision framework.
Much of its illustrative material is drawn from developing countries, but its
contents are relevant to developed countries and socialist economies in
transition. The main environmental impacts of projects and the methods
available for placing economic values on them are discussed, and the 
feasibility of environmental valuations is then illustrated for projects in a 
variety of sectors, including natural resources, infrastructure, the built
environment, industry, mining and tourism. A review of relevant policy issues
concludes the guide. <br>
<i>(In association with HMSO) </i><br>
<b>£16.50 <br>
1991 <br>
277pp <br>
ISBN 0 11 580257 6 cased</b><br><br><br>

<b><b>ODI Development Policy Study <br>
<li>Europe: 1992 and the Developing World</b></b><br>
<i>Michael Davenport with Sheila Page</i><br>
The authors analyse the implications of the Single European Market 
for developing countries. As well as looking at the impact of 1992 on the
Third World as a whole, the study examines the interests of a number of
developing countries in some detail. '..  get a copy of this quite
superb book. It is indeed the most important analysis of the effect 
of the SEM on ACP countries to date.' Desmond Davis, African Economic
Digest.<br>
<b>£9.95<br>  
 1992<br>
130pp<br>
ISBN 0 85003 151 6 paper</b><br><br><br>


<b>ODI Development Policy Study <br>
<li>Reform in Eastern Europe and the  Developing Country Dimension </b><br>
<i>Edited by Christopher Stevens and Jane Kennan</i><br>
Will Eastern Europe attract political interest and aid away from 
developing countries? Or will growth in the East be beneficial also for the
South? Have the economic reformers in Eastern
Europe anything to learn from the extensive experience of ldcs in 
structural adjustment and aid administration? These are the questions posed in
ODI s new book on the implications of
the changes in Eastern Europe. The book also reviews progress in five 
states of Central and Eastern Europe   Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Hungary,
Poland and Romania. <br>
<b>£9.95  <br>
1992 <br>
160pp  <br>
ISBN 0 85003 170 2 paper </b><br><br><br> 


<b>ODI Special Report<br>
<li>Eastern Europe and the Former Soviet Union: 
Economic Change, Social Welfare and Aid </b><br>
<i>Charlotte Benson and Edward Clay </i><br>
Examines the social implications of the rapid economic and political 
changes in Eastern Europe and the former Soviet republics and the extent to
which aid is being used to alleviate
the impact of reform. After outlining pre-reform economic and social 
conditions, the authors discuss the problems of food security and entitlement
losses which face the region. They assess the implications of the collapse of
the CMEA and of inter - republic trade within the
former USSR, and provide a wide-ranging overview of the role which 
the various aid agencies are playing in their efforts to support economic
reforms. <br>
<b>£17.50 <br>
1992 <br>
77pp <br>
A4 ISBN 0 85003 186 9 paper</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Europe and the International Division of Labour </b><br>
<i>Edited by Christopher Stevens and Joan Verloren van Themaat </i><br>
Analyses EC trade policy, European foreign investment in developing 
countries and the impact of EC enlargement. Also includes statistical analysis
of trade patterns under Lome, review of EC-ASEAN relations and assessment of
EC trade with OPEC  countries. <br>
<b>£11.95 <br>
1987 <br>
173pp<br> 
ISBN 0 340 41058 2 paper<br>
</b><br>  
  
<h2>To order ODI publications, <a href = "../../odi/pub_order.html">click
here. </a></h2>


<a name="oxfam">
<hr><br>

<img alt="[Oxfam]" align=left
src="../../oxfam/logo.gif"><br clear=left><br><br>


<b><li>Microfinance and Poverty Reduction</b><br>
<i>Susan Johnson and Ben Rogaly</i><br>
Small scale financial services, such as savings and credit facilities, are increasingly seen 
as effective means of poverty reduction. Microfinance and Poverty Reduction, a 
new book published by Oxfam in conjunction with ACTIONAID, examines the 
successes and pitfalls of such schemes across the globe and the lessons learnt, 
promoting debate around the issue.

<P>The book will be launched at the Microcredit Summit, Washington on 3 February. The 
panel of speakers at the launch will include the authors; Tom Dichter, independent 
microcredit expert, and Alfonso Castillo from URAC, Mexico. It will be chaired by 
Nigel Twose, Programme Development Director, ACTIONAID.

<P>Although  microfinance can increase incomes and contribute to household and 
individual security, the authors emphasise that credit is not a panacea for eradicating 
poverty. The continuing debate about the issue and different approaches are 
highlighted in case studies from the UK, Mexico, Pakistan, Ecuador and The Gambia.       

<P>The book recommends an overall approach to deciding whether, and in what ways, 
small scale financial interventions can be useful and relevant to poor people in different 
contexts.  <br>
<b>About the authors:</b><i>Susan Johnson is an economist and has worked for ACTIONAID since 1991. She is 
currently researching microfinance issues.<br>
Ben Rogaly is a socio-economist and former policy adviser to Oxfam UK.  He now 
teaches development studies at the University of East Anglia, UK.</i><br>
<b>£8.95<br>
paperback<br>
136pp<br>
ISBN 0 85598 369 8</b><p>


<P><A HREF="../../oxfam/publish/porder.htm"> Order this book</A><p>





<a name="save">
<hr><br>

<img alt="[Save the Children Fund]" align=left
src="../../scf/scf_pix/scf_logo.gif"><br clear=left><br><br>

<b><li>NGO Performance and Accountability<br>
Beyond the magic bullet</b><br>
NGOs are the main agents of relief in developing countries and the channel
through which much foreign aid is spent. This book follows on from the
original study by Edwards and Hulme on maximising NGO's effectiveness (Making
a Difference).   It examines how NGOs demonstrate and account for their
successes and failures. It makes a critical evaluation of the performance of
NGOs in third world development and proposes a range of alternative methods
and approaches to increase their effectiveness. The book argues that many NGOs
are fundamentally weak in this area and  that unless performance is improved,
confidence in their ability to deliver aid efficiently will be eroded.<br>
<b>£9.95 <br>
November 1995<br>
 256 pages<br>
Paperback<br>
ISBN 1 85383 310 X</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>The Advance of African Capital<br>
The Growth of Nigerian Private Enterprise</b><br> 
<i>Tom Forrest</i><br>
The Advance of African Capital provides the most detailed, most extensive
account of medium- and large-scale African business yet published. Up-to-date
and comprehensive, it examines the growth of private enterprise in Nigeria,
giving profiles of the country's key entrepreneurs. Combining ethnographic and
historical perspectives, it examines the strategies and patterns of
development employed by business people from the colonial period to the
present day. Through a series of highly readable case studies, it builds up a
broad picture of the various forms of capital accumulation and sectoral
advances in trade, transport, manufacture, agriculture, finance, and other
services, setting them all within the context of changing economic
opportunities, shifts in power and policy, relations with foreign capital, and
attitudes towards private business and the state. Not only an invaluable
digest of Nigeria's business activity, this important study also challenges
existing views about African enterprise and is highly relevant to
policy-makers concerned with economic development.<br>
<b>£39.50 <br>
xvi+309pp<br>
0 74860492 8<br>
(International African Library 14) <br>
Edinburgh University Press</b>
<br><br><br>

<b><li>Ranching and Enterprise in Eastern Botswana<br>
 A Case Study of Black and White Farmers</b><br>
<i>Isaac Ncube Mazonde</i><br>
Botswana's economic development has been extraordinary in Third World terms,
yet little is known about how different social groups have adapted to the new
economic opportunities. This comprehensive account studies a key group of the
new entrepreneurs: the ranchers. It describes their changing life styles,
their construction of personal and social space, and the way they have adapted
to state-initiated political and economic change, showing through a series of
case studies how ranching has grown from being the preserve of white settlers
to include Botswana and other African farmers as well. The relationship
between ranching and communal land tenure, and the effect of Botswana's Tribal
Land Grazing Policy are analysed in detail, while the careers of non-elites,
the practice of bordermanship, labour relations and the management of multiple
enterprises and risks are also covered. This book will appeal to Africanists,
development planners, historians and anthropologists. 

<p>Isaac Ncube Mazonde is a Senior Research Fellow at the University of
Botswana.<br>
<b>£39.50<br> 
xii+164pp<br>
0 7486 0467 7<br>
(International African Library 12)<br> 
Edinburgh University Press</b><br><br><br>


