<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> SIERRA LEONE</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/sierra.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=426 height=270 alt="Map of Sierra Leone">
</p>
<hr>

<p><b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	4.6 million

<p>Population growth rate	2.4% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	284
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	37%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	29%	
<br clear=left>
<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID began working in Sierra Leone in 1988. Programmes in two development areas are now
reaching more than 80,000 people. 

<p>In Kambia ACTIONAID has been working through village groups to reduce poverty by providing seed
credit to farmers, improving access to clean water and environmental sanitation and rehabilitating
schools. In Sella Limba work has focused on improving food security by helping farmers with seed
credit and agricultural training.

<p>The rebel war has devastated Sierra Leone's economy, disrupted community life and affected the
livelihoods of most people. As a result, while ACTIONAID is working on long-term development goals
with communities in these two areas, this is necessarily combined with emergency and rehabilitation
work as the situation demands.

<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work In Sierra Leone</h3>
<b>ACTIONAID:</b>

<p><ul><li>worked with communities in Kambia and Sella Limba in digging new wells and rehabilitating
old ones so that 59 villages now have wells and pumps, and two trained well-caretakers for each
village. Adequate sanitation is also important for the communities' good health. More than 3,000
people now have latrines in their homes.

<p><li>is making seed available to farmers on credit to ensure that even following a poor harvest
they have some to plant for the next season. Advice is also provided on improving land management for
better soil conservation. The building of safe seed stores means families no longer have to sleep on
their crop to protect it from pests and thieves.  

<p><li>concentrated on increasing communities' capacity to organise themselves and take complete
responsibility for development initiatives. In 1995 there was a marked increase in these initiatives
with communities managing construction of schools, arranging payment of teachers' salaries and
building literacy centres with little or no direct input from ACTIONAID. During 1996, the seed credit
programme is being handed over to community management.
</ul>
</font>

