<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 34 Friday 24 January 1997

</CENTER></H3>

<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></H4><A HREF="index.html">EUROSTEP Home Page</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. EU COUNCIL CALLS FOR CEASE-FIRE IN ZAIRE AND

EXPRESS CONCERN OVER RWANDA AND BURUNDI</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The EU General Affairs

Council last Monday 20 January launched an appeal to all parties

involved in the fighting in Eastern Zaire to declare a cease-fire

and, most importantly, keep it. The Council confirmed in its conclusions,

the need to respect Zaire's territorial integrity as well as those

of other countries in the region and its support to the mediation

efforts being undertaken by African leaders. The Council also

welcomed the confirmation from Zairian authorities that elections

will be held this July, called for the EU electoral unit to be

speedily set in place in Kinshasa and for the prompt appointment

of the head of the Unit. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> On Rwanda, the Council confirmed the EU's willingness

to help reintegrate the remaining refugees but said it was shocked

by the assassination of three Spanish volunteers working in humanitarian

organisations in Rwanda (see below). Concern was also expressed

over the 'serious degradation of the political climate in Burundi'

and the EU called for all parties involved to rapidly begin negotiations

to reach a 'lasting institutional consensus'. The Council concluded

by stressing the urgency of the need to hold an international

conference in the region under the aegis of the United Nations

and the OAU. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. MRS BONINO SUPPORTS NGOS DECISION TO EVACUATE

THE RUHENGERI AND GISENYI AREAS AFTER THE ASSASSINATION OF THREE

SPANISH VOLUNTEERS</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The European Commissioner for Humanitarian Aid,

 Mrs Emma Bonino, last week lent her support to the NGOs and international

humanitarian organisation's decision to evacuate the Ruhengeri

and Gisenyi areas. The decision was taken after the assassination

of three Spanish volunteers in the area. Manuel Madrazo Osuna,

Flores Sirera Fortuny and Luis Valtuena Gallego had been working

for Medicos del Mundo on a project financed by the European Community

Humanitarian Aid Office, ECHO. Mrs Bonino described the NGOs'

decision as 'inevitable' and stated, &quot;This sudden worsening

of the security situation also within Rwanda causes the greatest

concern and requires the international community to make a rapid

decision. ... No assistance to the population can be envisaged

without adequate protection.&quot; </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Later in a debate on the issue at the European Parliament,

opened by Spanish MEP Carnero Gonzalez, the new chair of the Parliament's

Foreign Affairs Committee (see below), British MEP Tom Spencer,

said everything had to be done to protect the staff of humanitarian

organisations on the ground. He said that the issue had to addressed

urgently by the authorities in the host countries as well as by

the representatives in the international community.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT ELECTS  NEW MEMBERS FOR

ITS COMMITTEES</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The re-forming of Committees in the European Parliament

began in earnest last week. Several of the Committees will retain

the same chairperson such as: </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Committee on Budgets chaired by Detlev Samland,

German Social Democrat; </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Committee on Women's Rights chaired by Nel

van Dijk, Greens, Netherlands; and </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Committee on Budgetary Control chaired by German

Christian Democrat Diemut Theato. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Among the Committees that have chosen new chairpersons

are: </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Committee on Foreign Affairs, Security and

Defence Policy where British Conservative Tom Spencer replaces

Gerardo Fernandez-Albor of the Spanish EPP Group; </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Committee on External Economic Relations where

Luciana Castellina, Italian member of European United left Group

succeeds Belgian Liberal Willy De Clerq and;</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Committee on Development and Co-operation where

French Socialist Michel Rocard takes over from Bernard Kouchner

who has joined the European Radical Alliance Group. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>British Conservative Lord Plumb should remain chairman

of the European Delegation at the ACP/EU Parity Assembly.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> By the end of last week only two of the groupings

had not been formed. These were:</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>- the Security and Disarmament Sub-Committee where

Dutch Liberal Jan Bertens is expected to keep his position as

chairman and; </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>-the Human Rights Sub-Committee of which French EPP

member Andr&eacute; Soulier is likely to succeed German Christian

Democrat Marlene Lenz. <B> </B></FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. EC OFFICIAL CONFIDENT ON EVE OF TRADE NEGOTIATIONS

WITH SOUTH                                 AFRICA</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Mr Philippe Soubestre,

the Interim Director of the European Commission's Directorate

General for Development Co-operation and chief EU negotiator in

the EU's trade talks with South Africa expressed his optimism

on the outcome of the talks just before he left for Pretoria last

Thursday. Mr Soubestre denying being disappointed over the slow

pace of progress said, &quot;The sooner the agreement is concluded

the better, but some aspects must be examined meticulously, notably

those affecting South Africa's neighbours.&quot; Mr Soubestre

declared, &quot;The two parties are now prepared to negotiate

and to create the climate of confidence needed to make progress

towards the common objective of a balanced agreement.&quot;</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Mr Soubestre described the EU's proposal of the

free trade area with South Africa as 'the best compromise possible

between the will to conclude an ambitious agreement going beyond

the GSP and the necessity of reconciling in the best way possible

South Africa's interest, the Union's internal constraints and

respect for WTO rules'. He added that South Africa also stood

to benefit from 'qualified accession' to the Lom&eacute; Convention

and that the European Programme for reconstruction and development

in South Africa has a substantial budget (500 million ECU for

1996-2000).</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Mr Soubestre's optimism sharply contrasts reports

of the South African government's misgivings on the agreement.

(See Last week's PAF, No.33)<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>DUTCH PRESIDENCY BRIEFING ON COUNCIL PREPARATION

OF THE UNCED REVIEW BY THE UN</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The European Environment Bureau (EEB) and the Dutch

Presidency have agreed to hold a briefing for NGOs on the results

of the EU Governments consultations on the EU involvement in the

UNCED review  on 18 February in Brussels. For security reasons

the EEB would like to be notified, as soon as possible,  if you

are coming. You should also notify them if you are not able to

attend but want to receive a report. (Contact: John Hontelez,

Secretary General, EEB, 26 Overwinningstraat/Rue de la Victoire,

bte 12, 1060 Brussels, Belgium. Tel: +32.2.5390037, Fax: +32.2.5392436,

<B>Changed </B>E-Mail: hontelezantenna.nl) Look out for further

details on related documents in the next edition of the PAF.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<HR>

