<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 13 Friday 31 May 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1. <I>EUROSTEP </I>FISHERIES CAMPAIGN</B> 

<P>

The Eurostep fisheries campaign was officially launched on 28

May with a very successful demonstration in front of the Council.

The Senegalese delegation, with representatives from Novib and

the Eurostep Secretariat, met the Italian Chairman of the Development

Council, spoke in front of the Development Committee at the European

Parliament, and met MEPs and officials from the DGXIV and DGVIII.

They presented their case as well as the report of a study on

the EU Fisheries policy with the West African countries, particularly

Senegal.

<P>

<B>2. FISHERIES</B> 

<P>

The European Commission is calling for a 40% reduction in fishing

activity in the Northwest Atlantic where certain fish stocks risk

being completely exhausted. The Commission has identified five

categories of fishing, one of which contain the concluded agreements

on stocks. These involve resources in third country and international

waters (beyond 200-mile limit).

<P>

<B>3. DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL - 28 MAY</B> 

<P>

The Development Council under the Presidency of Mr. Rino Serri,

Italian Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, adopted a settlement

and three common positions, UK blocking of conclusions or political

resolutions.

<UL>

<LI>The Council formally adopted the regulation on humanitarian

aid. This will provide a legal base for the activities of ECHO

which have developed to a very large extent (about MECU 750 in

1995). It also assigns clear objectives and general criteria for

humanitarian aid. It sets the procedures for implementation of

humanitarian actions conducted in co-operation with NGOs and aid

programmes financed by the Community.

<LI>The Council approved its &quot;common positions&quot; on the

3 regulations from &quot;Latin American and Asian LDCs&quot;,

&quot;fight against AIDS&quot; and &quot;environment and sustainable

development&quot;. For these three items, the UK delegation did

not bring into play its reserve in principle, arguing that the

qualified majority applied (in reality unanimity was required,

the Council having amended the Commission proposal on the controversial

item of comitology, without its agreement).

<LI>Links between emergency aid, aid to rehabilitation and long-term

development. A broad consensus was reached on the need for a link

between these three aspects of development aid which presupposes

that NGOs be involved in development action, even beyond emergency

situations.

<LI>Environmental impact assessment of development projects and

programmes. The Council held a political discussion on this subject

but did not adopt a resolution

<LI>Follow-up to Horizon 2000 resolution. The Council discussed:

a) operation coordination in the light of experience gained on

the ground, without adopting conclusions, still because of British

reservations. b) coherence between development policy and the

other Community policies at the request of the Danish delegation.

<LI>Decentralised cooperation. The Council held a discussion and

will approve conclusions as soon as possible.

<LI>Migration and development. The Council discussed the links

between certain forms of assistance to poor countries and the

increase in migratory flows.

<LI>Conflict prevention in Africa. The Council showed itself to

be largely in favour of the Commission's approach that recommends

an overall and voluntarist approach that integrates early prevention

of violent conflicts in the EU's policy for development cooperation.

</UL>



<P>

<B>The Great Lakes Region; the chocolate directive</B> 

<P>

During lunch, the ministers discussed the situation in the African

Great Lakes Region in order to draw up a first report. They expressed

their concern - notably about the situation in Burundi - and welcomed

the work accomplished by EU envoy, Mr. Ajello, whose mandate will

certainly be extended. They also expressed their support for UN

and OAU initiatives in favour of peace, and stressed that the

Union is willing to give maximum aid (whether emergency aid or

participation in reconstruction effort after peace is restored).

The cease-fire in Burundi and the creation of a control mechanism

for the movement of weapons remain, however, in the minister's

opinion, essential conditions for national reconciliation, the

establishment of lasting peace and the deployment of effective

humanitarian aid.

<P>

At the request of different delegations, the Council also tackled

the question of modifying the chocolate directive. Belgium, supported

by France, Spain and the Netherlands, stressed the need to take

into account the interests of LDC cocoa producers.

<P>

<B>4. GREAT LAKES REGION</B> 

<P>

European Commission President, Jacques Santer, and Development

Commissioner, Joao de Deus Pinheiro met former United States President

Jimmy Carter in Brussels for an exchange of views on the situation

in the Great Lakes region of Africa. Mr. Carter explained his

initiative aiming to bring about a negotiated settlement of the

conflicts in the region and said he would continue to work to

make the EU more directly involved in the peace process. The goal

is to organise a summit of the Heads of State of Rwanda, Burundi,

Tanzania, Uganda and Zaire with the participation of the EU, the

UN and the OAU. He also launched the idea of establishing a demilitarised

zone in Zaire along the border with Burundi and Rwanda to help

combat arms trafficking and to accelerate the return of refugees.

President Mobutu recently showed a positive interest in the idea.

<P>

<B>5. BURMA</B> 

<P>

The question of Burma was raised at the Development Committee

of the EP by Mrs Kinnock, PES,UK on 28 May. A representative for

the Commission said that despite the problematic incidents that

have occurred in Burma, the European Union would not break its

dialogue with the country. On the contrary, his feeling was that

the European Union would increase the dialogue with Burma as it

did after Tiananmen with China. Mrs Kinnock replied that this

was not necessarily the best example to give.

<P>

As far as economic sanctions were concerned, the representative

of the Commission doubted whether it was a good idea and questioned

whether all 15 countries of the Union would agree on that point.

<P>

On 30 May Mrs Kinnock asked for the situation in Burma to be discussed

at the meeting of the Development Committee in July (22-24 July)

for two or three hours.

<P>

It was agreed it would be one of the items on the agenda.

<P>

The British government has vetoed the EU statement on current

events in Burma. Contrary to statements from Dutch government

officials over last week-end, the blocked statement was not published

last Friday in Rome. The European Union has therefore not commented

on the crisis in Burma. Great Britain has come with its own statement,

followed by Germany and Denmark.

<P>



<HR>



<P>

<I>Eurostep</I>, 115 rue St&eacute;vin; B-1000 Brussels; Tel.

+32 2 231 16 59; Fax. +32 2 230 37 80; E-mail:eurostep@knooppunt.be

