  <h1> CHINA-DENG OBITUARY: The Long March is Finally Over </h1>

<ADDRESS>   By IPS Correspondents </ADDRESS>
<strong>BEIJING, Feb 20 (IPS) - China's last imperial dynasty had not yet  
fallen when Deng Xiaoping was born in 1904.  </strong><P>
   But the country had already flirted briefly with Western-style  
modernisation with the 100-days reforms of 1898. The reigning  
Empress Dowager was then determined not to let Western-oriented  
intellectuals ''threaten'' China's feudal institutions again. <P>
   Deng, the paramount Chinese leader died Wednesday in Beijing of  
Parkinson's disease at the age of 92.  <P>
   His death was announced by the Central Committee of the Chinese  
Communist Party, which called on the Chinese nation to unite under  
the leadership of President Jiang Zemin and continue with the  
policy of reforms ''for the building of a strong, prosperous,  
democratic, civilised and socialist China.   <P>
   State radio and television broadcast his death every hour,  
eulogising Comrade Deng. Authorities also announced the creation  
of a funeral committee of 450 members led by Party leader Jiang. <P>
   The chief architect of China's almost 20-year economic  
liberalisation programme, was born to a prosperous landowner in  
Paifungcun village in Guangan County, Sichuan province. <P>
   Almost nothing is known about his upbringing, though his Red  
Guard critics in the 1960s said he had been a ''protected child''.  
His early teen years were spent under the umbrella of his  
stepmother, his father's third wife. <P>
   After a few months of preparatory school in Chongqing, Deng  
left China at the age of 16 and with a group of more than 100  
Chinese teenagers began a work/study programme in France. He later  
said he never really went to school in France though he did  
briefly attend several secondary schools. As an unskilled worker,  
Deng held jobs in factories such as the Renault works near Paris. <P>
   Soon after arriving in France in late 1920s, Deng became active  
in the worker-student movement. He joined the Chinese communist  
youth league in 1922 and the Communist Party in 1924.  <P>
   Deng went underground when French police cracked down on  
Chinese communist students and deported their leaders in 1925. He  
left France in January 1926 to escape arrest, made his way home  
via the former Soviet Union and was assigned a series of party  
jobs on his return to China. <P>
   The early 1930s saw a bitter conflict between pro-Moscow  
faction leaders in the Chinese Communist Party and those like Deng  
who firmly stood behind the young maverick revolutionary, Mao  
Zedong, who founded the People's Republic of China in 1949. <P>
   In 1932, Deng was named director of the Party's central  
committee but was purged the following year for supporting Mao's  
policies. This was the first of the purges that Deng had to face  
in his tumultuous political career. <P>
   Still, Deng's infallible faith in Mao saw him take part in the  
Long March that began in October 1934 when Mao's revolutionary  
peasant force was kept on the move for more than a year across  
rural China then embroiled in a civil war with nationalist  
elements. <P>
	Subsequently, Deng held a series of party and military posts,  
including political commissar of the 129th Division of the Eighth  
Route Army that won key campaigns in the communists' power  
consolidation in the war against the Kuomintang and Japanese  
forces. <P>
   In the last years of the Civil War (1945-49), Red Army units  
under Deng's supervision achieved major victories in taking  
control over Nanjing, capital of the Kuomintang government,  
Shanghai and crossing the torrential Yangtse River. <P>
   Deng entered the Party's elite circle when he was elected to  
the central committee at the Seventh Party Congress in 1945 -  
where Maoist thought was firmly inscribed in the Party  
constitution and Mao's power became virtually absolute. <P>
   After Liberation in 1949, Deng was appointed the first party  
secretary and political commissar for south-west China, making him  
that region's most powerful figure. Three years later, he was made  
vice-premier and Party secretary general. He was elected to the  
Politburo and into its standing committee in 1956. <P>
   In the next two years, Deng was a leading figure in the  
crackdown on intellectuals in the ''anti-rightist campaign''. He  
called for the elimination of ''bourgeois intellectuals'' who  
advocated ''the so-called freedom of the press, freedom of  
publishing and the freedom in literature and the arts.'' <P>
   This was the first time Deng publicly expressed hardline  
political tendencies when confronted with popular calls for  
liberalisation of the system, China observers say. <P>
	Such political conservatism was later echoed against the  
Democracy Wall campaign of the 1970s and before the bloody army  
crackdown on pro-democracy protesters in Tiananmen Square in 1989  
when hundreds of students were killed,  <P>
   Initially, Deng's ability to lie low and speak only at the  
opportune moment helped him survive the political turmoil between  
the late 50s and early 70s -- an era of deadly purges under Mao's  
direction. <P>
	For example, he did not oppose the Great Leap Forward in 1958,  
until its disastrous effects were clear. Later, he said that Mao  
was ''overly enthusiastic at the time of the Great Leap Forward''  
and that ''the rest of us were overly enthusiastic as well''.  <P>
   In the early 1960s, Deng did try to remedy the setbacks of the  
period when, with then President Liu Shaoqi, he urged economic  
reforms similar to those he later adopted in the late 70s and  
early 80s. <P>
	Justifying a return to individual farming and a wage incentive  
system, he said: ''It makes no difference if the cat is black or  
white, so long as it catches mice it is a good cat.'' <P>
   Such apolitical practicality soon lost him favour with Mao who  
launched the decade long Cultural Revolution in 1966 in a  
successful attempt to regain the initiative in a power struggle.  
Deng was quickly labelled the ''second greatest capitalist roader  
in the party'' after President Liu. <P>
   In 1967, Deng was stripped of his posts and sent to a re- 
education camp, where he found himself waiting on tables in a  
Party canteen. Two years later, he was banished to Jianxi  
province, where he, his wife and his elderly stepmother lived in  
an abandoned army camp and raised their own pig and vegetables.  <P>
   Deng worked half-days in a tractor factory until 1973, when he  
was allowed to return to Beijing and regain his seat on the  
Central Committee. By 1974, Deng was entrusted to deliver a key  
address at the United Nations on Mao's 'Theory of the Three  
Worlds'. This was at a time when then Premier Zhou En-lai was  
trying to rebuild China's world image. <P>
   But it was not long after that Deng was again under ideological  
attack -- this time from Mao's ex-actress wife Qiang Qing and her  
ultra-leftist supporters. <P>
	Three months after Zhou's death in January 1976, Deng was held  
responsible for a commemorative demonstration in Tiananmen Square.  
He was again removed from his posts - Deng's third fall from power -  
though not so serious as the 1967 one. <P>
   After Mao's death later in 1976, Deng was cleared of any  
connection with the Tiananmen incident and his posts restored. At  
the important third plenary session of the 11th Central Committee  
in December 1978, Deng's political policies became the Party's  
predominant theme. <P>
   He attacked radical Maoists for preaching ''blind faith'' and  
phoney Marxism''. He asserted that ''practice is the sole  
criterion for truth'' and put forward the slogan gleaned from  
Mao's prolific writings: ''Seek truth from facts''. <P>
   In the following years, Deng eased out Hua Guofeng, Mao's  
nominal successor. In 1981, he gained Party approval for a re- 
evaluation of Mao.  <P>
   Deng once said that he did not like Mao's ''patriarchal  
behaviour.'' Mao ''really behaved in an unhealthy and feudal  
way'', Deng was quoted telling a foreign journalist in 1980.  <P>
   But he made a distinction between the ''political errors'' of  
Mao and the ''crimes'' of Lin Biao (Mao's former defence minister  
and once-favoured successor). Deng saw to it that Mao's wife and  
his closest followers were tried and sentenced to life  
imprisonment for their ''crimes''. <P>
   In 1983, Deng also launched a three-year ''rectification''  
campaign to purge leftist activists from the Cultural Revolution  
and re-educate the rank-and-file in his doctrine and policies. <P>
   By 1982, Deng had begun a thorough restructuring of the State  
Council and its ministries and in two years cut the military's  
manpower by over one million -- or one-fourth of its size. <P>
   Previously, he had announced a reform package for the rural  
economy in December 1978. A comparable programme for the urban and  
industrial sectors began in October 1984. These reversed Mao's  
programmes and redefined Marxism, in a way that befuddled his  
admirers and enraged orthodox Marxist critics.  <P>
   By 1985, Deng managed to rejuvenate the top levels of the Party  
and government with younger, better educated leaders who were  
nominally committed to his programmes.  <P>
   During this time, Deng started calling publicly for senior  
Chinese politicians to step aside from day-to-day Party activities  
to make way for the fresh talents to ''steer the country''. It was  
a signal that he intended to step behind the curtains, but still  
continue to control the Party's workings. <P>
   But he was to keep a high profile for another four years,  
overseeing displacement of his own chosen few in the ranks, such  
as party chief Zhao Ziyang, for supporting the student-led pro- 
democracy movement in 1989.  <P>
   But the manner in which the 1989 pro-democracy activists were  
suppressed generated enough heat within the country and overseas  
to curb Deng's sponsored reforms for a few years until late 1992. <P>
   The Tiananmen Square incident also hurt Deng's image as a  
benign Chinese patriarch who favoured relative political freedom  
over Maoist-style autocratic control, and accelerated the process  
of his much-awaited decision to ''retire'.'  <P>
   In November 1989, the official press carried Deng's ''letter of  
resignation'' to the Party Central Committee. ''In 1980, I had  
already proposed that...lifetime tenure (of holding senior Party  
posts) should be abolished,'' he wrote. ''In the past few years,  
many old comrades have withdrawn from their leading positions one  
after the another.'' <P>
   Despite giving up all his posts, Deng wrote that his life  
''still belonged to the Party and the state'' and that even after  
his ''retirement'', he would ''remain loyal to the cause of the  
Party and the state''.  <P>
   The moment had come for Deng Xiaoping, who had just turned 85,  
to manoeuvre himself into the post of communist China's paramount  
leader, which had been vacant since Mao's death.  <P>
   Since November 1989, Deng has been China's behind-the-scenes  
emperor, surfacing only rarely in the early 90s. At the time of  
his death, he had not been seen in public for three years. <P>
   His chosen leadership, headed by President Jiang Zemin, has  
continued to enforce market-style changes, gradually demolishing  
the centralised economic control China has known since 1949. 
(END/IPS/AP-IP/RC-AB/JS-RAL-CPG/97) 

<!-- end text -->
  </BODY>
  </HTML>
