<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Geography, Economy and Culture</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><a href="nnud_contents.html"><img align=right hspace=10 src="unicef_pix/nnud_leaf.gif"></a><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif" WIDTH="160" HEIGHT="53"><br><br><HR><BR><H1><CENTER>Geography, Economy and Culture</CENTER></H1><H3>Geography</H3>Tanzania lies on the East African coast between 1 and 11 45' south, and29 20' and 40 35' east. It covers an area of 945,166 km2 (about 42 timesthe size of Britain). Tanzania is bordered by Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundiand Zaire, Zambia, Malawi and Mozambique. Dar es Salaam is the capital,although a new, central city, Dodoma, is projected to become capital bythe end of the century.<BR><BR>Tanzania's name signifies the union between Tanganyika and the two islandsof Unguja and Pemba, which with several other smaller islands constituteZanzibar.<BR><BR>Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania cover a vast, flat plateau which rises to about1,500m from a narrow coastal belt. The region is famous for the 20 millionyear old Great Rift Valley which cuts a deep trough up to 2,000m deep throughthe plateau from the Dead Sea to Mozambique.<BR><BR>East Africa's highest mountains are volcanic in origin, created by the sameforces which created the Rift Valley. Kilimanjaro, the highest mountainin Africa, is the most recent of these. Ngorongoro Crater is the collapsedcaldera of a volcano. One active volcano remains in Tanzania - Ol DoinyoLengai.<BR><BR>Tanzania is bordered by three great lakes: Lake Victoria in the north, LakeTanganyika to the west and Lake Nyasa to the south-west. Lake Victoria isthe source of the Nile.<BR><BR><H3>Climate</H3>Most of Tanzania has a tropical climate with regional variations. The coastalbelt and Lakes Nyasa and Tanganyika are hot and humid while most of theinterior is hot and dry. October to April are hotter than May to Septemberwith November to May being the rainy season.<BR><H3>Economy</H3>77% of the population live a subsistence lifestyle in the countryside. Maize,millet (sorghum) and cassava are the staple crops, along with rice. Theyare used to make a stiff dough called ugali (oo-gar-ly). Ugali or rice,is eaten with green leaf vegetables, meat: beef, chicken or goat or fish.Avocados, apples, bananas, mangoes, passion fruit, pears, pineapples, onions,plantain, tomatoes, carrots, red beans, peanuts and sugar cane are grown.Many farmers keep cattle, for milk and meat, and goats and chickens.<BR><BR>The country's major exports are coffee, cotton, cashew nuts, sisal, tobacco,tea and diamonds. Zanzibar and Pemba export cloves and other spices. Gold,tin and coal are also mined.<BR><BR>External debt: US$ 4.6 million<BR>Debt service as % of exports of goods and services: 30<BR><BR><h3>Culture</h3>The country has a rich culture of music and dancing with many ceremonies.Carving, pottery and weaving are traditional crafts still practised to providegoods for everyday life, with many local variations in design.<BR><BR><HR>&copy;Copyright: UNICEF 1996 <HR><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif"WIDTH="45" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom>Unicef Home Page</A><HR></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
