<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">

<TITLE>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 35</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<pre>



</pre>



<CENTER></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 35 Friday 31 January 1997

</CENTER></H3>

<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></H4><A HREF="index.html">EUROSTEP Home Page</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. ECHO'S NEW DIRECTOR SPELLS OUT HIS INTENTIONS

TO MEPS</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The new Director of the European Community Humanitarian

Office, ECHO, Alberto Navarro, presented his plans before the

Development Committee of the European Parliament last week. Mr

Navarro confirmed that at a political level he was in agreement

with his Commissioner Emma Bonino, stressing that ECHO's purpose

was not to compensate for the lack of political solutions or will

in a region in crisis because humanitarian assistance could never

replace preventive diplomatic actions. He stated that in the near

future, ECHO's priorities would continue to be intervention in

Rwanda, Burundi, Zaire and in the former Yugoslavia and Caucasus

as well as assistance to women and children in Afghanistan. Mr.

Navarro added, that for the first time, the Commission will, in

February, present the Council with a strategic plan of ECHO's

activities.  </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The Director responded to the criticism of the rigid

nature of ECHO's agreement concluded with the 170 NGOs responsible

for implementing European aid on the ground, stating that ECHO

undertook to show flexibility and openness towards NGOs within

the limits of the rigorous financial management inherited from

his predecessor. He added that the framework/agreement, which

has been extended to May, will be reviewed this year. In response

to the MEPS queries on the cost of running ECHO, he emphasised

that in 1997 ECHO had been allocated a budget of  650 million

ECU. This corresponds to only 2% of the agriculture budget.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. ECHO COMMISSIONER IN ZAIRE EVALUATE OBSTACLES

TO THE RESUMPTION OF HUMANITARIAN AID</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> ECHO Commissioner, Emma Bonnino, is off on a four

day trip to Zaire today. She will assess the humanitarian situation,

logistical needs and the problems that need to be resolved to

allow aid to reach the Eastern part of the country. She is accompanied

by a delegation from ECHO and will visit Kinshasa and Kinsagagni

as well as the refugee camps recently set up in the region. Before

her departure, Mrs Bonino stated that she was counting on the

co-operation from the Zairian authorities to guarantee access

to the hundred thousand ill and starving refugees recently located

by NGOs.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT CALLS FOR MORE INTEGRATED

HUMANITARIAN AND DEVELOPMENT POLICIES           </FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>MEPs from the Development

Committee this week called for greater co-ordination of humanitarian

aid between the Community and its Member States, the UN Agencies

and the regrouping of external services of the EC. The MEPs on

the basis of the Raimondo Fassa Report called for the following

reforms: 1) the integration of diplomacy and humanitarian intervention

capacity with commercial and development aid policies in the Common

Foreign and Security Policy 2) the creation of a European Corps

made up of civilian and military units, in co-operation with the

WEU, responsible for peace keeping/making operations; 3) the creation

of a European research centre for the active prevention of crises;

4) the setting up of a permanent international criminal court;

5) fuller social participation and integration of local populations

to encourage democracy; 6) European monitoring of arms exports

and; 7) a clearer definition of the conditionally of European

aid. </FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>In a separate debate

on the work of the ACP/EU Joint Assembly, the Development Committee

called for an improvement of EU/ACP co-operation. On the basis

of a report prepared by Ms. Monica Baldi (Italy, UPE), the Committee

called for a) the European Development Fund to be incorporated

into the general budget to ensure EP scrutiny; b) the continuation

of the assessment of the right of intervention; c)the inclusion

of the Joint Assembly in discussions and negotiations on the future

of EU/ACP co-operation. </FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. EP CALLS FOR THE DENIAL OF ASYLUM IN THE COMMUNITY

TO TERRORISTS FROM MEMBER STATES</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> MEPs adopted a report on the fight against terrorism

by an overwhelming majority yesterday. The report drafted by Christian

Democrat Vivian Reding called for, inter alia, nationals of Member

States accused of terrorism to be denied the right to asylum or

refugee status in other Member States. This was with the aim of

introducing in the EU Treaty, &quot;effective principles for close

co-operation in the field of judicial assistance, as a crucial

component in  the fight against terrorism and other forms of organised

crime.&quot;<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. EUROSTEP MEETINGS WITH TOP OFFICIALS ON THE

GREEN PAPER</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The Chair of the Eurostep Steering Committee, Sabina

Siniscalchi of Mani Tese, along with fellow Eurostep members Phil

Bloomer and Brendan Gomerly of OXFAM UK and Simon Stocker - Director

of the Eurostep Secretariat, met with DG VIII Commissioner, Joao

de Deus Pinheiro, on 23 January 1997. The objectives of the meeting

were: to present Eurostep as serious player in discussions on

the future EU-ACP relationship; to press the main issues on the

Eurostep agenda for these debates; to establish a stronger political

entry into the Commission; and to offer help facilitate possibilities

for debate and consultation following the Green Paper.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Later on 28 January, Eurostep, the EC Liaison Committee,

APRODEV and Voice were invited to a meeting with Danish Minister

of Development Paul Nielsen and members of the Danish Foreign

Affairs Committee for an exchange of views on the future of EU

development policies in general and the Commission's Green Paper

in particular.  Eurostep was represented by Brita S. Nielson.

<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>6. EU ENVIRONMENT COUNCIL DOCUMENTS CONCERNING

BRIEFING ON DUTCH PRESIDENCY FOR NGOS.</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> As promised in last week's PAF here are the documents

concerning the European Environment Bureau/Dutch Presidency briefing

for NGOs on 18 February in Brussels. They are:</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>the Environment Council's - &quot;Preparation of

the 5th session of the Commission on Sustainable Development and

of the United Nations General Assembly Special Session&quot; (No.

12713/96) (This should be available in your Ministry in your national

language) an EC Communiqu&eacute; COM(96) 569 final and background

paper- SEC(96) 2069.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>7. POSTPONEMENT OF DEADLINE FOR PHARE AND TACIS

PROGRAMME</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The CEV has been instructed to inform you that the

EC Direction of DG 1A has moved the deadline for the submission

of projects for the above mentioned programme from 31 January

1997 - 1300 Hrs. to 30 April 1997 - 1300 Hrs.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<HR>

<H6><I>Updated on February 12, 1997<BR>

</I>Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the

Netscape browser. Please address comments to <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">EUROSTEP</A>

(Yvette Pierret)</H6>

<HR>



</BODY>

</HTML>

