<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 15 Friday 14 June 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1 EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT ACCEPTS DEAL WITH MOROCCO</B>

<P>

On Friday 7 June the European Parliament voted to accept the Euro-Mediterranean

agreement with Morocco.  The vote is seen as a great dissapontment

to many who were hoping for a clear rejection of the deal on the

grounds of the human rights situation in Morocco.  The basis of

the debate was a report to the Parliament which advised that the

agreement has great political and geostrategic importance.  Mr

Bernard Kouchner said in the debate that a 'yes' given hesitantly

would be more useful in the long run than an outright rejection.

 Although only the Greens and European United Left groups actually

voted against the agreement (65 votes against compared to 263

for), most of the members who spoke voiced some criticism of the

situation in Morocco.  MEPs criticised the continuing human rights

abuses and the failure of Morocco to give constructive support

to the settlement of the conflict in Western Sahara, an initative

started by the United Nations.

<P>

The vote was overshadowed by the recent history of the expansion

of the European Union's agreements with its neighbours, especially

the free trade agreement with Turkey which was approved by the

Parliament in December last year.  A similar logic was applied

on that occassion where the Parliament felt that engagement would

be more useful than rejection.  

<P>

<B><a href="reality.htm">REALITY OF AID</a></B>

<P>

The 1996 edition of <I>Reality of Aid</I> will be launched on

Monday 17 June.  The report aims to give a critique from an NGO

perspective and has a growing reputation as an accessible reference

for information and trends in official developlent aid and donor

policies.  The central theme for the 1996 <I>Reality of Aid</I>

is the eradication of poverty.

<P>

Key points highlighted in the report include the continuing reductions

in the aid budget of major donors and the difference between the

rhetoric and reality of donor policies.  Although every donor

(except the USA) has reaffirmed its commitment to the UN aid target

of 0.7% of GDP within the last five years, 8 out of 21 donors

cut their aid as a percentage of GDP in 1995.  

<P>

Figures published for the first time in 1995 reveal almost unbelievably

small expenditures on basic education (0.1% of total aid) and

basic health (0.3%).  The average amount spent by donors on water

and sanitation is just 4%.

<P>

<I>Reality of Aid</I> is published by Earthscan for Eurostep and

ICVA.  Not only is it being lauched simultaneously in Brussels

and Washington on Monday, but there will also be launches in many

other places including the Netherlands, Spain, Italy, Australia,

Canada, Vietnam, Nepal, Zimbabwe, Fiji and India.  It is designed

so that agencies can disseminate the report as widely as possible

and use it as an advocacy tool to highlight dwindling aid budgets

and the impact on the poor.

<P>

<B>3 EURO - AFRICA SUMMIT FOR AID</B>

<P>

The idea of a summit meeting between European and African countries

has been put forward as a means of revitalising the interest of

the european public in the EU's aid policies.  The suggestion

came from European Development Commissioner Jaoa de Deus Pinheiro.

 He said that the meeting, to be held in 1997, would throw open

the debate over the future of the Lom&eacute; convention and encourage

'people-driven' renegotiation.  Mr Pinheiro also hoped that the

Commissions green paper on Lom&eacute;, to be published in October

this year, would have a similar effect.

<P>

The Commission is evidently worried by the Eurobarometer poll,

which was mentioned in the PAF two weeks ago.  This survey of

the opinions of people across Europe showed that 'helping people

in poor countries in Asia, Africa, and South America' had slipped

down the list of priorities.  

<P>

<B>4 CONFERENCE ON RELATIONS BEYOND LOME IV</B>

<P>

Today is the last day of a conference on the future of relations

between European Union and ACP countries.  The conference is organised

in Maastricht by the European Centre for Development Policy Management

and started on Wednesday of this week.  The idea was to provide

an interface between the EU Commision and representatives of member

states with the views of all others interested in the negotiations

including NGOs, private sector, university etc.

<P>

<B>5 SOCIALISTS OPEN DEVELOPMENT DEBATE</B>

<P>

On 11 July the Socialist Group of the European Parliament is beginning

a series of talks with representatives from developing countries

over the European Union's development policy.  The discussions

will include issues such as the future of the Lom&eacute; convention,

the targetting of EU assistance to the poorest countries etc.

 These talks will continue until October of this year and will

culminate in some sort of socialist summit meeting, the exact

nature of which has not yet been announced.

<P>

<B>6 Publications</B>

<P>

<I>The Gendered Economy</I> - a study on the global economy from

a gender perspective.  The book examines the link between feminism

and economics. Available by depositing US$10 in account number

630495491 in the name of Stichting Ondersteuning Vrouwenberaad

Nederlandse at the General Bank, The Hague, Netherlands, reference

'the Gendered Economy'

<P>

<I>Women and War, Women and Peace</I> - new information pack on

the impact of militarism on womens lives.  Contains an activists

guide to campaigning and a directory of international womens groups.

 Available for &#163;3 from National Peace Council, 88 Islington

High Street, London N1 8EG.<HR>



