<H1><CENTER>BRITISH AID BACKS CHINESE AIRPORT CONTRACT </CENTER>
</H1>
<BR>
4 December 1995 <BR>
<B><BR>
The ODA is to provide an aid grant of up to &#163;8.4 million in support
of a Siemens Plessey contract to supply &#163;22.5 million of British goods
and services for the now international airport at Nanjing, China. Tho grant
comes from the Aid and Trade Provision budget. The balance of the total
project cost, some &#163;139 million, vall be raisod by the Governmentof
China. </B><BR>
<BR>
A new international airport is being built south of Nanjing, the capital
of Jiangsu Province, to replace the existing airport, which is unable to
meet the projected traffic demands of the city.<BR>
<BR>
Nanjing is an important economic centre, with major electronics, automobile
and chemical industries. It is planned that the city should also be developed
as a research and development centre for new technologies. Transport and
communications, and the new airport in particular, are seen as vital to
such expansion.<BR>
<BR>
It is expected that the new airport will bring times-savings for passengers,
boost export and tourist earnings and raise revenue from users. <BR>
<BR>
The contract will include:
<UL>
<LI>the design of the new airport's operating systems; <BR>
<BR>
<LI>the supply and installation of equipment and spare parts;<BR>
<BR>
<LI>and the transfer of technology for the operation and maintenance of
the systems and equipment installed. 
</UL>
<BR>
To ensure the successful operation of the project, the ODA is also providing
up to &#163;l million to train local staff in airport operations and management,
and for environmental management and land use plans. <BR>
<BR>
<B>NOTES FOR EDITORS </B><BR>
<BR>
1 . Under the terms of the arrangement, the ODA grant will meet 35 per cent
of the cost of the &#163;22.6 million UK contract. The balance of 66 per
cent to be financed on commercial terms. <BR>
<BR>
2. The UK banks West Merchant Bank Limited and Standard Chartered Bank are
providing the &#163;22.6 million loan, supported by the Export Credits Guarantee
Department. <BR>
<BR>
3. This is the largest ATP grant made under the &#163;55 million Third Concessional
Financing Arrangement between Britain and China signed in September 1994.
A Fourth Concessional Financing Arrangement was announced by the Foreign
Secretary in October 1995 for a total contract value of up to &#163;l00
million.<BR>
<BR>
4. The contact at Siemens Plessey is Mr Keith Damen (Tel: 01202 486344)
<BR>
