<head>
<title> THE GAMBIA</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> THE GAMBIA</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/gambia.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=350 height=200 alt="Map of The Gambia">
<p>
<br>
<p>
<b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	1.13 million

<p>Population growth rate	3.2% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	234
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with	77%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	35.6%
<br clear=left>
<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID began work in The Gambia in 1979 and now has three programme areas. They are all linked
by the common aim, best summed up by the word tesito  or self-help. 

<p>ACTIONAID now works in partnership with more than 178,000 people in 500 plus villages helping them
to tackle their needs in practical and lasting ways. 

<p>While each area faces its own difficulties, one problem is shared by all: inadequate food supply.
Drought and persistent poverty have forced people to cut down forests for fuel and over-work the
land. This leads to poor yields and low incomes, locking families into a downward spiral of debt and
deprivation.

<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work in The Gambia</h3><b>ACTIONAID has:</b> 

<p><ul><li>provided assistance to households and communities in developing income generating
projects. These include bee-keeping schemes, river fishing, and vegetable gardening with many of the
projects run by women. 

<p><li>supported visits by healthcare workers to rural villages to monitor children's development and
teach mothers simple, effective ways of treating potentially fatal diseases such as diarrhoea.
ACTIONAID is also training village-based healthworkers to teach villagers about preventative
healthcare. It is developing the skills of traditional midwives and, by constructing latrines and
sinking new wells, working to improve sanitation and hygiene.

<p><li>supplemented the government education programme  by building schools, training teachers and
supplying basic equipment such as chalk, pencils and books.
</ul>
</font>

