<html>
<head>
<title>ODA - Jan 95</title>
<!!keys: Overseas Development Administration+books+literacy>
</head>
<body>

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by</i> <a href="oda_info.html">Overseas Development Administration</a>
<hr>
<h2>Learning for life</h2>
<p>
Kamala's parents in Andhra Pradesh cannot help with her homework. Like almost half the people in this part of India they are illiterate. But six-year-old Kamala has opportunities her parents never had. She goes to school regularly now thanks to the ODA's largest education project - the Andhra Pradesh Primary Education Project. 
So far over 3,000 classrooms have been built and over 165,000 teachers have been trained and there are signs that fewer children are dropping out of school. 
<p>
Over the last decade many developing countries have spent their money on more immediate needs. But education, especially literacy, is one of the cornerstones of development.  Skills like literacy and numeracy change the way people see their world and help them to learn about vital issues such as health, political and social life, and the environment. 
<p>
A good basic education also equips people for further training and fulfilling work and enables them to play a more constructive role in the community. Educated girls and women can make informed choices about how many children they really want. 
In 1994, about half the world's children had had less than four years in primary school. Millions of people in developing countries do not learn to read or write. Dilapidated schoolrooms, badly trained teachers and poor learning materials hold children back even when they do attend class.  
<p>
The ODA is working harder than ever to help developing countries overcome these problems.  In 1993/94, total aid for education came to £117 million. This money is distributed according to a new global policy on education. Its driving force is support for basic education for children and adults.<p>
<p>
<b>New projects agreed under the policy include:</b>
<p>
<ul><li>in Zambia, a £12 million project aimed at raising standards of education in primary and secondary schools
<p>  
<li>in Egypt, a £2.5 milllion adult literacy project aimed specifically at women.
</ul><p> 
The ODA works, in concert with other donors, to help improve national education systems. It aims to help countries find ways of reaching the whole population, including disadvantaged groups like  young girls and people living in remote areas.
<p>
The ODA also funds training ranging from teaching to car mechanics, either in Britain or in developing countries. In 1993/94, the ODA supported the studies of over 10,000 overseas students in Britain. Although it is not a priority within its overall education policy, the ODA also helps universities and institutes overseas as well to improve their performance or management, or  increase the number of women students.
<p>
<b>Books</b>
<br>
Books - classroom basics - are in such short supply in some countries that 'book famines' are common. Britain helps keep book supplies steady in developing countries in several ways. 
<p>
The ODA gives some books directly to developing countries to fill specific gaps - several thousand college-level agricultural textbooks, for example. For a few decades the ODA has also supported the Educational Low-priced Books Scheme, which sells British textbooks at low prices to overseas students, and Book Aid International (formerly the Ranfurly Library Service) which distributes a broad range of donated books free to developing countries. 
<p>
In 1993/94 the ODA gave £216,000 and £15,000, respectively, to these programmes.
<p>
The British Council manages most of the ODA's education and training projects. It also receives a large grant to pay for its other activities in support of ODA's mission.
<p>
<b>Adult literacy</b>
<br>
Learning to read and write can often lift adults out of poverty to a new status, income and independence. The ODA funds many projects that encourage adult literacy, ranging from distance learning for people in isolated areas with no schools, to support for non-governmental organisations working at community level. 
<p>
In Malawi fewer than half the girls enrol in school and there is one teacher for every 80 pupils. The ODA is working closely with the US Agency for International Development and the World Bank on a seven year project to improve the availability of primary school education for girls and generally raise the quality of education.  
<p>
British experts help developing countries to write, produce and publish their own textbooks that meet local needs. In Jamaica, for example, teams of teachers on the Secondary Schools Textbook Project are writing materials for pupils who have difficulty reading English. Textbooks cover mathematics, English, science and social studies. Britain supports similar projects in Sierra Leone and Jordan.
<hr>
©Copyright Overseas Development Administration January 1995

