<HTML>



<HEAD>



<TITLE>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 24 </TITLE>



</HEAD>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 24 Friday 18 October</CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<P>

<B>1. SADC/EU SIGN NEW REGIONAL INDICATIVE PROGRAMME FOR SOUTHERN

AFRICA </B>

<P>

 Stefan Smidt, European Commission Director-General for Development

and Kaire Mbuende, Executive Secretary of the South African Development

community, SADC, signed a Regional Indicative Programme worth

121 ECU last Tuesday in Windhoek at the EU SADC ministerial conference.

The Programme seeks to promote the development of infrastructures

and services, trade, investment and finance and promotion of intra-regional

exchanges of information and macroeconomics issues. An annex to

the Programme providing additional funds from the European Investment

Bank, EIB, for regional investment projects in the areas of energy,

water supply, telecommunication, transport, industrial development

and the strengthening of the private sector was also signed by

Mr Mbuende and EIB Financing Director Louis Biancarelli. 

<P>

 Dick Spring, the Irish Foreign Minister and EU Council President

described the SADC region as, &quot;one of the top ten most important

markets of the future&quot; adding, &quot;the region has the potential

to make an important contribution to the development of Africa

as a whole&quot;.

<P>

<B>2. EU ENVOY EXPRESSES HOPE FOR RWANDAN REFUGEES</B>

<P>

 Mr. Aldo Ajello, the EU's Special Envoy to the Great Lakes Region

voiced his hope that positive results would emerge from the new

approach set out in Geneva last week by the UN High Commissioner

for Refugees and countries assisting the 16 million Rwandan refugees

in Zaire and Tanzania. Mr Ajello who is currently on tour in the

Great Lakes Region stated that the action plan could only be successful

if there is co-operation between the international community and

interested countries, especially those directly concerned. He

added &quot;the human, financial and political cost is no longer

bearable&quot;. 

<P>

<B>3. EU THROWS ITS WEIGHT BEHIND EAST AFRICAN SUMMIT ON PEACE

IN BURUNDI</B>

<P>

 The European Union has pledged that it will do all it can to

move the peace process forward in Burundi as the leaders of Ethiopia,

Kenya, Tanzania, Rwanda, Uganda and Zaire prepared for a summit

on Burundi on 12 October in Tanzania. The region's leaders are

considering whether the sanctions they imposed on Burundi after

the military coup this year should be extended or eased.

<P>

 The EU main contribution so far has been in backing Central and

East African nation politically and providing humanitarian and

financial to the countries in the region. Since 1995 the EU has

pledged 5.5 million ECU for health programmes, 2.4 million ECU

for the country's treasury, 700 000 ECU for human rights and democracy.<B>

</B>The EU Humanitarian Aid Commissioner has also appealed to

European lawyers to help restore Burundi's judicial system after

appeals from the Bujumbura government, but so far no European

lawyers have gone to the region. 

<P>

 Current EU proposals stop just short of sending personnel to

the region. Last month at a meeting with Tanzanian ex-president

Julius Nyerere, the UN-appointed mediator for the region, Dick

Spring, President of the EU Council of Ministers ruled out the

possibility of sending EU peacekeepers to Burundi. He stated that

there was no military solution to the problem. The Commission's

own office in Bujumbura is only manned by secretaries as the delegates

wait in Europe for security conditions to improve. 

<P>

<B>4. EU PRESIDENCY STOPS SHORT OF PRAISING POLITICAL REFORMS

 IN GAMBIA</B>

<P>

 The Irish Presidency of the EU on 15 October published a declaration

on the political reforms in Gambia. The Union welcomed the peaceful

passing of  presidential elections and congratulated the Provisional

Independent Electoral Commission (PIEC) for its role in the elections.

It however, voiced its regret &quot;that recommendations drawn

by the PIEC ignored and that conditions which would have ensured

free and fair elections were not met.&quot; 

<P>

 The Declaration called on the Gambian authorities to &quot;take

all necessary measures so that parliamentary elections due on

11 December 1996 meet the guidelines established by PIEC.&quot;

<P>

<B>5. EU CONTEMPLATES FURTHER SANCTIONS AGAINST BURMA UNDER CFSP</B>

<P>

 The EU Council President and Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring

told the Irish Parliament last week that the European Union is

considering imposing further sanctions on Burma after the Burmese

government's lack of response to the EU's legitimate concerns.

 Mr Spring said that the issue had been raised by the Common Foreign

and Security Policy, CFSP, working group and the Commission was

considering the suspension of trade benefits Burma enjoys under

the Generalized System of Preferences. This comes after Mr. Spring's

meeting with Burma Foreign Minister Ohn Gyaw in parallel with

the UN General Assembly on 26 September. Mr. Spring added that

the EU has also asked a special UN working group on arbitrary

detention and imprisonment to be allowed into Burma to investigate

circumstances surrounding the death of Danish Consul, Mr. Nichols

and for the UN Commissioner for Human Rights to take action on

the situation in Burma. 

<P>

<B> </B>The situation in Burma will be discussed on 22 and 23

October at the European Parliament in Strasbourg. 

<P>

<B>6. EU HUMANITARIAN OFFICE SHORTLISTS 18 TV AND RADIO REPORTS

FOR ITS AWARDS</B>

<P>

 The Selection Committee of TV and Radio Awards of the European

Community's Humanitarian Office shortlisted 18 TV and radio reports

for rewards. The ECHO awards are given to best reports on humanitarian

subjects. Emma Bonino, the European Commissioner explaining the

practice stated, &quot;with daily reports of humanitarian crises,

and concern about the loss of Iraq and Burma, to name but three

- a 'victim' can appear as just another face, another statistic.

Documentary reporting brings these statistics and faces to life,

making their fears and concerns real (...) This is why the ECHO

awards were created, to recognise the vital role that is played

by broadcasters in bringing to the public awareness issues and

situations which would otherwise go largely ignored.&quot; 

<P>

 A judging panel will meet in Brussels on 7 November  to choose

the winners who will be presented with their awards on 9 December

in the presence of  Emma Bonino and Irish President Mary Robins.

<P>

<B>7. ATD/FOURTH WORLD PRESENT REPORT ON POVERTY ON WORLD ANTI-POVERTY

DAY&quot; IN BRUSSELS</B>

<P>

 Last Thursday, 17 October,  ATD/Fourth World presented the General

Report on Poverty at a procession titled World Anti Poverty Day.

The Report was drawn up at the request of the Belgian government

and published at the beginning of the year. The ATD, who sponsored

the procession,  recalled the message its founder, Father J. Wresinski,

gave before 100 000 persons demonstrating for human rights in

Paris in 1987: Slavery has been abolished. Poverty can be abolished

also.&quot; The United Nations has proclaimed 1996 the &quot;International

Year for the Abolition of Poverty&quot;  



<P>

<HR>

<H6><I>Updated on November 5, 1996<BR>

