<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>PAF5</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">



<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 12 Friday 24 May 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1 <I>EUROSTEP</I> FISHERIES CAMPAIGN GOES PUBLIC</B> 

<P>

<I>Eurostep</I> will stage a public event in front of the European

Council offices in Brussels on Tuesday 28 May the day of the meeting

of the Development Council. The purpose is to raise awareness

of the fisheries issue and of the <I>Eurostep</I> campaign. The

delegation, which includes three representatives of the fishing

community in Senegal, will present a report to the Chairman of

the Development Council. The report &quot;The Fight for Fish:

Towards Fair Fisheries Agreements&quot; has been produced by NOVIB

and is now available in both English and French. After a one hour

demonstration on the street the party will move off to the <I>Eurostep</I>

office for a press conference.

<P>

Over the following two days the delegation will have a packed

schedule of engagements which includes an address to the Development

Committee of the European Parliament, and high level meetings

at both DG VIII and DG XIV.

<P>

<B>2 THE FUTURE OF THE LOME CONVENTION</B> 

<P>

The working group on the negotiations for the future of Lom&eacute;

beyond the year 2000 is meeting in the <I>Eurostep</I> office

today. Meanwhile, the Commissioner for relations with ACP countries

and South Africa Mr. Joao de Deus Pinheiro has been dropping hints

about the current thought processes within the Commission. At

a press conference on 21 May Mr. Pinheiro gave the results of

a public opinion survey on how Europeans perceive developing countries.

The survey - called the Eurobarometer - shows that the place of

development cooperation in the list of priorities of European

people has fallen since the last survey in 1991 (it is now in

tenth place). However, the good news for Mr. Pinheiro is that

the public do seem to believe that the EU is a particularly appropriate

institution to work in this domain. The public ranked development

cooperation fourth in their list of privileged fields of action

for the EU. The three areas felt even more appropriate for a European

level response were relations with the countries of Central and

Eastern Europe, the fight against unemployment, and defense policy.

<P>

As for the thought processes leading up to the end of Lom&eacute;

IV, Mr. Pinheiro confirmed that the reflection group which has

been established in the Commission will be producing a green paper

by the end of October. However &quot;the green paper will not

be a book of answers but a book of questions&quot; he said and

he gave examples of the question which were being asked -

<UL>

<LI>What will be the impact of the private sector in development?

<LI>Will the same cooperation instruments be applied to all countries

and to all geographical areas?

<LI>Should one separate the Caribbean and the Pacific from Sub-Saharan

Africa?

</UL>



<P>

Following presentation of the green paper the Commission will

work towards adopting a formal communication in 1997. The actual

negotiations for the new convention will begin in 1998.

<P>

<B>3 GREAT LAKES DEVELOPMENT MEETING</B> 

<P>

The United Nations Non-Governmental liaison service in Geneva

reports in its magazine <I>GO Between</I> that there will be a

governmental level conference in Kinshasa on June 10 to 14 to

discuss development projects for the Great Lakes region. NGOs

are welcome to attend the proceedings, as are regional

<P>

cooperation institutions, the private sector, and investors. The

conference will bring together the governments of Burundi, Rwanda,

Tanzania, Uganda, and Zaire.

<P>

We do not have any further information to give you except that

the official UN contact for the conference is the Multinational

Programming and Operational Centre of the United Nations Economic

Commission for Africa in Addis Ababa, telephone + 251 1 515 827,

fax + 251 1 515 907.

<P>

<B>4 HABITAT II</B> 

<P>

The United Nations Conference on Human Settlements - otherwise

known as Habitat II - will be taking place in the first two weeks

of June in Istanbul. The Women's Environment and Development Organisation

(WEDO) based in New York has formed a women's caucus to focus

efforts to influence the discussions at the conference. The caucus

has been lobbying the conference preparatory process in order

to influence the agenda and is offering facilities at Habitat

II itself including daily de-briefings and a special &quot;super-coalition

tent&quot; for 500 people to be a home from home for the conference's

women. They will give an orientation to the women's caucasus process

at the outset of the conference on Sunday 2 June at the NGO forum

in Istanbul. You can contact them in New York - telephone + 1

212 759 7982 or fax + 1 212 759 8647

<P>

<B>5 Health</B> 

<P>

Following on from last week's alternative PAF, we are glad to

say that the health of Peter Bastogi continues to improve. He

is now able to breathe without the help of a respirator and is

left with a much reduced infection. This is good news. <HR>



