<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 29 Friday 6 December 1996

</CENTER></H3>

<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. EU HUMANITARIAN AID FOR REFUGEES IN FORMER

YUGOSLAVIA<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The European Commission's Humanitarian Office, ECHO,

has approved a humanitarian aid package worth 85 million ECU for

refugees, displaced persons and vulnerable groups in the former

Yugoslavia (Bosnia, Croatia, Federal Yuigoslav Republic). The

programme which is primarily made up of food, hygiene supplies,

shelter and psycho-social assistance for the most vulnerable people

is to be implemented by NGOs, UN specialised agencies as well

as the Commission. The Commission will also assist in the reconstruction

of housing and basic social infrastructures in Bosnia and Herzegovina.

This is in order to encourage refugees and displaced persons to

return to original homes.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>According to the Commission almost one million people

are still displaced within Bosnia-Herzegovina while a million

others are refugees outside the country. The figure in Croatia

is 350 000. The ECHO programme in collaboration with the United

Nations Transitional Authority for Eastern Slovenia will focus

on the needs of the peoples of Eastern Slovenia. Within the Federal

Yugoslavia aid will go to the estimated 500 000 Croatian and Bosnian

refugees. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. COMMISSION ADOPTS GREEN PAPER ON FUTURE OF

ACP/EU RELATIONS<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The European Commission last week adopted its &quot;Green

Paper&quot; on the reassessment of EC/ACP relations. The Commission

deems it necessary to encourage wide debate on the relationship,

as the Lom&eacute; 1V Convention - the main framework of co-operation

between the two groups, nears its end in the year 2000.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The Paper raises the following pertinent issues -

a) whether the present vast diverse ACP grouping of states should

be maintained, giving that the grouping is neither an economic,

political or geographical entity; b) improving competitiveness

and reinforcement of the private sector; c) the role and workings

of the State; d) how the current system of trade preferences to

improve the ACP States ability to profit from the system. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The underlying points running throughout the Paper

are i. the need for greater efficacy or in other words a results

based approach to co-operation; ii. a greater role for the civil

society and the creation of 'investment friendly' environment;

iii. the differentiation of response to the different needs of

the ACP States receiving aid. This implies more flexible aid instruments

and 'positive discrimination' for the least developed countries.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>Debate on the Green Paper will go on for a year and

a half resulting in a Commission negotiation brief for the talks

with the ACP States which begin in 1998. EC Commissioner for Development,

Joao de Deus Pinheiro, said, &quot;We must have the courage to

examine everything, except our political commitment and our solidarity

towards the ACP countries&quot;. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. MOVEMENTS IN COMMISSION DEPARTMENTS<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>In line with its reorganisation and rationalisation

of management, the European Commission has reshuffled a number

of its senior officials and made a few new appointments in top

positions. Steffen Smidt the former Director General of Development

becomes Director General of Personnel replacing the retiring Frans

de Koster and Director General for Information and Culture, Collette

Flesh, becomes Director General of the Translation Service. Michel

vanden Abeele the former head of Commissioner Karel van Miert's

cabinet replaces Heinrich von Moltke as Director General for Business

and Tourism Policy who resigned after a series of fraud allegations

in his department.<B> </B>The former Spanish representation to

the EU, Luis Romero Requena and Anthony Wright, formerly responsible

for financial issues in the Agricultural Directorate General are

new appointees to the Directorate General for Budgets.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. SWISS PARLIAMENTARIANS APPEAL TO WTO OVER MARGINALISED

COUNTRIES <BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>A delegation of Swiss Members of Parliament met with

Renato Ruggiero, Director General of the World Trade Organisation,

WTO, on Monday 2 December, to present an open letter expressing

their wish that the WTO makes the marginalisation of poor countries

the top priority at the forthcoming WTO Ministerial Conference

from 9-13 December. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The letter calls for the halving of all trade barriers

facing the least developed countries by the year 2000. The MPs

also say that the participation of NGOs is important in providing

broad support for the WTO and call for further steps to be taken

to allow NGOs to participate more fully in the WTO's work. The

Parliamentarians' letter, in addition, calls for the creation

of a WTO parliament composed of individual members from the parliaments

of WTO member countries.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>Finally the MP's emphasise the need for evidence

that WTO trade regulations are of benefit to all and have no adverse

effects on poorer countries and the environment. They argue that

if the rich countries are the prime beneficiaries of WTO trade

regulations resulting in an increase in global disparities in

wealth, the legitimacy of the work of the WTO will be undermined.

<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. SUPPLIERS OF BANANAS TO EU SET OUT A COMMON

POSITION BUT GUATEMALA DISAGREES<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>A meeting of traditional suppliers of banana to the

EU held in the Canary Islands from the 18-22 November focused

on the Community system governing the import of bananas. Following

the explanation of their positions in the WTO, producers from

Europe, the ACP and Latin America adopted a joint declaration

stressing that &quot;an orderly and regulated market such as the

one in the EU, ensures higher prices&quot;. Guatemalan producers

however disagreed with the statement. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>Another declaration was also signed by Latin American

producers' associations from Costa Rica, Columbia, Nicaragua,

Venezuela and Ecuador concerning the Latin American Banana Producers'

Association.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT TO ADOPT 1997 EU BUDGET

AND DEBATE COMMISSION'S WORK PLAN<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>At its second reading the European Parliament is

to adopt the EU budget for 1997. It will, in addition, continue

the debate on the Commission's work programme. The Parliament

will also present is Sakharov Award for freedom of thinking to

Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>6. NEW PUBLICATIONS</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The latest edition of <B>DIALOGUE,</B> the monthly

journal concerned with Rwandan issues, reviews a number of publications

on the role of women in Rwandan society. Among the publications

reviewed in this edition are -<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=2>La Femme Rwandaise dans la Gestion des Conflits

et la Reconstruction Nationale</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2> by Bernadette

Mukamana, (former vice-president of the Rwandan association, SERUKA)

<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=2>La Femme et Son R&ocirc;le dans l'Evolution du

Rwanda</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2> by Benedicte Kayabinda (visiting

professor at the school of Public Health and Nutrition at the

University of Rwanda)<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=2>Le Droit Rwandais et la Femme</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2>

by Sp&eacute;cioze Kamanzi<BR>

<BR>

</FONT>

