<HEAD>


<TITLE> "A Developing World": Strategy for Danish Development Policy </TITLE>


</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<pre>



</pre>

<center><p>

<FONT SIZE=+2>A DEVELOPING WORLD:<br>STRATEGY FOR DANISH DEVELOPMENT POLICY TOWARDS THE YEAR 2000

</FONT> <P><BR>


<FONT SIZE=+1>Summary of a Strategy Paper presented by the Danish Government, March 1994</center>

</FONT><p><hr>


<P>


DANIDA

<br>


Ministry of Foreign Affairs

<br>


2, Asiatisk Plads

<br>


1448 Copenhagen K

<br>

<hr>

<B>Introduction</B>

<P>


In the light of the profound changes which have taken


place since 1989 in the developing countries, Europe and Denmark,


the Government decided in 1993 to prepare a new strategy for the


Danish development policy towards the year 2000. 'Me result of


this work is an extensive strategy paper which was presented to


the Folketing (The Danish Parliament) on March 22, 1994. A translation


of the executive <U>summary</U> of this paper is presented below.


<P>


The problems facing the developing countries and


the instability of international relations increased throughout


the 1980s and the early 1990s. At present, the poorest developing


countries have not overcome the econon3ic crisis of the early


1980s, which requires reform and structural change of state controlled


economies and autocratic political systems. For Sub-Saharan Africa


the 1980s were, in most aspects, a lost decade.


<P>


At the same time, the end of the Cold War fundamentally


changed the rules of the game for international co-operation.


The emergence of economically, ethnically and politically unstable


new states has given rise to increased local and regional tensions


- in several cases with far reaching international consequences.


<P>


In addition, considerable economic growth in a number


of developing countries in East Asia along with improved prospects


for countries in South Asia and Latin America have shown that


the course of development can be changed and that it is possible


to break the vicious circle of poverty.


<P>


For the industralized countries these developments


erect new demands for engagement, cooperation and development


assistance. As a growing number of local problems become regional


and global in character, there is an increasing need to face the


challenges - and to face them in partnership with developing countries


and the newly emerged states. Poverty, the environment, population


pressures, migration and local conflicts all stress the importance


of international solidarity and closer international co-operation.


We do have a responsibility to engage in changing the course of


development, not least in Africa, with the aim of turning the


1990s into the decade where the foundation for economic growth


and social equality was established.


<P>


Denmark has, as a small country, a vital interest


in sustaining international co-operation. A social and humanitarian


tradition has given us the experience that enable us to face these


international challenges. Through our membership of the UN, the


European Union and as a Nordic country, we have a strong basis


for a constructive and effective effort.


<P>


Denmark has a long tradition with international development


co-operation. Our experience has shown how difficult it is to


find sustainable solutions to complicated and often deeply rooted


problems of development. In certain instances, development efforts


have let to tangible results. Other efforts, however, never worked


as expected. The quality requirements to our development assistance


are ever growing, and greater efforts are being made to ensure


that the funds of the Danish development assistance are not misused


or diluted into large bureaucracies. We have a commitment to help


the poorest, and we must, for this reason, be certain that the


assistance we give, actually reaches the most vulnerable groups


of the population.


<P>


One precondition for the ability of Danish development


assistance to comply with these high standards is the continuous


adjustment of our policies in accordance with ongoing changes,


both in the countries we are co-operating with, and inside Denmark


herself. Development co-operation can not be static, but must


adapt to the ever changing environment.


<P>


In recent years, we have learned, for one thing,


the lesson that development co-operation must be looked upon in


a broader, foreign policy perspective involving our overall relations


with developing countries. This applies particulary to the questions


of human rights and democracy, women in development, the environment,


trade policies, debt etc.


<P>


During the 1986-88 period, the first strategic planning


process for Danish development assistance was undertaken. The


result of this process was an Action Programme which in 1989 served


as input to a debate in the Folketing from which decisions regarding


future directions of the development assistance were established.


These recommendations have since then, supplemented with subsequent


parliamentary decisions, guided Denmark's development policy.


<P>


The present strategy is written in line with the


main recommendations of 1989 Plan of Action. 'This means, that


the overall objectives of the Danish development assistance will


be maintained in the future. Especially, the principle of an overall


volume of Official Development Assistance (ODA) at one percent


of the Gross National Product persists including an approximately


even distribution between bilateral and multilateral assistance.


<P>


Within this framework the strategy provides a new


orientation and a revised set of guidelines for a dynamic Danish


development policy towards the year 2000.


<P>


The intention of the strategy is not to give an overall


exposition of every aspect of Danish development co-operation.


Instead, the strategy highlights the relevant aspects of the developments


from recent years, which are also expected to be central for our


development policy in the years to come.


<P>


During 1993, two special working groups dealt with


the Danida co-operation with Danish non-government organizations


and with Danish enterprises. The results of this work have been


incorporated into the present strategy.


<P>


Interest in, knowledge of, and collaboration with


developing countries are deeply rooted in the Danish society.


There is, therefore, a strong commitment in the society to development


co-operation. This, in itself, is an important prerequisite for


a Danish development assistance of the highest quality. During


the working process of this strategy, we have drawn on this engagement


and incorporated the knowledge and experience of various interest


groups. Having this in mind, I would like to take this opportunity


to thank the long list of people who contributed - in an essential


and most valuable manner - to the process that has culminated


with this strategy.


<P>


The Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs, March 1994


<P>


Helle Degn,


<P>


Minister for Development Co-operation


<P>


<hr><p><B>1. Background</B>


<P>


Very much has changed in the world over the last


five to six years. Major political balances have shifted, power


blocks have been dissolved and new states have emerged. New growth


centers have developed, trading agreements have been reached and


regional integration processes are increasingly gaining momentum.


<P>


A lot, however, remains the same. Poverty and underdevelopment


still affects large parts of the world and every fifth person


on earth live in absolute poverty. Despite this, there are positive


tendencies in most developing countries. But unless concerted


efforts are made to initiate comprehensive reforms and maintain


a significant level of development assistance, the development


towards the year 2000 indicates a worsening of the situation in


Sub-Saharan Africa.


<P>


Poverty is behind some of the most fundamental problems


of all developing countries in the years ahead. This applies to


well-known problems such as widespread social deprivation, persisting


population growth, environmental degradation at the local, regional


and global level as well as wars and conflicts. It also applies


to more recent problems such as the growth in migration both locally


and globally, increasing ethnic intolerance and fundamentalism,


and the spread of AIDS to large parts of the population in some


of the poorest countries.


<P>


As a small country, Denmark has a vital interest


in expanding international co-operation. A social and humanitarian


tradition has learned us the experience necessary to face these


international challenges. Through our membership of the UN, the


European Union and as a Nordic country, we have a strong basis


for a constructive and effective effort.


<P>


It is against this background that the &quot;Strategy


for Danish Development Policy Towards the Year 2000&quot; has


been drawn up.


<P>


<B>2.</B> <B>The Strategy's Main


Points</B>


<P>


<B>2.1</B> <B>Development Assistance


Policy towards the year 2000</B>


<P>


In recent years a growing recognition of the inverse


relations between some of the problems involved in international


development co-operation has emerged.


<P>


In many developing countries poverty problems, environmental


degradation, over-utihzation of natural resources, poor health


conditions and high population growth rates in combination produce


a negative dynamic. Lack of economic growth in the poorest, mostly


African, countries has weakened the opportunities for sustainable


improvements in the living conditions among the poorest. At the


same time, failure to integrate these groups into the development


process has, in itself, curbed development and economic growth.


A weak administrative capacity, characterized by inadequate and


incompetent leadership, corruption, ethnic conflicts and religious


intolerance, contibute to accentuating the problems.


<P>


In this situation the overall development policy


has to include a variety of instruments. These will range from


political dialogue on democratization and human rights, over well-targeted


assistance progranmes in key sectors, to special programmes aimed


at strengthening the collaboration between organizations and companies


in Denmark and in the developing countries.


<P>


The primary scope of this strategy is to translate


the overall objectives of Denmark's foreign policy and development


co-operation programme into a progressive and cohesive Danish


development policy based on mutually reinforcing components.


<P>


The strategy is conceived with due attention to the


problems of the developing countries and it attempts to identify


areas which are matching, in which Denmark possesses the preconditions


for, and interest in, a qualified effort.


<P>


The strategy is based on five basic principles:


<ol>


<li>Danish development policy encompasses all our


relations with developing countries, economic and political as


well as multilateral and bilateral. The official development assistance


is a central instrument in the development policy.


<P>


<li>The development policy is flexible and must continuously


be adjusted <B>to </B>new international challenges. The ability


to react quickly and coherently to new situations and react effectively


with emergency relief and other efforts is an integral element


of the development policy.


<P>


<li>Danish development co-operation is rooted in the


commitment to combat the poverty affecting large groups of the


population in many developing countries. 'This is done by providing


official development assistance aimed at developing socially balanced


and ecologically sustainable economic growth.


<P>


<li>Danish development assistance is directed towards


the needs of the developing countries. The priorities and conditions


for Denmark's development policy are reflected in the choice of


co-operation countries, organizations and sectors. Furthermore,


they are reflected in the dialogue with the recipient countries


holding responsibility for specific development activities.


<P>


<li>Development co-operation affects large parts of


the society - both in Denmark and in the recipient countries.


Voluntary and professional organizations, business and industry,


research institutions and public sector institutions comprise


a resource base, that makes qualified diversified Danish assistance


efforts possible. Non-governental actors therefore, must be actively


involved in the formulation, organization and implementation of


Danish assistance efforts.


</ol><P>


<B>2.2</B> <B>The General Perspective


of the Strategy</B>


<P>


Danish development policy is an integral part of


Danish foreign policy, in which the main objectives are: promotion


of common security, the promotion of democratic government and


human rights, the creation of economic and social development


and ensuring ecologically sustainable development The following


objectives have been laid down for Denmark's official development


assistance:


<P>


&quot;The objective of Denmark's official development


assistance to developing countries is through co-operation with


governments and public authorities in these countries to assist


endeavours aimed at achieving economic growth, thereby contributing


to ensuring social progress and political independence, in accordance


with the aims and principles of the United


<P>


Nations Charter and, in addition, through cultural


co-operation to promote "mutual understanding and solidarity."

<P>


Against this background, the overall perspective


of the Strategy for Danish Development Policy Towards the Year


2000 will be to assist developing countries in their efforts to


achieve sustainable development based on the improvement in living


conditions through socially balanced economic growth and with


respect for political independence. Equal and free opportunities


for the individual, in accordance with the aims and principles


of the United Nations Charter, and, in addition, to promote mutual


understanding and solidarity through cultural co-operation.


<P>


The efforts of Danish development assistance will


be organized to promote:


<ul>


<li>production, a socially balanced economic growth


and social justice;


<li>the development of human resources;


<li>pluralistic civil societies and respect for the


individual;


<li>the protection of the global environment and sustainable


exploitation of natural resources;


<li>global and regional co-operation, as well as


<li>cultural co-operation and understanding between


peoples.</ul>


<P>


Fulfillment of these goals will be conditional on


development activities showing due consideration to the respective


contributions of both women and men, together with the utilization


of development assistance in a mutual relationship between bilateral


and multilateral efforts.


<P>


<B>2.3.</B> <B>Poverty Orientation</B>


<P>


Poverty orientation constitutes a fundamental principle


for Danish development assistance.


<P>


The poverty alleviation strategy for Danish official


development assistance may be condensed into three main points:


<ul>


<li>the promotion of sustainable and socially balanced


economic growth;


<li>the development of the social sector, including


the promotion of education and health services as prerequisites


to the development of human resources;


<li>promoting Popular Participation in the development


process, the development of a society based on the rule of law


and good governance as prerequisites to stability and economic,


social and political progress.


</ul><P>


In the weakest countries, the problem of poverty


can only be resolved if the efforts of individual countries are


supported by official development assistance from a range of donor


countries. Denmark will Participate in and contribute to this


co-operation, and will, at the same time, continue its efforts


aimed at increasing the overall volume of official development


assistance of other industrialized countries in accordance with


the established UN targets.


<P>


The implementation of the general poverty alleviation


strategy in the Programme countries will be an integral component


of the formulation of country strategies and will appear explicitly


in these.


<P>


The formulation of specific poverty strategies will


be based on the preconditions prevailing in the individual recipient


country, thus varying from country to country.


<P>


<B>2.4. Cross-cutting themes</B>


<P>


A number of cross-cutting themes will be pursued at all levels within the assistance programme. In addition to


poverty alleviation three such themes have been identified: The


role Of women in development, environment and Promotion Of good


governance and human rights. is that they constitute aspects of


assistance common to all these areas while at the same time act as independent development


assistance areas.


<P>


In most developing countries, women play a critical


role in development. Not only as producers but also as bearers


Of social responsibility and bringing up the next generation.


Danish development assistance emphasizes <B>strengthening of the


role of </B>women in <B>the development process </B>In spite of


concerted efforts over many years, aimed at improving the situation


of women in developing countries, the results are few and scattered.


The global picture continues to show major differences in men's


and women's opportunities and living conditions within almost


all sectors.


<P>


In connection with specific development assistance


efforts, gender aspects will be analyzed. At the same time plans


and goals will be formulated with a view to improving the situation


of women in developing countries and promoting their involvement


in the development process.


<P>


At the operational level emphasis will be placed


on identifying specific goals for women's involvement in the development


process. In the preparation of policy papers, check lists and


other simple aids, steps will be taken to assure full integration


of women's interests throughout the project-cycle.


<P>


In relation to the environment, work will be carried


out at local, national, regional and global levels. To promote


sustainable development in the Danish programme countries, Denmark


will intensify efforts to incorporate the recommendations of the


Rio-conference (UNCED) into Danish development policy. In addition,


Denmark will ensure that environmental aspects are fully incorporated


into Denmark's poverty oriented development assistance.


<P>


Environment Impact Assessments will be undertaken


in all relevant development activities and institutions promoting


sustainable use of natural resources.


<p>

At the same time, Denmark will contribute to strengthening environmental protection and collaboration at regional


and global levels, i.e. by


<UL>


<li>creating incentives for individual developing countries


to engage in the formulation and implementation of regional and


global environmental agreements and programmes;


<li>committing financial and professional assistance


to regional environmental institutions, and


<li>implementing technical environmental studies and


pilot projects in programme countries.</ul>


<P>


The promotion of <B>democratization and human rights


</B>constitutes the last cross-cutting theme. The improvement


of human rights based on respect for <B>the </B>individual is


a goal in itself. It contributes - together with popular participation


in the decision-making processes - to the development of a stable


society.


<P>


Practical assistance to specific human rights and


good governance activities in developing countries will be supported


at all levels. Particular emphasis will be placed on creating


positive incentives for development <B>towards </B>democratic


government and respect for human rights.


<P>


A close and open dialogue with recipient countries


on economic, social, professional and political questions is an


integral part of Danish development co-operation.


<P>


This dialogue will also include questions on the


advancement of human rights and popular participation in the development


process. Continued violation of human rights and lack of interest


within the programme countries to enter into a dialogue on these


issues will be reflected in the extent and character of Danish


development assistance.


<P>


<B>2.5</B> <B>Bilateral Assistance</B>


<P>


The strategy provides for a further concentration


of Danish bilateral assistance efforts.


<P>


Danish development assistance will be concentrating


on fewer countries, and at the country level, on fewer sectors.


<P>


Bilateral development co-operation will concentrate


on activities in 20 programme countries. In connection with the


phasing in and out of programme countries, however, bilateral


co-operation may be extended to a total of 25 countries.


<p>

Due to Denmark's limited human and financial


resources, both bilateral and multilateral assistance will be


utilized selectively and in areas where Denmark has good prerequisites


to contribute.


<p>

Assistance to programme countries can, based


on the individual country's particular circumstances, embrace


all sectors and types of assistance.

<P>


A country strategy will be drawn up for each programme


country. This strategy will be updated on a regular basis.


<P>


Traditional project assistance will, to the widest


possible extent, be <B>concentrated </B>within selected sectors


or sub-sectors. The financial and human resource investments required


to conduct a qualified dialogue with recipient countries make


it essential that our efforts in individual programme countries


are concentrated in a <B>limited number of sectors.</B>


<P>


<B>Collaboration sectors </B>will in individual


countries be selected in accordance with the needs of the recipient


country. Within <B>this </B>framework emphasis will be placed


on areas where the Danish resource base has a strong basis for


supporting and implementing <B>the </B>assistance efforts.


<P>


Assistance within a sector will, to the extent


possible, take the form of <B>sector programme assistance, </B>which


will include broadly based assistance to activities within a given


sector or sub-sector. For example, education and training, running


costs, maintenance and new investment, as well as in the form


of budget assistance.


<P>


At the same time, a portion of Danish governmental


development assistance will continue to be contributed as <B>programme


assistance </B>in the future. This is done to support the implementation


of balanced structural adjustment programmes and to promote economic


growth in countries committed to the implementation of necessary


adjustments. A comparatively large portion of programme assistance


will, within a few years, be contributed in the form of <B>debt


relief.</B>


<P>


Besides activities to promote democratization and


human rights, it will be possible, to a limited extent, to continue


the implementation of innovative <B>projects, </B>outside predetermined


sectors. These projects must be of limited duration and be capable


of establishing a model for similar bilateral activities.


<P>


To ensure sustainability of individual development


activities, assistance will be arranged taking account of <B>the


</B>broad sectoral perspective and in <B>committed co-operation


</B>with the recipient country, which will take overall responsibility


for the <B>activities implemented.</B>


<P>


The changed emphasis of Danish development assistance


efforts implies increased assistance to <B>capacity building </B>in


institutions in recipient countries responsible for sectoral planning,


administration, budget and auditing.


<P>


Increased emphasis on capacity building and increased


local responsibility will be followed up by the gradual reorientation


of <B>personnel assistance. </B>To improve sustainability increased


emphasis will be placed on local advisers supported by short-term


consultants.


<P>


As part of <B>the </B>country strategy process


special efforts will be made to expose areas, where <B>Danish


advisers </B>can participate to promote improved utilization of


local resources in the planning and implementation stages of development


assistance projects.


<P>


Overall, efforts will be made to concentrate bilateral


assistance in the following assistance forms:


<ul>


<li><B>General Programme Assistance, </B>in


the form of balance of payments assistance, in kind assistance,


debt relief, and the like, to support broader socioeconomic reforms.


<li><B>Sector Programme Assistance, to </B>support


developments and reforms within a limited number of sectors or


sub-sectors, for example, within the health service.


<li><B>Project Assistance, </B>which


in the case of pro e co-operation countries will be limited to


minor projects, that are obviously newly created and can act as a model for


similar activities. In addition, projects which, in all developing


countries, can render assistance to the promotion of the democratization


process and human rights. Added to this is the Danish Associated


Financing scheme.


<li><B>Personnel Assistance, </B>is to be reorganized with greater utilization of local advisers and


the short-term deployment of Danish consultants.


<li>Sector programme assistance, assistance towards running


costs, more local responsibility and increased utilization of


local advisers will imply changed conditions for the achievement


of <B>immediate and visible results </B>of assistance, and for


the direct control with local use of Danish funds. A possible


short-term decline in effectiveness and visible results must be


expected to be counterbalanced by development activities becoming


more sustainable with the improved local anchoring. Therefore


they will become more effective, in the final analysis, compared


to projects implemented by posted experts who cannot achieve the


same level of local anchorage.</ul>


<P>


Recipient countries' increased responsibility and


involvement in the preparation and implementation of development


assistance will be followed up by reinforced efforts to <B>strengthen


institutions </B>in recipient countries, responsible for budgeting,


accounts and expenditure control. This strengthening of local control and auditing will be balanced by a reduction


in the direct control of Danish officials on Danish financed activities.


<P>


To strengthen the <B>administration and control


</B>of development assistance, top Priority will be given to assisting


central administrations and local authorities in recipient countries.


For example in the form of institution building, support to increasing


administrative and organisational efficiency as well as strengthening


<B>of </B>auditing and control organs.


<P>


At the same time access to <B>inspection and auditing


</B>of Danish supported programmes will be maintained. This will


also signify to authorities in recipient countries that abuse


of Danish development assistance resources will result in consequences


for the future of development assistance co-operation.


<P>


Besides Programme co-operation countries, bilateral


assistance will be confined to special areas: assistance <B>to


</B>Promote democratization and human rights, associated financing


and transitional assistance. Bilateral assistance will also be


awarded under the terms of the new Special International Environmental


and Catastrophe Facility.


<P>


Assistance to Promote <B>democratization and human


rights </B>will be awarded to a broader selection of developing


countries in accordance with prevailing income limits.


<P>


<B>Associated Financing </B>will only be awarded


to countries with a GNP of less than 2,160 US$ per capita.


<P>


Provisional <B>transitional assistance </B>will be


awarded to create or recreate preconditions for economic and social


development in countries which are undergoing basic social restructuring,


usually in connection with the termination of armed conflict or


transition from a centrally controlled economy to a market based


economic system. Transitional assistance will be awarded for a


limited period and will be used selectively. Assistance will predominantly


comprise product supply, assistance to multilateral programmes


or programmes implemented by non-governmental development organizations,


supplemented by bilateral democratic efforts. cf section 3.2.2.


<P>


In addition, <B>Danish non-governmental development


organizations </B>can engage in assistance in a wide range of


countries and sectors according to their own specific priorities.


<P>


<B>Regional assistance </B>will only include bilateral


and multilateral assistance to interstate or non-governmental


regional institutions and organizations, as well as assistance


to regionally oriented activities in Programme countries. This


implies that bilateral governmental assistance activities outside


programme countries, which formerly comprised Part of the bilateral


regional programme, will be phased out. Bilateral co-operation


outside programme countries will only occur to the extent it is


estimated as reasonable in relation to the administrative costs


associated therewith.


<P>


<B>2.6 Multilateral Assistance</B>


<P>


The <B>fairly equal division </B>of Danish development assistance between Multilateral and bilateral assistance is maintained.


<P>


The Danish contribution to multilateral assistance


will concentrate, to a greater extent, on activity areas highly


Prioritised by Denmark. It will to a lesser degree be based on


the contribution levels within the individual organizations.


<P>


During the preparation of multilateral assistance


emphasis will be placed on <B>prioritizing and concentrating </B>policy


and Professional efforts, both between organizations and within


individual Organizations. At the same time, attempts will be made


to Promote co-operation and clear division of work between the


multilateral organizations involved,


<P>


TOP Priority areas will be assisted through intergovernmental


or nongovernmental Organizations, which - on a case-by-case basis


- are estimated to be in the best Position to administer development


assistance to the areas concerned. Consideration of Denmark's


<B>relative </B>size compared to other donors and <B>the load


division principle </B>will not be decisive in the allocation


of multilateral assistance.


<P>


Efforts to secure <B>Danish appointments </B>to


international organizations will be reinforced.


<P>


In the UN, Denmark will actively contribute to


the development of new <B>operational assistance </B>types, that


can form part of the civil component of UN peace keeping and conflict


preventive efforts.


<P>


In relation to development policy, Denmark will


co-operate within the framework of <B>the European </B>Union.


This will include a contribution to drawing up common development


policies and assistance through the development of a more cohesive


EU policy towards the developing countries, encompassing development


assistance and foreign policy, as well as trade, environment and


agriculture policy areas.


<P>


Denmark will work to maintain <B>Africa in focus


</B>also in terms of European development assistance efforts.


<P>


In relation to dialogue with the World Bank and


other international financial institutions on the formulation


of <B>structural adjustment programmes, </B>Denmark will attempt


to ensure that combating <B>poverty </B>and protecting especially


vulnerable groups, comprise an integral element of the banks'


activities, and that they are broadly anchored in recipient countries.


<P>


As a follow-up to the World Bank's and other multilateral


donors' work in Danish programme countries, and to contribute


to a <B>strengthened dialogue </B>between recipient countries


and multilateral donors, especially in relation to structural


adjustment programmes, initiatives will be taken in 1994 to hold


a number of regional symposiums. The participants will be experts


and decision makers from both Danish programme countries and multilateral


organizations.


<P>


One or more <B>trust funds </B>will be established


with The Global Environmental Facility and/or the World Bank with


a view to <B>co-financing </B>activities within high priority


assistance areas, that are comprised in the organizations' ordinary


project portfolios.


<P>


In addition, a number of <B>strategic funds and


contributions </B>will be established <B>to </B>assist the development


<B>of </B>multilateral organizations' work within high priority


areas. Earmarking Danish contributions will also be employed in


relation <B>to </B>assistance to increase the effectiveness and


reform endeavours of individual organizations.


<P>


Compared to present levels, the extent of <B>multi-


bilateral co-operation </B>with multilateral agencies will be


reduced. In the future multi- bilateral arrangements will be concentrated,


to a greater degree, on those organizations and sectors where


experience has proved positive.


<P>


The new <B>Special International Environment and


Catastrophe Facility </B>means that, in the long-term, a proportional


increase in catastrophe relief, financed under development assistance


arrangements, is not expected. In the coming years however, a


certain increase is expected as part of the more development oriented


and broad-spectrum emergency relief efforts.


<P>


<B>2.7 Crisis Efforts</B>


<P>


Efforts will be stepped up to safeguard the essential


relationship between short-term emergency relief efforts and long-term


development assistance, by, among other methods, the utilization of various


forms of <B>restructuring assistance.</B>


<P>


In relation to crisis situations of a more permanent


character there will, to the greatest possible extent, be a conversion


of efforts from traditional short-term emergency relief comprising


supplies from outside, to a more <B>broad-spectrum </B>assistance,


which as far as possible is based on social structures in the


recipient country.


<P>


Options available to relief organizations to develop


emergency relief Programmes in the <B>grey areas, </B>between


emergency relief and more long-term assistance will be expanded.


<P>


In close co-operation with authorities involved


and private emergency relief organizations, a new initiative will


be taken to establish an &quot;international <B>humanitarian capacity&quot;,


</B>comprised of volunteers from various professional groups,


who, on a short notice, can be deployed in support of Danish or


international relief efforts.


<P>


To avoid that longer term crisis efforts in non-programme


countries developing into small, semi permanent assistance programmes,


individual efforts will be organized in such a way that they do


not require a permanent Danish presence over and above emergency


relief and restructuring assistance for a <B>limited period.</B>


<P>


A survey will be initiated, in co-operation with


Private emergency relief organizations and Danish industry, to


determine the steps that can be taken to engage Danish business


and industry and increase the volume of <B>Danish supplies </B>in


connection with international relief efforts.


<P>


<B>2.8 Thematic Priority Areas</B>


<P>


The strategy aims at strengthening Danish efforts


on three thematic priority areas: population, trade and debt relief


<P>


 As part of upgrading Danish efforts in the <B>population


area </B>a sector strategy will be formulated on this topic in


1994.


<P>


The strategy will focus on activities of assistance


which aim at strengthening the women's and the families' possibilities


of <B>choosing </B>the number of children they want as well as


their spacing.


<P>


In the area of <B>trade policy </B>Danish efforts


will include: the promotion of greater cohesion in EU's development


policy and EU's trade and agricultural policies. In relevant trade


policy fora, Denmark will contribute to breaking down barriers


that hamper developing countries' exports of manufactured products


and thereby counteract diversification of their production systems.


In addition, efforts will be made to increase the integration


of developing countries in the international trading system.


<P>


Through development assistance Programmes Denmark


will support the <B>internationalization </B>Of developing countries'


enterprises. In addition, training programmes and education in


business and commerce, which contribute to the promotion of internationalization


of business and industry, will be granted.


<P>


In the area of <B>debt relief </B>Danish efforts


will include:


<ul>


<li>when the need arises, supplementary contributions


to <B>multilateral arrangements, </B>which aim at helping Denmark's


programme countries repay and service debt to multilateral financing


institutions, of which Denmark is a member, and


<li>in instances where a Programme country is heavily


burdened with debt to multilateral institutions, of which Denmark


is a member, to award <B>bilateral contributions </B>towards interest


payments and reimbursements, possibly including total repayment.</ul>

<P>


<B>2.9 Co-operation with the Resource Base</B>


<P>


The strategy recommends a closer co-operation between


the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the many elements of Danish


society, that in various ways co-operate with developing countries.


Provision is also made for strengthening the co-operation between


various non-state actors.


<P>


Intensified co-operation with the <B>resource base


</B>implies that interested parties from business and industry


and development organizations, as well as other parts of the Danish


resource base, will be involved in the formulation of new <B>country


strategies.</B>


<P>


In relation to the formulation of strategy agreements


with Denmark's programme countries, provisions have been made


for additional efforts to develop and strengthen partnership initiatives


or <B>&quot;twinning arrangements&quot;. </B>Where such partnership


arrangements open a perspective for broader participation and


establishment of co-operation relations between the professional


environment and institutions in programme countries and Denmark,


the Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs will actively encourage


the involvement of those institutions and professional groups,


with particular prerequisites for such involvement.


<P>


<B>3. The strategy's Implementation and Follow-up</B>


<P>


Denmark has formulated an ambitious goal for its


development policy. Relative to the needs of developing countries


and the overall economic relations between industrial and developing


countries, Danish development assistance is - still - very limited


in quantitative terms. This makes it difficult to establish a


direct causal linkage between development policy goals and the


effects of Danish development efforts.


<P>


<B>Evaluating </B>the direct


and indirect effects of individual activities and programmes,


fully or partly financed by Denmark, will therefore be the most


important instrument in evaluating the annual fulfilment of development


policy objectives.


<P>


Implementation of the strategy's main elements


will be the subject of <B>overall assessment in 1997.</B>


<P>


Global distribution <B>and utilization of Denmark's


bilateral assistance must </B>comply with a number <B>of broad


spectrum objectives. </B>These goals will apply globally over


a number <B>of years, but not necessarily for </B>individual programme


co-operation countries, <B>or in specific years.</B>


<P>


The strategy is reflected in the rolling-five-year-plans


which will include comprehensive analysis of the strategy's implementation


status, beginning in 1996.


<P>


Within the framework of the overall development policy


a number of priority areas will be selected in relation to <B>multilateral


co-operation. </B>At the mid-term review of the strategy implementation


in 1997, it will be established to which extent these priority


areas, in practice, have been managed, taking into account:


<ul>


<li>the distribution of multilateral assistance between


organizations, utilization of the administrative resources of


the Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs in <B>the </B>process of


continuous follow-up of co-operation with multilateral organizations,


and


<li>the establishment of and resource injection to


strategic, goal-directed funds in individual multilateral organizations.


<li>the evaluation of the increased involvement of


the Danish Resource Base in assistance co-operation must begin


by determining whether or not the quality of Danish assistance


efforts has been strengthened. Moreover, the effect will depend


on the quality of country strategies and sector assistance programmes,


that will bear bilateral assistance, and which will be formulated


in dialogue with the Danish resource base.</ul>

<p><hr>


