<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>EU-LDC Trade and Capital Relations Network</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<H2><IMG SRC  = "../images/euldc.gif"><p>
EU-LDC Trade and Capital Relations Network<br>Annual Workshops</h2>
E-mail: <a href="mailto:memedovic@NEI.NL">Dr. Olga Memedovic</a></center>
<p>
<hr><p>
The annual workshop deals with a topical issue which is considered crucial for a strategic relationship between EU-LDCs. During the early 1990s the transformation in the Central and Eastern European Countries (CEECs) was one of the most important developments in this area. The issue has raised considerable concern among participants and economists in LDCs: Could trade and capital flows between the EU and the CEECs offer a substitute to interactions between the EU and LDCs, or could these flows be complementary to EU-LDC relations? The first workshop (May 1994) focused on this theme from both a theoretical and a practical perspective. Sector studies were included as some trade policy instruments are sector or product specific. Country studies highlighted differences in economic and political leverage. Papers were presented by academics from Europe and LDCs. Each paper was discussed by two speakers, a policy maker and a person with an academic background. Important topics of the workshop were trade creation and trade diversion as well as how trade and investment flows are affected by trade preferences. Most of the papers presented at the First Annual Workshop (May 1994) were published in January 1996 by Kluwer Academic Publishers as a volume titled Transition in Central and Eastern Europe Ñ Implications for the EU-LDCs Relations. This volume is the start of a new series dealing with the EU-LDC relations.
<p>
The 1995 Workshop of the Network focused on the topic: Globalization of Labour Markets - Challenges, Adjustment and Policy Response in the EU and LDCs. To the classical driving forces of migration such as poverty, oppression and war, yet another is being added: globalization. With the increasing economic interdependence between countries migration has become one of the important links. Many LDCs accept migration of their workers to developed countries because it reduces the pressure on their labour market, and remittances increase capital flows to the country. On the other hand, some of the developed countries see migration as a threat to their  employment and system of social security. Participants of the 1995 Workshop gave a broad view of the problem which developed and LDCs are facing in connection with the globalization of labour markets. The proceedings and the summary of the discussions of the 1995 Workshop are positively assessed by anonymous reviewers and will be published by the same publisher as the second volume titled: Globalization of Labour Markets - Challenges, Adjustment and Policy Response in the EU and LDCs. The forthcoming book consists of 11 chapters by scholars from the EU, the CEECs and LDCs which are presented in four parts: 1) Conceptual Issues; 2) Exporting Goods or Labour: Experiences of and Consequences for LDCs; 3) Private Sector Response; and 4) Policy Response in the EU and LDCs. This will be the second volume in the EU-LDC Trade and Capital Relations series. The publication is scheduled for the end of 1996.
<p>
The 1996 Workshop of the Network focused on the topic: External Resources for Development - With Particular Emphasis on the Role of the EU. Recent years have witnessed a sharp decline in developed countries spending on development assistance (aid). Yet, at the same time, many LDCs have demonstrated an ability to attract foreign private capital. They have abandoned development strategies based on active state intervention in allocating resources and promoting growth and have turned instead towards outward-oriented development strategies based on openness and an increased role for market forces. This latter strategy relies on a dynamic and expanding private sector to increase economic growth and efficiency and generate employment and income, but it also requires structural adjustments (i.e. upgrading private sector-led growth, creating an appropriate environment for enterprises, an efficient banking sector and efficient government) for which external financial and technical support is necessary. 
<p>
The end of the Cold War (in 1989) also triggered new demands on aid budgets. New thinking about development issues, liberated from the constraints of competing ideologies, has seen the emergence of the new paradigm of sustainable development. This is considered to be an integrating process of political and economic stability, good governance, capacity building, improved technical cooperation, human resource development, reliance on market forces, concern for the environment and promotion of the private sector. Such a catalogue of change has brought into sharp focus the issue of aid effectiveness and the measurement of results obtained through development assistance from the perspective of both the donors and the recipients. 
<p>
The goal of the 1996 Workshop was to contribute to the thinking about the prospects of official development assistance, and other official and private capital flows. Important questions raised during the workshop were: How can foreign resources be optimally targeted to stimulate development and how can they best be evaluated in terms of their results? What should LDCs do to benefit most from external resources (official and private)? What are the determining factors of external resource supply?
<p>
The programme comprized three sessions. Session I gave an outline of the theoretical and conceptual issues and the analysis to date. Within this session two papers were presented: one dealt with Private Finance and Development Issues and the other concentrated on Whether or Not Aid can Eliminate Aid Dependence? Session II focused on External Resource Supply and was divided into two subsessions: a) The Extent and Structure of External Resource Supply and b) Determining Factors of External Resource Supply. The latter had four short papers including: Dilemmas in Donor Aid Strategies; The Effectiveness of Development Aid; Determination of Private Capital Flows, and South-South Cooperation and External Resource Flows. Session III focused on Regional and Sectoral Patterns of External Resource Supply - Emphasis on Effectiveness of External Resource Supply to Different Regions.
<p>
In each session papers were presented by academics from Europe and LDCs. This was followed by a discussion by two (three) speakers, a policy maker and a person with an academic background from the developed countries and from LDCs. The Management Team of the Network succeeded in attracting high level academics and policy makers to participate in the workshop programme by either presenting or discussing paper. The Management Team has also tried to find good balance between academics and policy makers as well as a sufficient representation from the various LDC regions. Currently the editors are preparing material from the Third Annual Workshop (May 1996) for reviewing and assessment for publication during 1997. This will be the third volume in the EU-LDC Trade and Capital Relations Series.
<p>
At the Third Annual Meeting of the Network Steering Committee, held on 15 May 1996, it was decided that the 1997 Workshop should focus on the topic: <A HREF="w4.htm">Multilateralism and Regionalism in the Post-Uruguay-Round Era: What Role for the EU</A>? the Workshop will be held on 12-13 May 1997 in Rotterdam.
 
