<HEAD>

<TITLE>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 31</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 31 Friday 20 December 1996

</CENTER></H3>

<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></H4><A HREF="index.html">EUROSTEP Home Page</A></CENTER>

<HR>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>1.</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=1> </FONT><B><FONT SIZE=2>DEVELOPMENT

CO-OPERATION FALLS FURTHER BEHIND AS AN EU PRIORITY AS EUROPEAN

PARLIAMENT 1997 BUDGET CUTS MONEY FOR  CO-OPERATION</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The adoption of the EU

budget at its second reading by the European Parliament, EP, on

12 December may confirm the fears of many involved in international

co-operation of the relegation of development co-operation to

matters of lesser importance by the European Union. The EP in

line with its quest for austerity adopted an uncharacteristically

slim line budget for 1997 and there were hardly any differences

between the first and the second reading. Unfortunately, development

co-operation seems to be the sector which has been sacrificed

to achieve the near 0% growth in the budget over last year. (See

table provided in the last two pages of the PAF)</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Despite lobbying from the NGO community (Mr. Brinkhorst,

rapporteur of the budget committee,  received more than 200 letters

from NGOs), the Budget Committee agreed on the figure of 160 MECU

+ 36 MECU in reserve for co-finnancing of NGOs. This 36 MECU in

reserve would only be released after agreement by the Development

Committee. The Committee wants to have more control on this reserve

and will set up the conditions, be more strict and limiting. The

conditions will be set on the basis of reports from Reylandt,

(we do not know what the criteria will be yet). The DGVIII B/2

has to give a report to the Development Committee before May 1997

on how the funds are to be used.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> In the table the 'M' in the second column means

that those lines have been merged with the co-financing line,

so they will be administrated by the DGVIII. There is also a significant

reduction in the funds for rehabilitation. The Council had wanted

to decrease it to 50 million ECU, while the Parliament demanded

75 million and the 62.5 million represent the compromise between

the Council's proposal and the Parliament's. The B7-321 (Rehabilitation

in Southern Africa) is also part of the reserve. The B7-611N (Role

of women in development) has been created by the Parliament; it

should include the B7-633.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The rest of the sectorial budget lines are the same

as in 1996. There is a huge increase for the MEDA line, but the

line for NGOs has been suppressed. Concerning the Central and

Eastern Europe line, there is a new line for ex-Yugoslavia, which

is quite substantial. The B7-6008N is a line created to repatriate

the refugees with temporary asylum in Europe.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> On the whole it has been a quite difficult year

in the fight to maintain a decent level of funding for development.

NGOs need to be on the alert in the coming years. Member States

are trying to reach the level demanded of them to enter the EMU

system, which means that in the future there will be less money

for development. NGOs will have to step up the pressure on the

national governments. The Development Committee will start working

on the budget early in the next year.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>  Although the budget for 1996 has been entirely

allocated, there are still some problems in its provision. The

general conditions for funding have not been settled yet. There

are some advances from the Dutch government, who are planning

to take some decisions on this issue during their Presidency.

NGOs in Luxembourg will be pushing this issue during Luxembourg's

Presidency<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. BUDGET COMMITTEE REJECTS PARLIAMENTARY VOTE

ON ALLOCATION FOR TURKEY</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>In a major development

since last week's adoption of the budget, the Budget Committee

on Tuesday 17 December overruled the total allocation of 62 967

million ECU for Turkey under the MEDA programme.  The allocation

which came from two different budget lines had been agreed on

in the vote on the budget and had angered many MEPs who protested

Turkey's continuing poor human rights record and interference

from the Council and the European Commission. The European Parliament

has now threatened to freeze the entire budget for Turkey under

the MEDA programme if the European Commission does not bow to

its demands for the creation of a joint committee for approving

individual programmes in the MEDA package. The EP wants to examine

each programme to determine if it would benefit Turkey, and if

so to block it. Turkish officials have reacted saying that the

cut in funding will not hurt Turkey. They however concede that

the symbolic significance is great as it puts Turkey in a worse

category than Algeria and Syria who continue to receive money

from the EU. &quot;To compare us with those regimes is ridiculous

.... We are being treated pretty badly&quot; said a Turkish diplomat.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>  </FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. EUROPEAN PARLIAMENTS EU URGE TO PAY GREATER

ATTENTION TO HUMAN RIGHTS AND CALL FOR A EU HUMAN RIGHTS COMMISSIONER</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> With the adoption of its annual report on human

rights the European Parliament has asked for greater clarification

on aid conditionality so as to avoid  ambiguity in future agreements

with the likes of Turkey and Russia. Rapporteur Cath&eacute;rine

Lalumi&egrave;re, President of the Radical Alliance Group, said

that  preventive diplomacy requires international control of the

arms trade and a code of conduct for European Companies carrying

out activities in Third Countries. Mrs. Lalumi&egrave;re criticised

the council for its hesitations on human rights infringements

in Bosnia, Rwanda, Chechnya, Zaire, China and Turkey. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The EP report asked the ACP-EU Joint Assembly not

to schedule plenary sessions in countries where co-operation is

suspended. It also outlined EU priorities for 1997  as - support

to the international tribunals for former Yugoslavia and Rwanda,

establishment of democratic institutions in former Yugoslavia;

the inclusion of systematic rape to the list of war crimes; the

launching of programmes for reconciliation of civil society; confirmation

of European programmes in for reconstruction and development in

South Africa, the Near East and Bosnia Herzegovina.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>   During a debate on the report several MEPs criticised

the Union's attitude on human rights. As Jan Bertens, a Dutch

Liberal,  put much of the argument being made succinctly, &quot;economic

interests must never prevail over human interests&quot;. Mr. Jose

Barros Mouta expressed his hope that the year 2000 would be proclaimed

as the Year of Human Rights by the Union. In defence of the Union,

Hans van der Broek, Commissioner for External Affairs said that

a network designed to gather necessary information for conflict

prevention was currently being set up. He stated however, that

a code of conduct could not be imposed on European multinationals

and that even though he thought that every year should be a Year

of Human Rights, he had recommended the proclamation of 1998 to

be European Year of Human Rights in line with the fiftieth Universal

Declaration on Human Rights. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT DEBATES THE FUTURE OF DEVELOPMENT

CO-OPERATION</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>On Tuesday 17 December,

in a debate largely centring on the European Commission's recent

Green Paper on the future of EU-ACP co-operation, the European

Parliament's Development Committee discussed the future of the

EU's development co-operation with the EU Commissioner for Mr

Joao de Deus Pinheiro and other development experts.   </FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Mr. Pinheiro, expounded

on some of the Green Paper major themes such as the need for more

conditionally in aid provision and the need to develop a new political

partnership between the two regions. He cautioned however, that

the Green Paper in no way pre-empts the Commission's future position

on the ACP-EU relationship but was rather a document to encourage

debate. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Among those invited to provide constructive criticism

on the Paper was Mr Claude Cheysson who is a former Commissioner,

French Minister, European Parliamentarian and one of the negotiators

of the first Lom&eacute; Convention. Mr. Cheysson outlining his

misgivings about the Green Paper criticised the increased emphasis

on conditionally, warning that the Commission would have to be

very careful in implementing this policy as it could easily be

misconstrued as a case of the EU taking the decisions sovereign

African countries have to take. He added that political dialogue

between the two groups should be promoted to the fore and as much

as possible the identity of the poor African countries should

be preserved. Commenting on the general view of the difficulty

of maintaining equality of the partners in the ACP-EU relationship,

Mr. Cheysson compared the Lom&eacute; Convention to the US's Marshall

Plan after  the second world war which according to Mr. Cheysson

achieved success because of the equality of partnership between

Europe and the USA.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Mr. Pinheiro's sudden departure following Mr. Cheysson's

speech, provided a humorous point for discussion giving that Mr.

Pinheiro had said earlier that he was ready to openly discuss

issues raised in the Green Paper.<B> </B>Others present however

remained to express their views on the issues. The Netherlands

Foreign Minister Mr. Pronk reassured the MEPs that the forthcoming

Dutch Presidency would carefully listen to the requests of ACP

countries. Mrs. Kinnock of the Socialist group criticised of the

lack of co-ordination between the EU's policies in other sectors

with its development policies while Lord Plumb of the Christian

Democrats lamented on the lack of progress on the EU's Common

Foreign and Security Policy. Several speakers called for the European

Development Fund used to finance the Lom&eacute; Conventions to

be included in the regular EU budget. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. IN BRIEF </FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>- EC WANTS SUSPENSION OF GSP TO BURMA</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The European Commission

this week unanimously agreed to recommend to the Council the suspension

of the General System of Preferences to Burma.  <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>- REPORT ON DUBLIN SUMMIT AVAILABLE</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Copies of the reports

of the Dublin Summit, that took place on 13 and 14 December, and

the WTO Ministerial conference in Singapore, can be obtained from

the Eurostep office after the Christmas break.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>- EUROSTEP ELECTS NEW CHAIR OF STEERING COMMITTEE</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> On the final day of the Eurostep General Assembly,

Ms. Sabina Sinscalchi of Mani Tese was elected Chair-Person of

the Eurostep Steering Committee and Max van Berg of NOVIB Vice

Chair-Person. The other elected members of the Steering Committee

are Birgit Dederichs-Bain of DWHH, Svante Sandberg of Forum Syd

and Halle Johanssen of NPA. Curiously, in her acceptance speech

Ms. Siniscalchi made an earnest plea to Eurostep members for used

telephone cards for her son who has an extensive collection. 

</FONT>

<P>

