<html>
<head>
<title>Newsflash 1996 - Cattle Crisis: Britain's BurgerGate and Yaks in Yushu</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>

<center><h2>Cattle Crisis: <br>Britain's BurgerGate and Yaks in Yushu </h2></center>

<p>
Two simultaneous cattle crises are driving farmers to despair in two very different parts of the world. In Tibet, an unexpectedly prolonged winter has meant that a thick blanket of snow still lies heavily in regions that should, by now, have had stalks of spring grass appearing between light sprinklings of snowflakes. 
<p>
The yaks are starving to death. In some regions, like Yushu province, as many as 80% of the yak herds have already died, reducing the nomads who depend on these herds as their sole source of income to desperation.
<p>
Not that much information, however, is available via the world's media about the plight of these farmers who live - even in good years - on the edge of survival. The big cattle crisis is the one in Britain.
<p>
Here, the problem appears in reverse: cows that should have been killed many years ago were not.  Several scientists had argued since the early 1980s that 'mad cow disease' (Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy, or BSE) might be dangerous not only to cattle but also to humans. They feared a possible link between BSE and a new strain of the human brain affliction Creutzfeld-Jakob Disease (CJD).
<p>
Although no-one knew what, if any, the link might be, these scientists believed there was enough evidence to give cause for serious concern - and that the public should therefore be warned of the possible danger until clearer answers were found. 
<p>
Beef, in their view, could not be considered innocent until proven guilty: it had to be treated as suspicious until it was exonerated.
<p>
Britain's Conservative government, however, repeatedly took the opposite line, that BSE did not jump species from cows to humans - though the government's critics claimed that it has chosen put the interests of its supporters in the beef industry before its duty to protect public health.
<p>
One Minister, John Selwyn Gummer, unforgettably fed his small daughter a hamburger in front of the cameras to prove how confident he was that eating beef was perfectly safe. It was a smash-hit photo-opportunity - but one he might well be regretting since the revelations that have been emerging over the past few days. 
<p>
On Thursday 21 March, Ministers were forced to announce that 10 patients had been identified as suffering from a new and aggressive form of CJD, where the most likely cause was consuming beef. The Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg tried to calm the public outcry with the reassurance that extra new measures would be implemented to cut out all risk of infected meat from reaching the public - but it has been reported that as many as 40% of the slaughterhouses visited by food inspectors in lightning raids last autumn were failing to implement even the old, basic measures. 
<p>
Revelations of a Watergate-like cover-up have also shocked the British public.  On Saturday 23 March, the Guardian newspaper reported that: <p>
<i>'Whitehall knew for six years that beef from BSE-infected cattle might kill humans. Nothing was done. Except that experts who warned of deaths were vilified, had their funds cut or lost their jobs. Others were burgled and threatened, one man's home was burned.'</i>
 <p>
Among these scientists was Dr Harash Narang, a world expert in BSE. According to journalist Sarah Boseley, Dr Narang had established back in 1988 that BSE's infectious agent was linked to DNA. If he turned out to be right, this means, terrifyingly, that the infectious agent would be present in the best steak, freely available on supermarket shelves, as well as in the offal that had been officially banned.
<p>
He also began to create a same-day test that would detect infection in live cows - an invaluable device, says Boseley, since the Ministry of Food and Farming's tests could only work on slaughtered animals. Dr Narang applied for a MAFF grant to research his test - and:
<p>
<i> 'All seemed fine until he suggested that he would collect bovine heads from the local abbatoir rather than wait for MAFF to send him samples of BSE brains. Narang believes that MAFF officials suddenly saw an abyss opening at their feet. If Narang conducted random tests, the true proportion of cattle infected with BSE - and heading for butchers' shops - would become clear... There was no grant. 
<p>
Strange things happened to Dr Narang during this time... His car tyres were slashed five times, his brakes tampered with and his Newcastle flat broken into and his research papers messed up.'</i>
<p>
Stephen Dealler, a consultant microbiologist at Burnley Hospital, produced alarming data that eating any beef was risky - but says his fndings were brushed aside by Seac (the government's committee for investigating BSE). He says of Dr Narang's work:<p>
<b><i> 'His test worked in front of me. He is the guy who could have saved us.'</i></b>
<p>

It now appears that as many as a quarter of Britain's 11 million cattle may have to be killed, at a cost estimated at some 8 - 12 billion pounds (US$ 12 - 18 billion). It would have been far cheaper - as well as far more public-spirited - for the British government to have followed the Irish government's example and killed fewer cattle earlier.
<p>

<p>
STOP PRESS: McDonald's, the fast food chain, which has consistently maintained that its beef products are safe, has now announced that it is suspending the use of British beef in its burgers.
<p>
For more, see <b><a href=http://www.mcspotlight.org/company/thisweek/bse.html>McSpotlight</a></b>.<p>

See also this <b><a href="http://www.mcspotlight.org/beyond/bse_links.html">list of BSE links</a></b> - the best on the Web
<p>

<p>
<a href="index.html">Back to OneWorld News Service</a><b><br clear=left><a href="../owo_options.html"> Search Index</a><br>
<a href="../index.html"> OneWorld Online Home Page</a><p>
</body>
</html>

