<html>

<head>

<title>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 20</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 21 Friday 20 September 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1. REDEPLOYMENT OF  COMMISSION'S OVERSEAS STAFF</B>

<P>

 In accordance with the shift of interest in the European Union's

external relations the European  Commission is to complete its

redeployment exercise of delegation staff from various African

Caribbean Pacific (ACP)  countries to Asia, the Mediterranean

and Eastern Europe by the end of the year. This is intended to

reinforce offices in areas it now considers to be of increasing

importance to the Union. 

<P>

 Despite the efforts of Development Commissioner Joao de Deus

Pinhero to resist the downsizing of ACP delegations, 23 'A'Grade

posts in the ACP countries the are being redeployed to countries

such as New Independent states in Eastern Europe, Algeria and

Jordan from the Mediterranean and Bangladesh, India and Thailand.

Five of these posts however will  be used to strengthen the Commission's

activities in Southern Africa. 

<P>

 This exercise is a reflection of  the Union's current review

of its traditional ties with ACP countries and it's increasing

focus on Eastern Europe Asia and the Mediterranean. According

to senior Commission officials the redeployment is also a part

of a fundamental review of the breakdown between its permanent

and local staff in its 126 offices around the world. The Commission

is facing growing pressure from the European Parliament to reduce

its running costs and it believes that increasing the number of

local staff it hires would not only reduce its external relations

budget but also free full-time EU staff from more mundane tasks.

The Commission will however have to take account of the negotiations

taking place at the Intergovernmental Conference.  

<P>

<B>2. MEPS CRITICISE COUNCIL AND COMMISSION'S DECISIONS ON DEVELOPMENT

BUDGET</B>

<P>

 Members of the European Parliament Committee on Development and

Cooperation have criticised the European Council and European

Commission's decision to cut the co-operation budget for the Third

World by 10% in Strasbourg.  According to the members of the Committee

cuts will reduce humanitarian aid by 2.49% and other cooperation

measures by 13.35%. 

<P>

 Furthermore the Development Committee stated that the least developed

countries were being unduly penalised at the expense of other

more developed countries. The European Union is set to increase

its spending on the MEDA programme (Euro Mediterranean partnership)

from 400 to 800 million ECUs in its 1997 budget. The Development

Committee called for this money to be reallocated to the poorer

areas of the world in Africa and for MEPS to oppose heavy cuts

in the co-operation budget.

<P>

 The Development and Cooperation Committee's demand come as EU

governments aim to cut the Union's external budget by 15%.

<P>

<B>3. EUROPEAN UNION WELCOMES OUTCOME OF CONGRESS AGAINST SEXUAL

EXPLOITATION OF CHILDREN</B>

<P>

 The European Union stated its approval of the Declaration agreed

to at the World Congress of Against the Commercial Exploitation

of Children held in Stockholm from 27 to 31 August. The Declaration

emphasised the need  for partnerships between governments and

international organisations to be forged in order to prevent the

sexual exploitation of children. 

<P>

 The Union, on its part, stated its intentions to press ahead

with its efforts to put an end to what it called 'modern day slavery'

and have the traffic of human beings be declared a criminal offence

internationally.

<P>

<B>4. EU OFFICIALS REMAIN CAUTIOUS ON SITUATION IN THE GREAT LAKES

REGION</B>

<P>

 Mr.Ajello, the European Union's special envoy to Great Lakes

region in Africa expressed  his continuing anxiety over the political

situation in Bujumbura in talks with Mr Joao Pinhero on for development

on Monday, 16 September. Mr Ajello made his conclusions after

talks with political leaders and international observers including

the President of the Hutu guerrilla movement, CNCD, and the US

state department.  He stated that in spite of the changes by the

Buyoya regime towards democratic normalization the political situation

in Burundi is still a cause for concern.

<P>

 This comes after the Commission delegation was called from Bujumbura

for consultation and Mr.Pinhero's call for the suspension of aid

to Bujumbura following the 25 July coup d'etat. Although the EU

has not at yet forrmally suspended aid to Bujumbura, with the

exception of humanitarian assistance, EU aid is not reaching Burundi

because of the embargo by countries in the region. The situation

in the region will be reviewed at the forthcoming General Affairs

Council on 1 and 2 October.

<P>

<B>5. EU TO CLARIFY POSITION FOR FIRST WTO MEETINGS AT INFORMAL

SESSION IN DUBLIN</B>

<P>

 EU Trade Ministers are meeting with Irish minister Enda Kennedy

in preparation for the forthcoming  World Trade Organisation (WTO)

scheduled on the 9 and 13 December in Singapore. The ministers

aim to come up with common positions and guidelines on the following

issues to be on the Singapore agenda. 

<P>

<ul>

<li>the problem of ensuring third countries respect of Uruguay Round

Undertakings for opening markets to Community exports.

<P>

<li>the problem of the maintenance of the momentum of the liberalisation

of world trade in sectors excluded from the Uruguay round.

<P>

<li>whether EU wants new multilateral negotiations on the liberalisation

of  World trade

<P>

<li>if new international rules are needed in the area of competition

and investment

<P>

<li>whether greater importance should be attached to the environmental

and social aspects of international trade.</ul>

<P>

</PRE>

<HR>

