<TITLE>The Development Policy of Britain</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/gb.jpg"></H3>
<H3>From World Power to Influential Medium Level Donor:<br>The Development Policy of Britain<p>
<I>Paul J. Bendix</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 4, July-August 1996: pages 25-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<b>
Britain's traditionalism, its ties to its former colonies and
its chronic economic problems explain its contradictory image
as a mediumlevel donor, yet one which continues to play a dominant
role in multilateral organizations.</b>
<P>
Britain's development aid policy has been shaped by three radical
historical changes which have determined the country's policy
as a whole, and its foreign policy in particular:
<ul>
<li>its relative economic decline from a 19th century world power
to its present position as a European power;
<li>the breakup of what had been the world's largest colonial
empire and the formation of the Commonwealth; and
<li>its entry into the European Community following a lengthy
and controversial national decisionmaking process, together with
the renunciation of a special role in world politics.
</ul><P>
Because of their colonial past, contacts with the Third World
are a part of everyday life for the British people. But deeper
knowledge of it and more serious interest in it is limited to
the very active and relatively large 'development community' (NGOs,
individual MPs, academics, scientists and journalists). Most of
the British people regard themselves as 'not so well off', which
accounts for their relative lack of developmental commitment.
<P>
On the other hand, British academics and government experts, with
their background of experience gained during the colonial days,
have from the start greatly influenced and occasionally dominated
the international debate on development policy. They are very
much present in most multilateral institutions, providing direct
consultancy services to the governments of many developing countries.
<P>
During a phase of colonial development, which can be dated as
beginning in the 1930s, many concepts which were to reappear in
the years following the colonies' independence were discussed
and tested. After the Second World War, the Colombo Plan, elaborated
under British direction and proclaimed in 1950, can be regarded
as the starting point of Britain's development cooperation efforts.
It resulted in many years of successful cooperation between industrialized
members of the Commonwealth and the countries of South and Southeast
Asia.
<P>
<B>Development institutions</B>
<P>
Since 1964 there has been a central British development cooperation
authority, the Overseas Development Administration (ODA), whose
status and administrative arrangement have frequently changed.
But its mandate, internal structure and staff have remained largely
stable. Since the Conservatives came to power in 1979 the ODA
has been attached to the Foreign Office as a semiautonomous 'development
wing', headed by one of the FO's three secretaries of state. In
the previous five years it was the Ministry of Overseas Development
under a minister without portfolio.
<P>
In addition, two other ministries are substantially involved in
the planning and management of development cooperation. These
are the Exchequer, with responsibility for the budget and links
with the International Monetary Fund (IMF), and the Ministry of
Trade and Industry, responsible for UNCTAD and GATT/WTO. But the
latter ministry sees its development policy function as in particular
promoting Britain's export industry through the Aid and Trade
Provision (ATP), a mixedfinancing instrument.
<P>
The differentiated system of decentralization is a British peculiarity.
The pure administration of development cooperation is handled
by the aid sections of Britain's embassies (with seconded ODA
officials in important recipient countries). There are five regional
Development Divisions, in Bangkok, Barbados, Lilongwe, Nairobi
and (since 1993) Pretoria, as well as a country office in Bangladesh.
All of these have sectoral experts who, depending on the extent
of the projects manage bilateral development cooperation in their
area of responsibility largely on a decentralized basis. They
support the London headquarters in planning, implementing and
monitoring, especially in programme aid and structural adjustment
measures. In addition, consultation and coordination are handled
by the Regional Advisory Group in Fiji and the Dependent Territories
Regional Secretariat in Barbados.
<P>
Other implementing institutions with long experience of the Third
World include the Crown Agents (procurement authorities), the
Commonwealth Development Corporation (similar to Germany's DEG),
the British Council, as well as respected research organizations
such as the Overseas Development Institute or the Institute of
Development Studies.
<P>
The ODA's cooperation with British NGOs has been intensified in
recent years, but is still comparatively modest. During 1993/94
the Joint Funding Scheme disbursed &#163;29 million in enbloc
grants to five established NGOs, as well as project subsidies
of up to 50 per cent to numerous others. Britain's four development
services, including NGOs, were subsidized with about &#163;20
million for the employment of their 2,000 development aid workers
in 55 host countries.
<P>
<B>Quantitative trends</B>
<P>
Until the Thatcher government took over in 1979 there was a high
degree of continuity in Britain's development cooperation in applying
instruments, the quality and quantity of aid provided, and regional
alignment on the Commonwealth, despite several changes of government
and corresponding changes in organizational structures. But since
then there have been pronounced changes. Development cooperation
is under pressure from two sides:
<P>
&#183; as a result of the government's saving and consolidation
policy, the development cooperation budget shrank in real terms
for many years. The real volume of development cooperation during
the 1990s has also been below that of 1979. The official development
assistance (ODA) share of GDP has also dropped. In 1978/79 Britain's
ODAGDP ratio was 0.49 per cent, but is now 0.31 per cent (see
Table 1).
<P>
&#183; against the backdrop of British industry's diminished competitiveness,
the companies and the Ministry of Trade and Industry have increasingly
pushed development cooperation as an export promotion tool. Thus,
strict tieing of aid applies not only to the ATP mixed credits,
but essentially to overall project assistance and most of the
programme aid.
<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 1 : Quantitative trends</caption></B>
<tr><td><td>1978/78<td>1983/84<td>1989/90<td>1993/94
<tr><td>ODA in &#163;bn<td>0.9<td>1.05<td>1.55<td>1.90
<tr><td>ODA in US$bn<td>4.0<td>3.10<td>3.10<td>3.30
<tr><td>ODA as GDP %<td>0.49<td>0.35<td>0.29<td>0.31
<tr><td>Total flows in US$bn<td>25.0<td>11.3<td>7.0<td>10.1
</table>
<P>
Noteworthy is the decline in total financial flows to developing
countries since 1978/79, which is mainly the result of greatly
reduced new bank credits and simultaneous repayment of old debt,
especially in Latin America. By far the greatest part of aid is
provided as grants, so that Britain is consistently among the
leading donor countries in terms of grant element. The multilateral
share of aid has increased from 30 per cent in the 1970s to almost
50 per cent in the 1990s, mainly due to contributions to the European
Development Fund.
<P>
In bilateral aid, great value is placed on programme assistance.
As a rule, it is granted in close conformity with IMF standby
agreements and World Bank structural adjustment loans. Technical
Cooperation, which under the British system consists mainly of
seconding experts to recipient countries and paying the costs
of foreign students and trainees in Britain, accounts at times
for almost 50 per cent of bilateral ODA. Currently, it is being
revised in favour of local specialist staff and increased employment
of shortterm experts.
<P>
<B>Concentration on important recipient countries</B>
<P>
As before, British development policy is characterized by a strong
affinity for former colonial areas, whereby developmental links
are only one element of close economic and political ties.
<P>
About 70 per cent of bilateral aid still flows to Commonwealth
countries. About 4050 per cent of regional ODA is concentrated
on the 10 most important recipients, which traditionally include
India, Bangladesh, Kenya, Tanzania and Malawi and, since recently,
once again Uganda. The shift in geographical distribution from
Asia to subSaharan Africa is shown in Table 2.
<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 2:  Trends in geographic distribution
(in % of bilateral ODA)</caption></b>
<tr><td><td>1978/79<td>1983/84<td>1992/93
<tr><td>SubSaharan Africa<td>33<td>40<td>45
<tr><td>North Africa/Middle East<td>5<td>5<td>4
<tr><td>Asia<td>46<td>41<td>36
<tr><td>America<td>10<td>9<td>8
<tr><td>Europe/Oceania<td>6<td>5<td>7
</table>
<P>
<B>Trends in concepts and practice</B>
<P>
The last comprehensive government document on British development
policy was its White Paper of 1974. Since then there have been
many stepbystep conceptional and practical changes. At present,
for example, the focus is on implementing the resolutions of the
UN Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED) in Rio de
Janeiro in 1992. Seven Agenda 21 goals were formulated which have
since become obligatory for Britain's bilateral and, so far as
possible, multilateral development cooperation. These include
liberalizing economies, increasing production capacity, promoting
good governance (administration, the legal system, democracy),
alleviating poverty, the promotion of education, health, family
planning and women, and securing the environment.
<P>
The changes at the conceptional, as well as the practical, level
of development policy, have always been evolutionary in Britain.
That is, they have been about making efforts to accept the international
debate on development strategy, but at the same time not allowing
the gap between expectations and the reality imposed by political
tensions to become too great. As a result, Britain's development
policy has to date maintained a comparatively high degree of credibility.
<P>
<B>Paul J. Bendix </B>worked with the German Development Institute
(DIE) from1976-86. Since1991, he heads a section for development
policy in the German Development Service (DED) in Berlin.
<p>
<HR>
