<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.04z">

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 26 Friday 7 November 1996

</CENTER></H3>

<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. HUMANITARIAN ACTION IN GREAT LAKES REGION IS

NOT ENOUGH SAY PARTICIPANTS OF EU MINISTERS OF DEVELOPMENT CO-OPERATION

MEETING <BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>A special meeting of the European Union's Ministers

for Development Co-operation was held on Thursday 7 October to

discuss the ongoing crisis in the Great Lakes region. Irish Minister

Joan Burton who opened the session asked the participants to consider

the following key issues - access to the vulnerable populations

following an agreement between the Rwandan, Zairian and rebel

forces; effective delivery of humanitarian assistance to the refugees,

promotion of a safe and dignified return of the Rwandan refugees

in Zaire; ensuring the short-term aid does not create an unsustainable

camp situation and not contradict the political goals of attaining

greater regional stability.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>At a press conference later in the day Mrs Burton

stated that the Meeting had confirmed the absolute urgency of

the setting up of corridors to allow the safe return of Rwandan

refugees in Zaire as all participants were concerned about the

serious risk of an epidemic that the refugees currently faced.

EC Commissioner for Development, Joao de Deus Pinheiro stated

that the means and resources were available but the major problem

remaining was how to get the means and resources through to the

victims. Mr. Akashi, Deputy Secretary General for the UN's Humanitarian

Aid Department described the situation in the region as &quot;a

humanitarian calamity without comparison&quot;. He added that

the political questions such as who would get the aid through,

who would protect the corridors and where the corridors would

be situated will have to be addressed as pledge of humanitarian

assistance was just not enough. Mr Akashi hinted that a neutral

multinational force could contribute towards a more comprehensive

approach.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The participants provided further details answering

questions on the state of affairs in the region. On sending a

neutral force Mrs Bonino, EC Commissioner for Humanitarian assistance

said that clear conclusions had been reached at the Regional summit

in Nairobi and the case had now been referred to the UN Security

Council. She said that it was now up to the Security Council to

set up the mechanisms defined in Nairobi. Mrs Ogata, the UN High

Commissioner for Refugees, confirmed that the Rwandan authorities

had agreed to open up safe corridors through Rwanda and the remaining

concern was for the Zairian section.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The EU Ministers later adopted a resolution calling

for the UN Security Council to react immediately to the Nairobi

proposal in setting up safe corridors and a neutral international

force. According  to Mrs Burton the question of the composition

of the neutral force was not discussed at great length at the

Meeting as this was an issue for the Security Council to discuss.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The European Commission earlier on Wednesday said

it will release a further 25 million ECU for humanitarian aid

in the region. The Commission, which has been following events

in the region through the &quot;Crisis Cell&quot; set up by the

European Commission Humanitarian Office, ECHO, has already released

540 million ECU for humanitarian aid in the region since November

1993.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The EC also stated that it will insist on the setting

up of &quot;humanitarian points of reference&quot; such as the

known position of refugees; the precise identification of available

stocks; the transport routes for distribution of stocks and rapid

contacts with Member States which are willing to provide material

and transport for humanitarian action. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT PRESIDENT CALLS FOR REFORMS

OF EU'S CFSP AND EXTERNAL RELATIONS<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>After the seventh meeting of the Intergovernmental

conference totally dedicated to issues surrounding the Common

Foreign and Security Policy last week, Klaus Haensch the European

Parliament, EP, president, said at a press conference, that the

CFSP has to be &quot;identified by a person who has a sufficiently

long mandate. .. someone within the Commission.&quot; According

to Mr Haensch this idea had little support and another alternative

was for an eminent politician to front CFSP but this idea had

also been received coolly. Mr Haensch also stated that if the

EU does not have military instruments it would not be able to

have a long term credible CFSP. On the EU'S external economic

relations, Mr Haensch said that the Parliament would like to put

an end to disjointed EU foreign policy and that article 113 had

to be widened to include services direct investment and intellectual

property. Mr Haensch however, conceded that realisation of these

proposals will be a long term process requiring a step by step

approach.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. EU SENDS INQUIRY MISSION TO BURMA AS IT TIGHTENS

SCREWS SLORC REGIME<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>Manuel Marin, Vice President of the European Commission

announced on Wednesday 6 November that the Commission will be

sending an inquiry mission to Burma in the near future to check

up on the Burmese regime (SLORC)'s action on the practices on

forced labour in the country. This inquiry could lead to the suspension

the benefits of the generalised system of preferences for Burma.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>Last week the EU Council decided to impose new sanctions

on Burma, namely the ban on entry visas to the EU for senior SLORC

and military officials and their families and suspension of high

level bilateral government visits. These measures were taken because

of the Burmese government's refusal to respond to EU and UN concerns

over human rights violations in the country. Earlier this week

the Burmese foreign minister announced that Burma is planning

retaliatory sanctions against the EU. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. EUROPEAN VESSELS ACCESS TO FISH IN SENEGALESE

WATERS SUSPENDED AS EU/ SENEGAL NEGOTIATIONS OVER A NEW AGREEMENT

THE BREAKDOWN<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The fishing activities of European vessels in Senegalese

water have been suspended following the breakdown in negotiations

between the EU and Senegal on a new fisheries protocol in Dakar

last week. This fallout especially concerns financial compensation

paid by the EU as a counterpart for fishing rights in Senegalese

waters. Senegal is demanding 18 million ECU a year as a financial

counterpart while the EU has proposed only 10 or 12 million ECU.

Senegal has also asked for the EU fishing quota to be reduced

to 10 000 gross barrels from 13 500 in a previous fisheries protocol

signed in 1994.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>No date has been set for the resumption of negotiations

and most European vessels will now seek to redeploy in waters

of neighbouring countries with whom the EU has signed agreements.

<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. LEAST DEVELOPED COUNTRIES TO RECEIVE AID FROM

THE COMMISSION TO PARTICIPATE IN MINISTERIAL CONFERENCE IN SINGAPORE

<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>The European Commission will make funds available

to the least developed countries in order to enable them to participate

in the first Ministerial Conference in Singapore. The Commission

will provide 50 000 ECU which will cover at least 20 % of total

costs necessary for the participation of the Ministers and a second

officer from the least developed countries. The Commission hopes

that this financial support will help the least developed countries

to take an active role in the Singapore Ministerial Conference.

The Conference will be held from 9 to 13 December. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>6. COMMISSION'S GREENPAPER ON LOME ALMOST READY

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>According to <I>Eurostep </I>information the European

Commission's Greenpaper on the future of the Lom&eacute; Convention

will be submitted to the full Commission within the coming two

weeks.<BR>

</FONT>

<HR>

