<HEAD>

<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">

<TITLE>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 36</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<pre>



</pre>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 36 Friday 7 February 1997

</CENTER></H3>

<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></H4><A HREF="index.html">EUROSTEP Home Page</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. DENMARK CONSIDERS THE INCLUSION OF COUNTRIES

LIKE BANGLADESH, NEPAL AND VIETNAM TO LOME CONVENTION</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> According to information from Copenhagen, Danish

Minister for Development, Mr Paul Nielson, has called for countries

like Nepal, Vietnam and Bangladesh to be included in the Lom&eacute;

Convention. Mr Nielson called for a Community policy based on

the criterion of poverty as well as OECD recommendations adding

that the historical links between certain EU Member States and

former colonies should no longer be the foundation for EU development

policy. &quot;Some better-off states within the Lom&eacute; Convention

should receive less aid, but could, in exchange benefit from more

trade guarantees and greater access to the European Union markets&quot;

said Mr Nielson. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Earlier Mr Nielson, along with a Danish delegation,

met with the ACP Committee of Ambassadors in Brussels. The Committee

led by Mr Youssouf Ouedraogo, Ambassador of Burkina Faso and President-in-Office

of the Committee and Mr Lingston, Ambassador for Trinidad and

Tobago and Chair of the Sub Committee on 'future relations with

the ACP', met the Danish ministers to discuss fundamental issues

relating to the EU/ACP partnership and to identify areas in which

the ACP/EU partnership 'must adjust to world geopolitical realities'.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Mr Nielson and Mr Jorgen Estrup, Chair of the Danish

Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee, informed their partners

of the ongoing reflection in Denmark on the Commission's Green

Paper and development co-operation in general. They announced

that a conference involving all the Danish participants in development

co-operation will be held this year on 14 March in Copenhagen.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Denmark  is the first EU Member State to take the

initiative to begin an open and informal debate with the ACP countries

on the future of the EU/ACP relationship, in response the Green

Paper's efforts to encourage debate and dialogue on the issue.

<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. FIRST ACP HEAD OF STATES SUMMIT ON POST LOME

IV TO BE HELD ON 6-7 NOVEMBER IN LIBREVILLE</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The ACP Committee of Ambassadors have set a date

and venue for the first ACP Heads of State summit solely devoted

to the future of ACP/EU relations. The summit will be held on

 6-7 November 1997 in Libreville, Gabon. The idea for the summit

was conceived in Mauritius at the end of the signing of the revised

Lom&eacute; IV Convention and it will serve as an essential stage

of the discussion process in the run up to negotiations on a new

framework for the ACP/EU Co-operation in 1998. In accordance with

Mauritius Declaration, the summit will &quot;examine development

issues in an appropriate political framework and finalise the

strategy that must underpin future ACP/EU relations&quot; from

the point of view of the ACP countries. The summit will be preceded

by an extraordinary council of ACP foreign ministers and ministers

responsible for the Lom&eacute; Convention on 4-5 November in

Libreville. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. PINHEIRO CALLS ON AFRICAN COUNTRIES TO SPEED

UP CONFLICT PREVENTION MECHANISMS AND REGIONAL CO-OPERATION</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> Mr Joao de Deus Pinheiro, EC Commissioner responsible

for the ACP and South Africa, has appealed to African political

leaders to speed up conflict prevention and regional co-operation

mechanisms in order to create an environment conducive to stability

and economic growth.  Mr Pinheiro, on his first official visit

to East Africa, made this appeal during talks with the Heads of

State of Ethiopia, Eritrea, Uganda and the Secretary General of

the Organisation for African Unity, OAU, on the current tensions

and conflicts in the region. The Commissioner recalled that the

principles of good management in public matters and the respect

for human rights are key elements of EU development co-operation

policy. He emphasised the EU's efforts in promoting lasting peace

and stability in the Great Lakes region through the work of its

envoy to the region, Aldo Ajello. Mr Pinheiro expressed his hope

that an international conference on the Great Lakes region will

be held, organised under the auspices of the UN and the OAU.<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. DAC COMMENDS EUROPEAN COMMUNITY ASSISTANCE

TO LDCs BUT CALLS FOR IMPROVEMENT OF TRANSPARENCY AND CONTROL</FONT></B>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The Development Aid Committee,

DAC, of the OECD praises Community development policy for its

&quot;distinctive and ambitious goals&quot; but notes that the

EC still has a lot of progress to make on the road to control

and transparency, in its annual report &quot;Development Co-operation&quot;,

published on 5 February. In a chapter devoted to the Community,

the DAC states that the EC has &quot;introduced improved procedures

for designing and managing projects and upgraded the evaluation

programme&quot;. It adds that, concerning management, emphasis

had been placed on transparency and progress in country strategy.

This is expected to improve the focus and coherence of aid programming

at country level and the integration of different EC aid instruments

and policies. However, it states that &quot;the Commission needed

to strengthen further both its in-house and contracted capabilities

to plan, manage and implement its new generation of projects&quot;

adding that it would be advantageous if one independent and credible

evaluation unit covered the entire EC ODA programme. </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The report recalls that Community aid to developing

countries increased from USD $ 4.8 million in 1994 to USD $5.4

billion in 1995 and that the Community is the second donor body

after the World Bank. Sub-Saharan Africa's share of Community

aid is still the greatest (56% of ODA) but is decreasing compared

to that to the Mediterranean countries in North Africa and the

Middle East (16% of bilateral ODA) and Latin America (10%). The

share of aid for emergency and humanitarian aid greatly increased

from 1% in 1988/89 to 14% in 1994.  </FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> On the whole, world public aid for development co-operation

continues to decline. Payments by DAC countries to developing

countries and multilateral organisations fell by 9% in real terms

in 1995. In total, ODA accounted for less than 0.27% of the global

GNP of DAC member countries in 1995. The largest fall in ODA is

recorded in the USA where it represents only USD $ 2 per inhabitant

per month as compared to USD $ 12 for France and USD $14 for Denmark

and Norway. <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. EU WELCOMES SUCCESS OF AFRICAN MEDIATION IN

CENTRAL AFRICAN REPUBLIC</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=2> The Dutch Presidency on behalf of the European Union

published a declaration on Wednesday welcoming the success of

African mediation efforts in putting an end to the recent conflict

in the Central African Republic. The Declaration stated, &quot;The

Union would like the successful African mediation in settling

the conflict in the area of Central Africa, mediation undertaken

under the impetus of the Heads of State meeting at the Ouagadougou

Summit of December 1996, to be an encouraging example for on-going

mediations in other situations of conflict..&quot;<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<HR>

