<html>
<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - Chinese Dissident Wei Jingsheng Jailed</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="823308" alink=#d9d919 vlink="#FF7F00">
[ONEWORLD NEWS SERVICE]
<p>
<b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>


<h2>Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng jailed for 14 years</h2>


<p>

<b>Wednesday 13 December</b><p>

The Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng was jailed for 14 years last night, after being found guilty of conspiring to overthrow the Chinese government.<p>

The judges took a mere five hours to reach their decision.  The Chinese government had claimed that the trial would be open, but diplomats and journalists were prevented from entering the courtroom.<p>

The trial, at the Intermediate People's Court in Beijing, was carried out under heavy security, as police roped off the area around the building.  Wei faced the death penalty if convicted.<p>

Wei Jingsheng is regarded as the leader of China's fragmented and disillusioned dissident movement, most of whose members are now either in jail or in exile abroad.  He was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize this year.<p>

Although relatively unknown within China, Wei is well-known around the world for his uncompromising criticism of the country's Communist government.  He has described China's ageing paramount leader, Deng Xiaoping, as a dictator in the worst tradition of Chinese emperors.<p>

Wei Jingsheng - who had been a Red Guard during the Cultural Revolution - first fell foul of Chinese government repression in 1979, when he was sentenced to 15 years imprisonment for counter-revolutionary activities.<p>

At that time he was active in the Democracy Wall movement - named after the large political posters put on a wall at the side of Beijing's Tiananmen Square - and called for a 'fifth modernisation' of democracy to accompany the 'four modernisations' of economic development.<p>

Wei was released from prison in September 1993, after serving nearly all of his 15 year sentence - much of it in solitary confinement.  He was rearrested in April 1994 and held incommunicado for 19 months before being officially charged with sedition on 21 November 1995.  Wei Jingsheng has spent only 6 months in the last 16 years as a free man.<p>

The verdict of his trial is being seen as a sign of the Chinese government's determination not to give ground on the human rights issue.  This attitude was encouraged earlier this year by the United States' decision to renew China's most favoured nation trading status despite continuing human rights violations.<p>

Wei has himself condemned the attitude of Western governments and business leaders, whose interests he said would ultimately be harmed by their lack of interest in pushing for democratic reform in China.<p>

<ul><br><li>For more information on dissidents in China, see <b><a href="../index_oc/indexindex_cde.html">Index on Censorship</a></b><br>
<li>See also Index on Censorship's <b><a href="../realaudio/index.html#wei">RealAudio feature on Wei Jinsheng</a></b>  <br><font size=-1>Note: To hear this feature you'll need to <b><a href="http://www.realaudio.com/products/player.html">download and install the</a></b> RealAudio player.</font><p>

</ul>





<p>




