<title>Index on Censorship - Information</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" text="#000000" link="#9c181c" vlink="#9c181c">
<p>
<center><hr><hr></center>

<h1>About Index</h1>

<i>Index on Censorship </i>was founded in 1972 by Stephen Spender. Its aim was, and still is, to protect the basic human right to free expression. Over the past years <i>Index </i>has reported on censorship issues from all around the world and has added to the essential debates on those issues. Each issue of <i>Index </i>contains a list of attacks on free expression Ñ compiled country by country. These lists remain as extensive today as they were in the early days of <i>Index. </i>They are a trenchant and harrowing reminder that continued vigilance is essential.
<p>

The list of writers who have contributed to <i>Index </i>is an impressive testimony to its continued importance. They include Vaclav Havel, Nadine Gordimer, Salman Rushdie, Doris Lessing, Arthur Miller, A S Byatt, Aung San Suu Kyi, Noam Chomsky, Julian Barnes, Dubravka Ugresic, Ronald Dworkin, Umberto Eco, Jack Mapanje and Naguib Mahfouz. <i>Index</i> is also a forum for new writers of whom the world will hear more.
<p>

But perhaps the most telling testimony is that which we receive from readers in those countries where censorship is a life and death issue. <i>Index </i>operates an assisted subscriptions programme which allows readers in South America, Africa, Asia, and the former Communist countries to receive the magazine free of charge. The letters which we receive from readers in these countries are a telling demonstration of the magazine's importance.
<p>
<font size=2>Picture: &copy; Panos Pictures</font><p>

&quot;[<i>Index]</i> is greatly respected in our country.<br>&quot;
<i>Human Rights Organisation, Colombia</i>
<p>

&quot;I would like to thank you for this great offer which I'm unable to keep to myself but keep on offering to others who don't receive to also enjoy and see what goes on in other parts of the world. This has created more effort in self-expression.&quot;<br>
<i>Teacher/sculptor, Kenya</i>
<p>

&quot;<i>Index</i> has taught me a lot of things. 1. Respect peace. 2. Not to forget history. 3. Respect human rights. 4. To learn for future development.&quot;<br>
<i>Civil servant, Uganda</i>
<p>

<i>Index </i>is supported by its associated charity Writers and Scholars Educational Trust. It is funded by subscriptions and donations from individuals and foundations. A year's subscription to <i>Index </i>costs just £36 (£42 overseas, $50 USA). There is a special student rate of £25 or $35 world-wide.




<h2>How to find Index:</h2>

<p>

Index on Censorship<br>
33 Islington High Street<br>
London N1 9LH, UK<br>
Telephone 0171 278 2313<br>
Fax 0171 278 1878<br>
