</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title> Index on Censorship - 15 March 1996</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#9c181c" vlink="#9c181c"><img src="index_pix/index_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="info.html"> Index on Censorship</a></i><hr><h2>Unleashing the Furies</h2><h3>Adewale Maja-Pearce<p>15 March 1996</h3>The Trials of Brother Jero, which was first performed over three decades ago, has remained one of Wole Soyinka's best-loved plays. It centres on a beach divine, a self-proclaimed 'prophet by birth and by inclination', who fleeces his 'customers I mean worshippers well, customers, if you like' by playing on their gullibility. Brother Jero is a vicious little man, a liar and a sneak, forever manipulating those around him. But Brother Jero has a weakness: the 'Daughters of Discord', one of whom is currently tormenting him: 'Goes to swim over there and then waits for me to be in the midst of my meditation before she swings her hips across here, flaunting her near-nakedness before my eyes...' He tries it on with her before the day is out and gets a hiding for his pains, but he's presently confronted with a more pressing problem, which is how to get his assistant certified insane in order to evade the relatively insignifant debt he owes the poor man's wife. He succeeds, 'And so the day is saved'.<p>How much of contemporary Nigeria are we to read into this play? Or, rather, how much does the Federal Military Government of General Sani Abacha want us to read into it? On 27 February, a scheduled performance of The Trials of Brother Jero at the National Theatre in Lagos was suddenly cancelled owing to 'a technical fault' even as the audience queued outside. The following day, Fezi Productions, the company concerned, attempted to stage the play at a local secondary school. This time they were visited by members of the State Security Service (SSS), who proceeded to arrest the director, Israel Eboh, the technical director, Albert Odulate, and a third person, Richard Bruce. All three were taken to the SSS headquarters, put in seperate rooms, and asked to write statements about any other Soyinka play they had performed. Additionally, Israel Eboh was (in his own words) 'told to sign an undertaking stopping the show', before they were released. The irony in all of this, and the reason for staging this particular Soyinka play, is that The Trials of Brother Jero also happens to be a set-text in secondary schools throughout the country, which would seem to put the authorities in something of a quandary.<p>On the other hand, it might not have mattered much which of Soyinka's plays was being performed. 'Wanted Dead or Alive: The Junta Guns for Soyinka' was the cover story of a recent issue of Tell (5 March), the weekly magazine of no fixed abode since last Christmas when its editor, Nosa Igiebor, was taken into custody, where he currently remains. Soyinka himself, who has vowed to 'cripple this administration', even to the extent of temporarily abandoning literature, said in a recent interview that he was one of three Nigerians that the government is 'terrified' of. The other two Chief Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner of the annulled elections, and Shehu Musa Yar'Adua, a retired general of considerable political ambition are currently in detention, the one for treason, the other for supposedly planning a coup. According to the article in Tell, Soyinka might by now have been executed (as Yar'Adua so nearly was) but for his timely flight into exile. Writers are judicially murdered in Nigeria, as we all discovered when Ken Saro-Wiwa and his fellow Ogoni activists were hanged last November following a rigged trial.<p>The government, for its part, has openly accused the country's only Nobel laureate of being behind two unexplained bomb blasts and the crash of a presidential jet in which General Abacha's eldest son was killed: 'His utterances that he will cripple this government is a matter to be taken seriously, so people should talk to him. Those who know what triggered off the civil war in Nigeria (in the late sixties) will know that what Soyinka is presently doing was exactly a replica of what triggered off the civil war.' Thus the ever-garrulous Minister for Special Duties, Alhaji Wada Nas, in an interview he gave The Guardian newspaper (30 January) in the wake of the three incidents. As Soyinka himself retorted on the BBC: 'I think this regime has actually reached the stage of acute dementia. It's entire propaganda service has gone Goebbelsian.' <p>And that, after all, is the whole point about this government, in power now for just over two years. Lacking credibility either at home or abroad, it functions only as government-by-propaganda, which is why the economy is going to hell. At every turn the government tries to convince us that it seized power in order to save us from a fate worse than death, and at every turn Soyinka, with his unrivalled access to the hated Western Media and its 'orchestrated campaign of calumny' (to quote the even more garrulous Dr Walter Ofonagoro, the Minister for Information and Culture), pours scorn on a dictator who, 'totally lacking in vision', is 'prepared to reduce Nigeria to rubble as long as he survives to preside over a name...'<p> Brother Jero, in Soyinka's play, lives to fight another day; but: 'Ingrate! Monster! I curse you with the curse of the Daughters of Discord. May they be your downfall. May the Daughters of Eve bring down ruin on your head!' Thus his former mentor, whose land he stole in order to set up in business, and whose words continue to rankle, spoiling everything. It seems that Abacha, the man of war, is not so visionless that he doesn't understand the power of the word.<p><hr>©Copyright: Index on Censorship<hr><p><b>Send us your views</b><a href="mailto:indexoncenso@gn.apc.org"><img border=0 src="index_pix/red_button1.gif"></a><p><TABLE BORDER=6><TR><TD><a href="index.html">Back to INDEX Home Page</a></TD></TR></TABLE><hr></body></html>
