<html>
<head>
<title>TVE - Women of the World</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<hr>



<center><h1>WOMEN OF THE WORLD</h1></center>
<h3>Films for the Fourth World Conference on Women:  Beijing, September 5-13 1995</h3>


The Fourth World Conference on Women, being held by the United Nations in Beijing this September, is a chance for the world to take stock of just what women have achieved in the last 10 years  - and just how far, in all too many areas, they still have to go.
<p>

As just some examples, women work twice as many hours as men - but earn only one per cent of the world's wealth. Of the one billion adults in the world who can't read or write, two thirds are women. And eighty per cent of all refugees are women, or the children who depend on them.
<p>


TVE is offering a wide-ranging package of films - the majority made by Southern women directors - for broadcast in September to coincide with, and to raise awareness of, the Beijing Conference. These unique programmes focus on women's lives around the world, in all their colour and diversity: from the turbulent history of women's lives in China over the last 50 years - told through the story of four generations of women in one family - to a moving account of Guatemala's 45,000 war widows who are no longer prepared to live their lives invisibly; from a chilling investigation of the widespread sterilization of women in Brazil, and the culture that forbids them more humane methods of family planning, to the triumpant tale of women in India who are confronting the demons of 'arak' - the local village alcohol - as a result of education and literacy classes. <p>

 <center></center><p>



<h2>The WOMEN OF THE WORLD Programmes</h2>

The programmes available in the <b>Women of the World</b> series fall into the categories set out below. TVE holds all the rights to this package of programmes so if you are interested in purchasing them for broadcast or non-broadcast use please contact TVE's Distribution Office to request an order form.
<p>

<b>Tel: (44 171) 586 5526<br>			Fax: (44 171)  586 4866<br>
Electronic Mail: <a href="mailto:tve-dist@tve.org.uk">tve-dist@tve.org.uk</a></b>

<p>

<b>Women's Hour - </b>five 52 minute documentaries, made by women directors from the developing world - China, Vietnam, Palestine, India, Nigeria, and Brazil - and presenting audiences around the world with their own, unique perspective on gender;<p>


<b>Short Stories - </b>a series of six 10 minute news features on background issues on the Beijing agenda, also made by women directors, with an introduction from Elizabeth Dowdeswell, Executive Director of the United Nations Environment Programme;
<p>

<b>Beijing Features - </b>four 20-30 minute short documentaries and a series of five minute films from around the world on issues on the Beijing agenda;
<p>

<b>Beijing 'Spots' - </b>a series of 21 one-minute public service announcements, or 'spots' - on the status and condition of women worldwide.  



<h2>WOMAN'S HOUR  <font size=-1>5 x 52' documentaries</font></h2>			

<b>HALF THE SKY </b>is a timely exploration of the dramatic changes within the lives of four generations of women in the Xie family over the last 50 years in China - an appropriate subject for a film set in the country that is hosting the Beijing conference. Produced by Chinese director Sun Shuyun for  the UK's Channel Four, this 52 minute film takes its title from Chairman Mao Zedong's dictum that 'women are half the sky -  and absolutely the equal of men'.
<p>

<b>HANAN ASHRAWI - A WOMAN OF HER TIME </b>is an intimate portrait of the woman who played a key role in negotiating the Palestinian/Israeli peace accord. Directed and produced by award-winning Palestinian director Mai Masri, the film explores Hanan Ashrawi's early family life, her first encounters with the PLO, and her struggle to reconcile the demands of her public persona with her role as wife and mother - in a region where democracy has so far had little impact on the status of women.
<p>

<b>RISING ABOVE - WOMEN OF VIETNAM </b>is an exploration of the dynamics of sexual politics in Vietnam, directed by Lebanese filmmaker Heiny Srour, with Vietnamese associate producer Thu Ngyen. Women fought alongside men as equals in the Vietnam war; now the revival of Confucianism and the spread of market forces are conspiring to relegate them once again to the role of second class citizens.
<p>

<b>THE PREFERRED SEX ... THE DESIRED NUMBER </b>is a provocative documentary that provides a candid insight into women's reproductive health and status in Nigeria and India. Produced by Daniel Riesenfeld, the documentary is made up of two stories: Nigerian director Ngozi Onwurah examines the tradition in Nigeria of honouring a woman's ability to bear more than ten children, while Indian director Manjira Datta investigates the preference for male babies in India, and the tragic case of Lali Devi who poisoned herself and two of her girl children because she could not conceive a boy.
<p><center></center><p>



<b>LIBERATION (VENTRE LIBRE) </b>deals with issues of reproductive rights, illegal abortion and the promotion of sterilization as a family planning method for even teenage girls in Brazil - a country with the highest rate of unsafe abortions in the world. Brazilian director Ana Luiza Azevedo has a made a graphic film which tells the intimate stories of women who - with no access to safe family planning services - risk their lives and health to avoid having more children.

<a name="short"></a>
<h2>SHORT STORIES  <font size=-1>6 x 10' documentaries</font></h2>			

Introduced by UNEP's Executive Director, Ms Elizabeth Dowdeswell, these features focus on some of the <i>Critical Areas of Concern on the Platform for Action </i>due to be agreed in Beijing. They look at problems of domestic violence and substance abuse in the Caribbean; women's empowerment through an innovative fish farming project in Fiji; a women's literacy programme in Andrah Pradesh, India, which inspired a state-wide anti-liquor campaign; women as victims of militarization in Guatemala, where there are 45,000 war widows; women negotiating for their own health care provision in the new democracy of South Africa; and women caught up in the global drug trade in Hong Kong.

<ul><b>A Little Learning Goes a Long Way</b><br>
Napur Basu's film looks at rural women in the state of Andra Pradesh who first got together when they enrolled on a national literacy programme - and are now waging a state-wide campaign against the sellers of  'arak'- the local alcohol.
<p>

<b>Domestic Violence in the Caribbean</b><br>
Domestic violence in the Caribbean is on the increase and women - as both carers, and the victims themselves of violence - are at the centre of the struggle to combat the problem. Judith Laird's film uses drama and 'rap' music to show how Caribbean women are  challenging the problem head on.
<p>

<b>A Healthy Start</b><br>
South African society is undergoing momentous changes - amongst these, the debate over a new national health policy. Sandra Herrington's film follows a group of women fighting to ensure that their needs and experience were included in the decision-making process.
<p>

<b>Teach a Woman How To Fish and...</b><br>
In the overpopulated island of Fiji, women have long ensured their survival by subsistence fishing, involving long hours of work in precarious conditions. Amelia Simmons' film shows that a new initiative ensuring a greater role for women in the decision-making process has had a profound affect on their lives both in the waters and out!
<p></ul>
<center></center>


<ul>
<b>Footprints of Sorrow:  Widows of Guatemala</b><br>
In Guatemala there are 45,000 widows - mostly uneducated women who have lost their husbands as a result of decades of political violence. Claudia Acedevo's stirring film shows that the women are now fighting back, demanding that their rights as indigenous women be recognized and that human rights violations be brought to an end.
<p>

<b>Migrant Workers in Hong Kong</b><br>
In the 1990s over three million workers - mostly women -  left the Philippines to go and work as migrant workers in the Middle East, Singapore and Hong Kong. Anastasia Edwards' film looks at the lives of the Filipino 'amahs' who have decided to take the plunge and find work in the financial mecca of Hong Kong.
</ul>

<h2>BEIJING FEATURES</h2>		


<ul><b>Little by Little </b>(25 minutes) focuses on reproductive health as the key factor in both the empowerment of women and in sustainable development. In Ghana, Nepal and Bolivia, director Chris Walker's films shows women taking small but crucial steps to improve their lives and their health. 
<p>

<b>Almost Like Fire</b> (20 minutes) traces a journey home to the Philippines by development worker Fely Villareal. On the island of Cabugao she finds how women have revolutionised their lives by breaking cultural traditions and setting up their own fishing enterprises.  'In the past my symbol for this island was women crying quietly at night, but now they are free.' Other encounters are less encouraging with women from the overcrowded slums speaking about the constant threat of domestic violence. 
<p>

<b>Rites of Passage: Four Stories of Survival</b> (24 minutes) follows four teenage girls as they come of age and traces the personal cost of this transition. In Nicaragua, Aleyda is addicted to glue-sniffing and is slipping into a life of prostitution; in India, Tarranum has been taken out of school to be married off; in Jamaica, Natalyn is 14 years old and seven months pregnant, and in Burkina Faso Adjara faces the prospect of female genital mutilation - seen by local women as essential if a woman is to enter married life.
<p>

<b>Science for Survival</b> (50 minutes) is set in India and investigates rural women's knowledge of traditional crop seed varieties. Spearheaded by ecologist and ex-nuclear physicist-turned-activist Vandana Shiva, a people's movement in India has grown up in opposition to what it regards as 'reductionist' Western science. The film explores Vandana Shiva's ideas that putting 'the feminist principle' back into science will give poor countries back control over their own destinies.</ul>
<p><ul></center>
<br clear=all></ul><br> <p>


<ul>

<b>5-Minute Project </b>(10 x 5 minutes) was born from Women Empowering Communication, a conference which took place in Bangkok in 1994, where producers made initial commitments to prepare stories. Women from over 20 countries are participating in this global video project and the end result will be a video anthology that covers the issues most important to them. They will represent their points of view in five-minute segments - both documentaries and dramas. Other videos show how women gain confidence and raise their self-esteem by learning to value the work they do - often in innovative ways.
</ul>

 <h2>BEIJING SPOTS  <font size=-1>21 x 1' spots</font></h2>				

From the provocative and stylish opening graphics - accompanied by a saucy wolf-whistle - to the final title announcing the Beijing conference, these 'spots' offer a snapshot of gender, power and ownership in 1995 - five years before women were promised equality.

<p>


These latest <b>Moving Pictures </b>films were made possible by support from the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), United Nations Department of Public Information (UNDPI), United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), United Nations Secretariat, the World Health Organisation (WHO), the Danish International Development Agency (DANIDA), Norwegian Agency for Development Co-operation (NORAD), National Commission for Development Education, the Netherlands (NCO), the German Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ), UK Overseas Development Administration (ODA), the European Commission (EC), and the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation.
<p>

<b>The views expressed in the films are entirely those of the film-makers and do not necessarily represent the official views of the grant-making organisations.</b>
<p>


