<title>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 20</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 20 Friday 13 September 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>

<P>

</p>

<p><b>1.	EU/ACP: JOINT ASSEMBLY,  PLENARY IN LUXEMBOURG FROM 23 TO 27 	SEPTEMBER</b></p>

<p>The ACP/EU Joint Assembly, co-chaired by the UK Conservative Lord Plumb and Sir John Kaputin (Papua New Guinea), will open its autumn session in Luxembourg 23 September.</p>

<p>Between 23 and 27 September, MEPs and their colleagues of ACP States will discuss the reports by Jean-Louis Firmin (Haiti) on the future relations between EU and ACP countries, the situation in specific countries (Burundi, Rwanda, Liberia, Nigeria, Angola, Mozambique, Sudan, Somalia and Western Sahara), the development of relations between the EU and South Africa, the results of the Conference on the information society, the very controversial EU draft directive on cocoa and its consequences for producer countries among ACPs and the EU regulation on bananas.</p>

<p>A hearing will take place on Wednesday 25 September on Climate Change and Small Island Countries. </p>

<p><b>2.	IGC/AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL</b></p>

<p>According to Amnesty International, the IGC should provide the opportunity to place the respect for and protection of human rights and fundamental freedoms at the heart of legal basis of the Union. Rather than making new declarations, it should ensure that the existing ones are put into practice through providing new instruments with the European Union framework. AI makes four concrete recommendations:</p>

<OL>

<LI>The IGC should introduce a human rights impact assessment for all important decisions under Common Foreign and Security Policy.<P>

<LI>The Member States should undertake to fully respect international instruments such as the Conclusions of the UNHCR Executive Committee and the Handbook of the UNHCR on Procedures and Criteria for determining Refugee Status.<p>

<LI>The Treaty of Rome should be amended to allow accession to the European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms.<p>

<LI>The IGC should also provide the opportunity to establish a framework of transparency and accountability at EU level in the field of military, security and police transfers. An EU Code of Conduct on Arms Trade would be a good first step in that direction.<p>

</OL>

<p>At a more general level, Amnesty calls for the principles of transparency and accountability to be incorporated in the EU treaties as a fundamental basis for all activity and recommends that a right of information for the public matters concerning EU human rights issues be provided in the Treaty itself.</p>

<p><b>3.	EU/WTO/BANANAS</b></p>

<p>A World Trade Organisation arbitrarian panel has begun examining the complaint lodged by the United States and four Latin American producer countries against the Union banana import system. According to the legal advisers for the Caribbean exporter countries, notably the  European representative of the Caribbean Banana Exporters Association (CBEA), the US argued that only government representatives should be admitted to the hearing, thus excluding the legal advisers from the session, and "further infringing upon the right of Caribbean producers to defend themselves, when 60% of their export earnings are in danger". The CBEA also warned of the "economic disaster" facing its producers should the European scheme be judged illegal.</p>

<p><b>4.	GENERAL AFFAIRS INFORMAL</b></p>

<UL>

<LI>EU governments expressed their "absolute opposition" to US Helms-Burton legislation punishing European for profiting from Cuba. No nation, they said, should unilaterally impose its laws to others. But rather than carry out their threat to ask for a WTO arbitrarian panel on the dispute, ministers appeared to agree to postpone such action until after the US election.<p>

<LI>The Irish presidency reiterated its pledge to have a draft text of the revised Maastricht Treaty ready to give to Dutch officials when they take over the EU presidency. Foreign ministers set 5 October as the date for a mini-summit in Dublin, which Spring said would be an occasion for top-level reflection on IGC matters.<p>

<LI>Led by Belgium, ministers agreed to promote an EU-wide initiative to combat sexual abuse and the exploitation of children. They agreed that their governments would begin work immediately on proposals to be discussed by the EU justice and interior ministers at their informal meeting in Dublin on 27 September. The Commission also said it would present a proposal at that meeting.<p>

</UL>

<p><b>5.	EU/CITIZENS</b></p>

<p>"Grande Place Europe" (http://www.eurplace.org) is a new debate forum on the reform of the European Union now open on Internet. Initiated by seven European organisations with the support of the Commission, the net forum proposes subjects of discussion such as: citizen's rights, the aims of the EU defence policies, the relevance of social politics, the environment, the EU's role on the international scene etc. Contributions to the debate should be sent to: eurit@eurit/it. A special section is reserved for research centres, European associations and schools, which will be given a free WEB page for explaining who they are. Application forms are available from the project coordinator: Centro "Italia Europea", EURIT # Tel: +39 6 397 46 91 # Fax: +39 6 397 46 94.</p>

<p><b>6.	PUBLICATIONS</b></p>

<p>We would like to inform you about the following publications which we find relevant:</p>

<UL>

<LI>The CIIR from London has published a report<i> <b>Continental shift: European policies towards the South</b>.</i> The European Union has failed to deliver a set of coherent policies, preferring instead to create a new threat in the form of an over-populated crime-ridden South. This comment traces the path of EU development policy and makes recommendations for reform to benefit the South and the EU itself. CIIR Comment Series 1996 ISBN 1852871504  36pp  &pound;2.50<p>

<LI>The European Centre in Luxembourg publishes an interesting monthly bulletin called <b><i>eurOsur</b></i>. It is free of charge, containg monthly articles concerning the European Union /Mercosur Documentary Link, (14pp). The articles are in English, in French, in Portuguese and in Spanish. To obtain this bulletin you can contact:<BR>	

Centre europ&eacute;en<BR>

Place de l'Europe 2<BR>

B&acirc;timent Schuman, bureau 6.8<BR>

L-2929 Luxembourg <BR>

Tel: +352 4300 2907 Fax:<b> +</b>352 4300 2506.<p>

<LI>The DanChurchAid Burma Resources publishes articles concerning the situation in Burma and produces slides and videos which are lended for free. However most of the articles and the videos are in Danish. So there would be some translations costs. For information concerning media resources please contact journalist Bjarne Ussing # Tel: +45 33 15 28 00 # Fax: +45 33 25 18 40 # E-mail: ccc3325@vip.cybercity.dk.</font></p>

</UL>

