<head>
<title>UGANDA</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center>UGANDA</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/uganda.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=500 height=323 alt="Map of Uganda">
</p>
<hr>
<b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	21.8 million

<p>Population growth rate	3.1% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	185
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	28%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	59%	

<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID began work in Uganda in 1981. Today work in four development areas is reaching a
population of more than 180,000 people. Communities in all four areas are getting the support they
need to develop the management structures needed to take control of their own development. 

<p>As the capacity of these community groups increases, the need for ACTIONAID's input decreases.
Programme activities include development of adult and child literacy, primary healthcare,
agricultural production, access to clean water and improvement of sanitation.  

<p><h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work In Uganda</h3>
<b> ACTIONAID has: </b>
<p><ul><li> developed a distance learning scheme for primary school teachers which has now been
extended across Uganda by the Ministry of Education. Called MITEP (the Mubende Integrated Teacher
Education Programme), 900 teachers participated in the original scheme, 80 per cent of whom had had
no formal training.

<p><li> supported the development of TASO (The Aids Support Organisation), the first community-based
HIV/AIDS organisation in Uganda. Approximately 10 per cent of the population is affected by HIV/AIDS,
with the biggest group between the 16-40 age range. Through the Strategies for Action programmes,
ACTIONAID continues to support grassroots organisations providing counselling and services to people
affected.

<p><li> helped farmers whose production is hampered by declining soil fertility, prevalence of crop
disease and lack of access to markets. Discussion with local people helps identify the best strategy
for development, whether through establishing savings and credit groups, better storage facilities or
training in new techniques.
</ul>
</font<


