<HTML>



<HEAD>



<TITLE>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 18</TITLE>



<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Klaus Hoefsloot">

</HEAD>



<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">



<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 18 Friday 19 July 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1. BURMA</B>

<P>

The European Parliament adopted a resolution on Thursday afternoon

which calls for economic sanctions against Burma. The motion on

the political situation and human rights abuses in Burma welcomes

recent decisions of Carlsberg and Heineken to withdraw all investments

from Burma.

<P>

The motion also calls on the European Council to respond in full

to Aung San Suu Kyi's request that the EU implements economic

sanctions against the SLORC with the establishment of a trade

boycott, the cessation of tourism and the withdrawal of investment

in Burma by European Companies. Aung San Suu Kyi specifically

addressed the EP through a video, taped in Rangoon last week,

and smuggled out of the country by the Burma Center of the Netherlands.

The Burmese people will not suffer from economic sanctions, she

said.

<P>

At the General Affairs Council  of the 15 July, the Ministers

criticised Burma's government for suppressing democracy movements

there, but did not agree to Danish demands for sanctions against

Rangoon. EU governments said they did not want to impose sanctions

on Burma without UN backing.

<P>

Forty-six organisations based in thirteen European countries and

in the United States of America call today for economic sanctions

against Burma. The organisations endorse a petition in support

of the motion for a resolution by the European Parliament. A number

of member organisations from Eurostep, Aprodev and Euro-Cidse

have signed this petition.

<P>

On 24 July, a small demonstration will be held in front of the

Parliament Building at 8h30. Afterwards, the Burma group will

present the case at the Development Committee of the European

Parliament. The purpose of this meeting is to provide the Committee

with information and analysis of current political and economic

developments. After the meeting a press conference has been organised.

A follow-up meeting will be held at Eurostep from 14h00 to 18h00

on the European strategy with all NGOs who will be there.

<P>

<B>2. RULES OF PROCEDURES </B>

<P>

The European Parliament finally adopted this week the new rules

concerning the MEP's financial interests and the conduct for lobbyist.

<P>

The new rules aim to close the loopholes in the present arrangements

for the Parliament's 626 MEPs.

<P>

In future they will have to make a personal, detailed declaration

of their professional activities, any other paid functions or

activities and financial or staff support they receive from anywhere

except the Parliament. Nonetheless, they do not have to say how

much they earn. These details will be kept in a register, which

will be updated annually and open to the public.

<P>

In future, lobbyist will have to sign a register and comply with

a code of conduct in exchange for a pass granting them regular

access to MEPs and assistants. The code will be drawn up by the

Parliament's rules committee after the summer holidays.

<P>

The code is expected to take as its starting point the guidelines

which the institution's quaestors already require regular visitors

to respect. That 13-point set of instructions is directed at embassies,

consulates, representations of states and regions, commercial

organisations and public affairs practitioners dealing with EU

institutions.

<P>

As MEPs continue to bring more transparency into their own dealings,

they are also facing demands to clarify the status of their assistants,

many of whom live in Belgium in a legal twilight.

<P>

<B>3. CFSP</B>

<P>

The European Parliament, for which the external perception of

CFSP could be improved by giving a single Commissioner all competencies

in matters of external action, deplores the fact that the Commission

had presented no proposal for joint action to the Council, and

stresses the importance that the Commission should exercise its

right of initiative in the field. As for the Council, the EP regrets

that it had had insufficient recourse to the instruments provided

for by the Treaty as regards the role of Parliament in CFSP as

well as criticising the &quot;apparent confusion&quot; in the

use of common positions and joint actions. The EP therefore calls

on the Council to inform it regularly on developments in CFSP

and to consult it as a preventative measure on common positions

and joint actions that it intends adopting.

<P>

The Union is growing in size and in its institutions, Gay Mitchel,

Minister of State, observed on behalf of the Irish Presidency.

Its role as regards external relations is much greater that was

the case for the other presidencies, he observed. CFSP has to

evolve too and <I>Member States have vote to design CFSP institutions

to suit any foreign viewpoint, but to suit the evolution of the

Union</I>. In this context, the Union has to consider security

in its wider sense, including for example the fight against drugs.

Neutral countries would have a role to play in this context. The

WEU Treaty expires in 1998, but there needs to be exploration

of the role neutral countries could have within its framework:

the institutions have to show imagination.

<P>

Next Monday, 22 July, the negotiators of the CFSP will meet in

Brussels, and the Irish Presidency will bring new proposals on

the table.

<P>

Speaking for the Commission, Hans van den Broek, noted a &quot;dire

need&quot; for action, for instruments and political will.

<P>

<B>3. EU/ASEAN</B>

<P>

The European Commission is hoping to widen the Union's links with

Asia by moving quickly to reinforce ties with India and Pakistan.

<P>

External Relations Commissioner, Manuel Marin, will visit Pakistan

on 20 July before heading for Indonesia to hold talks with foreign

ministers from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).

Brief visits to Malaysia and Thailand will follow.

<P>

Before leaving for Pakistan, Marin said he wanted to expand the

Euro-Asia dialogue by either inviting India and Pakistan to the

London summit or by creating a separate &quot;political platform&quot;

for relations between Europe and South Asia.

<P>

Seeking to smooth ruffled feathers in Pakistan for example, Marin

says that instead of looking at negative measures such as sanctions,

he hopes to cooperate with Islamabad on eliminating child labour.

<P>

Unless South Asian countries made faster progress in developing

closer regional ties, said Marin, they could not secure a region-to-region

dialogue with Europe. But he promised that bilateral ties with

individual countries would be strengthened.

<P>

<B>4. PETER BASTOGI</B>

<P>

Despite that Peter is still in hospital, he is recovering slowly

but surely from his meningitis. He will probably come out next

week.

<P>

<B>5. PAF HOLIDAYS</B>

<P>

The PAF will have some rest and reappear again at the beginning

of September. We wish you all a  wonderful holiday.<HR>



