<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>National Non-Uniform Day Editorial</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><a href="nnud_contents.html"><img align=right hspace=10 src="unicef_pix/nnud_leaf.gif"></a><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif" WIDTH="160" HEIGHT="53"><br><br><HR><BR><BR><h1 align=center>Editorial</h1>National Non-uniform Day is the annual school event for the UK Committeefor UNICEF.</B> Now in its eighth year, 1996 is a special year for UNICEFas we celebrate our 50th Anniversary. <BR><BR>Our special supplement - 50 Years of UNICEF - provides a full descriptionof UNICEF's history, and how the organisation works today. The decade bydecade summary of UNICEF's activities clearly shows the changes in attitudeand approach taken by the 'First World'  towards 'development' in the 'Third'.<BR><BR>Many people are confused or angered by the use of terms like: developingcountries, less developed countries, developed countries, third world, north/south.These are all shorthand terms to express the discrepancies of wealth andstandard of living which exist between the fully industrialised countriesof Europe, North America, Australia and New Zealand and countries in LatinAmerica, Africa and Asia. Yet within these groupings are also vast discrepancies,and quality of life cannot always be directly related to wealth.<BR><BR>What is 'development'? Is the UK a 'developed' country? Try substitutingthe word 'change' for development. If development is change then aren'twe undergoing a process of change just as much as Tanzanians? In any examplewe care to look at we can ask - Who is benefiting? Who is losing out? Weall need to be prepared to cope with change/development and this is whyUNICEF calls its education programme <I>Education for Development</I>.<BR><BR><B><I>Education for Development's themes and methodology are designed tohelp young people deal with change.</I></B> To work cooperatively to cometo decisions by consensus, defusing conflict and considering consequences.It isn't a subject in its own right, but can be integrated into all subjects.It is a preparation for life, for a life of change, where ever in the worldyou might be. To repeat the words of President Nyerere, &quot;Developmentbrings people freedom, provided it is development for people. People cannotbe developed, they can only develop themselves.&quot;  <BR> <BR>To learn more about <B><I>Education for Development,</I></B>  or if youwould like one of our trained volunteers - called Education Representatives- to visit your school to talk to staff or a class about issues relatedto development and UNICEF contact <B><I>Education Department, UNICEF, 55Lincoln's Inn Fields, London WC2A 3NB.</I><TABLE BORDER=3 width=100%><TR><TD>I am interested in receiving a visit from a UNICEF Education Representative.<BR><BR><tr><td>NAME</td>		<BR><BR><tr><td>SCHOOL</td>		<BR><BR>		<BR><BR><tr><td>Tel. No.	</td></B><BR><B></TD></TR></TABLE></B><BR><HR>&copy;Copyright: UNICEF 1996 <HR><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif"WIDTH="45" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom>Unicef Home Page</A><HR></BODY></HTML>
