<html>
<head>
<title>TVE - TVE NEW PROGRAMMES (Titles)</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#333366" vlink="#666699">
<font size=5 face=helvetica, arial>
<div align=right><a href="index.html" target="_parent">About TVE</a></div></font>
<h2>TVE New Programmes</h2>
<font size=3 face=helvetica,arial><b>LIVING WITH DISASTER</b></font><br>

<font size=3 face=helvetica,arial>Over the past 20 years, four million people have been killed in natural
disasters. Drought, floods, earthquakes, typhoons and hurricanes have in some way disrupted the lives of
close to half the population of the planet. A conservative estimate of the cos of repairing the damage to
affected communities runs at US$40 billion per annum - almost as much as the rich countries provide in
development assistance every year. <p>


However, relatively inexpensive investment could reap huge rewards in reducing human suffering and
reconstruction. Creating seed banks for when crops fail; building earthquakes resistant housing; and
teaching people how to quickly set up small-scale enteprises in the aftermath of disaster are among
hundreds of cost-efficient containment measures which can work in even the poorest countries.<p>


To mark the launch of the 1996 World Disasters Report, TVE, in association with Intermediate
Technology, has produced four, 10' news features and a 26' documentary focusing on the untold stories
of disaster. Filmed in Colombia, Peru, the Philippines, Bangadesh and Zimbabwe, our crew has revisited
sites that made world television news coverage in the 1990s. Dramatic rights-cleared archive footage of
disasters is mixed with accounts of how local communities have bounced back.<p>
 

<b>Ordering Information:</b><br>

<small>VHS VIEWING COPIES OF THE LATIN AMERICA, PHILIPPINES AND BANGLADESH FEATURES WILL BE
AVAILABLE AT THE END OF MARCH 1996; THE ZIMBABWE FEATURE AND THE 26' DOCUMENTARY WILL BE
AVAILABLE AT THE END OF APRIL 1996. TV STATIONS MAY EDIT THE FEATURES TO SUIT THIR OWN
BROADCAST STRANDS AND ACCESS TO CAMERA TAPES CAN BE PROVIDED TO STATIONS THAT WANT TO
MAKE THEIR OWN VERSIONS.</small>
</font>
<p>


<font size=3 face=helvetica,arial><b><a href="../er/index.html">EARTH REPORT</a></b></font><br>

<font size=3 face=helvetica,arial>Starting on the 31st March, BBC World television will be transmitting a
weekly environment and development series introduced by David Attenborough whose Life on Earth,
Trials of Life and Secret of Life of Plants series are among the most popular BBC progrmming of all time.
<p>


Jointly produced by TVE with WWF International, Earth Report consists of 52 x 5' news features for
broadcast to BBC viewers in Asia, the Gulf, Africa and Europe. Arabic and Japanese versions will be made by
the BBC. Spanish versions will be beamed from Mdrid by ATEI to Latin America starting in the summer.<p>


Topics to be aired include: a new method of farming that can help save the Mountain Gorilla; the
ecological catastrophe enveloping the Black Sea; how banditry can be linked to desertification; improving
health care in Guatemala and Guinea Bissau; and ecolabelling for Indonesian hardwoods.<p>
 

In addition to the BBC and ATEI broadcasts, TVE and WWF will send out the programmes in packages of 25
to their respective broadcast networks around the world.</font><p>


<font size=3 face=helvetica,arial><b>AFRICA EXPRESS</b></font><br>

<font size=3 face=helvetica,arial>Africa Express is a new eight part series presenting Africa from an African
perspective. African reporters cover the stories which illustrate the life and culture of their continent
south of the Sahara. A TVE/Channel 4 and SABC co-production, the Africa Epress stories leave aside the
Western news agenda for a refreshingly different view of events in Africa. <p>


Reviewing the first episode, the UK's daily newspaper, The Guardian reports: "Good for Channel 4 UK and
the producers for commissioning a magazine which shows the real Africa rather than the endless white
man's tales of famine and war. This, they thought,would explode the myth that it's full of squabbling
tribes who spread deadly sexual diseases and would swindle their own grandmother. So far so good."<p>
 

<b>For further details please contact, Robert Lamb, TVE's Director on:  <a
href="mailto:tve-dist@tve.org.uk">tve-dist@tve.org.uk</a></b></font><p>

