conference2.html">"Public Order" executions in preparation for women's conference an outrage.</a><br>Amnesty International expressed outrage that the Chinese government executed at least 10 people in Beijing in its continuing crackdown to ensure "public order" during the Fourth United Nations Conference on Women.<li><a href="../oxfam/oxfam_press_11aug.html">Oxfam's concerns for the UN IV World Conference on Women</a><br>At the pre-Beijing press conference on August 23rd Oxfam will focus particularly on what has been termed the 'increasingly female face of poverty'.</ul><p><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p><a name="action"></a><h2>Action plans</h2><ul><img width=160 height=122 border=1 align=right hspace=20 vspace=5 src="../tve/tve_pix/three_liz.gif"><li><a href="../amnesty/ai_womensconf.html">Show your solidarity with the world's women and the people of China</a><br>'Whether at home or in China, please wear the Black Ribbon for Human Rights during the Fourth UN World Conference on Women,' says Amnesty International.<li><a href="../conf/margaret_owen.html">Widows in Development Panel at NGO Beijing</a><br>Margaret Owen will be attending the NGO Forum in Beijing to discuss aspects of widowhood in developing countries.<li><a href="../baby_milk/milk_intweek.html">180 Days, 180 Ways: Women's Action Campaign 1995</a><br><li><a href="../vso/action.html">Beijing - and beyond</a><br>Action plans from VSO for getting involved - including the world weaving project.</ul><p><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p><a name="briefing"></a><h2>Briefing documents</h2><ul><li><a href="../cafod/wncontnt.htm">Fourth UN World Conference on Women</a><br>CAFOD's Briefing Paper<li><a href="../christian_aid/vital_statistics.html">Vital Statistics</a><br>Christian Aid's briefing document on The fourth UN conference on women and the NGO forum.<li><a href="../oxfam/beijing_brief.html">The Fourth World Conference on Women</a><br>Oxfams's briefing paper.<li><a href="../amnesty/ai_unconf.html">THE PROTECTION OF HUMAN RIGHTS FOR WOMEN:</a><br> A guide to Amnesty      International's position on the UN Conference on Women </ul><br clear=left><p><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p><a name="analysis"></a><h2>Analysis and feature stories</h2><ul><img width=160 height=122 border=1 align=right hspace=20 vspace=5 src="../tve/tve_pix/two_rant.gif"><li><a href="../oda/ssch_women.html#women">Women work for fairer world</a><br>The British aid programme is helping women in developing countries to increase theiropportunities and rights. These case studies from the Overseas Development School Section show what this means.<li><a href="../oda/sbod_peking.html">Peking launches world vision for women's equality</a><br>Freedom of choice and working in partnership were the two key themes of Minister for OverseasDevelopment Baroness Chalker's address to the World Conference on women. <li><a href="../oda/sbod_womday.html">Widows find a voice in Peking</a><br>The fourth United Nations Conference on Women in Peking brought a largely forgotten andinvisible group of women together for the first time says ODA.<li><a href="../oda/sbod_womday.html#united">United Voice: Women in Bangladesh celebrate International Woman's Day</a><li><a href="../unicef/first_sept/beijing.html">Beijing - a wasted effort?</a><br>Vanessa Redgrave, UNICEF's Special Representative for the Performing Arts, outlines UNICEF'shopes for the Fourth World Conference on Women.<li><a href="../ni/270keynote.html">Women - still something to shout about</a><br>Is feminism dead? What has happened to women over the      last ten years? Nikki van der Gaag looks at women's      poverty - and women's power for the New Internationalist.<li><a href="../ni/270edge.html">Women on the Edge of Time</a><br>The forces of the extreme right are everywhere on the march - andthe women of Algeria are fighting to contain them. Their challenge isalso ours, according to Mahl (who uses a pseudonym for her safety), who is interviewed in the New Internationalist. <li><a href="../ni/270facts.html">The facts on women</a><br>Statistically speaking, there have been many improvements to women's lives in thelast ten years. Female life expectancy is up, more girls are going to school, morewomen are working, new laws exist to protect women's rights... But the positivestatistics often have a corresponding negative - and the gap between women Northand South is widening, says the New Internationalist. <li><a href="../ni/270fist.html">Disarming the fist</a><br>Wife-beating was part of the marriage contract in Papua New Guinea not so long ago.      Christine Bradley helped outlaw it. She reports for the New Internationalist. <li><a href="../gemini/gemini_women1.html">World conference women press to be seen and heard</a><br>While some women are discovering that Beijing is the Forbidden City, the Chinese government is finding that indeed hell hath no fury like women scorned, reports Gemini News Service.<li><a href="../gemini/gemini_housework.html">Activists press to get housework on the Beijing agenda</a><br>Although women do most of the world's work, much of it is unpaid. The International Wages for Housework Campaign is planning to change that, reports Gemini News Service, and will be among the lobbyists at the forthcoming world women's conference.<li><a href="../index_oc/women.html">Women: The Body Politic</a><br>Index on Censorship's latest issue, which was timed toprecede the fourth UN conference on Women, looks beyond theeconomic agenda set for Beijing to the issues at the centre of women'scontinuing fight for social, cultural and political equality.<li><a href="../vso/editor.html">Women and development</a> <br>The gathering has been heralded as the prime opportunity for women to dictate their agenda into the next century.  ORBIT asks if the enthusiasm is justified.<li><a href="../vso/janewat.html">The road to Beijing</a><br>Jane Waterman follows the path to the UN conference for ORBIT.<li><a href="../patp/pap_beijing.html">The challenge for Beijing</a><br>Cherry Farrow argues in People & the Planet that environmental sustainability is as crucial to women's battle for social and economic justice as more commonly discussed issues, like health, education and development.<br><li><a href="../patp/pap_hands.html">Women holding hands</a><br>Women's groups are more effective and more visible than ever before. Collectivelytheir actions are changing the lives of people in households, communities and societiesthroughout the world, says People & the Planet.      <li><a href="../patp/pap_radio.html">A radio voice for women</a><br>Inspired by the Women's Peace Tent at the UN Women's Conference in Nairobi in 1985, Feminist International Radio Endeavour (FIRE) waslaunched in Costa Rica in 1991, reports People & the Planet.      <li><a href="../patp/pap_profile.html">These women call the shots</a><br>Modern methods of communication are helping to liberate and mobilize women, evenin the poorest communities - this is the story of a group ofilliterate film-makers in India, from People & the Planet.        <li><a href="../patp/pap_widows.html">Widows banding together</a><br>Margaret Owen, a lawyer specializing in                                   women's rights,  reports for People & the Planet on efforts                                   by widows in many countries to band together                                   for social change.</ul><p><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p><a name="programmes"></a><h2>Television programmes, videos and books</h2><ul><img width=160 height=122 border=1 align=right hspace=20 vspace=5 src="../tve/tve_pix/three_mat.gif"><li><a href="../amnesty/ai_newtitles.html#women">Human Rights are Women's Rights</a><br>Book published by Amnesty International.<li><a href="../christian_aid/caid_footage.html">Free footage highlights local women's weaving project</a><br>Christian Aid has produced a video news release (VNR) highlighting the attractive weavings produced by British women as part of a 20-kilometre banner for the UN Conference.<li><a href="../tve/tve_women.html">Women of the world</a><br>TVE is offering a wide-ranging package of films - the majority made by Southern women directors- for broadcast in September to coincide with, and to raise awareness of, the Beijing Conference.<li><a href="../tve/tve_women.html">A Woman's Place - Short Stories</a><br>Introduced by UNEP's Executive Director, Ms Elizabeth Dowdeswell, these features focus on some of theCritical Areas of Concern on the Platform for Action due to be agreed in Beijing. A <a href="TVEfaces.mov">video-clip</a> of the introductions to the films from TVE.<li><a href="yunus.html">Credit Where It's Due</a><br> A television programme made by Word-Pictures in conjunction with Worldview International Foundation. </ul><br clear=left><p><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p><a name="other"></a><h2>Other sites of interest</h2><ul><li>Linkages - <a href="http://www.iisd.ca/linkages/women.html">http://www.iisd.ca/linkages/women.html</a><li>United Nations - <a href="http://www.un.org/Conferences/Women/index.html">http://www.un.org/Conferences/Women/index.html</a><li>UNDP  - <a href="http://www.undp.org/fwcw/daw1.htm">http://www.undp.org/fwcw/daw1.htm</a><li>WomensNet - <a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/womensnet/beijing/">http://www.igc.apc.org/womensnet/beijing/</a><li>InterAction - <a href="http://www.vita.org/iaction/beijing.html">http://www.vita.org/iaction/beijing.html</a></ul></ul><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p><TABLE BORDER=1 CE