<html><head><title>Children First - Beijing - A Wasted Effort?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="../unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../unicef_info.html"> UNICEF </i></a><hr><h3>BEIJING - A WASTED EFFORT?</h3><h4>Vanessa Redgrave, UNICEF's Special Representative for the Performing Arts, outlines UNICEF's hopes for the Fourth World Conference on Women.</h4>      This summer my granddaughter, age three, was playing in a park with a boy of the same age when he ordered "Clean the house, do all the ironing, make sure everything is ready when I get back from work.  OK?"  She replied, "No, I'm going to work too!"<p>     It's probably a typical story.  It shows us that whilst progress has been made in gender equality, much more still needs to be done.    The media, however, seems on the whole reluctant to accept this, preferring instead to trumpet the end of feminism and herald the dawn of a new age of equality. <p>      More concerned with disagreements about the location of the forum for non-governmental organisations, it is questionnable whether the media really understands why the Fourth World Conference on Women is so vital.  Do women themselves understand?  I was unaware until recently of some of the statistics which catalogue the shocking situation of women and girls - that 70% of the children in the world not attending school are girls, that 500,000 women still die each year from pregnancy and childbirth, or that because of sex-selective abortions or infanticide an estimated 100 million fewer women are alive today than could be expected.  As we look around we see the conditions of women at work growing worse in all countries.  Increasing unemployment means more and more young girls on the street.  Domestic violence continues to blight women's lives in rich as well as poor countries.  Look around.  It is not hard to justify the need for this Conference. <p>     We have to stress that these are not just issues for women.  Women's struggle for rights and justice (for this is what equality means) are issues of concern to all.  When world leaders meet in Beijing to set an agenda for the advancement of women into the next century, they will be discussing issues ranging from poverty to armed conflict, from the environment to media distortions and stereotypes.  If half the world's population continues to be denied the chance to participate fully in all areas of public and private life, it is not only individual lives that are affected, but the future of entire nations. <p>     Beginning from birth, girls in many parts of the world experience the "apartheid of gender".  Their fundamental rights - to nutrition, health care, education, to work at a trade or profession, to vote, even to survive are restricted or denied.  The apartheid of gender has many faces and many manifestations.  In South Asia, for example, neglect of girls means they have markedly lower survival rates.  In some countries, girls spend as much as 80 per cent more time than boys doing domestic tasks.   Girls and women continue to contribute a great deal to economic development, but their contributions go undervalued or unrecognised.<p>     Nor is the apartheid of gender  exclusive to poor countries.  The  situation for women in industrialised countries remains troubling.  In European countries long-term unemployment rates tend to be higher for women.  Women's jobs are increasingly segregated at the lower end of the labour market and most low-paid workers in the European Union are women.  The Women's National Commission in the UK has stated that "female poverty is a fundamental cause of inequality in the UK".  In many countries women remain under-represented in decision-making bodies such as parliaments and ministries.<p>     When Carol Bellamy speaks on behalf of UNICEF at the Beijing Conference she will be speaking for an organisation which places progress towards equality and equity at the core of its guiding principles and goals.  She will be stressing the need to look at the whole life cycle of girls and women.  Because the apartheid of gender begins for girls at birth, and in some parts of the world even before birth, UNICEF uses this "life-cycle perspective" to identify persistent forms of discrimination at each stage, and formulate appropriate programmes and projects to tackle them. <p>     UNICEF bases its work on gender equality on international law, as well as the Plan of Action agreed at the World Summit for Children in 1990.  At the World Summit for Children, national leaders  agreed that "girls must be given equal treatment and opportunities from the very beginning".  They also agreed to "work to strengthen the role and status of women."  10 of the Summit's 27 goals for the year 2000 relate specifically to the needs of girls and women. <p>      The Convention on the Rights of the Child, now ratified by 176 of the world's 191 countries, is another important tool.  It demands that its comprehensive standards for protecting children and ensuring their survival and development apply to all children without discrimination on any basis,  including gender.  UNICEF also supports the universal ratification of the 1993 UN Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women.  Children's and women's rights are inextricably linked.  Ensuring that all children's basic rights are safeguarded and needs are met builds a strong foundation for women's rights.  Similarly, eliminating discrimination against women will accelerate global progress in child survival and development.<p>     The foundation for any change in the situation of women has to be education.  It is the key to new opportunities in employment and political participation.  Educated women marry later, and have fewer and healthier children.  Addressing gender inequality in education is particularly important because it undermines the struggle for equality in almost all other fields.<p>       On every level and in every sphere of life women need equal access and full participation in decision making if gender equality is to be a reality.  Worldwide, women hold just 10 per cent of all parliamentary seats      (and only 9 per cent in the UK).  At the United Nations, including UNICEF, women are still far from having an equal role in leadership and decision making.  In the world of work and business, the gender gap widens dramatically as one progresses up the ladder of responsibility and power.  Violence against women and girls needs to be tackled with far greater effort.  Gender oppression, racism, poverty and political repression are all forms and faces of violence, and all affect women and girls disproportionately.  Domestic violence has been recognised as a severe global problem, from the least to the most developed countries.  The proliferation of armed conflicts is taking a brutal toll on civilians around the world, with women and children the main victims of atrocities.  We have all read the terrible reports of the use of rape as an instrument of war, from former Yugoslavia to Rwanda.  Sexual exploitation of girls and women, including sex tourism and child pornography, is a massive global violation of law and human rights.  Female genital mutilation affects some 2 million girls each year.  All these forms of gender-focused violence must be ended, as called for by the Convention on the Elimination of Violence against Women.<p>     What will the World Conference on Women be able to do about this?  Will it be just another talking shop where world leaders can make empty promises they forget as soon as they step on the plane home?  It doesn't have to be.  Since the World Summit for Children in 1990 UNICEF and its partners around the world have been monitoring progress towards the goals agreed for the year 2000.  Significant progress has been made, and UNICEF has seen the value of setting goals which can be used to mobilise action on every level.  Without time-bound goals that are concrete and can be monitored, international commitments will not be implemented.  Without these mechanisms the most inspiring  words will remain just that - words.  The Platform of Action agreed on at Beijing must be followed up in each country by concrete action plans for gender equality and equity.<p>     The voices of women are being heard on all the issues to be discussed at Beijing.  What is more important, they are starting to have an impact.  How much more equal the struggle for human progress would be if women didn't also have to fight against gender oppression.  Let us grasp this opportunity to end it, once and for all.<p><hr>©Copyright: UNICEF 1995<hr><a href="../index.html" target="_parent"><img src="../unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>  
