 10.15am</h3><ul><b>Ian Cook</b> meets riders from the National Association of Bikers with Disabilities.</ul><p><li><h3>The Crunch - BBC2, 11.25am<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"><img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>Six documentaries from around the world about children caught up in controversy. Today, Norwegian youngsters defend commercial whaling.</ul><p><li><h3>New Jerusalem - BBC2, 8pm</h3><ul>The second of a four part series which traces the history of the British Welfare State.  <p><b>A Place in the Class</b><br>Today's programme asks what happened to the classless society which was to have come about through free universal schooling. From grammars to independents, it traces the unresolved arguments about how to educate our children.</ul>                                                            <p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 3rd JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Race and Society: Artists and Photographers - BBC2, 7.10am</h3><ul>Does the fact that someone is black place demands on them to "represent" their fellow black human beings?</ul><p><li><h3>Panorama - BBC1, 9.30pm</h3><ul><b>Wish I Weren't Here</b><br>Panorama investigates rough justice in Europe. British citizens who are arrested for alleged crimes in EU countries such as Germany, Spain and Portugal are almost never given bail, are often not told what is happening to them and often feel isolated from any assistance the British Consulate is able to offer them. <b>Tom Mangold</b> looks at the cases of four Britons for whom the theory of Europe without frontiers ended in the reality of life behind bars. When everything else in Europe is being standardised, why not the legal and judicial systems?</ul><p><li><h3>Secret Asia - Ch 4, 11pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Continuing the series of controversial documentaries and feature films made in the Far East.<p><b>Inside the Miracle</b><br><img align=left vspace=8 hspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/whats_june30_asia.gif"><p><i>Now on the run from the government, activist <b>Kwon Young Gil</b> describes his struggles for basic trade union rights for Korean workers.<p>© Channel 4</i><br clear=left><p>South Korea has one of  Asia's fastest-growing economies, but it continues to suppress political activity and trade union rights. This documentary examines the human consequences of the country's labour and political laws. It follows film director <b>Park Kwang-Su</b> as he interviews people for a new film about a man who, in 1970, set fire to himself in protest at Korea's stance on union rights.</ul><p><p> <br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 4th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Black Girls in Search of Learning - BBC2, 7.10am<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Asian girls in Leicester talk about their experience of school. Was enough asked of them?</ul><p><li><h3>Barnado's Children - BBC1, 9.30pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>First of a three-part series marking the 150th birthday of Thomas Barnado, founder of the children's homes.<p><b>The Largest Family in the World</b><br>More than 300,000 children have been cared for by Barnado's since it began in 1866. Tonight, a look at the history of the organisation through the eyes of those who lived there, plus film footage from the Barnado's archive.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 5th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>First Sex - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul>The series that goes behind the headlines to take a look at issues significant to women.  Tonight, why is menstruation such a big taboo? Plus a report on the lack of support given to female partners of prisoners; a look at female pilots past and present; and a short film showing what a haughty Elizabethan royal might think of tampons.</ul><li><h3>Over the Edge - BBC2, 11.35pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>The second of six thought-provoking documentaries exploring issues central to the lives of disabled people.<p><b>Different Worlds, Shared Voices</b><br>If society disables people as much as the disabilities themselves, do different societies disable people in different ways? This was the fascinating question behind a video letter exchange set up between two groups of disabled people, with individuals in Norwich posing questions for their counterparts in Suva, capital of Fiji in the South Pacific. The replies from the people of Suva are revealing about cultural attitudes to disbaility in Fiji and the problems currently facing disabled people there, but their stories also create a powerful impression of optimism and self-reliance. As the correspondence between Suva and Norwich develops, <i>Over the Edge</i> shows that, despite their very different cultures, the two groups have a great deal in common.</ul><p></ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 6th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Rediscovery of the World - BBC2, 12noon</h3><ul><b>Borneo: Forest without Trees</b><br>Dynamite fishing and modern technology have changed the life of the nomadic Baju tribe, while on the land the vast, humid tropical forest is disappearing and with it the great orang-utans and elephants who live there.</ul><p><li><h3>True Stories - Ch 4, 9.30pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Deadly Experiments</b><br><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/whats_june30_exper.gif"><p><br><i><b>Pritam Kaur</b> was involved without her informed consent in official experiments monitoring the absorption of radiation in Asian diet.<p>©: Channel 4</i><br clear=left><p>It sounds like the plot of a particularly scary episode of <i>The X Files</i>: a woman is making regular visits to hospital for migraine treatments, only to discover that the "hospital" is an atomic research station and the "treatments" are doses of radiation. She's just one of the human guinea pigs featured in this alarming report that claims the Government has sanctioned gruesome experiments on patients both living and dead to see how they stand up to nuclear radiation. <i>Deadly Experiments</i> is made by the same team who produced the 1991 <i>Cutting Edge</i> report on abuses in Ashworth Psychiatric Hospital, which led to a public inquiry and full-scale reforms. A warning: the experiments revealed in this film are very distressing.</ul><p><li><h3>Inside Story - BBC1, 10pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Terrifying Love</b><br>An investigation of a court system set up to deal with domestic violence. Each year in the US, over six million women are beaten by their abusive partners and around 1,000 are killed. To deal with this hidden crime, a unique and groundbreaking court was established in Miami, Florida. <i>Inside Story</i> travels to the Domestic Violence Court, where the judges are determined to break this horrific cycle of violence. The court deals with wife beaters by sending them for treatment to reform their abusive behaviour. Since the court was set up, the number of victims prepared to prosecute has more than doubled, and many women tell the judges that they have literally saved their lives.</ul><p><li><h3>Walk on the Wild Side - Ch.4, 11.30pm</h3><ul>The second programme in a repeat showing of the hard-hitting seven-part documentary series about young people.<p><b>Scar Boys</b><br>Mick was attacked with a cut-throat razor. Kevin was slashed by someone who jumped through his front window. Steven had his face cut by a Stanley knife. Nick's attacker used a glass-cutter. All four victims bravely talk about their feelings and how their lives and attitudes were changed by the attacks.</ul><p><li><h3>First Sex - Ch.4, 12.05 am</h3><ul><i>Repeated from Wednesday 5th, 9pm.</i></ul><br><p><a name="fri1"></a><h3>FRIDAY 7th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Jungle Pharmacy - Ch 4, 11.20am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Medicine men in Brazil and Peru explain how their traditional remedies are now being used by the West in new, life-saving drugs. How will they benefit from imparting their knowledge to Western scientists?</ul><p><br><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 8th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Rural India: A Vulnerable Life - BBC2, 9.20am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>In India how vulnerable you are depends on a combination of luck and the decisions you make - but all families are at risk in some way.</ul><p><li><h3>Science Matters: Acid Rain - BBC2, 9.20am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>After 20 years of debate, Britain has signed an agreement to help reduce acid rain.</ul><p><li><h3>Sign On - Ch 4, 12noon</h3><ul>Another chance to see the award-winning programme examining the problem of child abuse among deaf children. Research shows that proportionally more deaf children are likely to suffer abuse, but there is far less support available to them. With signing and open subtitles.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 9th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul><b>Ian Cook</b> reports on a legal landmark for the disabled.</ul><p><li><h3>The Crunch - BBC2, 11.25am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Six documentaries from around the world about children caught up in controversy. Today, Swedish children express fears about radioactive leaks.	</ul><p><li><h3>New Jerusalem - BBC2, 8pm</h3><ul>The third of a four part series which traces the history of the British Welfare State.  <p><b>Safe in Their Hands</b><br>In 1945 the jewel in the Welfare State's crown was the National Health Service. The government pledged to ensure that no one would lie sick or die merely because of poverty. As the medical community began to embrace the idea more and more, the NHS became the envy of the world. But, instead of demand tailing off as the general health of the nation improved, it steadily increased over the succeeding half century with each pharmaceutical breakthrough, and the utopian vision was blighted by escalating costs, rising expectations and the needs of an ageing population. Funding the service became a political issue and the patients were those most immediately affected. The realisation was starting to dawn that the NHS could not carry the weight of the nation's ills alone.</ul>   <p><li><h3>Coral Grief - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>The world's coral reefs are the oldest, richest natural community on earth and a valuable source of information about the history of the world. Now, though, the reefs are under threat, victims of human expansion and tourism. This programme journeys from the Italian Dolomites to Australia's Great Barrier Reef to examine the chance of this resource surviving.</ul><p><li><h3>Heart of the Matter - BBC1, 10.35pm</h3><ul><b>Testing Times</b><br><b>Andrew Blake</b> loves animals but, as a sufferer of a rare nervous disorder, he is also leading a campaign to protect the right of medical researchers to use animals for experimentation. <b>Joan Bakewell</b> explores changing attitudes to animal rights. Do the recent protests over veal calves mark society's acceptance that animals have rights, or is public opinion being altered by a tiny minority of animal activists?</ul>                                                         <p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 10th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Travels with My Camera - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>The series returns for a second season, featuring five highly idiosyncratic journeys filmed on Hi-8 and made by personalities with a purpose.<p><b>Adventures in Bomb Country</b><br><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/whats_july_camera.gif">New York journalist <b>Reggie Nadelson</b> investigates the United States' nuclear obsession as she makes the journey along Interstate Highway 25, which runs from Las Cruces in south New Mexico to Chugwater, Wyoming - "the wild west of the bomb".<br><i>©: Channel 4</i><br clear=left></ul><p><li><h3>Secret Asia - Ch 4, 11pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Continuing the series of controversial documentaries and feature films made in the Far East.<p><b>Sex Warriors and the Samurai</b><br><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/whats_july_samurai.gif"><p><b>Jo-An</b> works in a sex bar in Manila. Once a year he makes a working visit to Japan to earn money to support his large and destitute family. His story illustrates the changing balance of economic power, both in the Philippines and throughout the Far East.<p><i>©: Channel 4</i><br clear=left></ul><p><p> <br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 11th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>See Hear! - BBC2, 12noon</h3><ul>Featuring a report from Las Vegas. With signing and subtitles.</ul><p><li><h3>Witness - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Beyond the Rainbow</b><br><img align=left hspace=6 vspace=2 src="tvandradio_pix/whats_july_rainbow.gif"><i>©: Greenpeace</i><p>Ten years ago the Greepeace ship <i>Rainbow Warrior</i> was destroyed in Auckland harbour in New Zealand, claiming the life of photographer <b>Fernando Pereira</b>. His daughter <b>Marelle,</b> just eight years old at the time, has now embarked on a quest to find out more about the father she barely knew, and the cause for which he fought and died. She looks at the political aspects of the ship's sinking and talks to Greenpeace founder <b>David McTaggart</b> and <b>David Langew,</b> the New Zealand Prime Minister at the time, as well as to the people who shared the last moments of her father's life. Finally, she sets out to seek an apology from those she holds responsible for her father's death.<br clear=left></ul><p><li><h3>Disappearing World - Discovery Channel, 10pm</h3><ul>How life has changed for the Kayapo since gold was found on their land in 1982.</ul><p><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 12th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Special Friends - BBC2, 9.05am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul><b>Ciara MacNeill</b> and <b>Aileen Corrigan</b> are the best of friends. Both suffer from Down's Syndrome, but their friendship during 19 years has enabled these two young women to nurture in each other a level of independence not usually associated with mental disability. While the mothers of both worry about the long-term problems that their daughters may face, Ciara and Aileen's strong and realistic approach has allowed them to take risks and experience life to the full.</ul><p><li><h3>Richard Leakey: Africa's Wildlife Warrior - BBC2, 9.30pm</h3><ul>The man who saved his country's elephants now turns his attention to saving the country. As a prelude to the <i>African Summer</i> season (which begins next week), one of Africa's most famous wildlife conservationists is profiled in this documentary narrated by <b>Julian Pettifer</b>. From paleontologist to conservationist to politician, Leakey tells the story of his remarkable career. In 1989 he was appointed head of Kenya's Widlife Service and successfully saved Kenya's elephants from extinction. Using the determination that helped him win that battle and overcome the loss of both his legs in a mysterious plane crash, Leakey set up a political party earlier this year to wipe out the widespread corruption within the Kenyan government.</ul><p><li><h3>First Sex - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>The series examining women's issues. Tonight's programme uncovers the secrecy surrounding the "comfort women" - approximately 160,000 Korean women who were used as sex slaves by the Japanese during the Second World War. </ul></ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 13th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>How the West was Lost - BBC2, 9.05am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul><b>A Good Day to Die</b><br>Series focusing on the native Americans' fight to protect their territory and preserve their way of life. This programme looks at the Lakotas' struggle against the gold seekers pushing through their land. Despite their great victory over Custer in the Battle of Little Bighorn, they faced eventual defeat.</ul><p><br><a name="fri"></a><h3>FRIDAY 14th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Price of Salmon - Ch 4, 11.30am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Fish farming has brought prosperity to the Highlands and Islands of Scotland, and a plentiful supply of cheap salmon to the supermarkets. But the environmental cost of this bonanza is still being counted.</ul><p><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 15th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Management of Nuclear Waste - BBC2, 11.50am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>A look at the research needed in order to contain nuclear waste safely.</ul><p><li><h3>Live Aid 10th Anniversary - BBC2, 6pm-1.35am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Ten years ago this week, BBC Television presented the most memorable rock concert ever. Live Aid was the world's biggest single fundraising event and is still the biggest non-sporting event ever televised, seen by over one and a half billion people in 170 countries. Live Aid saw The Who reform for the day, Paul McCartney sing solo, U2 perform at Wembley and Mick Jagger & Tina Turner in Philadelphia, with Phil Collins playing on both sides of the Atlantic. Tonight - for the first time since 1985 - you can relive the highlights of this spectacular concert. Also, <b>Bob Geldof</b> returns to Ethiopia and presents short reports throughout the evening which give a refreshingly new perspective on a country which has seen so much tragedy in the last 10 years.<p><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=4 src="../owo_logos/regfeat_more.gif"><a href="live_aid.html">"Live Aid became the focus of everyone's frustration and anger and shame." - Bob Geldof.</a></ul><p><li><h3>Jean Michel Jarre's Concert for Tolerance - Ch 4, 12.15am</h3><ul>Last night in Paris, on Bastille Day, <b>Jean Michel Jarre </b>performed in concert. Combining spectacular laser light shows and grandiose synthesized music, the concert is being relayed in its entirety. Jarre is a UNESCO Ambassador for Tolerance and Youth and the performance celebrates the UN Year for Tolerance.</ul><p><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 16th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Developing World: the Cutting Edge of Progress - BBC2, 7.30am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Documentary series about developing countries. This programme explores the impact in Zimbabwe on the Tong of the construction of the Kariba dam and its aftermath.</ul><p><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul>Author <b>Aileen Armitage</b> talks about how she started writing when her sight began to fail.</ul><p><li><h3>The Crunch - BBC2, 11.25am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Six documentaries from around the world about children caught up in controversy. Today, the friendship that flourishes between two children when  a child from Chernobyl in the Ukraine spends six months in rural Ireland.</ul><p><li><h3>New Jerusalem - BBC2, 8pm</h3><ul>The last of the four part series tracing the history of the British Welfare State.  <p><b>For Richer, for Poorer</b><br>The great promise of the welfare state was that it would offer cradle-to-grave security, banishing the bleak memories of the hunger of the 1930s. But, through the instructive example of Sheffield and its changing fortunes, the programme shows how different the reality was. Both inflation and unemployment rocketed as the effects of the oil embargo of the 1970s began to be felt. Political theorists dictated that spiralling prices must be checked, even if it meant paying the cost in jobs. The consequences were disastrous for Sheffield. Once the heartland of the steel industry, it was caught in the poverty trap of the early 1980s, with 40,000 workers put on the dole. </ul>   <p><li><h3>The New Map of Africa - BBC2, 8.50pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>In the Zimbabwean capital Harare, presidents, politicians and activists from across the continent discuss how they would react to imaginary crises. The debate is accompanied by films made by participants, including footage of the <a href="../chrwanda/chrwandsp_top.html">conflict in Rwanda.</a></ul><p><li><h3>TV Afrika - BBC2, 10pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>A channel surf through African television. Namibian programme maker <b>Hilda Basson</b> presents extracts from stations broadcasting in over 25 countries of the continent, including a colourful range of local drama, documentaries, music, entertainment and current affairs.</ul><p>                                       <p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 17th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Travels with My Camera - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>The series returns for a second season, featuring five highly idiosyncratic journeys filmed on Hi-8 and made by personalities with a purpose.<p><b>Feeling Hungary</b><br>Family therapist, literary agent, gourmet, actor and journalist, <b>Richard Gollner</b> returns to his native Hungary. He retraces the escape route he took during the uprising of 1976, in which his mother was killed, hoping to find her grave and to discover whether he fits with ease into the newly democratic Hungary.</ul><p><li><h3>Secret Asia - Ch 4, 11pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Life on the Line</b><br>Burma's human rights record is one of the worst in the world - but that has not stopped two western oil companies investing in a major pipeline there. <i>Life on the Line </i> follows the parallel stories of two opponents of the Burmese regime. <b>True Love,</b> a human rights activist, uncovers evidence of murder, slave labour, concentration camps and the razing of whole villages, caused by the regime's forces clearing a jungle area for the pipeline. <b>Ma Thida,</b> a Burmese journalist living in exile, looks into the refusal of the oil companies to justify their investment.</ul><p><li><h3>To the Starry Island - Ch 4, 11.45pm</h3><ul>The <i>Secret Asia</i> series of films continues with this fact-based drama set against a background of Korea's turbulent history. <b>Chae-Woo</b> finds a Korean community unable to forget the past when he tries to have his father buried on his island. In Korean with English subtitles.</ul><p> <br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 18th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>See Hear! - BBC2, 12noon</h3><ul>Featuring a report from Las Vegas. With signing and subtitles.</ul><p><li><h3>Big Science - BBC2, 7.30pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>First of a six-part magazine series investigating the relationship between science and modern society. Tonight's report include a look at whether drug treatment can prevent violent behaviour, and a debate on the priorities of the Green movement with <b>Dr Wilfred Beckerman.</b> Presented by <b>David Malone.</b></ul><p><li><h3>Witness - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul><b>For the Love of a Leader</b><br>Continuing the series of documentaries about personal belief. <b>Colonel Muammar Al Gadaffi</b> says that his life is in the hands of a small group of women: his elite bodyguards, <b>the Jamahiryan Guard.</b> Regarded by their leader as a model for all Libyan women, its members are selected from the ranks of the Tris Girl's Military Academy, founded by Gadafii in 1979. Cadets for this, the only female officer school in the world, are chosen from all over the country, and must have a "certificate of morality" from their neighbourhood popular commitee, vouching for their purity and political correctness. Through unprecedented access to the Colonel and the Tris Girl's Military Academy, <i>Witness</i> examines the cult surrounding the Libyan leader and looks at how women's rights in Libya, though in theory greater than in many western countries, are in reality defined by his ambiguous attitudes.</ul><p><li><h3>Barnado's Children - BBC1, 9.30pm</h3><ul>Last of the series about the Barnado's children's homes.<p><b>In the Doctor's Footsteps</b><br>Tonight's programme focuses on the way Barnardo's has developed beyond its original scope. Although Dr Barnado might find some of the charity's more recent initiatives to help youngsters surprising, he would acknowledge that young people are still very much at risk - even in the nineties.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 19th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Radical Option: Reparations to Africa - BBC2, 7.30pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>The slave trade was one of the worst atrocities in world history. Its legacy is racism and the devastated economies of Africa. <b>Trevor Philips</b> chairs a discussion which considers the extent of Europe's moral debt to Africa and the financial settlement which would be an appropriate recompense for centuries of colonialism and exploitation.</ul><p><li><h3>Over the Edge - BBC2, 11.15pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Shocks</b><br>In 1995, 20,000 people in Engl