ire, madness and obsession with sometimes startling images from the heart of contemporary Africa.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 23rd JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>See Hear! - BBC1, 10am</h3><ul>The third in a series of programmes for deaf people from Danish television features <b>Eva Abildgaard</b> with a personal view of Berlin, Germany.</ul><p><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul><b>Ian Cook</b> meets blind Derbyshire vicar <b>Reverend Helen Patten.</b></ul><p><li><h3>The Crunch - BBC2, 11.25am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Six documentaries from around the world about children caught up in controversy. <p><b>Saving Jesus</b><br>This programme portrays the efforts of <b>Eddie Cabral</b> to keep his younger brother, <b>Jesus,</b> out of trouble. Eleven-year-old Jesus often skips school, admits to shoplifting and hangs out in gangs.</ul><p><p><li><h3>General Idi Amin Dada - BBC2, 8.10pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Made with the dictator's full co-operation, <b>Barbet Schroeder's</b> masterly documentary of Idi Amin shows him at the height of his dictatorial poweres. Amin stages a swimming race with his cronies, and cheats. He makes his troops practice an invasion of Israel, and he lets the camera into a cabinet meeting after which one of his ministers is murdered.</ul><p>                                       <p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 24th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Travels with My Camera - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul>The series returns for a second season, featuring five highly idiosyncratic journeys filmed on Hi-8 and made by personalities with a purpose.<p><b>The Last Safari</b><br><b>Denis Hills,</b> teacher, philosopher, adventurer and writer was sentenced to death in Uganda in 1975 for writing a book in which he called Idi Amin a "village tyrant". He was only reprieved at the last minute by the perso