ing dissent in Muslim communities. They condemn Jews, Hindus and gays and have no time for democracy. Their goal is a worldwide Islamic state.</ul><p> <li><h3>Witness - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul><b>Better Dead than Gay</b><br><b>Simon Harvey</b> was Christian and gay. Unable to come to terms with his sexuality, he gassed himself to death in a car while a hymn played on the car stereo. The letters and diary he left behind reveal the great anguish he experienced in attempting to reconcile his homosexulaity both with his Christianity and the society in which he lived. <b>Christian O'Hare's</b> film pieces together the last six months of Simon Harvey's life, and examines how religious belief can be used to justify social prejudice.</ul><p><li><h3>The Decade of Destruction - Ch 4, 1.45am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Search for the Kidnappers</b><br>The destruction of the Amazonian rainforest is one of the greatest current threats to the world's environment. This five-part series of documentaries examines the bloody feuds for land and gold that have arisen as individuals have sought to make the rainforest their own. The first programme follows the case of <b>Chico Prestes,</b> a Brazilian farmer whose son was kidnapped by Indians angry at the presence of so many outsiders on their land. It is the tragic story of how Chico set about finding his son and the rage that fuelled the Indians' actions.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 26th JULY<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Bookmark - BBC2, 7.30pm</h3><ul><b>The Poet, the President and the Travelling Players</b><br>A film following the English Shakespeare Company's 'Macbeth' tour in Malawi in 1992. Staged in small villages around the beautiful but impoverished country of Malawi, the production affords an insight into the fate of the troubled state.</ul><p> <li><h3>Lucinda Lambton's Alphabet of Britain - BBC2, 8.20pm</h3><ul><b>P is for Prisoner