ople behind the counters and the quality of advice he is given.</ul><p><li><h3>Deaf-Blind Education in Russia - BBC2, 7.30pm</h3><ul><b>Andrew Sachs</b> narrates the story of the pioneering work of a school for deaf-blind children near Moscow. Developed by psychologists in the former Soviet Union who shared a firm belief in the power of education to realise human potential, their teaching methods include model-making with Plasticine, which helps in understanding the mental images of these children.</ul><p><li><h3>The Great Rift Valley - BBC2, 8pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3> <ul><b>Footprints in the Valley</b><br>First of a three-part journey to the birthplace of humanity and a natural wonder of the world - the Great Rift valley of Africa. As well as hosting some spectacular landscapes, the valley also offers habitats to a wealth of wildlife species. Narrated by <b>Andrew Sachs.</b></ul><p><a name="lucky"></a><li><h3>Lucky People - BBC2, 8.50pm  <img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul>In this short opinion piece, <b>Christopher Andrew,</b> Professor of Modern History at Cambridge University and a leading writer on military intelligence, argues that we are all lucky people - lucky to have escaped the horror of nuclear armageddon in the 50 years since the Hiroshima bomb. In a chilling assessment based on years of study in the Soviet and US archives, and interviews with high-ranking diplomats and politicians, Andrew maintains that our luck will run out sooner rather than later, despite the end of the Cold War.</ul><p><li><h3>Travels with My Camera - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul>The series returns for a second season, featuring five highly idiosyncratic journeys filmed on Hi-8 and made by personalities with a purpose.<p><b>Greetings from Out Here</b><br>On a year long excursion to America's southern states, video-maker <b>Ellen Spiro</b> documents gay culture in what is widely perceived as one of the country's most conservative regimes. Her witty film features compelling characters whom she meets in surreal circumstances such as the Texas Gay Rodeo, and local personalities including gospel singer <b>James Cox</b> and author <b>Allan Garganus.</b></ul><p><li><h3>African Political Broadcast - BBC2, 10.25pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>Tonight, <b>Ian Smith,</b> who as Prime Minister of Rhodesia from 1964-79 led the rebel white government that declared its independence from Britain in 1970, speaks out on what place he thinks there is, if any, for whites in Africa now.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 1st AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Czech Education: After the Revolution - BBC2, 7.10am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Determining the priorities now for educationalists in the Czech Republic.</ul><p><li><h3>See Hear! - BBC2, 12noon</h3><ul>Magazine programme for the deaf community.</ul><p><li><h3>Big Science - BBC2, 7.30pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Research implies that 10,000 people could be dying from the traffic pollution in Britain each year. Presenter <b>David Malone</b> discovers that Britain has just seven EU-approved pollution measuring sites, compared with Germany's 200, and that there are no national standards for ozone or nitrogen dioxide levels. Will Britain have to follow the example of smog-filled Athens, where residents wear face masks in the summer? He also investigates the environmental row between Greeenpeace and the chemical industry over chlorine, the basis of some of the most common chemicals in the world. Some feel it may be the cause of decreasing fertility in men, as sperm counts have halved since the Second World War.</ul><li><h3>Public Eye - BBC2, 8pm</h3><ul><b>Sex in the Dark</b><br>How would you feel if someone had sex with you knowing that they might give you AIDS? In the US, a man was convicted of attempted murder in 1993 for doing just that. There are those within the British AIDS orgainsations who refuse to condemn people for risking infection, on the grounds that people who are HIV positive already suffer harassment and discrimination - to be told it is wrong to have sex which risks passing on a life-threatening virus would be simply offensive. Other activists disagree, and feel that people who are HIV positive or have AIDS should show more responsibility in their sexual behaviour. New research suggests that a substantial number of people are failing to do so. <b>Mark Easton </b>reports on the controversy and examines the argument that Britain should make such behaviour illegal, and talks to those whose lives have been affected.</ul><p> <li><h3>Witness - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Fifty Years of Silence</b><br><b>Jan Ruff-O'Herne</b> is a Dutch woman with a terrible secret that she has not shared with anyone for 50 years. During the Second World War, Jan and her family were interned in a Japanese prison camp where for two years they endured hard labour and brutal treatment. Then in 1944, she was removed from the camp to work in the Japanese officers' brothel. For three months she was repeatedly raped night and day. Only by travelling to Holland to meet the other nine women who suffered the same torment can she hope to find inner peace. This intimate film, directed by Jan's son-in-law, pays tribute to a woman of great courage, strength and humanity, and follows her efforts to lay her ghosts to rest.</ul><p><li><h3>The Decade of Destruction - Ch 4, 1.45am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>In the Ashes of the Forest</b><br>Award-winning director <b>Adrian Cowell's</b> series records the human tragedies that have resulted from the exploitation of the Amazonian rainforest. Tonight's film follows <b>Renato</b> and his family into the forest where, like hundreds of thousands of colonists encouraged to settle by the Brazilian government and financed by the World Bank, they hoped to farm. In 1990, 60 per cent of the land cleared for farming had been returned to scrub and most farmers like Renato had been moved on.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 2nd AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><a name="hiroshima"></a><li><h3>Return to Hiroshima - BBC2, 7pm <img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul>One day in 1990, a party of five elderly Americans were being shown round a hospital in Hiroshima, destroyed in 1945 but now rebuilt. <i>"Do you know what happened to the men who dropped the bomb?" </i> asked one of them. <i>"I think they are all dead," </i> replied the Japanese doctor who was leading the tour. <i>"No they are not," </i>came the reply.<i>"They are standing in front of you." </i><p>This programme, first shown five years ago, records the return journey of the US airmen who led the A-bomb raids that ended the Second World War. They were not there to apologise. <i>"No, there was no question of that," </i> said Major Charles Sweeney. <i>"The Japanese had done terrible, terrible things. By ending the war this way, we were saving millions of lives - Japanese as well as American."</i></ul><p> <li><h3>Over the Rainbow - C4, 9pm</h3><ul>First in a powerful four-part series which examines what it means to be gay or lesbian in modern-day America. Tonight's episode outlines the evolution of the gay movement in the 1960s.</ul><p><li><h3>HMS Brilliant - BBC1, 9.30pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Watchman Nine Zero</b><br>A fly-on-the-wall documentary series following the exploits of HMS Brilliant and its crew as they try and enforce the UN arms embargo in the dangerous waters off <a href="news/bosnia.html">Bosnia.</a> Tonight's programme follows as the crew are given the job of boarding and searching ships off the coast of former Yugoslavia, to seek out gun-runners.</ul><img align=middle hspace=8 vspace=4 src="../owo_logos/regfeat_more.gif"><a href="../news/bosnia.html"><i>One World Online's </i> Special Report on Bosnia.</a></ul><p><a name="game"></a><li><h3>Africa's Big Game - BBC2, 9.30pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>A series examining why some of Africa's animals are facing the threat of extinction, with rare archive photographs, early film footage and memories of the hunters, settlers and the Africans themselves.<p><b>Gardeners in Eden</b><br>The big white hunters are returning. If you're rich enough, you can now shoot elephant and buffalo - even leopard and rhino - on safari. But unlike the ruthless butchers of colonial times, today's hunters are calling themselves conservationists and kill big game with the blessing of the wildlife rangers. Can people really save animals by killing them? The final programme in the series examines the dilemma of game management across Africa and features dramatic footage of a present-day big game hunt.</ul><p><li><h3>Over the Edge - BBC2, 11.15pm</h3><ul>A documentary series focusing on society's attitudes towards disability.<p><b>Freak Out!</b><br>Disabled people are taught and expected to reject their bodies as broken, useless and, above all, not sexy. Tonight, disabled people put themselves back on the sex agenda.</ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 3rd AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Black Bag - Ch 4, 8pm</h3><ul>Return of the series that examines topical issues in Britain's black and Asian communities.<p><b>Closing Downs</b><br>London's Hackney Downs used to be one of the best boys' schools in the area, boasting Michael Caine, Steven Berkoff and harold Pinter among its further pupils. But in recent years, it has been a school in crisis, plagued with bad academic results, poor discipline and rapidly sinking morale.m Last autumn, Hackney Council proposed closing the school because it was failing the dwindling numbers that still attended, 95 per cent of whom were from ethnic minorities. <i>Closing Downs</i> traces the course of the disputes that arose as a result of this decision, talks to those who have fought to keep the school open, and shows how the efforts of parents and teachers brought about a transformation that eventually led to the school being granted a reprieve in June.</ul><p><a name="foot"></a><li><h3>African Footsteps - BBC2, 8pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>Well-known people make personal journeys through the continent of Africa.Tonight,  MP and barrister <b>Paul Boateng</b> takes his ten-year-old son Ben to his childhood homeland of Ghana for the first time. They visit Accra, where the family lived nearly 40 years ago until a coup forced them to escape to London, and then head north to be reunited with Boateng's father, a former Minister of Information and political prisoner.</ul><p><li><h3>African Political Broadcast - BBC2, 10.25pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>Nigerian writer and Nobel Prize-winner <b>Wole Soyinka</b> argues that, despite Africa's history of blood-letting, ethnic differences do not always hve to result in conflict.</ul><p><li><h3>Walk on the Wild Side - Ch 4, 12midnight</h3><ul>The last programme in a repeat of the hard-hitting, seven-part documentary series about young people.<p><b>Dedridge Cowboys</b><br>Tonight's programme explores law and disorder on the streets of Dedridge, near Edinburgh. It's a new town, where young men play out a game of nerves with the police. In and out of trouble, these young men are hardly good guys, but the police aren't always angels, either. A discussion about the series follows at 1.40am.</ul><p><br><a name="fri"></a><h3>FRIDAY 4th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><ul><i>A day of rest after a long week of development TV.</i></ul><p><br><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 5th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Africa's Rock'n'Roll Years - BBC2, 10.50pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>With telling images and evocative music, this programme recalls the key events in the African continent from 1960 to the present day. The wind of change heralded by Harold MacMillan ushered in an era of optimism and hope for newly independent African nations. In the succeeding years the horror of war and famine, the struggle against apartheid, the search for democracy and Mandela's triumph are all part of the story. The fusion of old and new musical traditions and the emergence of African music on the world stage is charted by musicians including <b>Angelique Kidjo, Youssou N'Dour, Salif Keita</b> and <b>Hugh Masekela.</b></ul><p><li><h3>Hiroshima Remembered - BBC2, 11.50pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul>Fifty years after Hiroshima, <b>John Tusa</b> presents live coverage of the Peace memorial ceremony. Japan's Prime Minister leads his nation in homage to the estimated 200,000 people who died as a result of the first atomic bomb attack.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 6th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Crunch - BBC2, 11.25am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>Six documentaries from around the world about children caught up in controversy. <p><b>Green Corridors</b><br>The story of 12-year-old <b>Owen Wilkins</b> and his campaign to persuade the Austrailian government to create "green corridors" to protect endangered mammals and birds from the effects of development.</ul><p><li><h3>One Day in Africa - BBC2, 8pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>On 5 May 1995, in six countries across Africa, six "ordinary" people filmed their lives for 24 hours. Inspired by the succes of <i>Video Nation </i> and <i>Video Diaries, </i> the BBC has taken their camcorder format to Africa, where a soldier in Liberia, a teenager in the new South Africa, a farmer in Tanzania, a cabby in Cairo, a politican in Uganda and a nomad in the desert of Mali recorded a diary of one ordinary day.</ul><p><a name="moscow"></a><li><h3>The Moscow Criterion - BBC2, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Secret History of Britain's Nuclear Weapons</b><br>For 40 years, Britain measured the effectiveness of its nuclear defence policy by the "Moscow Criterion", the ability to hit the Soviet capital. <b> Mark Urban</b> uncovers the story of Britain's nuclear weapons, from the earliest tests in the Pacific to the arrival of the first Trident submarine, and finds out from leading figures involved whether it was worth Britain's struggle to keep up with the nuclear arms race.</ul><p><a name="shadow"><li><h3>Witness - Ch 4, 9.40pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Shadow of Hiroshima</b><br>Award-winning poet <b>Tony Harrison</b> has written and directed this "film-poem" to mark the 50th anniversary of the Hiroshima bomb.</ul><a name="decision"></a><p><li><h3>Hiroshima - the Decision to Drop the Bomb - BBC1, 10.10pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august4_bomb.gif"><br><p>Archive footage and first-hand accounts of Hiroshima and the suspected hidden America agenda behind the world's first nuclear attack.<p><i>©: BBC</i></ul><p><br clear=left><li><h3>Heart of the Matter - BBC1, 11.10pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/radioactive.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Legacy of the Bomb</b><br>A special edition hosted by <b>Joan Bakewell.</b> An international panel of experts - including <b>Bruce Kent,</b> Vice-President of CND, and <b>Lord Terence Lewin,</b> former Chief of Defence Staff - debate the ethics, the effectiveness and the future of nuclear weapons.</ul><p> <li><h3>African Political Broadcast - BBC2, 12.10am<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>Tonight, <b>President Meles Zenawi</b> of Ethiopia discusses the type 