rest. Tonight's programme reveals the rural conflict that has erupted along the Belem-Brasilia highway, the first development road in Amazonia, as rich ranchers drive off poverty-stricken squatters who are subjected to intimidation, violence and murder.</ul><p> <br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 9th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>I'm Still a Tourist - BBC2, 9.55am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul><b>Jenny Green</b> assesses facilities for disabled people at the National Trust's Wallington Hall.</ul><p><li><h3>The Day That Changed My Life - BBC2, 8pm</h3><ul>The second of six programmes about momentous events and how they affect people's lives.<p><b>A Nomad in New York</b><br><b>Waris Dirie</b> fled her Somalian desert home when, at the age of 13, she found out that her father intended to sell her to a 60-year-old man in exchange for four camels. She came to Britain in 1982 and, five years later, was discovered by photographer <b>Terence Donovan</b> who put her on the cover of the Pirelli calendar. This programme offers a personal insight into Waris's remarkable transformation from nomad to international supermodel, and culminates in her first journey back to Africa and a reunion with her mother after 15 years.</ul><p><li><h3>Siege Doctors - BBC2, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Destination Sarajevo</b><br><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august4_seige.gif">The first in a five-part series following British doctor <b>Tony Redmond</b> and a group of NHS colleagues as they try to alleviate the suffering in war-torn Bosnia. Their patients include a young boy maimed by a land mine and innocent vicitms hit by snipers' bullets.<p><i>©: BBC</i><p><img align=left src="../owo_logos/regfeat_more.gif"><a href="../bosnia_sp/bosniasp.html"> OneWorld Online's Special Report on Bosnia</a><br><br><br clear=left><be clear=left></ul><p><br><li><h3>Over the Rainbow - C4, 9pm</h3><ul>Second in a powerful four-part series which examines what it means to be gay or lesbian in modern-day America. Tonight's episode looks at the relationship between lesbian and gay organisations and the fundamentalist right. The spread of AIDS and increasing lesbian and gay power has led to as revival of the anti-gay sentiment, and the civil rights protection in the United States has proved to be tenuous.</ul><p><li><h3>When the State Kills - C4, 10pm</h3><ul><img align=right hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august4_chair.gif">The death penalty is supported by a majority of British people. In the USA, capital punishment is a major vote-winner for politicians. Channel 4 is firing up the debate for and against with a summer season entitled <b>Lethal Justice</b>. <p><i>©: Channel 4</i><p>This programme opens the season with a look at the reality of state execution, drawing on the opinions of historians, criminals and families of murder victims. Three cases are considered: <b>Glenn Ashby,</b> hanged last year in Trinidad; <b>David Lawson,</b> gassed in North Carolina; and the notorious <b>Gary Gilmore,</b> who was shot in 1977. Among the interviewees are <b>Mikal Gilmore,</b> Gary's brother, and Lawson's lawyer who describes how Lawson took 18 minutes to die, all the while repeating the words "I'm human."</ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 10th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Black Bag - Ch 4, 8pm </h3><ul>A special edition of the series that examines topical black and Asian issues.<p><b>Date with Death</b><br><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august4_mumia.gif"><b>Mumia Abu-Jamal,</b> journalist, former Black Panther activist and convicted murderer, was sentenced to death in 1982 but has been on Death Row in Pennsylvania ever since. His case has been turned in top a national issue in the US by his supporters, among them author <b>Alice Walker</b> and <b>Whoopi Goldberg,</b> and his conviction has been questioned by Amnesty International. In June, the new state governer signed Jamal's death warrant; execution by lethal injection is set for 17 August at 10pm. As the day draws near, <i>Date with Death </i> examines Jamal's life story and asks whether the state's case against him might be flawed.</ul><br clear=left><p><li><h3>Hanratty - C4, 11.25pm</h3><ul>An updated version of the <i>True Stories </i> documentary, first shown in 1982, which presents new evidence to support the claim of <b>James Hanratty's </b> family that he was not guilty of the grisly A6 murder. He was hanged in 1982 for the crime.</ul><p><br><a name="fri"></a><h3>FRIDAY 11th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Death Row Stories - C4, 7.55pm </h3><ul>People talk about friends and relatives who are sentenced to death around the world.</ul><p><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 12th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Summer Dance - BBC2, 8.15pm</h3><ul><b>Outside In</b><br>First seen earlier this year, <i>Outside In </i> was choreographed by <b>Victoria Marks</b> for the partly able-bodied, partly disabled CandoCo Dance Company. It won the Grand Prix at the recent Prague Television Festival.</ul><p><li><h3>African Political Broadcast - BBC2, 11.55pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>Vice president <b>Major General Paul Kagame,</b> leader of the rebels who swept away the regime responsible for last year's ethnic genocide in Rwanda, considers the issues of tribalism and conflict.</ul><p><li><h3>Africa Uncut - BBC2, 1.25am<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>A selection of compelling, unedited sequences from some of the many African contributors to this year's <i>Video Nation.</i></ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 13th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h