litary assistance to the Rwandan government between 1990 and 1994, despite evidence that at the heart of the regime was the murderous Network Zero. "In a day it would have been over if the French hadn't been there," a Legionnaire says about attempts to defend the French-government in Rwanda.</ul><p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 21st AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Human Face of Indonesia - BBC2, 11.40am</h3><ul><b>We Are Nothing Without the People</b><br>In the first of five programmes, administrators of one of Indonesia's poorest provinces speak out.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 22nd AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Agenda 21 - Discovery Channel, 7.30pm</h3><ul>Reports on the lost children of Italy who are rounded up by the Mafia, and the flying hospital which has restored sight to 8 million people.</ul><p><li><h3>The Decade of Destruction - Ch 4, 1.55am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Crusade for the Forest</b><br><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august11_decades2.gif"><br>Director <b>Adrian Cowell's</b> five-part series follows the human tragedies which have resulted from the exploitation and destruction of Brazil's tropical rainforest. Tonight's film records the tale of <b>Chico Mendes,</b> a leader of the seringueiros (rubber tappers of the Amazon), who lost his life while halting the plans of developers..</ul><p><font size=-1>©: Channel 4</font size><br clear=left><brclear=right><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 23rd AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><a name=siege><li><h3>Siege Doctors - BBC2, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august4_seige.gif">The third in a five-part series following British doctor <b>Tony Redmond</b> and a group of NHS colleagues as they try to alleviate the suffering in war-torn Bosnia. <p><b>Wounds of War</b><br>In September 1994 Tony took another team of British doctors into Sarajevo. At the time the ceasefore was still holding but the city was tense and full of uncertainty. More than half of Sarajevo's doctors have been killed or have managed to escape. Those left behind struggle on, with very little hope for the future.<p><font size=-1>©: BBC</font><p><img align=left src="../owo_logos/regfeat_more.gif"><a href="../bosnia_sp/bosniasp_top.html"> OneWorld Online's Special Report on Bosnia</a><br><br><br clear=left><be clear=left></ul><p><br><li><h3>Over the Rainbow - C4, 9pm</h3><ul><b>Hollow Liberty</b><br>Final episode in a powerful four-part series which examines what it means to be gay or lesbian in modern-day America. Tonight's programme examines the rise of gay activism in the US and shows how teenagers are contributing to queer consciusness and how their growing strength and knowledge is increasing awareness of lesbians and gay men.</ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 24th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>African Footsteps - BBC2, 8pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/african_summer.gif"></h3><ul>Continuing the documentary series in which celebrities travel to selected African destinations to reveal the hidden facts of the continent.<p><b>Egypt</b><br>Feminist writer <b>Nawal El Saadawi</b> presents her personal vision of Egypt. She explores the bustling streets of Cairo, before travelling to the Temple of Isis on the banks of the River Nile. Along the way, she talks of her dream of Egypt as a truly democratic country whose people are free to express their opinions, and in which women are "totally liberated".</b></ul><p><li><h3>The Black Bag - Ch 4, 8pm </h3><ul>Continuing the series that examines topical black and Asian issues.<p><b>Money Drugs Lock-Up</b><br>Tonight's programme goes behind the locked doors of Feltham Young Offenders and Remand Centre