ison and he has only recently been released on licence. <b>Maureen Shiels</b> sees it as an opportunity to raise her family in peace. <b>Donna Bradley's</b> husband, an IRA activist, was shot dead but at least their children now have a chance to live in peace.<br><font size=-1>Gary Fleming<br>©: Channel 4</font></ul><br clear=right><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 30th AUGUST<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Day That Changed My Life - BBC2, 8pm<img  src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>I Hate Terminal 2</b><br>Teenager <b>Diba Kapic</b> grew up in the Bosnian town of Stolac, where her father was a surgeon. When the town underwent "ethnic cleansing", her family fled alongside all the other Muslim residents who make up 80% of the population. Diba was one of the the lucky ones: she got a flight to London, where she is now trying to begin a new life, while her family remains at home. This is her account of the loneliness and frustration that marked her arrival at Heathrow.<p></ul><a name=siege><li><h3>Siege Doctors - BBC2, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><img align=left hspace=8 vspace=8 src="tvandradio_pix/august4_seige.gif">The third in a five-part series following British doctor <b>Tony Redmond</b> and a group of NHS colleagues as they try to alleviate the suffering in war-torn Bosnia. <p><b>Children of the Siege</b><br>This programme tells the moving story of the parents of two children caught in a gas explosion - one of the hidden dangers of living in this beseiged city.<p><font size=-1>©: BBC</font><p><img align=left src="../owo_logos/regfeat_more.gif"><a href="../bosnia_sp/bosniasp_top.html"> OneWorld Online's Special Report on Bosnia</a><br><br><br clear=left></ul><p><br><a name="trouble"></a><li><h3>The Trouble with Peace - Ch 4, 11.10pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Second of two documentaries on the fragile peace process in Northern Ireland.<p