otv&radio_line.gif"></h3><ul><i>No development TV today.</i></ul><p><br><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 9th SEPTEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Brazilian Immigrants: In Search of Identity - BBC2, 6.50am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>How immigrants in the Brazilian city of Sao Paulo are contributing to the life of their adopted home town.</ul><p><li><h3>People First - Ch 4, 7.35pm</h3><ul>The investigative documentary series dealing with disability issues.<p><b>Hailing a CAB</b><br>When architect <b>Gabriele Bramante</b> set out to build a new Citizens' Advice Bureau, her brief was to make it as accessible as possible to disabled people. This programme tests the result.</ul><p><a name="ophuls"><li><h3>War Correspondent: the Troubles We've Seen - BBC2, 9.05pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>The second of two journeys by veteran French documentary maker <b>Marcel Ophuls</b> into the world of the war correspondent. Ophuls pulls no punches in his investigation into this most hardbitten of professions, paying scant respect to supposedly intimidating reputations. He poses a host of hostile enquiries, questioning the very need for journailsts suspected of exploiting images of suffering without placing them into their proper context. He has nothing but contempt for those who value ratings over responsible reporting. But, in the final analysis and after a kaleidoscope of experiences during visits in 1993 to war-torn Sarajevo, his overall impression is one of admiration and courage of the great majority of journalists.<br clear=right><br><img align=left src="../owo_logos/regfeat_more.gif"><a href="ophuls.html">Exclusive video clip & images, and the story behind the films and their Director</a><br><p></ul><br clear=right><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 10th SEPTEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Developing World: Mozambique Under Attack 