when the potato crop was destroyed by blight. Over a million perople fled the horrors of starvation and disease by taking ships to Britain, Canada and, most of all, the United States. In the second of two programmes, Dublin-born writer <b>Ian Gibson</b> tells how thousands of the Irish poor died on board "coffin ships" that carried them across the Atlantic to the fever sheds of Quebec and the slums of New York. He explores some of the myths of famine history, finding them to be more complicated than on superficial examination, and explains how the bitter experience of the mass emigration has shaped Irish-American support for nationalist causes, from the Fenians to the Irish Republican Army.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 12th SEPTEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Agenda 21 - Discovery Channel,  7.30pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Environment and development issues. How AIDS has fuelled child prostitution, plus a doctor who stings patients with bees to cure illness.</ul><p><li><h3>Black Families - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>A House Divided</b><br>A look at how deportation, or the threat of it, can damage families. Asian women are usually seen as the lodestone of family life, upholding values and keeping stability in the household. But two women who have family commitments in Britain have found life has become a constant battle as stringent immigration legislation threatens to break up their domestic situations.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 13th SEPTEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>The Human Face of Indonesia - BBC2, 9.55am<img src="tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul><b>But I'll Always Continue to Write</b><br>The life of newspaper journalist <b>Debra Yatim,</b> whose passionate words endeavour to alert her readers to the plight of low-income jobs.</ul><p><li><h3>Frontline - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul>