iries, and found her husband hadn't been admitted at all. But when she returned, the woman - and the baby - had gone." Many others, mainly young and poor, are talked into giving up their new-born infants by "midwives", who get commission for every child they secure. These women scour the country looking for suitable victims, often telling them the babies will go into state care, rather than being sold to foreign families. Would-be "purchaser" parents are reluctant to confront the issues - or to talk on camera. "You can understand their position," says Buchanan. "Many of them are desperate for children, having tried fertility treatment and having spent a lot of time and money applying through Paraguayan channels."</ul><p><li><h3>Ths Shadow of a Gunman - BBC2, 8.55pm</h3><ul>A dreaming poet is mistaken by a romantic young girl for an IRA gunman on the run in this production of <b>Sean O'Casey's</b> famous play.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 8th OCTOBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul><b>Sian Vasey</b> looks at how children's books deal with disability, plus ballroom dancing for wheelchair users.</ul><p><li><h3>Everyman - BBC1, 10.40pm</h3><ul><b>Everyob</b><br>Ten years on from the Church of Engliand's "Faith in the City" initiative to tackle inner city problems, this special programme confronts leading Christian voices with a nightmare vision of Britain - seen from the bottom of the social and economic ladder, where young people are trapped in a cycle of hopelessness, alienation, boredom and addiction.</ul><p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 9th OCTOBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Cutting Edge - Ch 4, 9pm</h3><ul><b>Fighting for Breath</b><br>Filmed during this year's long, hot summer in Britain, tonight's documentary follows the lives of four seriously ill patients living in Birmingham, and reveals new research into the condition that link