led to safety in America. The net result of Nazi hostility to the surrealists was France losing her position as leader of the modern art movement. The focus of attention shifted to New York.</ul><p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 13th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>World in Action - ITV, 8.30pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>As controversy mounts over the threat that so-called mad cow disease might pose to humans, tonight's investigation reveals new figures about the number of infected animals which, after death, might have ended up in Britain's food chain.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 14th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>From the Edge - BBC2, 7.30pm</h3><ul>Are jokes about disability acceptable? <b>David Hevey</b> discusses the issue with disabled comics <b>Wonda Barbara</b> and <b>Tony Gerrard</b>. Plus, to mark the first anniversary of the National Lottery, a look at how organisations of disabled people have fared in the cash handouts.</ul><p><li><h3>Nice Work - BBC2, 9.30pm</h3><ul><b>Mad, Passionate Dreams</b><br>All over Britain there are pockets of almost total unemployment. This programme visits Penrhys estate in Mid Glamorgan to see how residents are dealing with the 95% unemployment rate.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 15th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Here and Now - BBC1, 7.30pm</h3><ul><b>Sue Lawley</b> joins the team which, through a mix of hard-hitting investigations and entertaining features, speaks up for people whose lives are affected by politicians and decision makers. </ul><p><li><h3>Cities of the Future - BBC2, 11.15pm <img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>As forecasters predict that economic dominance in the next century will belong to the nations of the Pacific Rim, this series of three programmes attempts 