eries in which culinary expert <b>Dorinda Hafner</b> visits six African countries.</ul><p><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 18th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Developing World: The Cutting Edge of Progress - BBC2, 8.20am<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Cutting Edge of Progress</b><br>How the Tonga of Zimbabwe were forced from their homes by the building of the Kariba Dam.</ul><p><li><h3>Asia Two - BBC2, 10am</h3><ul>A series of Asian cultural shows.<p><b>10am - Chanakya</b><br>Continuing the epic saga set in ancient India. The political crisis in Magadh blows over. <br><i>In Hindi with English subtitles.</i><p><b>10.40am - Video Byte</b><br>Pop videos from the UK, India and Pakistan.<p><b>10.50 - Network East</b><br>Asian arts show. Today's guests are actor <b>Naseeruddin Shah</b> and director <b>Shyam Benegal.</b></ul><p><li><h3>Sign On - Ch 4, 12pm</h3><ul><b>Your Views</b><br>A discussion following on from last week's propogramme about the problems faced by deaf prisoners. With guests <b>Judge Stephen Tumim</b> who recently delivered his report on the prison service, and <b>Richard Tilt,</b> its new Director General.<br><i>Signed in British Sign Language with open subtitles.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Four Fingers and a Thumb - Ch 4, 4.25pm</h3><ul>Ending the week-long initiative promoting British Sign Language. <b>John Wilson</b> signs his short story, <i>Dolls' Ears.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Assignment - BBC2, 7.20pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>East Beats West</b><br>The Asian economic miracle has gone one better than its counterpart in the West. Countries such as Malaysia have reaped the financial rewards of rapid industrialisation but, unlike the West, they have preserved their traditional social values of the extended family and social cohesion. The interests of the community at large take precendence over what Asian leaders feel is the Western obsession with individual liberties. Malaysia's Prime Minister, <b>Dr Mohamad Mahathir,</b> tells <b>Julian Pettifer</b> what lessons we can learn from the Eastern experience and explains the price of that knowledge.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 19th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>See Hear - BBC1, 10am</h3><ul><b>Jack Ashley</b> talks to comedian <b>Eric Sykes,</b> who has been deaf for over 30 years, and deaf headmistress <b>Mabel Davis</b> and <b>Winifred Tumim,</b> a hearing mother of two deaf daughters and ex-chairman of RNID.<br><i>With signing and subtitles.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul><b>Ian Cook</b> reports from parliament where disabled people are protesting over local authority care charges.</ul><p><li><h3>Soviet Echoes - Ch 4, 8pm <img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>For years, rumours spread through the Russian musical world of hidden stores of musical treasures left over from the Soviet period. This three-part series draws on material uncovered by American TV producer <b>Tristan Del,</b> which tells the tragic and moving stories of the stars of Soviet culture.</ul><p><li><h3>The Money Programme - BBC2, 8.20pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Selling to Kids</b><br>Schools are the new battleground in the brands war. As the cost of television advertising spirals, advertisers are looking for more direct ways of reaching one of their brightest markets - young children. Their new weapon is the direct marketing of products through schools, using educational materials and free gifts. But unease with the methods being used is growing.</ul><p><li><h3>Heart of the Matter - BBC1, 10.50pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Legacy of Nuremberg</b><br>On the 50th anniversary of the Nuremberg trials, <b>Joan Bakewell</b> chairs a debate from the original courtroom, examining the arguments for amnesty and retribution in dealing with war crimes. Joining her are Archbishop of Cape Town <b>Desmond Tutu,</b> Bosnian Foreign Minister <b>Mohamed Sacirbey,</b> </b>controversial French lawyer <b>Jacques Verges</b> and British historian <b>David Cesarani.</b></ul><p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 20th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Inside Out - Ch 4, 8pm <img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>A new documentary stand focusing on individuals whose stories chart both their problems and society's prejudices.<p><b>From Despair to Where?</b><br><b>Gill</b> is a young mother and fan of the <b>Manic Street Preachers</b> and, like band member <b>Richey Edwards</b> whose disappearance followed a life of self-harm, she regularly cuts herself. In this journey of discovery, she meets other self-harmers and tries to find out why the syndrome is so prevalent.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 21st NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Network First - BBC2, 10.40pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Man and Animal</b><br>A powerful exploration, filmed on four continents, of man's relationship with other animals - from love and devotion, to cruelty and greed. In New York, pampered dogs model high fashion outfits; in Guan's Cantonese restaurants live cats are plunged into boiling water. Indian monks commit a crime if they kill even the smallest insect, while bulls are ritually tortured in the name of religion in Spain.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 22nd NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Here and Now - BBC1, 7.30pm</h3><ul><b>Sue Lawley</b> joins the team which, through a mix of hard-hitting investigations and entertaining features, speaks up for people whose lives are affected by politicians and decision makers. </ul><p><li><h3>Dispatches - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Another investigative report in the acclaimed current affairs series.</ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 23rd NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Midlands Report - BBC2, 7.30pm</h3><ul><b>Under the Carpet</b><br>Violent attacks by people with a history of mental illness continue to hit the headlines. Do they signify the failure of care in the community?</ul><p><li><h3>Doctors in the Dock - BBC2, 10pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Kidneys for Sale</b><br>Medical ethics rather than medical blunders are at the centre of this documentary which examines a case the media dubbed the "kidneys for sale racket". In 1989 two pioneers in the treatment of kidney disease, <b>Mr Michael Bewick</b> and <b>Dr Raymond Crockett,</b> were involved in four kidney transplants where the donors were not genetically related to the recipients and received payment for the operation. While Bewick and Crockett had not broken the law at that time, they were both punished for their actions by the General Medical Council. Neither can see anything wrong with what they did. Crockett asks what parent would not pay for a kidney if it would save his child's life, while Bewick asks why, if it is acceptable for the recipient to send the donor a thank-you card, or a present of a holiday, is it unacceptable to give cash?</ul><p><br><a name="fri"></a><h3>FRIDAY 24th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Children in Need - BBC1, 7pm</h3><ul>Pudsey's back with <b>Terry Wogan</b> to bring news of this year's fundraising extravaganza. <b>Sue Cook</b> takes a look at how your money is helping needy children, and <b>Gaby Roslin </b>presents <i>Celebrate Children, </i> a series of short films.</ul><p><li><h3>A Taste of Africa - Ch 4, 8pm</h3><ul><b>Tanzania</b><br><b>Dorinda</b> visits the Chagga people of Kilimanjaro where she cooks a four course meal with bananas in each course.</ul><p><br><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 25th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Asia Two - BBC2, 10am<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>A series of Asian cultural shows.<p><b>10am - Chanakya</b><br>Continuing the epic saga set in ancient India. King Dhana Nand orders Vishnu Gupta to be banished from Magadh. <br><i>In Hindi with English subtitles.</i><p><b>10.40am - Video Byte</b><br>Pop videos from the UK, India and Pakistan.<p><b>10.50 - Network East</b><br>This week, the Asian arts show meets a photographer who has captured on film the migration of Scottish Asians, and a racing driver fulfilling a childhood ambition. Presented by <b>Sujata Barot</b> and <b>Snajeev Bhaskar.</b></ul><p><li><h3>Sign On - Ch 4, 12pm</h3><ul><b>At Leisure</b><br>For one week in October, 41 teams competed in the 1995 NFC Deaf Auto Challenge in the grounds of Rockingham Castle, Northamptonshire. Events included grass karting, clay pigeon shooting, quad bikes and a checkpoint rally. <b>Carolyn Edwards</b> follows the progress of the teams aiming to become the all-action champions.<br><i>Signed in British Sign Language with open subtitles.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Assignment - BBC2, 7.20pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>The New Inquisition</b><br>Thirteen years ago <b>Filipe Gonzalez's</b> Socialist party was swept to office in Spain on a tide of popularity. Today his minority government is clinging to power, rocked by a series of scandals, amidst allegations of corruption, extortion, bribery and illegal phone tapping. <b>Peter Godwin</b> investigates new allegations concerning the prime minister and asks how long Gonzalez can survive.</ul><p><li><h3>The Big Snog - Ch4, 10.45pm</h3><ul>Comedy and music from London's Astoria Theatre to mark the beginning of World Aids Week.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 26th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>See Hear - BBC1, 10am</h3><ul>A disussion on deaf people's access to law and justice.<br><i>With signing and subtitles.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul>An art exhibition by former patients of an east London pyschiatric hospital.</ul><p><li><h3>Soviet Echoes - Ch 4, 8pm </h3><ul>The second of three programmes drawing on previously unseen Russian archive footage and following the great Russian composers who suffered terrible hardship  under the Soviet regime.<p><b>Rewards and Punishments</b><br>The story of how musicians such as Stravinsky, Shostakovich and Prokofiev coped with the sustained pressure, and in some cases the threat of death, to produce work that was truly theirs rather than influenced by the state.</ul><p><li><h3>The Last Europeans - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"> </h3><ul>A three-part series about the most divisive issue in post-war British politics - our relations with Europe. Presented by <b>Hugo Young.</b><p><b>Crossed Channels</b><br>The first programme traces how Britain, still with illusions of being a world power, ignored the moves that led to the founding of the Common Market in 1957. The Suez crisis changed all this, but Britain's applications to join in 1961 and 1967 failed. It was not until after de Gaulle's resignation and death that the way was clear for Edward Heath to win British membership in 1972. But, as a late entrant to the club, Britain paid a higher price and, as the "last Europeans", had played no part in making the rules.</ul><p><li><h3>Everyman Special - BBC1, 10.10pm</h3><ul><b>Breach of Faith</b><br>Charismatic priest <b>Chris Brain</b> speaks for the first time on television about the sex scandal that rocked the Church of England this summer, when it was claimed that he had sexually abused more than 20 female members of his church. The programme also features some of the women involved as well as church leaders speaking about the issues this has raised. A debate follows in <i>Heart of the Matter.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Heart of the Matter - BBC1, 11pm</h3><ul><b>Beware of False Prophets</b><br><b>Joan Bakewell</b> asks what lessons are to be learned from vicar <b>Chris Brain's</b> controversial Nine O'Clock Service and looks at how mainstream religion is coping with the changing religious needs of individuals in modern times.</ul><p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 27th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Inside Out - Ch 4, 8pm </h3><ul>Continuing the documentary strand focusing on individuals whose stories chart both their problems and society's prejudices.<p><b>Ivy's Genes</b><br>Will genetic screening eliminate disability? <b>Tom Shakespeare</b> and his seven-year-old daughter, <b>Ivy,</b> both have restricted growth and together they look at her future reproductive choices.</ul><p><li><h3>World in Action - ITV, 8.30pm</h3><ul>Another topical investigation by the award-winning documentary team.</ul><p><li><h3>Nature Special: City Trees - BBC2, 9.45pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Under the Axe?</b><br>Without trees, our cities would be unbearable. Not only do they add beauty to otherwise sterile environments, they also cool the air in summer, filter pollution and absorb noise. They harbour and feed wildlife all year round, creating miniature eco-systems in the heart of the urban landscape. Yet for all this, city trees are constantly under siege.  Developers think nothing of chopping down avenues that may be over 100 years old, while careless use of weedkiller can destroy roots of nearby plantations. Many people are fighting to protect these  essential city dwellers, but without a coordinated strategy our lives may be less green in years to come.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 28th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Picture This - BBC2, 9.30pm</h3><ul><b>No Ordinary People</b><br>The final documentary in the series is a celebration of the experiences of a group of people who worked for the French resistance in the Second World War, and their courage in the face of fear - a powerful reminder of how ordinary people can be transformed by the extraordinary events of war.</ul><p><li><h3>Friends - Ch 4, 10pm</h3><ul>A Film on Four Premiere. In South Africa  in the mid-eighties, three young women graduate from university: Sophie is from a privileged white family; Annika is an Afrikaner, while Thoko was raised in a Zulu township. Some years later, the trio's friendship is tested when one of them reacts against the injustices of apartheid.</ul><p><li><h3>Equal Before the Law - BBC2, 11.25pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Can black and Asian people feel confident that they will receive a fair trial in Britain? With some lawyers now calling for ethnically balanced juries, <b>Johnnie Cochran,</b> the black American lawyer who defended O J Simpson, joins a discussion in this <i>Public Eye </i> special with leading figures from the law, the police and the black community.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 29th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Dispatches - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Another investigative report in the acclaimed current affairs series.</ul><p><li><h3>Short and Curlies - Ch 4, 9.45pm</h3><ul><b>Home Away from Home</b><br>A poignant film about a woman from Nigeria who dreams of her African childhood and feels the need to establish her own identity as well as to find a better way of getting closer to her daughter. To this end, she starts to build a mud hut in her garden in Britain.</ul><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 30th NOVEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Midlands Report - BBC2, 7.30pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Dirty Driving</b><br>Fifty per cent of car pollution is caused by just ten per cent of vehicles - and people aren't safe inside their cars either. Exhaust fumes can concentrate inside a car at levels often six times higher than those on the kerb. <b>Bob Jefforson</b> reports on the measures that might have to be taken to combat the menace of traffic-related pollution.</ul><p><br><a name="fri"></a><h3>FRIDAY 1st DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>A Taste of Africa - Ch 4, 8pm</h3><ul><b>Mali</b><br><b>Dorinda Hafner</b> travels up the River Niger to Mali, where she cooks capoitaine (a freshwater fish) brochettes with salad, before gaining first-hand experience of the body decoration and hairstyling techniques that make Malinese women so elegant.</ul><p><br><a name="sat"></a><h3>SATURDAY 9th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Developing World: Towards a Better Life - BBC2, 8.20pm</h3><ul>Schools programme.</ul><p><li><h3>Asia Two - BBC2, 10am<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_yes.gif"></h3><ul>A series of Asian cultural shows.<p><b>10am - Chanakya</b><br>Continuing the epic saga set in ancient India. <br><i>In Hindi with English subtitles.</i><p><b>10.40am - Video Byte</b><br>Pop videos from the UK, India and Pakistan.<p><b>10.50am - Network East</b><br>Today, a look at the Asian comedy scene. Presented by <b>Sujata Barot</b> and <b>Snajeev Bhaskar.</b><p><b>11.20am - Bollywood or Bust!</b><br>The second semi-final in the Asian movie quiz.</ul><p><br><a name="sun"></a><h3>SUNDAY 10th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>See Hear - BBC1, 10.15am</h3><ul>Looking at how family history can predict deafness.<br><i>With signing and subtitles.</i></ul><p><li><h3>Link - ITV, 10.15am</h3><ul>Today, an interview with disabled playwright <b>Sheila Hill,</b> plus a report on disabled children in residential care.</ul><p><a name=#wrongs><li><h3>Human Rights, Human Wrongs - BBC2, 4.15pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"><img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_new.gif"></h3><ul>To mark International Human Rights Day, the first in a six-part, daily series of short programmes highlighting the human cost of rights violations. Today, BBC Foreign Affairs Editor <b>John Simpson</b> reviews 1995's record of human mistreatment.</ul><p><li><h3>Soviet Echoes - Ch 4, 8pm</h3><ul><b>Traditions and Hopes</b><br>The final programme in the series highlights the traditions of opera and piano, with the help of tenor <b>Ivan Koslovski</b> and pianist <b>Maria Yudina,</b> and illustrates the story of Yudina's clash with Stalin. The former Soviet leader was so moved by one of her performances that he tried to commission a recording, but she responded by saying she would pray for his soul. Also, there's a look at how contemporary Russian music has evolved along the line of the country's politics.</ul><p><li><h3>Heart of the Matter - BBC1, 11pm</h3><ul><b>Granny, Come Home</b><br>Tonight, <b>Joan Bakewell</b> chairs a studio debate on where the responsibility lies for the care of the elderly - with the state or with the famly? <b>Robina Crowe</b> made the difficult decision to put her mother into a home, but the money she raised by selling her own house is running out. Should she sacrifice the higher education of her children or should society as a whole provide more support? Is an environment being created in which generations are being pitted against one another?</ul><p><br><a name="mon"></a><h3>MONDAY 11th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Human Rights, Human Wrongs - BBC2, 7.50pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Summary Executions</b><br>Chilean writer <b>Isabel Allende</b> describes the reality of execution without trial, from the victims of Kashmir's civil war to the Bosnian men and boys who "disappeared" after the fall of Srebrenica, and the street people removed by "social cleansing" in Colombia.</ul><p><li><h3>Inside Out - Ch 4, 8pm </h3><ul>Continuing the documentary strand focusing on individuals whose stories chart both their problems and society's prejudices.<p><b>Whose School Is It Anyway?</b><br><b>Sahira Khan</b> is 15 and she's deaf. She attends her local comprehensive in the London Borough of Newham. Through an interpreter, she takes full part in mainstream National Curriculum classes. This is integrated education as its best, yet many disabled children are still underachieving in special schools.</ul><p><li><h3>World in Action - ITV, 8.30pm</h3><ul>Another hard-hitting investigation by the award-winning documentary team. Tonight's programme is the last in the current series.</ul><p><br><a name="tue"></a><h3>TUESDAY 12th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Human Rights, Human Wrongs - BBC2, 5.50pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Weapons and Human Rights</b><br><b>Archbishop Desmond Tutu</b> examines the devastating effects of light weapons, such as pistols and land mines, on civilian life, as arms come into the hands of criminal gangs and vigilantes and unexploded mines left over from warfare exact a terrible price.</ul><p><li><h3>Birth of the Bomb - BBC2, 9pm</h3><ul>The genesis of the atomic bomb, from early experiments in Nazi Germany to the US Manhattan project, which developed the  bombs dropped on Japan in 1945.</ul><p><br><a name="wed"></a><h3>WEDNESDAY 13th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Home Fires - Ch 4, 10.55am</h3><ul>A documentary about army families separated by the Gulf War. Women who watched television pictures of their husbands and sons going off to the Gulf War talk about the experience. </ul><p><li><h3>Human Rights, Human Wrongs - BBC2, 5.50pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Gypsies</b><br>The actress <b>Catherine Deneuve</b> looks at the persecution of gypsies in eastern Europe. In the wake of Communism's collapse, gypsies have become scapegoats for the economic and social ills of many countries. In Bulgaria, <b>Anya Velikova</b> has seven children, no money and no access to health care - and she lives in constant fear of vigilante groups and aggressive police. She's just one of Europe's eight million gypsies - the continent's biggest minority - who are gradually being stripped of human rights.</ul><p><li><h3>Dispatches - Ch 4, 9pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul>Another investigative report in the acclaimed current affairs series.</ul><p><br><a name="thu"></a><h3>THURSDAY 14th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Human Rights, Human Wrongs - BBC2, 6.50pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>Human Rights and the Environment</b><br>Scientist <b>Richard Dawkins</b> exposes the economic interests that threaten people's homelands, including the logging that is destroying the forests in Cambodia.</ul><p><li><h3>Doctors in the Dock - BBC2, 10pm</h3><ul><b>Lethal Injection</b><br><b>Dr Nigel Cox</b> was convicted of attempted murder because he helped a patient to die. Here he talks candidly about the incident.</ul><p><br><a name="fri"></a><h3>FRIDAY 15th DECEMBER<img src="../owo_logos/online_logotv&radio_line.gif"></h3><li><h3>Human Rights, Human Wrongs - BBC2, 6.50pm<img src="../tvandradio/tvandradio_pix/whats_wco.gif"></h3><ul><b>The Right to Belief</b><br>In the last programme of the series, actress <b>Billie Whitelaw</b> examines the rise of religious intolerance and persecution around the world.</ul><p>