<head>

<title>City Speech 15th July</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center></a>

<h2>THE UK AND THE WIDER DEVELOPMENT AGENDA<br>BARONESS CHALKER'S SPEECH AT ROBERT FLEMING & CO, 15

JULY 1996</h2>



<p><a href="http:../../oda/index.html" target="_top">Visit the ODA WWW Home Page</a>

</center>

<hr>

<p>

Introduction I am most grateful for the opportunity to speak to

you today.  I want to examine how Government can work in

partnership with the private sector on the wider development

agenda.





<p>

We already work extensively with the private sector.  I want to

deepen this relationship - both at home and abroad.  Partnership

with the private sector is essential to promoting sustainable

development.  Sustainable development is not only important in

its own right, but it is also the key to building the markets of

the future, and vital to Britain's own long-term interests.





<p>

In speaking today, I should therefore like:



<blockquote>- to explain how the Government sees the wider

development agenda, the complementary roles of the

public and private sectors, and British interests;    

<p>

- to describe what the UK is doing to promote this agenda, and  

the changes to ODA's own role;     

<p>

-    to share with you some of the successes;    

<p>

-    and to invite you to tell us more about the ways in which government

may be able to help

you to play a part.</blockquote>



<p>

The wider development agenda As you know, two weeks ago the

heads of G7 governments met in Lyon for their annual summit. 

Global interdependence and development were two of the main

themes of the meeting - and rightly so.  Let me touch on each in

turn.

<p>

My overseas visits constantly remind me of how interdependent a world we live in.  The global exchange is unending:  of goods

and services, of information, of people and ideas, of disease. 

Conflicts, terrorism and crime spill over borders.  Competition

for and misuse of natural resources threaten our common

environment.

<p>

It is ever clearer in today's complex and interdependent world

that 'development' is about more than aid flows from the Western

public sector.  The development agenda is a much wider one.  It

has to be.

<p>

It is an agenda in which the private sector has a key role to

play.  This is vividly demonstrated by the net resource flows to

developing countries.  Total flows in 1995 were $231 billion. 

Private capital accounted for threequarters of this total.  Ten

years ago the official sector accounted for more than half

aggregate resources flows.  Last year it amounted to a quarter. 

Alongside these huge private flows has gone the much-needed

injection of private sector experience, and disciplines. 

Against this background I am particularly pleased that the

Summit paid tribute to the record levels of private investment

flows to the developing world, and acknowledged the key role of

the private sector in-country, as the main engine of growth.

<p>

Governments have a crucial role to play too.  It is only

governments who collectively - can put the right international

policy framework in place.  It is only governments in developing

countries who can get the local policy the  environment right.

<p>

Turning first to the international framework, trade policy

clearly has a key part to play.  It is vital that developing

countries should have the opportunity of greater market access

for their goods and services.  Alongside this, action needs to

be taken internationally to relieve the debt burden of heavily

indebted countries - helping these countries back into private

capital markets.  

<p>

Governments have a vital part to play as aid donors too. 

Despite the vast flows of private capital, the fact remains that

these are heavily skewed towards a small number of the more

successful countries.  There is a continuing role for donors -

in providing concessional flows and directing these to those

countries who need them most, and can use them effectively.  

<p>

There is a fundamental role too for the governments of

developing countries.  It is they who must create a positive and

welcoming climate for both the domestic and the foreign private

sector.  This is not just a question of getting the right

economic policies.  It is also about pursuing the wider good government agenda:  establishing open and accountable

institutions, the rule of law and genuine participation in the

process of government.  The prime responsibility in all these

areas rests with developing countries themselves.  Without real

commitment on their part, the domestic private sector on which

growth depends will not develop.  Nor will the country be able

to compete in the market place for private sector flows from

outside.

<p>

Complementary roles of public and private sectors The message in

all this is clear.  The private sector and Government can and

must support each other.  Their roles are complementary.  The

effort the public sector is putting into development, both by

trying to create the right policy framework, and by its own

resource flows - in the form of aid cannot succeed without an

active private sector role.  

<p>

But equally, private sector activity can be given a greater

stimulus by what governments can do - to create the environment

in which the private sector can thrive, and development can take

off.  Carefully targeted and effectively managed aid has a

crucial role to play in this process - by  supporting and

encouraging change.  



<p>

We are fortunate in that there is now a widespread consensus on

these two parts:  the shape of the wider development agenda, and

the complementary roles of the private and public sectors.  This

consensus provides a sound basis for success.





<p>

Britain has an important stake in this success.  It is right in

itself that we should be responding to the key challenge of

reducing poverty.  But it is also in Britain's interests, and

the interests of Britain's businesses that we should be

promoting development.  We cannot afford to take a parochial

view.  Exports account for a quarter of our GDP.  The shape of

the world is changing around us.  By the turn of the century

four-fifths of the world's population will live in developing

countries.  If we can promote growth in these countries we will

be helping to create the markets of the future on which our own

growth and prosperity depends.





<p>

May I therefore to the part the UK is playing internationally to

promote this wider agenda.  It is a part we - both government

and private sector can be proud of.

<p>

The UK has a larger stock of investment overseas (some @@700

billion) than any other country bar the United States - which

has an economy six times our size.  Indeed as a proportion of

our natural wealth we have more inward and outward investment

(nearly twice as much) than any other country.





<p>

The private sector in the UK is of course a provider not just of

essential capital flows - but of intellectual capital too.  Here

in the City you are an unrivalled source of know-how and

expertise on privatisation and financial restructuring.  These

are areas in which Britain is a world leader, and they are areas

of huge importance across the world - not only the rest of

Europe but also Africa and South Asia.





<p>

For our part, the Government has taken a leading role

internationally in promoting the liberalization of the global

trading system.  We have long had a forward position in the

European Union on this.  We will continue to argue for the

liberalizing agenda, both in Europe and on the wider

international stage.  This will be particularly relevant when we

come to consider the future of the trade aspects of the Lom&#233;

Convention.  We shall continue to play a leading role on

initiatives to help resolve the debt burden of the poorest

countries.





<p>

We have played a key role in promoting prudent macro-economic

policies and essential economic reforms.  Examples from Africa

alone range from:  civil service reform in Ghana, to venture

capital in Tanzania; and from reducing the regulation of private

business in Zimbabwe, to simplifying taxation and improving its

administration in Zambia.





<p>

And we maintain a high quality aid programme, complementing the

private sector by reaching into areas where private investment

does not yet reach, helping with basic social investment such as

health and education, helping with infrastructure provision, and

underpinning policy reform.



<p>

Successes I said earlier in my speech that the public sector

could help create the environment in which the private sector

could thrive, and development could take off.  Let me take this

chance to offer you some proof of this particular pudding.  Out

of Africa, perhaps for a change, some good news.  The vast

majority of African countries are now committed to prudent

macro-economic policies and private sector led growth.  Private

investment is welcomed and the more liberal policy environment

is increasingly one in which it can be profitable. 

Privatisation, after a slow start, has gathered pace recently. 

Successful examples like Ashanti Goldfields in Ghana, and Kenya

Airways, are part of a Continent wide trend.  The change in

attitude and policy is far reaching, and ODA has been at the

centre of supporting the changes.  And the results are starting

to pay off.  In 1995 African GDP as a whole grew by 5%, and

prospects are for a further good year in 1996.  Better weather

and higher export prices are part of the story.  But more

fundamental changes are also giving new momentum.  There have

been false dawns and cruel disappointments in Africa.  But there

are now real grounds for optimism about the future.





<p>

Against this background, I am pleased that the City is showing

renewed interest in Africa, with the existence of new investment

funds.  The most successful visit by President Mandela

highlighted the investment opportunities in the new South

Africa.  I hope you will respond to his encouragement of inward

investment.  I know that you will stay in touch with

developments there - and I urge you to stay in touch with other

positive investment locations in Africa too.





<p>

There are hundreds of similar success stories which show that aid can

work, and above all that British development assistance does work.  





<p>

At the same time, the wider development agenda needs to be

reflected in a widening of ODA's own agenda too.  It has been. 

The Overseas Development Administration, as the development wing

of the FCO, has too often been seen as essentially an agency

only for designing and managing aid projects.  







<p>Designing and managing aid projects is an essential part of what

the ODA does - and it is something the ODA is recognized

internationally as doing particularly well.

<p>

But it is only part.  Last year we undertook a far-reaching

review of ODA's role and activities.  We have, as a result of

this, drawn up a new Mission Statement in which we recognize the

wider development agenda.  Part of our mission is now explicitly

'to promote international policies for sustainable development',

and alongside this 'to enhance the effectiveness of multilateral

institutions'.





<p>

As ODA, we will seek to ensure that the role of developing

countries is taken into account more fully in the formulation of

the government's and international policies on trade and

investment.  We are now involving ourselves more closely in

trade and investment issues, such as the role of investment

guarantees, and the forthcoming first Ministerial Conference of

the WTO this December.  And we shall help ensure that the UK

continues to take a lead on debt initiatives.





<p>

We have traditionally played a leading role in international

institutions, by drawing on our own experience to push forward

policy development.  We have played a leading part in the

successful replenishment of IDA and the African Development

Fund, and in helping to refine the policies these institutions

should follow.  We have made it clear that the aid institutions

of the EC must improve the effectiveness with which they

operate.    We want to see better co-ordination in Brussels and

the field, and above all improvements in management.  I have

pressed this cause myself, directly with the Commissioners

concerned.  We will continue to do so.





<p>

Finally, and of particular relevance to this audience, we are

developing closer links with the private sector.  Many of my

senior officials attended a seminar at Chevening earlier this

month with key members of the private sector.  We set out to

consider how to extract the full benefits from ODA's

relationship with the private sector, pass on best practice, and

learn from each other's huge range of experience.  We sought in

particular to get the message across to business about what we

are doing, and the benefits to both business and ODA from closer

co-operation.

<p>

Where do we go from here/Listening to you I see today as an

important part of a wider process of increasing contacts between

government and the private sector on development issues.





<p>

Where then do we go from here?  Let me put forward some specific

ideas.





<p>

We want to look more systematically at how Government - through

the aid programme and through our international policies - can

help facilitate private sector investment in poorer countries. 

To achieve this, we want to learn from you.  What are the

barriers which you see to this process, and what do you believe

we can do to help overcome these?





<p>

We want to develop dialogue in particular areas where we can

co-operate more closely, and where you have particular

expertise.  Examples of this are privatisation and financial

restructuring.  I believe that ODA can help provide a link in

these areas to other governments.

<p>

I want to carry forward the recent meeting in the City which

explored the growing opportunities for investment in private

finance institutions.





<p>

We will ensure that our programme managers consult business in

the preparation of country and sector strategies and research

programmes; and that we look for opportunities for cooperation. 

Many British companies already run developmental projects as

part of their overseas investments to improve local education,

health and in other areas.  We are ready to share our experience

and expertise in such cases.





<p>

We will look at how to make more information available in

electronic form, as part of a new Business Information Strategy.





<p>

We will develop short term staff attachments and exchanges with

the private sector, both to work on particular projects, and to

learn from each other's experience.





<p>

Conclusion<br>







I believe that these ideas will help to provide a better basis

for us to work in partnership on what I have described as a

wider development agenda.





<p>

This is an agenda which stretches far wider than development

assistance.  It encompasses wider government policies, and the

private sector.  It is an agenda which the UK is active in

promoting, and it is an agenda to which ODA is responding by

developing its own role, in ways which I have sought to

describe.  It is an agenda which is producing success stories -

though there is far to go.





<p>

These are themes which strike a particular personal chord.  I

have always believed that the roles of the private sector and

government are complementary.  Britain has a major interest in

promoting the growth and prosperity of potential trading

partners in the developing world.





<p>

I am delighted to have had the opportunity of speaking to you

today on these themes.  Thank you.



<p>

<hr>

</body>

</html>



