<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>NEWS: Cuba cracks down on independent journalists</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="ffffff" text="#000000" link="#9c181c" vlink="#9c181c"><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../info.html">Index on Censorship  </a></i><hr><h2>Cuba cracks down on independent journalists</h2>Cuban police appear to be stepping up their campaign of harassment against the countrys few independent journalists. Over the past weeks, several reporters belonging to the unofficial Independent Cuban Press Bureau (BPIC) have been arrested or threatened by state security officials.<p>On 19 January Luis Solar Hernandez, BPICs religious affairs correspondent, was detained in the town of Ciego de Avila while waitingto catch a train to Havana. He was held for a day and then released, but his book of contacts and other personal effects were confiscated.<p>The same day security officers also visited Roxana Valdivia, a BPIC reporter based in Ciego de Avila, and summoned her to appear at state security headquarters. She was warned for breaching an order imposed on her inOctober 1995 not to receive dissidents in her house. Hernandez had been visiting Valdivia prior to his arrest.<p>Juan Antonio Sanchez, a reporter for another independent agency, Cubapress, was also arrested by state security police in Havana on 14 January, while visiting the home of poet Raul Rivero. Rivero himself was detained at the same time.<p>A handful of small independent news agencies have set up in Cuba over the past few months, marking the first attempts at creating independent media there since the 1959 revolution which brought Fidel Castro to power. They operate in defiance of government restrictions on the press, accordingto which all media are owned by the state and all journalists must belongto the official journalists' union. The only outlet BPIC, Cubapress and Havana Press have for their reports is with foreign news agencies and media, mainly in Miami.<p>Since the release from prison of BPIC's president, Yndamiro Restano, in June last year, the climate for independent journalism has improved slightly. Police harassment and threats are common, but the full weightof legal sanction, for offences such as clandestine printing or subversion, has not lately been brought to bear against reporters working outside the official system.<p>However, the latest wave of harassment - which began with the brief arrest of Restano's parents on 10 January - has caused some concern for Restano's own safety among his colleagues. He is currently travelling abroad, and there are doubts as to whether he will be permitted to return home and continue working.<hr></BODY></HTML>
