<html>
<head>
<title>PRESS RELEASE - RESTRICTIONS ON WOMEN LEAD TO WITHDRAWAL FROM WESTERN AFGHANISTAN</title>
</head>
<body>

<br clear=right>
<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="scf_info.html"> Save the Children Fund</i></a>
<hr>
<p>




<h3>RESTRICTIONS ON WOMEN LEAD TO WITHDRAWAL FROM WESTERN AFGHANISTAN</h3>

Thursday 7 March 1996 <p>


Save the Children (UK) has suspended its operations in western Afghanistan. The
decision follows the implementation of new regulations by the Taliban authorities
in Herat over recent months, which have placed severe restrictions on the
employment of women and the access of women and girls to basic services.<p>


In the light of these developments, Save the Children issued a statement today
calling on humanitarian aid organisations working in Afghanistan to: <p>
<ul>

<li>suspend education programmes in areas where girls and women are denied
access to education (following the example set by UNICEF); <p>


<li> consider suspending non-emergency programmes in sectors where women's employment is prohibited by regional authorities; <p>


<li>continue to seek practical ways in which women and children can be
involved in programmes designed to help them, which are acceptable to
Afghan culture and traditions.</ul><p>


Save the Children's decision to suspend operations in the region has been taken
reluctantly and primarily on practical grounds. During the six months since Taliban
forces took over Herat, Save the Children has found it increasingly difficult to
pursue its work in the areas of education and health. <p>


All girl's schools in the Herat region have been closed indefinitely. The denial of
access to education for girls and young women, and the impact even on boy's


schools of the loss of women teachers, have cast doubt on the sustainability of any
further support to education.<p>


Since January, women have been prevented from working (outside the home and
health sector). These new restrictions on women's employment remove any
opportunity for Save the Children to consult and communicate directly with Afghan
women, who are the main carers of children. This in turn makes it impossible for
the agency to measure the long term effectiveness of its work. 

<p>




<h4>NOTES FOR EDITORS:</h4>
1. This initiative is backed by Save the Children (US) and Radda Barnen (Sweden),
who are both International Save the Children Alliance members currently based in
Afghanistan. The Alliance is an association of Save the Children organisations
throughout the world.<br>
2. Save the Children (UK) has been working in Afghanistan and with Afghan
regugees in Pakistan since the mid 1970s. <p>



<h4>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</h4>
Save the Children press office	0171 703 5400<br>
Out of office hours	0831 650409<p>


