<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> BURUNDI</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/burundi.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=428 height=272 alt="Map of
Burundi"></p>
<hr>
<b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	6.5 million

<p>Population growth rate	2.9% a year

<p>Under-5 child mortality rate	178
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with	54%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	33%
<br clear=left>

<hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID began work in Burundi in 1976 with a range of country-wide development initiatives. In
1988,
the focus shifted to the eastern communities of Ruyigi and Bweru in Ruyigi province, which today
remains
the main ACTIONAID programme area.

<p>ACTIONAID's long-term development work was suspended in 1993 following the coup d'tat in October
of that year. An emergency relief programme was instigated to help the thousands of displaced within
the country.

<p>In 1996 the threat of significant outbreaks of violent conflict continues to hang over Burundi.
However, the ACTIONAID programme in Ruyigi province has recommenced, helping communities in the
area return to their homes and organise so that they can plan which development projects to
implement. The priorities for ACTIONAID's work with the villagers will be seed credit schemes,
protection of
water sources, developing income generation and training of community health workers.   
<hr>
<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work in Burundi:</h3>

<p><ul><li>the core of ACTIONAID's work before the coup was an adult literacy programme, helping 500
learners each year develop the skills and confidence to make more informed choices about their lives.

<p><li>the October 1993 coup left 150,000 people dead, 700,000 displaced and caused an estimated $79
million of damage. The communities ACTIONAID was working with experienced some of the most serious
fighting and fled the province. ACTIONAID worked with local groups through 1994 to distribute seeds,
tools
and shelter materials to 20,000 families. By May, 98 per cent of the families had been able to plant
the
seed and were looking forward to a good harvest. 
</ul>

</font>

