<title> VIETNAM</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a
href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center><font face="arial, helvetica">VIETNAM</font></h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/vietnam.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=414 height=267 alt="Map of Vietnam">
</p>
<hr>
<font face="arial, helvetica">
<p><b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	75.7 million

<p>Population growth rate	2.1% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	48
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	21%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	92%
<br clear=left>
<p><hr>
<h3><font face="arial, helvetica">Programme Overview</font></h3>

<p>ACTIONAID started working in Vietnam in 1991. Programmes in two areas of the country are now
helping more than 20,000 people in the poorest communities who have not benefited from the move
towards a market economy. 

<p>The emphasis is on helping to improve agricultural production and establishing savings and credit
schemes so families have access to cash without being subject to the exorbitant rates of interest
charged by informal money lenders. ACTIONAID works  in partnership with government and local
organisations so that the skills and expertise they develop stays with the communities for the
long-term future.

<h3><font face="arial, helvetica">Examples of ACTIONAID's work in Vietnam</font></h3>
<b>ACTIONAID has:</b>

<p><ul><li>been working with more than 3,000 households in Son La Province to help improve land
productivity. By talking to a wide cross-section of people, including villagers and state officials,
ACTIONAID  passes on new farming techniques and skills. Demonstration plots were established to show
how to protect poor upland terrain from erosion by planting hedges. Training, the key to long-term
success, is carried out through a network of government staff and volunteers.

<p><li>worked with The Women's Union to set up savings and credit schemes to give women more control
over the small resources they do have. By saving small amounts each week, members of the scheme can
then take loans to buy much needed tools, seeds or food during the hungry period. 
</ul>
</font>
<p><hr>
