<html><head><title>Unicef  - Children First: Issue 32, Supporters News</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="../unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h2 align=center>Supporters News</h2><h3 align=right>Children spread message of peace and goodwill</h3>IN 1922, Sir Ifan ab Owen Edwards founded &quot;The Urdd&quot; to provide a youth service for the children of Wales. His aim was to foster relations with other countries, and over the past 75 years the Urdd has supported humanitarian projects from Bosnia to Brazil. Each year a Message of peace and goodwill is sent round the world. Over 90 countries receive the message, and many reply in support. The Urdd has been working very closely with UNICEF in Wales, and last year they raised over £5,000 through an International Children's Concert at the Urdd Eisteddfod and a 5-day 'singathon'.<p>To celebrate UNICEF's 50th anniversary, this year's message focuses on children and UNICEF's work: &quot;We the children of Wales call upon the children of the world to join us in celebrating the fiftieth anniversary by supporting the aims of UNICEF and by demanding justice for all the children of the world.&quot;<p><hr width=71%><p><h3 align=right>Check out for children</h3><img align=right hspace=10 vspace=10 border=1 src="pg6a.jpg"><br>THE Check out for Children partnership between UNICEF and ITT Sheraton is on target to raise half a million pounds in its first year. The initiative, launched in Europe at the end of 1995, will be rolled out to the Asia Pacific division in the next few months. The scheme adds an optional $1 or its equivalent (£1 in the UK) to the bill of each guest staying at the ITT Sheraton hotels in Europe and Israel. The initiative has been warmly received by ITT Sheraton's guests and in the first six months raised nearly £250,000. Robert Cotter, President of ITT Sheraton Europe division, said: &quot;Each of our European hotels has welcomed the initiative and our guests, who are the generous supporters in this project, have applauded the scheme and have been more than happy to give. We look forward to rolling the programme out in other divisions of ITT Sheraton&quot;. As a mark of their confidence in the success of Check Out for Children, ITT Sheraton has pledged and guaranteed the anticipated funds for the rest of the year - a grand total of £500,000.<p><small>Mr Robert Cotter (left), President ITT Sheraton Europe Division, presents a cheque for £500,000 to HRH The Duchess of Kent, Patron of the UK Committee for UNICEF and Richard Reid of UNICEF, at an event at the Park Lane Hotel, London.&copy;Always Photography</small><p><hr width=71%><p><h3 align=right>Sunflower festival in Hampstead</h3><img align=right hspace=10 vspace=10 border=1 src="pg6b.jpg">THE Hampstead Chapter of the Sokkai Ghakki Buddhist Group, who are supporting UNICEF nationally throughout 1996, organised a Sunflower Festival at the Kings College Campus in Hampstead. The rooms were festooned with sunflowers of every shape, hanging from the lights and decorating the walls, as well as real sunflowers on every table. Children's faces were painted with sunflowers and even one bald head was adorned with a painting of the flower! The event, with the help of a very lavish raffle with a large number of excellent prizes, raised £2,000.<p><small>Sokkai Ghakki Buddhist (SGI) groups around the country are celebrating UNICEF's 50th anniversary. The first Scottish event was a car boot sale in Barrhead, which raised £2,000 - thanks to the crowd-pulling skills of these SGI buskers!</small><p><hr width=71%><p><h3 align=right>Summer lunch in Suffolk</h3>ONE of Suffolk's premier restaurants - Le Talbouth in Stratford St Mary - held a luncheon for over 150 guests to celebrate UNICEF's 50th anniversary in July. Organised by the Ipswich and District Branch, the guests were entertained by a string quartet before being served with a mouthwatering barbeque in a silk-lined marquee. As well as being a memorable day for the guests, the event also raised around £4,000 for UNICEF.<p><hr width=71%><p><h3 align=right>Running laps for UNICEF</h3><img align=right hspace=10 vspace=10 border=1 src="pg7.jpg"><br>Children from the Prins Willem-Alexander Dutch School in Woking got sponsorship from parents, family and friends to run laps of their school playing fields during their PE classes. They raised an impressive £2,000 for UNICEF.<br clear=all><p><hr width=71%><p><h3 align=right>UNICEF Visa card tops the bill</h3>THE new UNICEF Visa card came out top in a survey of charity affinity cards published recently in the <i>Sunday Telegraph</i>. The survey showed that the UNICEF card is top of the bill for both the consumer and for UNICEF. <p><b>A good deal for you:</b> Our chart below, correct at the time of going to press, shows how the UNICEF Visa card stacks up against the standard rates of a selection of other cards - in terms of the Annual Percentage Rate (APR) and annual fee:<p><pre><b>Card Issuer	       APR	    Annual Fee</b>Beneficial Bank	          14.9% 	    None(UNICEF Visa Card)  (19.5% after 6 months)MBNA	                   18.9%	    NoneCo-operative Bank	   21.7%	    £12Barclaycard	           22.3%	    £10Midland Bank	           22.3%	    £12Royal Bank of Scotland	   23.2%	    £10</pre><b>And a good deal for UNICEF:</b> The following selection shows how the benefits of the card to UNICEF compare with those of other affinity cards:<p><pre><b>Charity	     initial donation	   Donation per	£100   Annual Card  issuer             from bank to charity      spent on card    fee	</b>UNICEF	              £5	             50p	        None	      Beneficial BankNational Trust	      £10	             5p per	        None	      Midland		                            transactionRSPB	              None	             25p	        None	      Co-opBritish Heart	      Non