<a name="top">

[Books on Information Technology]<br clear=left><br>

To speed things up, click on the partner's name to scroll straight to their publications.  You can find details on how to order books at the end of each partner's section<p>


<center>
<TABLE width=90% BORDER=4 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR>
<TH><a href="#intermediate">Intermediate Technology Development Group</A></TH>
<TH><a href="#voluntary">Voluntary Service Overseas</A> </TH>
</TR>
</TABLE></center></h1><p>

<a name="intermediate"><br>


[Intermediate Technology Development Group]<p>


<b><li>IT Studies in Indiginous Knowledge and Development</b><br>
<i>General editors: Dr David Brokensha, Dr L. Jan Slikkerveer and Dr D. Michael Warren</i><br> 
IT Publications is pleased to announce the launch of this significant series of books, which will highlight the contributions to local, national and international development made by indigenous knowledge systems -- and the tensions which ignoring that knowledge can create. The series will constitute an important and growing contribution to the tools available to both the development and the academic communities in understanding these processes. <p> 

<b><li>Island Technology: Technology for Development in the South Pacific</b><br>
<i>Edited by Tony Marjoram </i><br>
Pacific island countries have united internationally to contest the negative external impacts of Western technology - such as the disposal of poison gas and toxic waste at Johnston Atoll, the transportation of nuclear materials, nuclear testing at Mururoa, and the overwhelming prospect of global warming and a rising sea-level. They have been less attentive, however, regarding the significant yet often more subtle internal effects of technology transfer and dependence. These internal effects encompass the well-identified problems caused by unsustainable fishing, forestry and mining, and also effects rarely noticed by headline writers, namely the widely various costs --and benefits -- of the spread and use (through trade and aid) of new technology in the region. <p>

The contributors focus on the management of technology in the South Pacific and developing island countries and 'island' communities within larger developing countries. <p> 

The twenty-seven contributors to this book are experienced senior researchers, project managers, policy-makers and administrators who are closely involved in the provision of technology for development in the South Pacific. Their analyses and observations span the broad range of issues of concern, and focus on agriculture and forestry, aid and technology, aviation and shipping, banking, communications, development policy and planning, education and training, energy, the environment, fisheries and marine resources, food-processing, gender issues, health, housing, industry, mining, project management, technology choice and transfer, sanitation and water supply. <p> 

<b>Contributors:</b> Bill Aalbersberg, David F. Abbott, Lisiate 'A 'Akolo, Richard Burton, Elizabeth Cox, Tony Finch, Sue Fleming, Ben Higgins, Stephen Hill, Rodney C. Hills, Stuart Kingan, Ruth E. Lechte, R. Keith Leonard, Don Mansell, Tony Marjoram, Tevita H. Moengangongo, Helen Molnar, Philipp Muller, Susan Parkinson, Lukis Romaso, Suliana Siwatibau, Clive Stewart, Don Stewart, Tony Utanga, B. David Williams, Jim Wilkinson, Andrew Wright. <br>
<b>November 1994<br>
436pp.<br>
249 x 177mm. <br>
Paperback<br>
ISBN 1 85339 223 5</b><br><br><br>

<b><li>The MIBIS Manual</b><br>
<i>Anne Di Lauro and Ed Brandon</i><BR>
Preparing records in microcomputer-based bibliographic information systems<BR>
<b>£19.95<br>
1995<br>
Paperback<br>
364pp<br>
(IDRC). ISBN 0 88936 728 0</b><BR>
