<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - Demobilisation of Rwandan Child Soldiers</title><!!keys: UNICEF+Rwanda+children+child soldiers></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h3>Demobilisation of Rwandan Child Soldiers</h3><i>UNICEF is supporting the demobilising education and skill-training of up to 3,500 children, aged 10-17 years, attached to military units, and their re-integration into community and foster family life.</i><hr>Approximately 2,000 children, between the ages of 10-17, were part of the Rwandan Patriotic Army and are now attached to military units in Rwanda.  It is estimated that there are some 1,500 children living with the exiled army in Bukavu and Goma (Zaire).<p>Most of these "child soldiers" have been separated children often joined or were absorbed by mobile combatant units that were passing through their areas during the war.  Others joined because they were assured of food or employment, or motivated by a desire for revenge or prestige.<p>Many of these children have witnessed killings and other acts of extreme violence.<p>The objectives of this UNICEF programme - Demobilisation of Child Soldiers - is to separate these children from their current military environment and gradually reintegrate them into schools and community life in Rwanda.<hr>©Copyright: UNICEF, May 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
