<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - CHILD TRAUMA RECOVERY</title><!!keys:children+UNICEF+trauma+psychology ></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><br><hr><h3>UNICEF'S ROLE IN CHILD TRAUMA RECOVERY</h3>Rwanda is rightly called a nation of traumatized children.  Children have been exposed to atrocities to a degree never been seen before.<p><ul><li>300,000 children were killed, often in brutal ways.  In some of the largest mass graves up to 45% of the victims were children;<li>Over 95,000 children, 40,000 in Rwanda, lost their parents or were seperated from them.<li>42% lost both parents.<li>56% witnessed a family memeber being killed.<li>75% wittnessed other people being killed.<li>47% saw children killing other children.<li>64% witnessed massacres.<li>20% witnessed rape and sexual assualt.<li>Many children are able to name more than 20 persons close to them who are dead.</ul>In August 1994, UNICEF's child psychologists visited the sites of massacres and talked to the children in the area, producing the first assessments of the traumatic effects of war on children.<p>The Trauma Recovery Programme (TRP), within the Children in Especially Difficult Circumstances Section (CEDC), was established to address the immediate and long-term psychosocial needs of war-affected children and their families.  As part of the Programme UNICEF will train 12 Trauma Advisors, one for each prefecture, in trauma alleviation methods.  These advisors will then pass on their knowledge to teachers, social workers, health care providors and religious leaders.  So far, The TRP has trained a total of 1,843 social agents in basic issues of trauma identification was broadcasted and over 1,500 Trauma First Aid messages to various social agents throughout Rwanda have been disseminated.<p>The TRP has conducted and analyzed data from a pilot survey completed in December 1994 on levels of trauma ammong children in centres and family settings.  Amongst the findings was the fact that 62% of those interviewed felt they had no future and did not expect to live long.<p>A set of "Guidelines for Psychological Trauma Healing" was produced by the Ministry of Social Rehabilitation in collaboration with UNICEF and seven NGO's.  The Government of Rwanda has acknowledged the importance of psychosocial intervension with traumatized children as one of its priorities.<p>A national Child Recovery Centre will be opened in April 1995 in Kigali to become a focal point for training, documentation and research, with an outpatient clinic for severely traumatized children/families.<hr>©Copyright: UNICEF 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
