<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - HOPE FOR UNACCOMPANIED CHILDREN</title><!!keys: UNICEF+children+Rwanda></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><br><hr><h3>HOPE FOR UNACCOMPANIED CHILDREN</h3><i>Last August, UNICEF was mostly involved in collecting children separated from their families in Rwanda or along the refugee's paths in Zaire, Tanzania and Burundi.  Today, UNICEF is witnessing numerous family reunifications.  The encouraging results of the tracing and family reunification programme show that UNICEF and its partners are on a very promising path.</i><hr>Up to 8,980 have already been reunified with their families: 5,043 in Rwanda; 3,085 in Goma, 540 in Bukavu, 300 in Ngara and 12 in Uvira.  UNICEF, together with ICRC, has registered and photographed 12,600 children in Goma.  The photographing of unaccompanied children - an important aid in the re-unification process - has begun inside Rwanda, and is continuing in other refugee locations.<p>UNICEF Goma, in cooperation with its NGO partners, is assisting foster families as part of a larger of de-institutionalization and prevention of child abandonment.<p>While tracing continues, children receive temporary care in centres and foster families.<p>To date, about 26,070 children inside and outside Rwanda are living in 117 centres.  In Rwanda, 12% of the children living in camps are under 5 years old - About 50% of the centres are run by Rwandese.<p>It is estimated that 67,410 (limited statistics/Caritas/FHI/UNICEF) children have already been taken in by foster families inside and outside the country.<hr>©Copyright: UNICEF May 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
