<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - CHILDREN IN PRISON</title><!!keys:UNICEF+children+Rwanda ></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h3>CHILDREN IN PRISON</h3><i>UNICEF has finalized an agreement with the Ministry of Justice for the protection of juvenile prisoners.  UNICEF will ensure, in cooperation with the Office of the High Commisioner for Human Rights (CHR), the respect of the rights of all imprisoned children and women with particular attention given to children accused of genocide.</i><hr>As of mid-April, 1,019 minors were detained in some of the thirteen major prisons and over 145 detention centres in Rwanda.  Children as young as 5 years of age have been accused of criminal  acts.  Other young children have not been accused themselves, but are accompanying a charged parent.<p>UNICEF, ICRC, and HCHR staff make regular visits to the Kigali prison, and have visited other prisons and detension centres around the country.<p>UNICEF will provide support costs for 10 Rwandan lawyers over the next year, who will focus on children' cases.<p>With the support of the HCHR, all minors and women in Kigali prison have been interviewed and photographed and their dossiers are being compiled.<p>UNICEF has delivered food stuff, mattrasses and children's clothes to the children in prison.<p>A juvenile detention centre is presently being refurbished at Gitagata, 42km South of Kigali.  It is expected that the first group of 200 children under 15 years of age will be transfered there by the end of April.<hr>©Copyright: UNICEF. May1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html> 
