<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - AIDS IN RWANDA</title><!!keys: UNICEF+children+Rwanda></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h3>AIDS IN RWANDA</h3><i>Before the war of April 1994, Rwanda suffered one of the highest incidence of AIDS in Africa.  The number of people infected by the AIDS virus has risen considerably in the aftermath of the war.  the high incidence of rape, promiscuity in refugee and displaced camps, and the loss of social values and inhibitions explains this rising tendancy.  For 1995, UNICEF will support a programme of AIDS prevention and awareness for children and adolescents.</i><hr>The prevalence of AIDS virus cases in Rwanda before the war - 91 cases per 100,000 persons was one of the highest in the world.<p>The incidence of AIDS has increased dramatically in urban areas: 30% of the total number of pregnant women have tested HIV-positive during neo-natal examinations.<p>Generally speaking, 15 to 19 year-old girls in urban areas are more affected than boys of the same age.  The highest incidence of AIDS victims is among non-educated urban dwellers.<p>The number of orphans who have lost their parents due to AIDS - 13,000 in Kigali alone - is worrying.  UNICEF will support family-like homes headed by a primary care-giver (mother) responsible for at least 10 AIDS orphans.  These homes will be run by NGOs.<p>In comparison to the atrocities of war, the risk of AIDS appears of secondary concern to the population as a whole.<p>In the AIDS awareness programme, budgeted at nearly 1 million USD for 1995, UNICEF will train a cadre of 5,000 adolescents aged 15-19 according to the 'child-to-child' teaching method.  In schools, a special programme, "survival reflex", will be initiated to teach basic preventive approaches for younger children from 5 to 14 years of age.<hr>©Copyright:  UNICEF. May 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
