<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - HEALTH</title><!!keys:UNICEF+children+health+Rwanda ></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><br><hr><h3>HEALTH: ONE OF UNICEF'S PRIORITIES FOR 1995</h3><i>Almost a year after the upheavals which cost the lives of a million people, the health situation is still extremely precarious.  The fragility of the country continues to increase the vulnerability of the population, particularly women and children.  In 1995, UNICEF and its many counterparts are committed to rehabilitating the health system.</i><hr>The challenge to UNICEF and its partners is not to create, but to re-establish, a primary health care system which, before April 1994, was well developed.<p>The task is not simple: most centres and dispensaries have been looted if not destroyed and there is a shortage of trained medical professionals.  Many medical doctors and nurses have been killed, disappeared or have fled to neighbouring countries, leaving only 20% of the prewar health centre positions filled by qualified staff.<p>UNICEF has spent nearly 14 million dollars in the emergency phase of 1994 to meet immediate needs.<p>UNICEF is rehabilitating some 100 health centres throughout the country.  The cold chain store in Kigali has been installed and is distributing vaccines and other medical equipment throughout the country.  The central pharmacy in Kigali has been repaired and drug distribution began in September 1994.<p>Malaria, diarrhoea and respiratory diseases represent the principle causes of mortality.  The overcrowded conditions in the camps and the lack of sanitation have considerably increased the morbidity rates.  Epidemic diseases like Cholera, bacillary dysentary and meningitis have caused the deaths of thousands of children.<p>In 1995, UNICEF is undertaking a sensitization and prevention campaign by disseminating health messages to combat illnesses, such as malaria, water borne and diarrhoeal diseases.<p>UNICEF has increased the immunization rate to 70%.<p>UNICEF supports the Ministry of Health in its efforts to increase the quality of health services.  This is being done by intensive training in EPI, control of diarrhoeal diseases (CDD), as well as acute respiratory infections (ARI).  UNICEF is also training health workers in Mother and Child Health Care (MCH) and Health Information Systems.<hr>©Copyright:  UNICEF. May 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
</DOC>
