<html><head><title>CHILDREN FIRST - WATER AND SANITATION</title><!!keys:UNICEF+children+Rwanda+refugees ></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h3>WATER AND SANITATION - FOR A BETTER QUALITY OF LIFE</h3><i>The much publicised health crisis in Goma underscored the need for preparedness and a rapid response in the water and sanitation sector.</i><hr>The uncertain times that prevailed during Rwanda's war resulted in massacres, shooting, vandalism, looting and the abandonment of posts by many employees.  This brought about a total disruption of most public services, including electricity and water supply.<p>UNICEF was assigned as the lead agency responsible for water and sanitation in the Rwanda Emergency Operation.  Its intervensions in this sector, which cost some $11.4 million in 1994, have had a significant impact on the quality of life and hygiene of the population in local communities and refugee camps.  UNICEF has contrinuted to the reduction of water and hygiene-related diseases, prevented further epidemics, and promoted stability and normal life which has attracted some refugees to return to their home communes.<p>Since August 1994, 95% of the pre-war urban water supply facilities and 70% of the pre-war rural water supply infrastructure have been substantially restored.  In addition, sanitation coverage to the population has now reached about 80% of the pre-war level; 85% of the population of Kigali now has access to potable water every day or on alternate days.  UNICEF has supplied chemicals to 13 water treatment plants nationwide and diesel for 16 generators in the water pumping stations in Kigali.  UNICEF has also spearheaded the training of local water personnel and the promotion of hygiene education.<p>UNICEF now considers the restoration of the National Electricity Grid as its number one priority.  The enormous costs associated with the operation and maintenance of diesel generating units for treatment plants and pumping installations, cannot be sustained and should be eliminated as soon as possible.  To date, 7 out of 11 towns have been reconnected to the national grid.  At the beginning of March 1995, UNICEF procured US$ 500,000 of materials for Electrogaz for the further rehabilitation of the national electricity grid.<p>UNICEF provides water and sanitation services to refugee camps, internally displaced persons camps, and unaccompanied children centres in Goma and Bukavu and dug 30 deep borehole wells in Ngara, Tanzania, for some 300,000 refugees.  UNICEF has installed 5 mobile water treatment plants, rehabilitated 17 gravity flow pipelines, protected four springs, installed 160 Oxfam tanks and water bladders, reconstructed some 7km of water pipelines.  Eleven UNICEF water tankers distribute an estimated 200 cubic metres of water per day in various parts of the country.<p>Throughour 1995, ina ddition to completing the full rehabilitation of pre-war facilities, UNICEF's main objectives in the water and sanitation sector will be:<ul><li>Capacity building for policy development at the central government level.<p><li>Strengthening capacity for service delivery.<p><li>Community capacity building for water, sanitation and hygiene.</ul>A major constraint to the achievement of the above objectives is the absence of adequately trained personnel at government and community levels.  Consequently, there is a need  to train new staff to replace lost skilled manpower.  This will take time and may slow down activities.  The government's limited vehicle fleet, and the lack of adequate office equipment should help to alleviate these problems to some degree.<p>UNICEF's Rwanda appeal for its 1995 Water and Sanitation programme is $13.1 Million.  This includes provisions for cross border intervensions in refugee camps in Goma, Bukavu and Ngara.<hr>©Copyright:  UNICEF. May 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif">UNICEF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
