<head>
<title>'Power to the people' land reformers defy critics</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="panos_info.html"> Panos </i> </a>
<hr>




<h2>'Power to the people' land-reformers defy critics</h2>

<h3>By Eddie Koch,  environmental reporter with the Johannesburg Weekly Mail</h3>

Johannesburg: South Africa is pushing ahead with an ambitious land-reform programme despite attacks from right and left.<p>

White commercial farmers say new black settlers will spoil the soil through improper farming - causing food shortages. Other opponents of the scheme say the poorest people will not benefit, and that much of the state cash being invested in it will end up in the pockets of local elites.
Minister of Land Affairs Derek Hanekom is determined to prove the critics wrong.<p>

Current land ownership, strongly favouring the minority whites, is a legacy of the apartheid era. Little more than 10 per cent of the population  owns 87 per cent of the best agricultural land, while much of the black majority lives on poorer terrain in overcrowded reserves set aside under the old system of segregation.<p>

Conflict over land, say University of Cape Town academics Mamphela Ramphele and Francis Wilson in a recent book, Uprooting Poverty,  "runs like a seismic fault through the body of South Africa...(and) threatens to engulf the country in the flames of civil war".<p>

Hanekom plans to change all this. His programme, launched earlier in 1995, is designed to redistribute about 30 per cent of arable land over five years.<p>

The reform plans consist of separate restitution and redistribution schemes.<p>

A Land Claims Court has been established, with the power to restore title to people - or their descendants - who were forcibly removed from their property under apartheid. In all, 3.5 million were evicted.  Compensation will be paid to current owners.<p>

The redistribution scheme will allow rural people to buy out white farmers who are willing to sell. No land will be expropriated. Unused tracts of state land will also be offered for sale at subsidised prices.
The emphasis is on empowering local people to plan and manage their own development, says Hanekom, a land specialist.<p>

"Our approach to land distribution ... is a demand-led or needs-driven process, rather than one imposed from above by the state," he says.
"The beneficiary groups will identify their own needs, develop their own plans and make decisions on the allocation of funds within the department's policy framework... It is important not to repeat the iniquities of the past."<p>

His ministry has launched nine pilot schemes,  one in each of the country's new provinces.<p>

A total of  315.81 million rand (about $88 million) has been allocated for the entire process. Each pilot scheme will receive 35 million rand ($9.7 million).  More than 50 per cent of the grant will provide essential social needs, such as shelter, sanitation, water supply, schools and electricity.
A national task force of government and non-government organisations has been set up to implement the plan. Beneath this are provincial-level steering committees,  which will employ pilot managers and establish district land reform forums.<p>


These elected bodies will be given the right and the money to appoint professional advisers to assist in devising a development plan for the newly-acquired land. The forums will consider economic potential and propose uses for various plots that must be ecologically sustainable.
Conservative commercial farmers say the new settlers will degrade the land by placing too heavy a burden of animals and people on it and by using outdated farming methods. Moving inexperienced farmers on to productive land, they say, will begin to undermine the country's breadbasket of mainly white-owned farming estates - increasing the risk of famine.<p>

Meanwhile,  a liberal farmer, Graham Macintosh, from KwaZulu-Natal province, says: "All Hanekom is doing is spreading rural poverty from where it exists to the new land that is being made available for settlement."<p>

A black elite comprised of teachers, taxi owners and local chiefs had already taken command of the rural forums, he said. "These people will always find creative ways of ensuring that the lion's share of the resources now being pumped into the area goes into their pockets. If you are serious about the poorest of the poor, then much more attention should be paid to the conditions of farm workers. It is the efficient commercial farmers who should be promoted and then encouraged to treat their workforces in a decent way."<p>

Ironically,  this view is supported by the research findings of John Sender, a left-wing economist from the University of Witwatersrand, who predicts that the poorest will not benefit.  His work indicates that five to six million rural people are completely dependent for their survival on wages obtained from labouring on commercial farms.<p>

"The issues of poverty and gender are not taken seriously (under the land-reform plans)," he says. "Rather, the vision is of a package of state subsidies to a class of male black capitalists."<p>

But Hanekom defends his programme, saying: "We want people to make sound decisions based on access to a resource that has to be used beneficially and sustainably."<p>

Concerns about possible degradation of land re-allocated to black settlers can be dealt with in the local forums.  Plans submitted by these to provincial reform committees will be carefully scrutinised for their sustainability, says Sue Lund, manager of the redistribution programme. "Their plans will have to meet strict standards and must be environmentally sustainable."<p>

She admits the scheme may be over-ambitious. "How this will work in practice, we will have to wait and see."<p>

But rural people have been emboldened by the plans and are confident they will work. Mpase Ndladla,  a black farmer from KwaZulu-Natal, says: "Our message to the white farmers who are saying we will destroy our new land is that, frankly, we thought of taking it back by force.
"But we didn't want bloodshed and war. Now that we are able to sit down and discuss things like brothers, we can be given training and advice from the neighbouring white farmers about how to use this land.
"We should unite," he adds. "We can make it work."<p>







<p>

