<html><head><title>Unicef  - Children First: Issue 32, The facts of life - and death</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="../unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h2 align=center>The facts of life - and death</h2><img align=left width=185 height=123 hspace=10 vspace=10 border=1 src="pg16.jpg"><br><font size=4><i>Imagine four of your friends or family are pregnant. Then imagine knowing that, statistically, one of them is going to die or be disabled because of it. For women in the developing world this horrifying statistic is the reality of pregnancy and childbirth.</i></font><p><small>A pregnant woman is examined at a mother and child health clinic in Banjul, Gambia. Reducing maternal deaths will depend on the early identification of the 15 per cent of pregnancies that require modern obstetric care.&copy;UNICEF/C54-20/Carolyn Watson</small><br><center><hr width=71%><br><font size=4 color=blue>&quot;You don't needfive star hospitals&quot;</font><p><hr width=71%></center><p>This story of the unimaginable suffering of pregnancy is the centrepiece of the 1996 edition of UNICEF's &quot;<i>The Progress of Nations</i>&quot;. Revised calculations this year show that as many as 585,000 women die each year from causes related to pregnancy and childbirth - 20 per cent more than was previously thought. For the most part, these are the deaths of healthy women in the prime of their lives, vital caregivers on whom young and old depend. The 585,000 women who die every year leave behind at least a million motherless children, whose own chances of survival may be severely affected.<p>And for every woman who dies, another 30 suffer unspeakable and often untreated injuries. Perhaps the worst of these is fistula, which leaves as many as 80,000 women a year chronically incontinent. Cumulatively, between 500,000 and one million women are living with the miseries of fistula; unknown numbers commit suicide as a result.<p>If the toll of maternal death and injury is to be reduced, the first task is to break the silence that surrounds the issue. Families and communities must be taught to recognise the danger signs. And governments and aid programmes must give priority to ensuring that local hospitals and clinics can provide modern obstetric care to the 15 per cent of pregnant women at serious risk. &quot;You don't need five-star hospitals,&quot; says Deborah Maine, a leading authority in maternal health, &quot;there are thousands of hospitals that, with minimal upgrading, could provide adequate obstetric care. But many are unusable for a lack of $100 (around £60) worth of maintenance.&quot;<p>The Progress of Nations also casts a new light on one of the oldest problems of the developing world - child malnutrition. Africa is often thought to be the home of the malnourished child. But in fact, both the number and percentage of children affected by malnutrition is far higher in South Asia. Half of all the world's malnourished children are to be found in just three countries - Bangladesh, India and Pakistan - where malnutrition rates are typically twice as high as in the poor countries of sub-Saharan Africa. The difference cannot be ascribed to any significant variation in income levels or availability of food. Instead, UNICEF points the finger at far higher rates of low birth weight in South Asia, far greater population density, poorer hygiene, less satisfactory patterns of breastfeeding and weaning - and the generally lower status of Asian women.<p>Dr Monica Sharma, UNICEF's Senior Advisor in Child Health, is the author of a hard-hitting chapter in the report which documents the five preventable diseases - measles, diarrhoea, malaria, pneumonia, and malnutrition - which kill as many as eight million children a year in developing countries, while children in richer countries are routinely treated and thus spared. For Dr Sharma it is &quot;as though a cure for heart disease or cancer or AIDS had been discovered but not used.&quot;<p><i>Copies of the report, which includes statistical tables ranking every country in the world according to its progress for women and children, are available from: UNICEF, Unit 1, Rignals Lane, Galleywood, Chelmsford, CM2 8TU. The report is priced £5.95. Please quote stock code 16026.You can also visit the </i>Progress of Nations<i> web site at: http://www/unicef.org</i><p> <hr>©Copyright: UNICEF 1996<hr><center><SMALL><b> [<ahref="../index.html" target="_parent"> UNICEF Home Page</A>] [<ahref="http://www.childrenfirst.org">Support UNICEF</A>] [<ahref="../news.html">News</A>] [<ahref="../events.html">Events</A>] [<ahref="../publications.html">Publications</A>] [<ahref="../education.html">Education</A>]</font></SMALL></b></center></body></html>
