<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - Yitzak Rabin killed by Jewish extremist</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>

<center><h2>Israeli prime minister Rabin <br>assassinated at peace rally</h2></center>
<p>

The Nobel Peace Prize-winning Israeli prime minister, Yitzak Rabin, was gunned down and killed by an extremist Jewish assassin in Tel Aviv after a peace rally on Saturday night.  <p>

As the country mourned the loss of a leader who has done more than any other to make peace with Israel's Arab neighbours, world leaders arrived for the state funeral.  Up to a million people - a fifth of the entire Israeli population - filed past the coffin as it lay in state last night.<p>

Rabin's assassin, the 25-year old law student Yigal Amir, was arrested at the scene.  He claimed that Jewish law permitted the killing of a "traitor" who was giving away parts of Israel.  "I acted alone on God's orders and I have no regrets," he said.<p>

Amir claimed that he also intended to kill the Israeli foreign minister Shimon Peres, but was foiled when Peres and Rabin left the peace rally separately.  Peres has now taken over as acting Prime Minister and is expected to become leader of the Labour coalition in the Israeli parliament.<p>

The killing has blown open the widening divide between rightwingers who oppose reconciliation with the Palestinians and more moderate Jews.  While the Likud opposition has declared that it will not oppose the reconstitution of the Labour government, many extremists have expressed delight over the death of a 'traitor'.<p>

Jewish settlers on the West Bank, who are at the forefront of those opposing the Arab Israeli peace process, said they feared a backlash against them once the funeral was over.<p>

As world leaders flew in to pay their respects to Mr Rabin, one man was notable for his absence - the prime minister's fellow Nobel peace laureate and PLO Chairman, Yasser Arafat.   Arafat was absent ostensibly for security reasons, and also because his presence was felt to be inappropriate in order not to further provoke Israeli hardliners.<p>

Perhaps the most fitting memory to Yitzak Rabin, the military man turned peacemaker, were his own words - spoken at the peace rally where he was killed:<p>

"This government which I have the privilege to head with my friend Shimon Peres, decided to give peace a chance; a peace which will solve most of the state of Israel's problems.<p>

"I was a military man for 27 years.  I waged war as long as there was no chance of peace.  I believe there is now a chance for peace, a great chance, and we must take advantage of it."<p>

                                                                                                            


