</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Unicef  - Children First: Issue 32, Growing up urban</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000"><img src="../unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><h2 align=center>Growing up urban</h2>By the year 2025, six out of every ten children in the developing world will live in a city. More than half of them will be poor. Urban issues, and the strategies to deal with them, have been high on the international agenda this summer with governments meeting in Istanbul in June for the UN Conference on Human Settlements - &quot;Habitat II&quot;.<p>UNTIL the 1970s it was assumed that poverty in its most grinding form was to be found in the countryside, and that development agencies should focus their attentions on rural areas. Today, at least 300 million children in the cities of the developing world live in absolute poverty and in both industrialised and developing countries, poor children are crammed into overcrowded, unsafe and pol- luted areas offering few opportunities for learning or play. <table align=right width=150><tr><td><img hspace=10 vspace=10 border=1 width=134 height=89 src="pg17.jpg"></td><tr><td><small>Image: The challenge of the future is to provide safe and healthy environments for the increasing numbers of children growing up in cities. These Cuban girls find plenty of space to play outside their primary school in the capital Havana.&copy;UNICEF/DOI95-0400/Barbour</small></td></tr></table><br><br>As well as being overburdened by efforts to make a living, many poor urban families lack the safety net provided by the extended families typical of rural areas. They can find it hard to provide appropriate care and supervision of their children, especially if they lack access to child care services and affordable education. These pressures, which are often coupled with violence at home, mean many urban children end up working, and often living on the street to ensure their own survival. &quot;UNICEF and so many of our partners have been determined to put children onto the agenda of Habitat II,&quot; said UNICEF's Deputy Executive Director, Stephen Lewis, in his address at the conference. And this determination was well received by the delegates who recognised the degree to which poor children are affected by the lack of resources invested in basic infrastructure in many urban areas. The conference recognised that: &quot;The needs of children and youth, particularly with regard to their living environment, have to be taken fully into account. Special attention needs to be paid to the participatory process dealing with the shaping of cities, towns and neighbourhoods.&quot; <p>UNICEF has certainly seen how community participation pays off. For the last three decades the organisation has been tackling the problems of the urban poor through &quot;urban basic services&quot; programmes, which call for a commitment to &quot;planning from below&quot; - communities themselves establishing priorities. <p>The Brazilian seaport of Santos is a shining example of what can be achieved through community participation backed by a child-sensitive local authority. In seven years the city has managed to cut the number of infant deaths from 34 to 22 per 1,000 live births, cut the school drop-out rate to under 1 in 100 students and even reduce the number of cavities in children's teeth by adding fluoride to the city's water.<p>This was all the result of a programme started in 1989 by the municipal government, which aimed to improve children's lives by expanding or creating new programmes in health, education and recreation. The campaign was strengthened in 1993, when the Mayor gathered the support of volunteers, business leaders, the media, municipal city government and community groups, including the city's two guardian councils - watchdog child rights groups elected by citizens. The key to the programme's suc- cess was encouraging these groups to run programmes such as job training for youths and a radio programme organized by children. <p>Children themselves have shown that they have an important role in improving urban life. In San Ramon, Nicaragua, a children's movement founded by 14-year-old Juanita Guerrero Artista teamed up with the town's Development Committee. At the request of the children, who voiced their opinions in the town's public hearings, the municipal government constructed a new school, sports grounds and 120 latrines in the town. &quot;Adults make decisions that affect children without realising that children can think and analyse by themselves,&quot; said Ral Lpez Dvila, the Deputy Mayor. Municipal authorities are key partners for UNICEF in its work for urban children. Since 1992 an international alliance &quot;Mayors' Defenders of Children&quot; have committed themselves to ensuring that children's rights are being met in their cities. At the World City Assembly preceding the Habitat conference, several hundred mayors made a particular point of affirming children's rights in the urban environment. Lewis says: &quot;They collectively agreed that child well-being is an indicator of good governance.&quot; <p>Ensuring community participation in cities that are well-managed and socially equitable is the recipe for a positive urban future. As Stephen Lewis states: &quot;If we can transform urban settlements into child-friendly cities, we will build a better world for all&quot;.<p> <hr>©Copyright: UNICEF 1996<hr><center><SMALL><b> [<ahref="../index.html" target="_parent"> UNICEF Home Page</A>] [<ahref="http://www.childrenfirst.org">Support UNICEF</A>] [<ahref="../news.html">News</A>] [<ahref="../events.html">Events</A>] [<ahref="../publications.html">Publications</A>] [<ahref="../education.html">Education</A>]</font></SMALL></b></center></TR></TABLE></center></body></html>
