<head>
<title>Comic Relief Why?</title>
<!!keys: Comic Relief+Charity Projects+Red Nose Day 1995+information>
</head>
<body>

<hr>


<p><p><p>
<p><p><p><p><p><p>
<ul>


</ul>
<p>
<h3>QUOTE UNQUOTE</H3>

When Lenny Henry visited Somalia to make a film for the 'Night of Comic Relief' in March 1993 he said:
<p>
<ul><i>
"Of course the normal response to all this is to say, well, it's Africa, if it's not one problem, it's another, you know? So why should I bother? Why should I help them? What difference could I make anyway? No one should feel bad or evil about feeling that, because it is a normal attitude to have. But what we do know is this: if this was happening to a neighbour of yours you would bust a gut to help. The point is this: forget geography. These are your neighbours. This is your doorstep." 
<p>

</i></ul>
Jane Tewson - Chief Executive, Comic Relief.
<p>
<ul><i> 


"When we began Comic Relief we could never have imagined that ten years on we would still be raising money and still be raising laughs. The tragedy is the need continues to grow. We are totally thrilled at the continued support we get from the public. When there is a need they have always been there to help. There is much talk of compassion fatigue at the moment but we at Comic Relief know that the capacity of public to care and get involved is extraordinary, for which we are extremely grateful."<p> </i></ul>Paul Jackson - Chairman, Comic Relief.<p><ul><i>"What is strange but true and strangely humbling is the way that when Red Nose Day comes around, many of the greatest talents in Entertainment and leading professionals in advertising, PR, banking, telecommunications and across the media give freely their time and skills to help out. We could not do without them."<p> </i></ul>

Richard Wilson at Koboko Refugee Camp Northern Uganda, Christmas 1994.<p><ul><i>"I'm not going to say 'I don't believe it', but there are some things that are hard to believe. It's hard to believe that the people here are left with so little. It's hard to believe that their lives will ever be right again. But there's something else that's hard to believe. It's hard to believe that when I did that Comic Relief sketch two years ago, lying in a bath with only a flannel covering my privates and you rang in money, we were directly helping the people in this camp."<p> </i></ul>Michelle from Panda (Peoples Alternative to narcotics Drugs and Alcohol)<p><ul><i>"Without PANDA I don't think I could cope, because I'm still in the very early stages of recovery and to me this place plays a very big part of my life. I spend most of my days in here working, and at nights I come to meetings and socialise."
</i></ul>
<p>
<h3>"SOME OF THE STATISTICS THAT KEEP US GOING"</h3>
<ul>
<li>18 of the 20 poorest countries in the world are in Africa. Millions of people are displaced and living difficult lives because of conflict. Many more face a daily struggle to meet their basic needs like simply having clean water.
<li>There are still many thousands of young homeless people in the UK who need help and support.
<li>There are 6 million disabled people in the UK, yet young disabled people are still excluded from most schools and many find travel on public transport inaccessible.
<li>There are 10 million older people in the UK: two million live on the breadline and one million below it. Too many older people still live in real poverty.
</ul> 
<p>


