<html>
<head>
<title>Comic Relief - Press Launch</title>
<!!keys: Comic Relief+Press +Aims>
</head>
<body>

<hr>




______<BR>

<br>


____ <B><i> - FACE THE CAMERAS</i></B><br>



<p><p>
<b><i>- MEET THE PRESS </i></b>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>

</ul></ul></ul></ul>
<h3>Press Launch of Red Nose Day '95</h3>
Tuesday 7th February: It's 38 days to Red Nose Day '95.  At London's Empire Leicester Square, media celebrities - including Lenny Henry, Richard Wilson, Jonathan Ross, Angus Deayton and Emma Freud - combine forces to put out the word on this year's extravaganza.<p>
This time the theme is <i>difference</i> - one day spent fooling about for Comic Relief will make a crucial difference to the lives of some of the poorest people in the UK and in Africa.
<P>
<h3>SOME OF THE SOUND BITES...</h3>
<b>Paul Jackson, Chair, Comic Relief/Charity Projects</b><br>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>


</ul></ul></ul></ul>
"I want to make one point about the 'golden pound', as we call it, for Comic Relief. Obviously it costs a lot of money to organise something like Comic Relief - and here today you see a lot of money being spent. But today's a case in point. Not a single penny from today has been contributed by the charity. All the expenses of the day have been sponsored or contributed by the people we work with. So the 'golden pound' means every penny that anybody gives between now and March 17th will go directly to the beneficiaries intended with nothing taken off the top."
<P>
<b>Lenny Henry</b><br>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>


</ul></ul></ul></ul>
"Last Red Nose day was a fantastic, groovelistic success. We raised over £18 million to take our grand total to date to over £92 million.  And this year we're going to pass the £100 million mark. We've had great time making the new TV show. 
<p>
"Richard Wilson, Billy Connolly and Victoria Wood have all been completely brilliant and generous with their time and travelled out to Africa for us to report back on projects we fund there. And we make television history by pairing Jane Torvill and Rowan Atkinson, skating together to create the soon-to-be-legendary Torvill and Bean.
<p>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>


</ul></ul></ul></ul>

"Every year we do have the red noses, which I'm sure you know and love and we all look forward to wearing all the time. And every year we put a little twist in them. This year we decided to go with the new, magical, colour-changing nose. When first viewed, the nose is that lovely plastic red colour we all favour. But when it's rubbed up against any part of your anatomy that's warm - as Emma Freud will now demonstrate...
<ul><ul><ul><ul>

</ul></ul></ul></ul>
...it does magically change colour. There you go - the pinkest of pinks and the yellowest of yellows. And we have car noses: they change colour as well. If it's a very cold morning, below freezing, you find it goes purple.
<p>
"So all of these products will hopefully raise many millions of pounds, as they have done each year."

<p>
<b>Jane Tewson, Chief Executive, Comic Relief/Charity Projects</b><br>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>



</ul></ul></ul></ul>
"The reasons that we set up Comic Relief nine years ago are even more pressing today. I'm ashamed to say that - because I couldn't have believed that things would be worse. I was working in Ethiopia and the Sudan at the height of the famine, and I was working with people with disabilities before that. And it was pretty terrible then. But now, here in the UK, for example, homelessness, which was just emerging as a problem in 1984, has escalated. Centrepoint estimate that there are over 50,000 young people without a home in central London alone. And in Africa 11,700 children die every day from very preventable diseases like malaria and diarrhoea. So the needs are growing. And we've done an awful lot, but we need to do more and we need your help to do more.
<p>
"Comic Relief is very much committed to people. And what gives us hope is the people themselves that we are helping - their communities and the programmes that they run for themselves. There's much more to Africa than the emergencies that we are always seeing on television. Comic Relief exists to work with these people to overcome their problems. And we're proud to be supporting African people to work to solve their own problems.
<p>
"I'm going to give you a small example of how we spend our money, and the example is from Burundi. Burundi isn't in the news at the moment, but over the past two weeks there have been many massacres and killings of innocent people. On Thursday, a school was hand-grenaded. Three children were killed and many more were maimed. This could be the next genocide, following Rwanda. And it was wonderful that Comic Relief was able within a few days to make an emergency grant to fund the African component of a conference that was attempting to bring round the table all the people concerned in Burundi. This was local Burundi leaders, the United Nations, world governments and international charities, and they were working together to try to prevent a tragedy."
<p>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>


</ul></ul></ul></ul>
<hr>

<p>
<b>JOURNALISTS</b><br>
For media information and pictures please contact:<br>
 0181-576-0932 <br>
Comic Relief Press Office, B104, BBC Sulgrave House, 1 Woodger Road, London W12 8QT. <p>

<b>PUBLIC</b><br>
For a fundraising pack: 0891 665544<br>
Information Hotline:  0891 405060 <br>
Credit Card information: 0345 910910<p>
<a href="comic.html"><b>Comic Relief/Charity Projects<br></a>
1st Floor,<br>
74 New Oxford Street,<br>
London WC1A 1EF
<p>
Tel: +44 (0)171-436 1122<br>
Fax: +44 (0)171-436 1541</b>
