<html>
<head>
<title>Comic Relief Who?</title>
<!!keys: Comic Relief+Charity Projects+Red Nose Day 1995+information>
</head>
<body>

<hr>


<p><p><p>
<p><p><p><p><p><p>
<ul>


</ul>
<p>
LENNY HENRY will start the night of <b>Comic Relief </b> at 7pm on Friday March 17th on BBC1. Then he travels to Belfast during the programme to host a live St Patrick's Day broadcast from the Grand Opera House in Belfast, featuring BEN ELTON, JULIAN CLAREY, JO BRAND  and PATRICK KIELTY.
<p>
This year's other presenters include CHRIS EVANS, HARRY ENFIELD, PAUL WHITEHOUSE and chums, DAWN FRENCH and JENNIFER SAUNDERS, MEL SMITH and GRIFF RHYS JONES. Collectively they will create 6 hours of definitive live television and attempt to set new records in money raised on the night. Each hour will feature wild and wicked ways of getting people to raise money and raise a laugh.
<p>
In March 1993, we manned 750 phone lines and were inundated with calls from the time the programme started to the moment it finished. For 1995 we have set up a total of 5,000 phone lines to collect the public's money.
<p>
It will be a fabulous event, an unmissable night of TV, a mean-machine of fundraising, featuring original comedy to delight and thank our supporters, and original material to show why Comic Relief has to keep on keeping on.
<p>
<h3>New Comedy</h3>

We couldn't get Charles Dickens, but Richard Curtis has been persuaded to write OLIVER 2, the sequel to Oliver Twist. The world (or at least Lionel Bart) thought Oliver's story was over but, as will be revealed, it has only just begun. This sumptuous costume drama in three short parts is performed by Dame Diana Rigg, Pauline Collins, Alan Cumming, Michael Palin, Jeremy Irons, Angus Deayton, Stephen Fry and Oliver Reed to name but eight.
<p>
We present a unique opportunity to witness Jayne Torvill and Rowan Atkinson skate together as, obviously, TORVILL and BEAN. This Comic Relief Exclusive will feature BOLERO as never seen before and an extraordinary performance of LET'S FACE THE MUSIC AND DANCE.
<p>
PHIL COLLINS has recorded a rather unusual version of OLD MACDONALD HAD A FARM with a remarkable stable of animal impersonators that boasts Goldie Hawn as a duck, Martin Sheen as a cow, Emma Thompson as a pig, Whoopi Goldberg as a chicken, Hugh Grant as a cat and Desmond Tutu as a sheep.
<p>
RUBY WAX is going ON THE RAMPAGE to try and raise RUBY'S MILLION. Anywhere Anneke Rice can go, Ruby can go badder - she'll spend the programme bribing, scheming and blackmailing the British Public (especially the rich ones) to help her raise her own million to add to the pot.
<p>
DROP THE DEAD DONKEY are creating a wickedly funny and shockingly up to the minute DTDD Special just for Comic Relief. Victoria Wood has written a comedy special called 'Dawn' featuring Dawn French. Viewers should also look out for bits by other regular Comic Reliefers like Jonathan Ross, Joanna Lumley, Tony Robinson, Ade Edmonson and Rik Mayall.
<p>

<h3>New Documentaries </H3>
<h4>In the UK </h4>
For the first time ever on Comic Relief, We have asked some of the people who have received Red Nose money here in the UK to tell their own stories. <p>There is the story of how Michelle in Belfast overcame drug dependency with teh help of PANDA (Peoples Alternatives to Narcotics Drugs and Alcohol); of Damien Barry in Birmingham working to create opportunities for deaf people with Friends of the Young Deaf; and of how Claude Hendrickson and Randolph Morton (and an inspiring group of unemployed), young men in Leeds who decided to fight being homeless by building their own homes.

<h4>In Africa </h4>
We've also asked some of our comedians to report on the work in Africa. BILLY CONNOLLY revisits some of the projects he first saw in Mozambique in 1989 to find a real sense of progress and hope now the war is over.
<p>
RICHARD WILSON spends time in a refugee camp in Northern Uganda and sees first-hand just how crucial Red Nose cash can be to those living on the edge.
<p>
VICTORIA WOOD goes to Zimbabwe to stay with a family for week and experience what it feels like to live in an area threatened by serious drought. 
<p>
We will also be screening two full length documentaries on BBC1 during the Red Nose campaign:
<p>
<ul>The first follows Billy Connolly on his trip to Mozambique and is a close-up of his emotional journey as he meets and talks with local people.
<p>
The second is a fuller insight into the world of Michelle in Belfast as she leads us through her struggle to stay off drugs.
</ul><p>
Finally with the support of Live and Kicking and Harper Collins we are producing the Live and Kicking Comedy Showcase, a compilation of jokes and sketches written by their viewers and available in all good bookshops.
<p>
<a href="comic_launch.html"> click and see</a>
<p>
<hr>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>
<br>

</ul></ul></ul></ul><hr>

