<html>
<head>
<title>Comic Relief What?</title>
<!!keys: Comic Relief+Charity Projects+information+Red Nose Day 1995>
</head>
<body>



<p><p><p>
<p><p><p><p><p><p>
<ul>


</ul>
<p>
<h2>What a Difference a Day Makes</h2>
Red Nose Day this year is focusing on difference - one day spent fooling about for Comic Relief will make a crucial difference to the lives of some of the poorest people here in the UK and in Africa.
<h2>The Night of Comic Relief</h2>
<b>BBC1 - Friday March 17th - 7pm to 1am</b>
<p>
It will be a fabulous event, an unmissable night of TV, a mean-machine of fundraising, featuring original comedy to delight and thank our supporters, and original material to show why Comic Relief has to keep on keeping on.
<p>
This year's other presenters include CHRIS EVANS, HARRY ENFIELD, PAUL WHITEHOUSE and chums, DAWN FRENCH and JENNIFER SAUNDERS, MEL SMITH and GRIFF RHYS JONES. Collectively they will create 6 hours of definitive live television and attempt to set new records in money raised on the night. Each hour will feature wild and wicked ways of getting people to raise money and raise a laugh.
<p>
In March 1993, we manned 750 phone lines and were inundated with calls from the time our programme started to the moment it finished. For 1995 we have set up a total of 5,000 phone lines to collect the public's money.
<p>
<h2>BBC Radio 1FM</h2>
Radio 1FM will be supporting Comic Relief as never before with five weeks of comedy, competitions and documentaries.
<p>
BILLY CONNOLLY recorded a special series of reports when he was in Africa, which will be broadcast exclusively on 1FM.
<p>
1FM will be waging THE WAR OF THE NOSES as each day-time show adopts an area of the country to see which houses the most outwardlyrageous inhabitants.
<p>
The week leading up to Red Nose Day will climax in a series of live broadcasts from around the country as the search hots up for the most imaginative and active fundraisers. Those demonstrating particular ingenuity will be rewarded with THE ORDER OF THE NOSE - a special medal in recognition of the highest originality in the face of battle.
<p>
And on Mark Goodier's Show, there's the chance to win a fantastic customised RED NOSE CAR, when listeners' cars are spotted sporting the new magical colour-changing cold nose.
<p>
<h2>A SERIOUS COMMITMENT TO EDUCATION</H2>
Our education programme, which began in 1990, aims to pass on the knowledge gained through the experience of fundraising and grant making. We are thrilled at the incredible support given over the ten years by the public in raising money. However, we believe that, lasting change will only come about by raising awareness too. It is crucial not only to make people aware of the needs which their money will help to address, but also some of the causes and potential solutions that can contribute to resolving those needs.<p>
To date the education programme has been a mixture of three different types of work:
<p><ul>
<li> we have run educational projects in association with TV programmes like Going Live! which have challenged young people to create something that explores the issues arising from their work. These have included Video Relief, News Relief, and Pop Relief.<p>
<li> we have produced resources for the classroom dealing with development issues in Africa and the background to their areas of funding in the UK.
<p>
<li> we have reported back through short documentaries on the BBC and regular Newsletters to their supporters and the general public on where money from Red Nose Day has been spent.
</ul>
<p>
To co-incide with Red Nose Day '95, we have been able to provide FREE to nearly 4,000 schools to date a specifically commissioned RIOTOUS ASSEMBLY pack. This pack includes a Comic Relief RIOTOUS ASSEMBLY tape with Ben Elton and Tony Robinson - so that teachers can pop the cassette into the video and let the assembly take care of itself. The main issues covered are Disability Access and Fair Trade.<p>
The good news is, they've all gone, the bad news is, they've all gone!
<p>
<h4>Teacher Relief 2</h4>

This is an interactive video pack for secondary schools based around the best footage from Comic Relief's documentary output of the last three years. Targeted at Key Stage 3 and above of the National Curriculum, it aims to provide a grounding in the skills, knowledge and attitudes that will enable young people to make an informed and active response to the challenge of good citizenship in its broadest context.<p>
<h4>Altogether Better Resource Pack</h4>
This pack is aimed at teachers and school governors and combines a booklet and video which explains clearly why it is important to educate disabled children in mainstream schools. Including a history of disabled people in education, it gives lots of examples of how to put inclusion into action. An excellent resource to help schools understand the issues and face the challenge of implementing the Code of Practise for Special Needs.
<p>If you wish to review these or any other Comic Relief educational materials, please contact the
 Communications Department on 071 436 1122.
<p>
<a href="comic_launch.html"> click and see</a>

<p>
<hr>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>
<br>

</ul></ul></ul></ul>

