<html>
<head>
<title>Comic Relief How Much?</title>
<!!keys: Comic Relief+Red Nose Day 1995>
</head>
<body>


<hr>

<p><p><p>
<p><p><p><p><p><p>
<ul>


</ul>
<p>
<h2>What a Difference a Day Made</h2>
Our last Red Nose Day (1993) raised 18.1 million pounds and broke all records for the number of calls attempted during a TV telethon. 4.1 million attempted calls were registered - and our telephone competition hosted by Chris Evans took more calls than any phone competition has done before or since. This year up to 5,000 lines are available to take donations on the night.
<P>
In four Red Nose Days, Comic Relief has raised over 92 million pounds, which has made the difference between hope and despair, self-reliance and poverty and sometimes life and death for thousands of vulnerable people in the UK and Africa.

<p>
<h2>How the Money is Spent</h2>
In the UK we've supported work with older people, and young people who are homeless, disabled or have problems with drugs or alcohol.
<p>
In over 40 countries in Africa we've supported long term development work and, when needed, emergency relief. Most recently our money has paid for land mine awareness education for Rwandan refugees and over £100,000 has been allocated to a Ugandan organisation to provide loans to more than 1,000 small traders who would not qualify for credit from banks. The money is helping them become self-sufficient.

<p>
In all their grant giving we stress the importance of consultation with the people whose needs we are trying to meet. Our aim is that they can become stronger, more confident and self-reliant so that they will no longer need the help of charities like ours.
<p>
Over the years Comic Relief has supported over 2,500 projects. We've supported an army of workers, including drug counsellors, lawyers, health workers, nurses, teachers, engineers, artists, welfare advisers, AIDS counsellors, researchers, writers, builders, pastoralist herders, mechanics, pilots, eye-surgeons, lorry drivers, tailors, seamstresses, vets and entrepreneurs.
<p>
There are Comic Relief funded projects in every county of the UK. So far we've spent nearly £30,000,000 on more than 2,000 grants, which includes enabling accommodation to be provided all over the UK for over 2,000 homeless young people every night.
<p>
Every penny of the money donated by the public has gone to the charity because all our fundraising costs are sponsored in cash or in kind by companies and individuals.


<p>
<a href="comic_launch.html"> click and see</a>

<p>
<hr>
<ul><ul><ul><ul>
<br>

</ul></ul></ul></ul>

